<HEADLINE>Accident at fire was avoidable, says chief</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FIREFIGHTER who lost a foot while tackling a blaze in an operating grain
dryer was ``out of line'', his chief officer told a court yesterday.
Grampian firemaster Sandy Lobban said the accident had been avoidable and that
there had been no need for the part-time firefighter to have entered the dryer.
``It should never have happened in the first place. There was no need for the
machinery to be on,'' said Mr Lobban.
He was giving evidence on the second day of a trial at Peterhead Sheriff Court,
where Grampian Regional Council faces a charge under the health and safety
legislation.
Leading firefighter Francis Paterson, 40, of Copeman Place, Peterhead, lost his
right foot when he slipped after trying to clear grain from the inside of the
functioning dryer.
The accident happened on August 1 this year when the retained unit from
Peterhead was called to the fire at Eastlonghill Farm, near the town.
In what is being described as a test case, the council, which is ultimately
responsible for the region's fire brigade, denies failing to provide adequate
training for fighting fires in grain dryers and not preventing Mr Paterson from
entering the dryer when it was working.
``Mr Paterson was out of line ever considering entering the dryer in the first
place,'' said Mr Lobban. ``I would have thought that in particular his
experience would have covered him from that.
``I was extremely surprised and very disappointed to hear about the accident.''
Mr Lobban said it was a golden rule within the service to isolate power at its
source immediately on arrival at a fire. ``It is to ensure there is no chance
of it starting moving when a crew is present,'' he explained.
Mr Paterson, a former slater, is now a temporary training officer with
Peterhead fire station.
The trial, before Sheriff Kieran McLernan, was adjourned until January 4 for
closing submissions.
</TEXT>
