<HEADLINE>Williamson's answer is out of Africa</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week, Norrie Williamson called a meeting of athletes in Edinburgh - the
logical first step for the city's development officer for the sport. He wanted
to hear competitors' views, and put their interests at the centre of the
capital's plans to turn the tide of stagnation.
Yet until recently, in his previous job, such a meeting could not have taken
place, for it would have constituted an illegal gathering.
In Durban he was one of 20 whites among a university staff of nearly 500,
teaching 7000 students, 99% of whom were black or Indian. He helped unify five
different sports associations in several sports at regional and national level,
becoming adept at navigating a political jungle of such complexity that he
might even survive in Edinburgh.
The capital should be the focus of athletics in Scotland. It had everything
going for it after the 1970 Commonwealth Games, most notably an all-weather
track and the country's only arena worthy of the name. True, the main clubs,
Edinburgh Athletic Club and Edinburgh Southern Harriers, flourished briefly in
the British league, but real development was neglected.
Edinburgh's athletics has at least one thing in common with South Africa - it
has been bedevilled by factions with limited prospect of finding common ground.
But just as the forces of light triumphed in South Africa, so Williamson may be
the man to change Edinburgh's fortunes, though he stresses that it is no part
of his remit to pursue club amalgamation.
A former Royal High School pupil, he left these shores in 1981 with a degree in
structural and civil engineering and little interest in athletics. Rugby was
his game. He had played hooker for the FP first XV for several years, for
Panmure, and Howe of Fife, and at junior district level with North and Midlands.
When he left, he weighed 13 stones, but he discovered ultra-distance running,
and his racing and training mileage in the interim - the equivalent of more
than twice round the world - had reduced him to less than nine stones by the
time he returned last month.
In the intervening years, he has dominated the South African endurance scene,
during the years of sporting isolation, eventually representing Scotland and
Britain, and winning innumerable medals in events at 100 kilometres, 100 miles,
250k, 24 hours, and even 1000k. He set a record between Johannesburg and Durban
(5 days, 11hr 27min) and when trust funds were introduced in 1983, to the envy
of the track brigade, he had the biggest in South Africa. Victory in one 1000k
(625 miles) event alone brought nearly #5000.
He raced the London and Boston marathons on successive days in 2-42 and 2-45,
took team medals with Scotland in the Commonwealth 100k championships, and has
competed in international triathlons, including the Hawaii Ironman, and to a
high level in cycling, canoeing, and modern biathlon.
He found time to become a qualified coach, international team manager, IAAF
course measurer, broadcaster, commentator, and author of three athletics
coaching books, including the first translated into Zulu.
Sport's role in combating apartheid is perhaps not fully understood, as he
explained: ``With meetings - except sport - of more than 10 people being
illegal, student sport fixtures were the cover. Five hundred `supporters' would
travel to plan the next step. Sometimes their biggest problem was putting two
teams on the pitch to maintain the charade.''
Some whites shunned and reviled him, but for a man used to Scottish concepts of
equality, there was only one path to follow. His contribution to the
democratisation of sport in KwaZulu is unlikely to be forgotten.
A copy of Nelson Mandela's autobiography, Long Road to Freedom, which was his
parting gift, is signed by dozens of colleagues of every colour and creed,
ranging from national sports leaders to one of the cast of the classic film,
Cry the Beloved Country.
Shortly, he will be joined by his wife, Karin, and steps to develop athletics
in Edinburgh will begin in earnest, from the old clubrooms of Meadowbank
Thistle. The next move is an introductory meeting on Wednesday (7.30pm at
Meadowbank) of stakeholders in the new plan - representatives of the Scottish
Sports Council, Scottish Athletic Federation, District Council, local clubs,
athletes and coaches. All are welcome.
It's a while since he used his engineering degree, but Williamson still builds
bridges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
