<DOCNO>GH951216-000004</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000004</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rich legacy of penniless roving `ambassador' Andy Murray relates the story of a German diplomat who rejected Hitler and devoted his life to recording the crafts and traditions of Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andy Murray</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUT for the scourge of the swastika, Werner Kissling might have been buried
amid the pomp and pageantry usually accorded to a Prussian diplomat. As it
turned out, Kissling died penniless in a public-sector old folk's home in
Dumfries, and it was two years after his death that #500 was raised to finance
a simple granite headstone above his pauper's grave, a stone's throw from that
of Robert Burns.
Kissling, who might have become German ambassador had Hitler been liquidated,
died aged 92 in 1988; a documentary on his life will be screened by the BBC
next year.
He spent the last 20 years of his life in Dumfries, from where he toured the
country in a battered old van. Little did many people know that this
distinguished-looking man, who captured vanishing Scottish crafts and
traditions on film with his pre-war Leica camera, had played a part in the
history of the Third Reich.
Trundling around Scotland in a jalopy taking photos of crofters and weavers,
however, is a world away from the Weimar republic, in which he had been an
influential man.
As assistant to Gustav Stresemann, the German Chancellor, Kissling, had ordered
Hitler's arrest after the abortive Munich beer-hall putsch on May Day, 1923.
Born into an aristocratic family of landowners in Silesia, he had served in the
Prussian cavalry and the Imperial Navy during the First World War.
When the Nazis came to power in 1933, Kissling resigned his post as First
Secretary in the German embassy in London and became an anthropologist at the
Museum of Ethnography in Cambridge.
In 1934, fearing that the tentacles of Nazi agents would prove his undoing,
Kissling sailed to Eriskay and South Uist in a borrowed yacht, where he
recorded the lives of Hebridean crofters.
In his capacity as an anthropologist and photographer he later worked from a
lean-to annexe at Dumfries burgh museum, where he charmed students and
visitors, and David Lockwood, who is now the museum curator.
``He considered his research to be a race against time, and he only gave up
when forced by ill-health and crippling arthritis,'' Mr Lockwood wrote in his
obituary.
The School of Scottish Studies in Edinburgh is indebted to Werner Kissling,
whose brother was hanged on a meat hook after the ill-fated plot to assassinate
Hitler in 1944. During one visit to Scotland in the 1930s, Kissling made a
film, which is thought to be the first featuring spoken Gaelic.
Alfred Truckell, ex-curator of Dumfries museum, describes Kissling as ``a
brilliant man whose interests were wide-ranging and of international
importance''.
He says: ``He took some magnificent photographs, one of which I thought was
sheer brilliance. It was of the advance of the Red Army over the bridge at Riga.
``He made a splendid film on the Maoris of New Zealand, and he spent three
months in a black house getting an insight into crofting life.''
Kissling bought the Kings Arms Hotel in Melrose, but his brilliance did not
extend to hotel management. He later moved to Dumfries.
All that is left to remind Dumfries folk of the silver-haired gentleman with
the beat-up van and the tranquil demeanour is his headstone in the town's St
Michael's kirkyard. On that memorial are inscribed the words, ``Soldier,
Diplomat, Scholar, Gentleman''.
Ralph Coleman, a librarian in Dumfries, who organised the public subscription
for the stone, comments: ``The epitaph is fitting. That's what he was; an
amazing man with a depth of perception which allowed him to see what Nazism
meant to Europe.
``He once told me that Hitler's henchmen came to the Reichstag to meet
Stresemann, but Werner kept them waiting for ages and then they were refused
entry.
``After Werner resigned, Hitler rang to tell him his regiment needed him.
Werner told him that his regiment no longer existed.
``Hitler told him that he was a traitor to Germany, but he replied he might be
a traitor to Hitler, but not to his country.
``Werner actually told me he had never married because a diplomat was married
to his country. He was hunted by the Gestapo in Britain and he had to get
friends to rescue him from the situation.''
The BBC commissioned a documentary on Werner Kissling from Argyll-based Eala
Bhan. Michael Russell, chief executive of the Scottish National Party produced
the film, which was launched publicly in Dumfries yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000005</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000005</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mention asylum and the whole world goes crazy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LONG time ago asylum was something which people sought in a church when they
were on the run. The church provided a safe haven. Then asylum came to mean a
madhouse, until we adopted more enlightened ways of treating mental illness.
Today asylum has reverted to something of its original meaning - a safe haven
in another country sought by those who are fleeing from persecution in their
own country. However, after the actions of some churchmen last week over the
proposed changes in Britain's asylum procedure, I am convinced the church is
now the madhouse.
First some facts. Britain has one of the most generous benefit systems towards
asylum seekers in Europe. The proof of this are the applicants themselves, who
are streaming here in ever-increasing numbers - up from 22,000 in 1993 to an
estimated 40,000 this year. Meanwhile Western Europe's total has dropped from
500,000 to 320,000. To cope with the upsurge in applications to Britain the
Government intends to spend #37 million in the next three years on extra asylum
caseworkers and adjudicators. Hardly the stuff of a heartless state, is it?
Now the nitty gritty fact - how many are actually genuine cases for asylum and
how many are people who simply want a better opportunity in life? The answer is
that 4% are deemed to be genuine refugees by the Home Office and a mere 4% of
appeals are upheld by independent adjudicators. That leaves well over 90% which
are not genuine cases of asylum. This figure does not surprise me at all, and I
do not blame the asylum seekers for trying to win the bread ticket which is
held out by our liberal system. Neither do I blame the Government for trying to
bring some realistic accounting to the whole process.
However, some churchmen are making the issue an excuse for some cheap
campaigning at the expense of the facts, and an excuse for indulging themselves
as the champion of the exploited. They are clever men, and they are succeeding
in muddying the waters by distortion and throwing mud at the Government to
distract attention from the 90% of cases which prove them wrong.
Earlier this week, the Kirk's Church &amp; Nation Convener, Rev Andrew McLellan,
claimed on this page that the new legislation would ``treat all asylum seekers
as if they were here illegally''. That is simply not so. The Home Secretary
will have the power (subject to parliament) to declare that certain countries
are not prone to persecution but those arriving from them will still have the
right to present evidence in rebuttal. What is wrong with that? It is a well
documented fact that some claims of persecution are without foundation, and
anything which helps speed up the assessment process is to be welcomed.
Next up with a letter was the ecumenical machinator, Rev Maxwell Craig (and
former C.&amp;.N man) with his claim that ``from any point of view the changes to
be enacted are draconian''. What nonsense! As long as people claim asylum on
arrival in Britain they will still be eligible for benefit and they will remain
entitled to housing at the taxpayers' expense (but this will be restricted to
public sector housing). What is wrong about insisting that claims be made on
entry? People do not suddenly wake up in the middle of the night after several
months and find they would be unsafe back in their country of origin. They
usually do so after reading the social security benefits to which they might be
entitled.
The third C.&amp;.N man in action this week was the Iona Community Leader, Rev
Norman Shanks who joined the Rev Keith Steven in persuading Glasgow Presbytery
to denounce the Asylum Bill. Keith &amp; Norm's double act was remarkable for the
fact that they totally misprepresented the Bill's proposals. They bypassed the
Prebytery committee reports by raising their biased version of the issue from
the floor with no prior notice. Faced with their version of homeless,
persecuted people being flung out on the street, no other person spoke, and
their motion carried. I just hope that no-one imagines it represents an
intelligent appraisal of the issue.
The trouble is that the C.&amp;.N men are clever chaps. They know how to pull the
strings of the church publicity machine. Words like compassion and justice go a
long way in commanding respect when uttered by churchmen, even in today's world
and I am glad about it. But devaluation of that respect is inevitable when the
prophets prefer a partisan, selective version of the facts.
This is not a Christmas story about the goodies (Joseph &amp; family seeking
asylum) versus the callous Government (Herod). It is about clever men
manipulating church opinion over an issue upon which our country need feel no
shame at all. They offer no solutions, no basis upon which immigrants are to be
admitted other than the desire to be in the UK.
I want to see this country enriched by talented immigrants but there must be
selection and there must be limits. Not long ago I stayed overnight at the home
of a foreign couple in London. It was an excellent council flat in a good area.
It emerged in conversation that they were awaiting a decision on their
application for asylum. He worked and she was expecting a baby. That couple
were talented and decent people, but they have more chance of being run down by
a bus here than they do of being persecuted back where they came from. By all
means let us have immigrants like them, but let us not encourage them to make
fraud applications for political or personal asylum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
