<HEADLINE>Row erupts after health board resignation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE general manager of a Scottish health board was at the centre of a political
row last night after Labour called for an urgent investigation into its
management style.
The call followed the resignation of Professor Richard Olver as vice-chairman
of Tayside Health Board.
Friends of the professor said he had been frustrated by the conduct of the
board's general manager, Miss Leslie Barrie.
Now Scottish Labour health spokesman John McAllion, MP for Dundee East, has
written to Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth asking him to investigate.
The MP's call has support from the local health watchdog, Tayside Health
Council, which yesterday demanded an urgent investigation into the running of
the health board.
Professor Olver, who works as a paediatrician at Ninewells Hospital in Dundee,
explained that he was left in an ``impossible'' position as the board moved
resources away from hospitals and into more community-based health projects.
He also accused senior health managers of creating a ``them and us'' attitude
between health board purchasers and the trusts that delivered services, which
he said was a ``destructive waste of energy''.
Miss Barrie was in a meeting yesterday and was not available for comment. A
Tayside Health Board spokesman declined to comment.
Mrs Ruth Leslie-Melville, vice-chairman of Tayside Health Council, added:
``Professor Olver's resignation was, for us, confirmation what we had been
worrying about for some time. We feel that there is too great a gap between
what is happening at grass-roots level and at board level.''
</TEXT>
