<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Belgian Bosman wins his transfer case Price is fright after European ruling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR Chief sports writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PANIC began to set into Scottish football yesterday after the European Court of
Justice in Luxembourg ruled the transfer system illegal. The judgment, which
vindicated the stance of the long-suffering Belgian player, Jean-Marc Bosman,
who took his case to Europe's highest court, could have far-reaching
implications for the sport which no longer is free to buy and sell players when
they are out of contract.
For instance, Cowdenbeath warned they could be forced to switch to amateur
status, while others like Hamilton and St Mirren questioned the merits of
continuing with youth development schemes.
However, not everyone was fearful of the consequences. The judgment also
outlaws the system which prevents clubs from fielding only three non-nationals
in European club competitions, and while there was talk yesterday of a
five-year phasing in period, Rangers will be pushing for the immediate removal
of the three plus two (assimilated players) ruling.
The Ibrox club have championed the removal of the non-national rule within
football and were of the belief yesterday that, next season, they will be able
to select their players on merit rather than by observing UEFA restrictions in
which ever European competition they may find themselves. ``It seems to me that
if something is judged illegal, then it is precisely that,'' said Rangers'
vice-chairman Donald Findlay.
``We will be contacting both UEFA and the European Commission to find out what
exactly the impact will be, but we will be pushing also for the immediate
application of the judgment as it affects the three non-national rule.''
Of course, UEFA and the various member associations will be determined to do
all they can to slow the effects of the Bosman judgment, which UEFA president
Lennart Johansson attacked, and it would be naive of anyone to believe they are
without cunning.
Johansson and his people were gathering last night in Birmingham where the draw
for the European Championship finals will be held tomorrow afternoon, but no
one was able to say whether the judgment means transfer fees could still be
demanded within Britain. Scottish lawyer David Will, who is a FIFA
vice-president, said: ``The UK is one country from a political point of view
but four in football terms.''
Nevertheless, other than compromise with FIFPRO, the federation of players'
unions throughout world football, there appears little UEFA or anyone else can
do now to have the judgment overturned. Reasoned debate is the only way forward
and if UEFA realise that then a workable system which takes account of European
law and the needs of football can be negotiated.
SFA chief executive Jim Farry stood above the deepening gloom and stated that
the game would survive. ``It will be business as usual,'' he said.``The system
works. I'm not convinced it is broken and it is my belief that life will go
on.''
However, despite the defiant stance, Farry does not underestimate the perils
which could lie ahead if the correct procedures are not followed by
associations, and he disclosed that high-level talks among UEFA and players'
associations have been held. ``There is a contingency plan,'' he added.
Although the Bosman judgment affects the freedom of movement within the
European Union as dealt with in Article 48 of the Treaty of Rome, it should be
pointed out that transfer fees are now illegal only when players are out of
contract.
The relevant part of the judgment states the court has ruled: ``Article 48 of
the Treaty precludes the application of rules laid down by sporting
associations, under which a professional footballer, who is a national of one
member state, may not, on the expiry of his contract with a club, be employed
by a club of another member state unless the latter club has paid to the former
club a transfer, training, or development fee.
``Article 48 of the EEC Treaty precludes the application of rules laid down by
sporting associations under which, in matches in competitions which they
organise, football clubs may field only a limited number of professional
players who are nationals of other member states.''
Although the consensus among administrators last night was that the transfer
system could continue within Scotland and England, the Scottish Professional
Footballers' Association would not tolerate any attempts to perpetuate the
system without consultation with them.
``It is the case that the judgment applies only to players moving across
European Union borders, but it would be a nonsense if we were to have a
situation where a Scottish player could move without a fee to a French club at
the end of his contract here while that same player could not go freely to a
club in England,'' said SPFA secretary Tony Higgins.
q ENGLAND were stripped of an extra UEFA Cup place for 1996-97 by UEFA's
executive committee yesterday over their clubs' attitude to the Intertoto Cup
this summer. They now will have three clubs in the tournament.
q IBROX has failed to gain nomination to host the 1996 European Cup-winners'
Cup final. UEFA awarded the May 8 event to King Baudouin Stadium, Brussels. The
venue for the European Cup final on May 22 is Rome's Olympic Stadium.
q A new ball game - Page 31
</TEXT>
