<TEXT>
TINA JAMES has got her botany in a twist (Weekend Extra, December 9).
The oca is likely to be Tropaeolum tuberosum and belong to the family
Tropaeolaceae or it could be Chinese artichokes (Stachus affinis or
tuberifera), which is a labiate. Both are listed in The Plantfinder.
Nasturtium belong to the cabbage family (Cruciferae), oxalis is from the
wood-sorrel family (Oxalidaceae) and sorrel is from the dock family
(Polygonaceae).
None of these are related.
M Holm Hansen,
10 Craigton Avenue,
Milngavie.
</TEXT>
