<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is hard to object to the proposals in the Government's Broadcasting Bill
which allow greater cross-ownership between newspaper groups, television
companies, and radio stations at both national and regional level. After all,
nobody in Scotland will ever forget Roy Thomson's ``licence to print money''.
The increased stake permitted in television companies is welcome, while the
greater the opportunities to diversify into radio that regional and local
newspapers have the better. Such diversification will help ensure a stronger
future for a beleaguered section of the newspaper industry. It is the diversity
of his empire, after all, that has allowed Rupert Murdoch to fund the
cover-price cuts on his newspapers. As the Newspaper Society pointed out
yesterday, the complex criteria governing what local and regional newspapers
may do are hard to understand, and how they are applied will be what really
matters.
All in all, the opportunities the Bill opens up will be good for regional and
local newspapers, both commercially and in terms of news gathering and
dissemination. There is a danger, of course, in such cross-ownership that one
ends up with one medium plugging the contents of the other. Mr Murdoch's papers
already do that shamelessly with Sky's television programmes, and it could
happen elsewhere under other owners. As far as national newspaper groups are
concerned the ownership rules prevent Mr Murdoch's News International or The
Mirror Group from taking more than a 20% stake, which is something to be
grateful for. Where the new rules governing the ownership of ITV companies give
greatest cause for concern is that they could result in an all-out media war,
in which the big independent companies will try to swallow up the little ones.
When Carlton, not one of Britain's better television companies, declares that
it is delighted by the news, it behoves the viewer to beware. The Bill opens
the way for Mr Michael Green's Carlton Communications, Lord Horlick's Meridian
Broadcasting, and Granada to plunder the field, although Carlton's ownership of
Central Television does inhibit its scope for predatory action. But in the
harsh free-for-all world which lies ahead, companies like Scottish Television
and Yorkshire-Tyne-Tees could be up for grabs, as the movement in share prices
following the Bill's publication yesterday made clear. One of the great things
about British commercial television, indeed about British television generally,
is its diversity. Small companies like Border, HTV, Ulster, Grampian, and West
Country Television have genuine links with their viewing audience. The
regulatory system, which the Government has spent the past six years
dismantling, is considered by many to have been the reason for the regional
diversity of programmes. The Scottish Office appears to have ensured that there
is some protection against hostile takeovers for the Scottish companies, but
the ending of the two-licence limit in favour
of a 15% audience ceiling is likely to cause problems for all of them.
Grampian's chief executive, Donald Waters, was convinced yesterday that the
Scottish Office had fought the good fight successfully on behalf of companies
like his, but the proof of the pudding will be in the eating. If Mr Waters is
wrong, and the Bill opens the way for companies like his to disappear, then the
Scottish Office will stand condemned. Like everyone else affected, he will be
studying the small print with care over the weekend. One thing is certain:
stations like Grampian will not be saved simply because they are popular with
their audiences and have won Bafta awards for their programmes. Mrs Virginia
Bottomley, the Heritage Secretary, claimed her proposals would ``liberate
British broadcasters to become world leaders''. What she appears to have in
mind is the creation of companies which can take on the giants of the industry,
Ted Turner's CNN and Rupert Murdoch's News International, on their own terms.
In such a world, there is no place for minnows.
</TEXT>
