<HEADLINE>Profitable calling Unlike many in the mobile phones business, Woodend is making real money</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is nothing inevitable about the way the mobile telecommunications
business in the UK makes its money. Despite intense competition, the entire UK
marketplace for this Christmas's number-one fashion accessory has been coralled
down one particular road.
You buy a handset - value #130, say - for as little as #4.99. You may even be
offered free connection to a network. Thereafter the service provider and its
agents make their money on the much higher cost of calls compared with
fixed-wire telephony.
There are alternative roads. In Scandinavia, the same handset might cost you
the equivalent of #500. But the calls are much, much cheaper. The UK formula -
giveaway hardware, high cost tariffs - encourages a lot of churn in mobile
subscriber lists, when they discover how much it can cost to put their new toy
to use. Churn rates of 40% or higher are not uncommon.
Given the nature of the UK market, success seems to depend on breakneck
expansion, fuelled by ever more ``generous'' front-end giveaways. This is not a
business for wimps. Some of the familiar High Street names find it hard to show
a serious profit for all their efforts.
Eddie Prentice and his partner June Houldsworth at Woodend Communications know
all the pitfalls. They've been in the sector virtually from the start. Their
main focus is the business market, which has limited Woodend's exposure to the
High Street promotion war. Their company makes real money.
When Scottish Telecom, the offshoot of ScottishPower, decided to learn about
mobile service provision it bought a 25% stake in Woodend last year, with a
time-limited option to acquire the business outright.
When ScottishTelecom announced last month that it was to become Vodaphone's key
service provider to corporate customers in Scotland, its chief executive Rod
Matthews claimed the Woodend investment ``remains a central part of our
strategy''. If that means exercising the option, it will make Prentice and
Houldsworth seriously well-off.
Eddie Prentice came to telecommunications via accountancy. Having mixed an
economics degree at Glasgow University with Men's Union politics in the era of
Andrew Neil, he had the opportunity to become a tax inspector. Instead he
trained as a CA.
By 30, he was chief accountant of the SUN group of local newspapers, under a
finance director who was only a few years older. That implied a career block
so, two years later, he moved on to the Hamilton-based Russell office equipment
empire, created by entrepreneur Jim Russell, as group          financial
controller of a #20m turnover business.
Russell, which had outlets from Aberdeen to Sussex, had been sold by its
founder to London and Liverpool Trust. When LLT went into receivership, Jim
Russell bought back control of two of the biggest parts. In 1985, alerted by
people in Cellnet to the potential of mobile telecommunications, he set up
Woodend.
When, in 1987, Russell sold the office equipment side to David Murray, in his
pre-Rangers days, Prentice and the Woodend business moved to East Kilbride's
College Milton estate. ``The telecoms industry in Scotland was very fragmented
at the time. It was served by a lot of small businesses and I saw our move as a
chance to become pre-eminent,'' Prentice recalls.
Jim Russell didn't fully share that vision. He had made his pile. By the late
eighties, Prentice says, Woodend was afloat but drifting. Russell was looking
for a buyer. On holiday in France, lying on a beach, he suddenly thought: ``I'm
40. What if we're bought and I have to uproot the family. Why don't I make an
offer?''
He talked to colleagues, formed a team of four and told Russell they were
interested in an MBO. Within six months a deal was done. Many potential funders
rejected it. ``We were looking for #1m basically to buy 5000 subscribers. It
looked like a lot of goodwill and fresh air,'' he says now.
Through Mike Livingstone and Hamish Grossart at EFT, a group of Irish private
investors agreed to come in. ``We were in charge but not in control,'' Prentice
continues. ``The Irish guys had 51%.''
Woodend made #350,000 in its first year's trading after the buy-out. Eventually
Houldsworth and Prentice went to the bank seeking the resources to buy out
their two partners and the Irish investors.
``There were personal guarantees in place. We had had to borrow heavily. If
anything had gone wrong, we would have been in big trouble. But I was confident
in my own mind. By then we were connecting more people in a month than the
business had done in the whole of 1990.''
From there, the Woodend group developed a branded identity in the marketplace,
embraced quality standards through BSI (garnering four separate
accreditations), emphasised its uniqueness as a Scottish-based service
provider, and developed a thriving arm supplying fixed telecom systems which is
now Panasonic's biggest distributor in Scotland and northern England.
``We are the only company other than BT and Mercury which can connect phones
direct into networks,'' says Prentice. On the mobile side there are now eight
shops, from Aberdeen to Birmingham, to give the business a High Street presence.
``Woodend is not a telecoms retailer,'' he says emphatically. ``Our strength is
in serving the business community. Most businesses now regard mobile phones as
an essential tool. Having your staff out of touch for two hours just insn't
acceptable any more.''
</TEXT>
