<HEADLINE>Each man carries a cannon ball in a tortuous retreat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>45</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Michael Fry witnesses the long climb back over
the Cumbrian mountains as the English forces
scent disarray in the Jacobite camp
KENDAL, December 16 - The Jacobites' retreat to Scotland is turning into a
nightmare. As they retrace the route they took in high spirits only three weeks
ago, they are hampered by discord in their own ranks, by the worst winter in
living memory, by the now open hostility of the English people and by
harassment from the Government's pursuing forces.
Today, the clansmen had great difficulty controlling the situation round this
little town, where they had halted overnight before the long climb back over
the Cumbrian mountains. Even as the first of them set out under Prince Charles
Edward Stuart, townsfolk shouted insults and threw stones. Without their
officers' knowledge, some soldiers retaliated. They are reported to have killed
three civilians and looted several houses.
By the time the rearguard formed up, Kendal's resentment was boiling over. As
the prince's military commander, Lord George Murray, gave the final orders to
move off, a group of snipers organised by the town's parsons opened fire. In
their haste to get out, the clansmen left several horses behind.
They also soon learned that the road in front may not be clear. Murray had sent
ahead a detachment of cavalry under the Duke of Perth. It was to make for
Scotland with all possible speed and round up the available reinforcements, two
regiments from Perthshire raised by Lord Strathallan and the French force of
800 under Lord John Drummond which recently landed at Montrose.
But Perth's party was ambushed at Shap Fell by local militiamen, who at
Carlisle last month had just run away. Called out again under orders from the
Duke of Cumberland, commander of the royal forces in England, this time they
shot up the Jacobites and forced them to turn round.
Progress through the hills is anyway painfully slow. The rearguard has only
heavy wagons for transport over poor roads in torrential rain, with snow and
ice at high levels. Often the clansmen have to manhandle equipment across
rivers and through deep mud, a job so backbreaking that the officers join in.
To hurry things up, Murray proposed abandonment of the heavy baggage and
artillery. But Prince Charles refused, and insisted that not a single
cannonball was to be left behind. Today the balls, which if loaded on a cart
would be impossible to move, are being carried one by one in their plaids by
the soldiers of the Glengarry regiment. Murray has promised to pay each of them
sixpence for the extra effort.
The main body of Highlanders should be able to brush aside any screen of
militiamen at Shap and get across to Penrith. But the crawling rearguard runs
the danger of becoming separated, and of being caught by the English forces now
in pursuit.
While Murray spares no effort to get his army quickly to the Border in one
piece, he is often obstructed by Prince Charles, who has been intent on
stressing that this is a tactical withdrawal, not a flight. As a result, the
Jacobites have lost the three days' lead which they had when they started their
retreat from Derby on December 6.
At Preston, which they reached five days later, the prince halted and called a
council of war. The purpose was to debate a plan put forward by the Duke of
Perth and the Marquis d'Eguilles, French envoy to the Highland army. The pair
proposed that it should go into winter quarters in this town, which it could
use as a defensive base while waiting for the expected reinforcements from
France via Scotland. The clan chieftains rejected the idea out of hand. But by
the time the talking was over scouts had spotted the approach of English
troops. The Highlanders left Preston with only an hour to spare.
On December 13, while they were making for Lancaster, they found they had not
only the Cumberland but also General Wade on their tail. Wade's army is charged
with the defence of the eastern side of England, but has so far had nothing to
do because the Jacobites advanced down the western side, and snow has blocked
his routes over the Pennine Hills. This week he at last managed to get an
advance guard across under Major-general James Oglethorpe, which skirmished
with Lord Elcho's regiment of Jacobite cavalry at Garstang, 10 miles from
Preston.
But the Government in London then suspended all operations when it received
intelligence that the French were at last making moves to invade the South of
England. They have been gathering troops along the Channel for some weeks,
though without till now making any obvious preparations for boarding ship or
putting to sea. This seemed about to happen when the designated leader of the
expedition, the Duc de Richelieu, arrived at Boulogne with Prince Charles's
younger brother, Prince Henry.
Orders were sent to Cumberland to halt his pursuit and turn round. The duke in
turn recalled Oglethorpe, unaware how hard on the Highlanders' heels he was.
Before they could start for the south, it became clear that in fact an invasion
could not be under way, because the French were making no serious attempt to
break the royal navy's blockade in the Channel.
In the North of England, the royal armies then resumed the chase. The Jacobites
had gained a day, and at this stage Prince Charles was still hoping to fight a
battle on English soil and regain the initiative. Once at Lancaster, he sent
out Lord George Murray to select a suitable site. When they saw, however, that
two enemy forces were again closing in, they decided against making a stand.
The clansmen were ordered to move on to Kendal.
</TEXT>
