<TEXT>
Good causes
on the cards
TO send or not to send, that is the question in many people's minds at this
time of year as they examine last year's Christmas card list.
Some, like KPMG, decide not to. It advertised this in The Herald yesterday
under the heading ``What! No Christmas Card?'', explaining that it was not
sending any this year, but instead was making a donation to charity.
Lanarkshire Development Agency took the same decision and is giving #2000 to
good causes instead.
Many companies, however, continue the traditional practice of sending greetings
to their clients, and help charities at the same time by purchasing their cards.
If your company is among this band, and you haven't sent out yours yet, or you
have run out and need to buy more, you might consider the cards produced with
businesses in mind by the Prince &amp; Princess of Wales Hospice in Glasgow's
Carlton Place.
They are priced at 75p each, and we are told a hefty chunk of this goes to the
hospice which recently launched a #1.4m appeal to extend its day and home care
provision. If you are interested in making a purchase, give Jim McFatridge a
call on 0141 429 5599 extn 159.
While on the subject of charities. LDA staff are to be congratulated for their
efforts in raising #3200 from bottle collections, sponsored football matches
and a charity ceilidh. The money will go to seven deserving causes.
Engineering
excellent value
THERE is still a chance for Strathclyde companies to grab themselves a highly
trained engineer for a year at the knockdown price of #7500.
Business Diary readers will recall that several weeks ago we featured the
initiative by Lanarkshire Development Agency and Scottish Design to place
redundant Rolls-Royce engineers in small to medium-sized firms. The engineers
are paid #15,000 but the companies only have to pay 50% of this.
Following our piece more than 20 firms contacted David Robson at Scottish
Design, who is now in the process of placing the engineers, but he tells me it
is not too late for companies to avail themselves of this opportunity by giving
him a call on 0141 221 6121.
Joking apart,
congratulations
THE Women's Technology Centre, which is housed in the Dalmarnock Initiative
Base in Glasgow's East End, held its annual diploma presentation ceremony
yesterday in the city's Merchant's Hall.
Comedian Elaine C Smith made the presentations to the 70 women who took part in
its business start-up course, a year-long technology course, and a training
course for women from the ethnic communities. Well done everyone, and I am told
Smith was in top form.
Course is just
the job for men
STRATHCLYDE Business Development should be congratulated for the cut price deal
it has struck with Babson College in Boston to allow Strathclyde businesses to
participate in its Working for the Yankee Dollar course. The cost has been
reduced to between #700 and #800, about a fifth of the normal price.
Hopefully, the experience of taking part will help reduce the number of MCPs in
the Scottish business community. For Bob Creighton, president of the Scottish
Trade Group, reveals that one of the classic mistakes made by Scots businessmen
trying to break into the North American market is to underestimate the power of
women on company boards.
He explains: ``Many Scottish firms are not prepared for the large number of
powerful women in US firms. We still get incidences of Scots businessmen
talking down to a woman, then finding out they have blown the deal because she
is the president of the company.''
If you would like to find out more about the course, which takes place next
March, contact Harry Baxter or Eileen Anderson at SBD on 0141 227 3874.
Pooling their
resources
SWIMMING pools are keeping Frank Thomas busy these days in and out of business
hours. He is the senior partner of Thomas &amp; Adamson, one of Scotland's leading
firms of quantity surveyors, which is currently completing the modernisation of
the Dollan Baths in East Kilbride and also the upgrading of Glasgow
University's pool.
In his spare time he is a member of STOP (Save The Outdoor Pool) which is
trying to convince East Lothian District Council that the North Berwick outdoor
pool should remain open.
Today Scottish rugby internationalist Scott Hastings and Santa Claus are
joining forces to help the STOP campaign. Hastings will be at North Berwick
pool at 11am to sign autographs and around the same time Santa will be arriving
in a horse-drawn carriage.
It is not surprising Thomas takes a keen interest in this particular pool as he
is a local and also a former swimming champion. He won the Scottish men's
220-yards freestyle championship at the Bon Accord baths in Aberdeen in 1958.
He also coached David Wilkie to his Olympic silver medal, and of the 21 Scots
swimmers who took part in the 1970 Commonwealth Games, ten were his proteges.
</TEXT>
