<HEADLINE>Casualties can be expected in Scotland Bosman ruling means a whole new ball game</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR, CHIEF SPORTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE man's five-year struggle to prove the injustice and insensitivity of
football's authorities ended yesterday, but, ironically, Jean-Marc Bosman's
persistence could have serious repercussions for footballers throughout Europe.
It never was the Belgian's intention to undermine the sport's system to the
effect that fellow professionals could lose their jobs, but that could be the
scenario, although the effects might not be as devastating as many fear.
When the European Court of Justice ruled yesterday that football's ways of
transferring footballers and restricting movement were illegal, Bosman, denied
the right to earn a living within his chosen sport, was able to celebrate. He
and the players' unions who had backed him were vindicated. They had triumphed
over the might of UEFA, a typically intransigent football body which needed
reminding of its place in the wider world, and as the judgment, said to be 100
pages in detail, is analysed, a black reality begins to emerge.
While all fair-minded people who believe in basic human rights and freedoms
will welcome the judgment, it would be callous, not to say foolish to ignore
the growing fears of the people who have benefited from the game's bartering
system. The possibility of casualties is strong. Some clubs which have enjoyed
professional status for many decades could close, or slip into the anonymity of
the amateur ranks.
Clubs like Rangers and Celtic will thrive on the judgment, which will allow
them to play as many non-Scots as they wish in European competition, and they
may also be able to take the best players from clubs without paying a fee. Of
course, the Old Firm stand to lose players to other, larger clubs, but in
general the effects of the judgment should work in their favour.
Throughout the leagues of Europe the rich will become stronger. It is perverse
irony this will be one of the consequences of Bosman's quest to expose one of
the wrongs in football.
Clubs, especially those like Dundee United who are adept at nurturing young
talent, now must reconsider their work. If they cannot be guaranteed a transfer
fee for a player their expertise, time, and money has produced, there would
seem to be little point in persevering with a serious youth policy. However,
the judgment is open to various interpretations. There are loopholes and ample
room for UEFA's lawyers to manoeuvre, which means arguments will rage before
everyone understands what they can and cannot do.
Nevertheless, that won't prevent the jowls of club chairmen in the traditional
mould from quivering in fear. They believe yesterday's judgment was a death
sentence for some clubs.
Cowdenbeath's chairman, Gordon McDougall, said clubs like his could be driven
to amateur status. ``If the full force of the judgment hits, I can see no
alternative but to turn amateur,'' he said. McDougall claims it costs his
third-division club #10,000 a year to operate a youth programme, but he fears
that if players can walk away at the end of their contracts, there would be no
point in bringing them through in the first place.
``Could I work with a boy for years, coaching him to first-team level and then
he says, `thank you,' and he goes elsewhere without compensation for us?''
asked a bemused St Mirren manager Jimmy Bone. ``Our directors will need to
decide our furture plans.''
Hamilton manager, Iain Munro, also voiced concern about youth development and
suggested the SFA could take on the responsibility. ``It could be laid down
that no-one could sign any of the players until they were 16 and a small fee
would have to be paid,'' he said.
``As the boy advances in to a first team and possibly an international side, an
extra sum could be paid to the SFA.''
It is this kind of thinking which will be required now as football comes to
terms with the implications of the Bosman judgment, but yesterday was a day
when football people were wrapped in paranoia. Eventually, however, sanity will
be restored.
``There must be compensation for clubs which produce players from within their
own ranks,'' said Roy Aitken, whose club, Aberdeen, have a pedigree in rearing
talent. ``There must also be a period of time allowed for clubs who have
invested heavily in players to come to terms with the new system.''
Rangers were happy with the outcome and their vice-chairman, Donald Findlay,
argued that the development of young players would not be slowed because some
clubs might wish to sign more foreign players. The three non-nationals rule
also was deemed illegal, and Findlay said: ``If you have a player like Charlie
Miller, for instance, he would come through in any case.
``It will always make sense for clubs to bring through their own players. For a
club like Rangers the secret will be finding the balance between the real
Rangers players, men reared in the club, and the hired guns.''
Celtic's chairman, Fergus McCann, welcomed the judgment more cautiously. ``I am
glad to see the three-      foreigners rule has changed,'' he said. ``That
brings football in line with other fields of work.
``I would also like to see the 10-player limit on non-EC players widened as it
puts Scottish football at a disadvantage.''
Enough, Fergus. The months ahead are going to be tricky enough trying to
tip-toe through the pages of the court judgment without complicating matters
worrying about non-union citizens. Common sense and reasoning will get everyone
through, and two men who will be called upon to counsel and advise realise also
there is now a need to reach compromise. Tony Higgins, the Scottish
Professional Footballers' Association secretary, and SFA chief executive Jim
Farry will have much to say.
``First we will have to find out what the legal framework is and go from
there,'' said Higgins. ``A long-term view between players and governing bodies
will have to be developed.''
Farry appeared comfortable with the situation, even though he had been hoping
it would all just go away. ``Re-investment in youth is a vital component of our
sport,'' he said. ``The importance of such re-investment should not be
minimised.''
Farry agreed that one aspect of the Bosman ruling could be a reworking of
Scottish football's finances, and that would not necessarily be a bad thing. If
approached properly, the Bosman case could be seen as a blessing for everyone,
but if the wrong decisions are taken, it could, indeed, mean the end for some
clubs.
</TEXT>
