<TEXT>
Frank McGroarty talks
to Bob Monkhouse about
his silent favourites
THROUGHOUT 1995, movie buffs have been treated to a veritable feast of cinema
classics on television as a build-up to the 100th anniversary of the cinema.
The celebrations themselves start on December 28 and when it comes to film
fans, one of the most famous in this country is comedy star Bob Monkhouse.
``I watch a lot of films on video,'' he said, ``but I prefer to go to my local
cinema and see them because that is what they were originally made for.''
Monkhouse is regarded as one of the country's renowned movie buffs and since
the age of 16 has built up a collection of classic films from the industry's
golden era, with the silent films being among his prized possessions.
The host of TV's Celebrity Squares and Memory Masters and On the Spot has his
own batch of movie memories to last him a lifetime. When Monkhouse started to
frequent the local picture houses, the silent-movie era was still fresh in a
lot of people's minds. So it comes as no surprise that he lists Buster Keaton
among his heroes.
``He was a wonderful comedian, a clown and an acrobat,'' he said. ``There was
certainly no-one like him,'' he said. ``A heroine of mine from the silent years
was Mabel Normand who starred in the Mack Sennett comedies. She was a waif-like
creature who was also a great comedienne.'' His love of those old films became
intertwined with his television career when he used his collection of silent
comedies as part of the hit show from the late sixties, Mad Movies. ``There was
talk of me doing a similar series but we are still negotiating.'' Unfortunately
for him it was that collection of films that led to him appearing in the dock
of the Old Bailey on June 6, 1979, where he was charged with conspiring to
illegally import copies of films. The case was thrown out of court but the
story did not completely finish on a happy note. ``I was unable to get all of
my films back. Those that were not returned to me were destroyed, it was very
sad.''
When he was seven years old, it was a trip to a cinema in Sydenham that was to
have a profound effect on Monkhouse and to shape his destiny. ``I was taken to
see Boots Boots, starring George Formby, in 1934,'' he said. ``I was spellbound
in the darkness.''
Over the years he marvelled at the antics of the Marx Brothers. He also became
a fan of Bob Hope while watching the film The Cat and the Canary. Years later
he was to work with the comic legend as one of his scriptwriters.
Monkhouse does not stick to just watching old masterpieces. Whenever he gets a
break from his exhausting schedule he pays regular visits to his local cinema
in Milton Keynes. ``One of the strangest movies I have ever seen has been the
film Ed Wood starring Johnny Depp. That fact that they make such a wonderful
film about a guy who could not make films himself, fascinates me.
``I enjoy watching films such as Quiz Show, made by Robert Redford, and Murder
in the First, starring Christian Slater. I still watch comedy films. I consider
myself to be a student of comedy. There was the film, The Ref, starring Dennis
Leary, that was a really funny movie.''
However not all films he has seen meets with his approval. ``There was a film
starring Shirley MacLaine called Guarding Tess,'' he said. ``Whoever you write
this for, you can tell them that it is a load of old rubbish.''
</TEXT>
