<DOCNO>GH951216-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jazzmen turn snowmen for a cool Christmas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER the years jazzmen have, like most other musical artists, dabbled in
festive season songs and we have been entertained by Fat Waller's irreverent
Jingle Bells and Louis Armstrong's White Christmas and sundry others . . .
Then, a little more than 20 years ago, an entire album named Hark The Herald
Angels Swing was released by The World's Greatest Jazz Band of Yank Lawson and
Bob Haggart. My three daughters grew up listening to it, my non-jazz friends
were absolutely captivated by it and it remains a staple on  my turntable over
the Christmas season.
The band mixed Tin Pan Alley songs along with traditional items and hymns and
the mix was so successful that other groups followed this example.
The Sackville All Stars with Ayrshire's own Jim Galloway on soprano saxophone
brought out their record; another all-star group with yet another Scot,
baritone saxophonist Joe Temperley, had an album on Dreamstreet and even the
pianist Art Hodes drenched Joy To The World with Chicago-based blues figures
Jimmy Yancey would have envied.
Now we have two Christmas CDs on the market to allow us to celebrate the
holidays in jazz mode. One is on Concord and it was issued a year ago and the
other is on Chiaroscuro and has just appeared on the specialist shop listings.
Both feature major stars who have recorded for these labels and, amazingly,
just a single featured artist turns up on both. Pianist Dave McKenna is that
man with a sensitive version of Mel Torme's beautiful Christmas Song on the
Chiaroscuro and an equally respectful reading of O Little Town of Bethlehem on
the other. It's difficult to pick a favourite between the two new issues though
I would lean a little towards the Chiaroscuro. These various recordings began
as a bonus for the label's owner Hank O'Neal. When he recorded the various
musicians he asked for an extra couple of tracks which he then had pressed as
singles and sent them out as Christmas cards to his friends.
The first was the McKenna, the next had the legendary Earl Hines playing White
Christmas which is on the current CD.
However, best of all, are the tracks featuring Flip Phillips and Summit
Reunion. Phillips, the one-time rabble rouser with Jazz At The Phil, still
remembered for his tenor battles with Illinois Jacquet confirms his stature as
a superior ballad player with a track which begins with O Come All Ye Faithful
and then segues into Silent Night for five minutes and fourteen seconds of
bliss.
Summit Reunion, with main protagonists Kenny Davern and Bob Wilber swinging
superbly, perform It Came Upon The Midnight Clear with the usual support from
the rhythm section of Dick Hyman, Milt Hinton, Bucky Pzzarelli and Bobby
Rosengarden.
Among other featured artists on this album are Louie Bellson, Roger Kellaway,
Junior Mance, Ralph Sutton and Jay McShann and the pianist Dick Wellstood with
a joyous recreation of Waller's Jingle Bells enlivened by the presence of
trumpeter Herman Autrey who had been on the original with Fats and hung around
for some 40 years or so to do it all again.
Poor Autrey did have some difficulties with the whole session, though. I
remember Wellstood telling me once that the trumpeter, well into his seventies
by this time, had turned up loaded and was unable to complete all the numbers.
This one, however, must have been done early because that rough-toned trumpet
which was on most of the Waller records sounds unaltered by time.
Concord, more of a major label, has some bigger guns to trot out on their
seasonal offering. Rosemary Clooney is here with Christmas Time Is Here and
pianist Gene Harris plays I'll Be Home For Christmas and tenorist Scott
Hamilton does Christmas Love Song.
But it's one of the lesser-know men musicians from the Concord stable,
guitarist Frank Vignola who steals the show with a bluesy version of Jingle
Bells.
Normally a guitarist who is linked with various Django Reinhardt revivals at
such New York clubs as Michael's Pub, Vignola shows much more than just a
Django influence on this track.
The great thing about all the recordings I have mentioned is that none of them
sound as if they have been done as some sort of gimmick. There is a genuine
warmth about them all.
You'll find out when you listen and, if you can find the WGJB album on World
Jazz then look out for Billy Butterfield's version of Christmas Song - that
beats all the rest!
Ken Gallacher guides us through
a thoroughly
blues Yule
</TEXT>
