<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rural Scotland Yet more countryside quangos</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE White Paper on rural Scotland issued yesterday offers a plethora of fine
words and pretty ideas. The Scottish Office will work in partnership to enable
rural Scotland to be prosperous, with a range of job opportunities enabling
natives and newcomers to ``enjoy worthwhile ways of life'', to be vigorous in
its community life, to be culturally confident, cherishing local traditions and
distinctive ways of life - all noble aims. Rural Scotland would also be ``able
to protect, conserve and enhance its outstanding natural environment'' through
this four-pronged policy framework embracing economic, social, cultural, and
environmental aspects. But the bottom line is that it creates yet more
countryside quangos and is vague on resourcing and yet again, we suspect, it
will lump the onus of actually doing anything about poor transport provision,
rural homelessness, lack of job opportunities for the young and other chronic
rural problems on to the new local councils.
The third of the Scottish population classed as rural dwellers usually share
some common aspirations, such as the desire to live in beautiful surroundings
while rearing and educating families away from cities and their drawbacks.
Often the attainment of such goals means sacrifice, accepting a lower level of
economic participation or poorer services, or paying higher prices for
essentials. Many have always been willing to accept these and other minuses to
secure a share of rural Scotland's benefits. There has, however, been a growing
consciousness that change is possible, that rural community living need not
equate for ever with low expectations. It is difficult to pinpoint any single
influence which has triggered this mood but it is possible to see it in the
debate on Harris and Lewis over the super-quarry proposal, the emergence (from
the womb of the Scottish Office) of the community forest concept at Laggan, and
the raid on the market by which the crofters of Assynt took control of their
own land. There are other similar land initiatives on the boil around the
Highlands. Whatever his long-term reasons, Mr Michael Forsyth, the Scottish
Secretary, has now assumed a role in this land reform - belatedly, towards the
end of a long spell of power - and a cynic might say that it reeks of a
last-ditch attempt to win back rural Scotland for the Tories. The same cynic
might add that yesterday's paper does nothing to address key issues, such as
the pressing need for genuine measures backed by real vision in the matter of
preserving our natural heritage. Many of the natural wonders about which the
Scottish Office gushes are already in reality devalued by inappropriate
forestry and inappropriate sporting use. The accelerating slaughter of
Scotland's birds of prey by the lairds, the vast over-proliferation of deer to
provide easy targets for rich foreigners - even the de facto hand-over of Loch
Lomond, one of the jewels in the heritage crown, to speed boaters and water
skiers by the expected promulgation of inadequate by-laws
- are cases in point.
At a time when our Irish neighbours are pumping millions and much thought into
angling tourism as their major rural asset, the Scottish Office seems content
to leave what is potentially one of rural Scotland's most major economic assets
to drift downwards in a policy vacuum dominated by netting interests. The
trumpeting of a commitment to sustainable development is fine; the reality with
which we are all familiar is very different. The White Paper may represent some
kind of vision, but it remains hard to see whence any tangible benefit will
accrue.
</TEXT>
