<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lorry driver claims van's actions could be explained only if AA patrolman had become ill Driver denies death crash blame</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JURY was told how a young Ayrshire woman died on a new bypass when the car in
which she was a passenger was involved in a head-on collision with an
Automobile Association patrol van.
Ms Alison Dunn, 20, of Arran Place, Ardrossan, was taken to hospital in Paisley
following the accident on the A737 Johnstone By-pass in June, last year.
However, she was already dead from ``catastrophic internal injuries'' to her
head and body.
Mr Bernard Coyle, 58, of Campsie Road, Slaemuir, Port Glasgow, who was an AA
patrolman at the time, denies causing her death by dangerous driving.
The trial at Paisley Sheriff Court was told how the car's driver, Mr Andrew
Allan, 24, of Ardrossan Road, West Kilbride, could do little to avoid a
collision when the accused's van suddenly appeared in front of his vehicle from
a stream of west-bound traffic.
Lorry driver John McLelland, 29, of Kirknowe Cottages, Howwood, Renfrewshire,
said he had been driving his articulated lorry east on the by-pass when the
accused's van suddenly appeared directly behind him.
He saw the van appear close to the rear of his trailer in his offside wing
mirror and it ``caused him some alarm''.
The next thing he knew, the van had pulled out as if to overtake his 40ft truck
and, almost instantaneously, there was an impact with the car.
He told the court: ``The van took off as if it had gone up a ramp. It was
spinning through the air.'' Asked what that ``ramp'' had been, he replied:
``The other car.''
The witness said he later told police he thought the van driver must have
suffered a heart attack or stroke, causing him to lose control of the van.
``That was the only way I could explain the van's actions,'' he added.
Giving evidence, Mr Coyle said that, since the accident, he had been paid off
on medical grounds, due to the injuries he sustained.
He said he had served as a special constable for 23 years and had at times
assisted police in road safety competitions, as he had passed his advanced
driver's test.
He denied that he had driven on the wrong side of the road in the seconds
leading up to the collision and said he had no recollection of driving behind
Mr McLelland's lorry, or that he had tried to overtake any vehicles.
The accused said had been on his way to assist a female member who needed a
wheel changed. It was an urgent call but he had not been driving fast.
He claimed he had seen Mr Allan's car coming towards him on the wrong side of
the road and had tried to take evasive action by swerving to the right onto the
other carriageway, but could not avoid a collision.
Under cross examination, he denied he had been momentarily disorientated before
the accident, or that he had been unwell.
Giving evidence for the defence, another lorry driver, Mr John Davis, 32, from
Erskine, claimed Mr Allan's car had overtaken him just before the two vehicles
collided.
He felt the accident occurred as Mr Allan's car had failed to fully complete
the overtaking manouvre and had clipped the AA van which, he maintained, had
remained on its own side of the road.
The trial, before Sheriff Colin Higgins, is expected to conclude on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Country dancing past and future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO the report from the Scottish Office Schools Inspectorate is advocating the
teaching of Scottish Country Dancing in secondary schools.
We in primary schools were away ahead of ourselves 40 years ago when many of us
had the job of preparing P7 for the ``Quali'' dance.
With the help of Jimmy Shand records and an old gramophone I put my class of 51
pupils through their paces - pas de basque, jig, and skip change of step
teaching the Dashing White Sergeant, Gay Gordons, and even attempting the
Eightsome Reel.
My most difficult task was persuading the boys to choose a partner and to hold
her hand. Incidentally the dress in those days was very formal - sticky-out
taffeta dresses and perms were obligatory for the girls, and the boys wore
suits.
Over the years the dances remained the same but the dress of both sexes changed
dramatically. Eventually it was the most outrageous gear available - taffeta
dresses were definitely out and no boy would have been seen dead in a suit.
They say that if you live long enough everything comes back into fashion. Any
day now the Schools Inspectorate will be recommending the chanting of the
multiplication tables and learning by rote.
Jean Macluskie,
9 Mansewood Drive,
Dumbarton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shedding light for charity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Shedding light
for charity
TAXI driver Brian Roe and his wife Isobel have spent almost #2000 on Christmas
decorations for their Dumfries council house and garden - and a further #300 on
a video security system to protect the display from vandals, who struck five
times last year.
The outside illuminations are so spectacular they stop the traffic. Inside the
house is like Santa's grotto and will be open to the public each evening next
week, with all donations going to Children in Need.
Triple portrait
A PORTRAIT of the Citizens' Theatre's directorial triumvirate by Glasgow artist
Adrian Wiszniewski was unveiled yesterday at the theatre by Jeremy Isaacs. The
painting - of Giles Havergal, Robert David MacDonald, and Philip Prowse - was
commissioned by the Scottish National Portrait Gallery. It will be on display
at the People's Palace in Glasgow for two months before moving to the Edinburgh
gallery.
Disney deal
THE success of Pocahontas could bring more jobs to Grampian Records of Wick,
which produced 150,000 soundtrack tapes from the film. Disney is to discuss
future contracts with the Caithness factory and the possibility of establishing
a European production centre.
Postal pay offer
MORE than 155,000 Royal Mail delivery and sorting staff are being urged by
their unions to accept an inflation-busting pay offer, revealed yesterday,
worth 3.5%.
Radiator recall
THOUSANDS of oil-filled electric radiators are being withdrawn because they
could catch fire or leak dangerous fumes. The Dimplex radiators in question
were sold mainly through B&amp;Q and Norweb stores and were marked with model
numbers: CR1507, CR2009, CR2009T, and BQ15CR.
Man charged
AN unnamed, 30-year-old Aberdeen man appeared in private at the city's Sheriff
Court yesterday on two sex assault charges against women. The accused made no
plea or declaration and was committed for further examination and remanded in
custody.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Noir behind bars</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Morin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARK, the disturbed husband in Fritz Lang's Secret Beyond the Door, says that
``under certain conditions a room can influence what happens in it''. Mark,
like so many film noir actors, has murder on his mind. As children of Cain, the
voyeurs in the audience have also thought of murder - usually the kind of
seductive murders you get in black and white movies.
On my way to the premire of the Fun Film Club, I came close to killing a cab
driver who accused me of looking like Liz Hurley. ``Aren't you that what's her
face?'' he asked, as we waited in a traffic jam on Park Lane. When he said her
name I reached for my gun, but the lights were too bright. If a lifetime as a
movie junkie has taught me anything, it's that murder needs chiaroscuro.
Impulsive femmes fatales are doomed victims of sexy psychotics in the land of
shadows and secrets.
This Hollywood logic was at the back of my mind when I accepted the job showing
movies to murderers in Wormwood Scrubs. The play list for the Fun Film Club was
up to me. Every Thursday evening from September until December, we'd sit in the
dark together in an atmosphere of tragedy and revelation. After the show, there
would be time to confess to private obsessions with Jean Harlow's hair or
Montgomery Clift's eyes.
The day before I first met my murderers, I went to a 2pm screening of Naked
Kiss in the old cinema in Chinatown. Some people need an excuse to go to the
movies in the afternoon, and that day I had one. I had to decide whether to
start the Fun Film Club with Naked Kiss, or play safe with Reservoir Dogs. My
hands trembled as I bought my ticket. Out of the 40 cinemas in central London,
this one's practically my favourite. It was a good omen having Sam Fuller's
sexiest movie on in the Chinese rep - a place that would give your mum a heart
attack.
The best movies are often on during the day in cinemas frequented by wankers.
I'm the sort of voyeur who feels like taking a hammer to the head of anyone who
talks during a performance, so I have to avoid the OAP popcorn fights in the
Hampstead Everyman and the giggling teenagers in the Warner West End. Chinks on
opium sit through the whole film. China has always been my own private
Hollywood - a fantasy world of Fu Manchu power, Mother Gin-Sling decadence, and
Empress Ming eyeliner.
Naked Kiss had started already when I took my seat in the balcony. Constance
Towers, the actress who plays Kelly the prostitute, is scrutinising her face in
a sunlit mirror. Normally I sit in the stalls, as close as possible to the
screen. As Louis Malle said: ``My kind of cinema is based on the human face''.
But on my way in the manager warned: ``I wouldn't sit down there if I were
you''. He's not me, but I took the hint. I used to go to a cinema like this
when I was supposed to be watching cartoons at the Saturday Club. Mad Moira,
the Rio's usherette, shone her torch erratically in the dark, exposing wankers.
Masturbating men never sit next to me when I say in my Mae West voice: ``Pick
another row or I'll cut your head off and feed it to my dog''. In the dark,
it's impossible to tell if there's an Alsatian under the seat or not.
In Johnny Eager, early period Lana Turner says: ``He'd beat a woman if she made
him mad''. There's a look of longing on her face. She's a descendant of those
destructive heroines Scott Fitzgerald invented, disgusted and enthralled by
their dangerous glamour. Girls who ``had never, all along, intended doing
anything at all''; other than being too gorgeous to live.
Kelly in Naked Kiss is an unusual heroine. At the start of the film, she's
beating her pimp's brains in. In 90 minutes of tabloid action, Kelly gives up
prostitution for nursing; murders her millionaire child-molesting fiance; and
is imprisoned and released, ready to seduce another day.
Critics who deride Fuller's B-movie brutality underestimate the unique talent
involved in revealing a picture both decadent and pure. Constance Towers - an
actress I've only ever seen in Fuller movies - has the tainted purity of
Marilyn Monroe, the ironic intelligence of Marlene Dietrich, and the convincing
goodness of Audrey Hepburn. Kelly is that rare thing - a femme fatale who
survives, smiling.
Even in real life, the Hollywood goddesses are gone. Often deranged or
destitute before they died, at least they had the decency to drift into
obscurity first. Garbo stayed in her Manhattan apartment so that she could be
celebrated as a celluloid memory. Ava Gardner suffered insomnia in a flat
overlooking Hyde Park. Dietrich stayed in bed, alone, in Paris.
One fallen star remains, alive and obese, to symbolise those distorted
illusions lurking at the edge of MGM's soundstages. It's a long time since
large Liz has been beatific, but the evidence is there for anyone who can bear
to watch Taylor in A Place in the Sun. Incestuously cast with Montgomery Clift,
young superLiz is at her most ravishing. While watching her play Angela
Vicerks, it's almost possible to forget the bloated picture of her on the cover
of Hollywood Babylon.
The superficial intimacy between the audience and actors disintegrates when the
lights go back on. At the end of Naked Kiss, I still wasn't sure whether I
could risk showing it to the murderers. I might go berserk if they didn't like
it. Stumbling out into the rain, I walked from the Chinese cinema to the chapel
in Soho to light a candle. There was a leaflet left over from Cantonese mass -
a good omen.
After endless costume rehearsals, I decided to wear a Grace Kelly dress with a
solemn cardigan to my first Fun Film Club.
When I arrived at the prison everything seemed familiar. Passing through the
photogenic gates, recognisable from Ealing movies, I thought about that long
lineage of charismatic clever psychostars - from Cary Grant in Suspicion, to
Bob de Niro in Taxi Driver.
But, as Rita Hayworth said: ``Men go to bed with Gilda and they wake up with
me''. None of the murderers who slouched into the cramped screening room
adjoining a toilet was a dead ringer for Travis Bickle. Rather than tall, dark
and dangerous, they were alarmingly timid, with complexions which had never
benefited from broccoli.
A man with a stammer who bears a passing resemblance to Dr Lecter asked: ``Are
we seeing Superman?'' Dr Lecter's glamour comes from his intelligence, not his
pasty smile. This murderer is hot for films where, ``You know, people get hurt
but it isn't real''. I explained that actors rarely kill each other, but he
didn't get the joke. ``You don't understand,'' Dr Lecter said, ``in Superman
everybody really loves each other, really.''
I had two tapes in my bag and neither of them were Superman. A rave gangster in
the back row switched out the fluorescent light. I pressed play, and the
Reservoir Dogs gang appeared. The murderer on my right was eating smoky bacon
crisps. The murderer on my left had a carton of Ribena he offered to share.
After the show, I looked up my fellow voyeurs in the prison filing cabinet. The
babyish writing of Smoky Bacon's psychiatrist was scrawled in the margin of the
faded typewritten report: ``He is sorry''. Smoky Bacon battered a baby to death
with a hammer. Not his baby, just somebody's baby. But that's OK, because he's
sorry now. The psychiatrist is pleased.
Ribena, on the other hand, doesn't see what he's got to be sorry about. Ribena
stabbed a girl he didn't know 36 times, which reminds me of weepy Joan Fontaine
in Rebecca when she says: ``I wish I was 36 and wearing black velvet with a
string of pearls''.
There's something disturbing about leaving a movie before the end, even when
you've lost interest in the plot. At the Fun Film Club, I played the part of
Catwoman - verbally scratching anyone who didn't like my favourite films. But
the show didn't go on. I couldn't face finishing the season. Murder, like so
many things, is much more fun on-screen than it is in real life.
The movies have always been there for me, when I want them and when I need
them. I couldn't bear to have the purity of voyeuring soiled by seeing too many
movies with murderers. I'd rather sit in the dark with the devil I don't know.
The most universally accessible medium the world has ever known is 100 years
old. From the first flickering, jerky figures, through the heyday of Hollywood
to the hi-tech glamour of today, cinema has reached into and touched the dreams
of kings and commoners. In a
special issue this week, Weekend Extra takes up a
position behind the camera to celebrate the magic of
the movies. For the first reel Carole Morin, an addict who has braved some
seedy joints in pursuit of her
passion, appears in a dramatic episode at the
Fun Film Club in Wormwood Scrubs
</TEXT>
