<HEADLINE>Henry rekindles dreams of golden glory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE'S been there, done that and has even got the T-shirt - Commonwealth Games,
Auckland, 1990 - to prove it. But Peter Henry, older, wiser and amazed by the
lack of opposition, is now ready for a second coming as a Scottish
international swimmer.
This weekend he begins his serious challenge to return to the fold at the
Scottish Winter Championships at Ayr. He has entered six events, and his sights
are firmly set on claiming gold in the 50m and 100m butterfly.
It is six years since he last appeared at Scotland's flagship short-course meet
- and much has happened in the interim.
Following the 1990 Commonwealth Games, Henry headed from Dunoon to the
University of New Mexico in Albuquerque on a swimming scholarship. But mid-way
through his five-year double major degree in Law and History, he opted out of
sport.
``I was completely burned out,'' he explained. ``I had been in competitive
swimming since I was 10, and I had had more than enough.
``There is a lot of pressure when you're swimming for a US college team.
They've invested a lot of money in you, and if you swim badly, you're in
trouble. It just got too much.''
But he is quick to stress that he has no regrets. He has secured a good degree
and he admits: ``It was a great life experience. I got to travel, and had a lot
of fun.''
His only regret is that he did not have a real go at making the 1992 Olympic
Games. ``The trials were a week after my finals. I hadn't prepared properly,
and I didn't perform.''
Henry, now 24, returned to Scotland at the start of this year, and filled in
some spare time with the odd visit to Dunoon pool. He entered the West District
Championships in March and, to his amazement, won the butterfly.
``I couldn't believe it,'' he said. ``With hardly any training, I was the best
in the West. It is a sad reflection on the state of Scottish swimming. It's not
very competitive, and the standard has certainly fallen during my years away.''
He then spent a couple of months in New Zealand, and trained with former
Warrender coach, Kim Swanwick, at the Jasi Club near Christchurch. ``He's one
of the most talented coaches I've ever worked under. It's just a pity Scotland
lost him,'' commented Henry.
This season, he has continued his successful comeback at the West Open
Championships, and at the world-class Cumbernauld International Meet last month
he was the leading Scot, finishing a creditable sixth in the 100m butterfly in
58sec.
Suitably encouraged, he has stepped up his training, and has been working out
in the gym in readiness for this weekend.
He's also hoping that it will be a week of double celebration following recent
applications for accountancy traineeships. ``I've got as far as second
interviews, so I'm keeping my fingers crossed that I'll have a job by the end
of the week.''
While his career will take priority, he is equally set on adding to his
swimming credentials. ``I've always loved competing, and it would be nice to
get back into the Scottish squad.''
And how about a trip to Kuala Lumpur for the 1998 Commonwealth Games? ``It will
depend on work, but it's a nice thought,'' he agreed.
However, his ambitions remain realistic. He made friends with the former world
No.1, Tom Jager, during his time in the US, and admitted: ``I am never likely
to get anywhere near his standard.''
His time in America also made him starkly aware of the deficiencies in Scottish
swimming. ``The amount of money ploughed into the US college sport is
unbelievable. We had two Olympic-size pools and wonderful training facilities
at New Mexico.''
At Ayr, he aims to prove the benefit of that background, and force the Scottish
selectors to welcome him back.
