<HEADLINE>Public image of farmers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER reaction about the risk of contracting BSE from eating beef is
completely irrational given the available facts, yet beef sales are down
considerably, setting in motion a huge chain reaction down the line.
Even the store sales from crofters and hill farmers will be affected despite
the excellent product they produce.
As a means of getting killed, eating beef is less risky than driving a car,
climbing in the Glencoe hills, or even having sex. In fact, winning the lottery
is easier than contracting BSE for the simple reason that there is no record of
anyone being affected.
What is at stake is not the scientific facts but the public image of the farmer
as seen by a remote urban consumer.
Until now, the farming industry has not worried about its public image
preferring instead to concentrate on maximising production through the use of
high quality feeds and hormones which are a far cry from traditional methods.
Yet the consumer is attracted to those traditional methods whether classed as
``organic farming'' or ``sustainable farming.'' The label is all!
If the beef industry is to win back some of the ground lost to public reaction,
it must concentrate on traditional quality before permanent damage is done to
the industry.
For that reason, it is encouraging that the Scottish Agricultural Colleges are
conducting experiments at Craibstone and Morayshire on the production of
Aberdeen Angus beef on a sustainable farming basis.
These experiments, at least, give some hope for the future.
Hector J MacInnes,
50 Inshes Crescent,
Inverness.
Public image of farmers
</TEXT>
