<HEADLINE>Witnesses' church gets in way of festive lights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Jehovah's Witnesses have blocked a plan to brighten up Christmas in Lanark.
Civic leaders wanted to put on a dazzling display of lights after last year's
show was widely criticised. They planned to string them on shop fronts up and
down the High Street.
However, the cable had to run along the side of the Jehovah's Witness Kingdom
Hall near the top of the street.
When the council requested permission to use the church wall, it was refused.
``We don't celebrate Christmas. We don't want the cable along our church
wall,'' said Mr Jack Bell, who is in charge of the church, and known as the
presiding overseer.
Planners had to string up special lighting features on lampposts running down
the centre of the street, and a tree with lights in front of St Nicholas Parish
Church.
In the ensuing row on the issue, Mr Bell blames Clydesdale District Council for
leaking his name.
He said: ``All we asked is that they respect the sanctity of the church. It is
a consecrated building.
``Nobody has made a complaint about it to us. We don't believe in Christmas. We
believe it is a pagan festival. As far as I'm concerned, it is a matter of
confidentiality, between myself and the congregation.
``I feel that this is now a breach of confidence.
``The council asked us very politely if they could pin the lights to our
Kingdom Hall.
``In all senses of the word, it is a church so we felt it could not be done
because it was a commercial venture.''
However, Ms Janice Plenderleith, 50, of Wright's Florists, in Well Gate, summed
up many shopkeepers' feelings when she said: ``It's really mean.
``They don't like Christmas, so no-one else is going to. I think it is Scroogy.
I don't think they have got the right to force other people into it.
``We have been fighting for these lights for years, and now look what happens.''
Mr James Alexander, 56, a local butcher, said: ``It shows a very unchristian
attitude.
``I respect other people's religious beliefs but it's not right that people
should suffer because they don't believe in Christmas.''
Mr Robert Aitken, chairman of Lanark Merchants' Association, said: ``We were
trying to bring more shoppers to town with a great display of lights. The more
attractive the town looks, the more shoppers come.
``We were trying to overcome last year's lighting display which was a bit
pathetic.''
He said he had spoken to local people who told him that if Jehovah's Witnesses
``knock on their doors they'll get a heck of row''.
Last year, townsfolk were angry that the Christmas lights display consisted
merely of an unsightly yellow cable with lights draped around one tree in the
main street.
Clydesale district last night declined to comment on the row.
</TEXT>
