<HEADLINE>Footprints of dispossession</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864416</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIRGINIA Ryan Izzo says, in a matter-of-fact way: ``Series are perfect for
people who have to move around a lot. They give continuity.'' As the Australian
wife of an Italian diplomat, with two children and postings to Egypt, Brazil,
Belgrade, Rome, and Edinburgh over the past dozen years, she has experienced
both the good and bad of a peripatetic life - and learned how to put down roots
fast. Now after three years in Edinburgh where she and husband Giancarlo Izzo,
Consul-General of Italy, quickly became well-known and loved, they say farewell
next week, to return - for a while at least - to Rome.
Izzo takes with her a postgraduate diploma in art therapy (``I don't know when
I'll next be in an English-speaking country, so I decided to get my
qualifications here!'') but leaves a beautiful studio at the very top of their
huge New Town house.
``Giancarlo doesn't comment on my painting or interfere. He says `It's your
world'. But he's always made sure, when house hunting, that I have a studio.
This is a great room with top lighting, a Victorian iron fireplace, and superb
views of Edinburgh Castle. I even have a balcony! The studio is strangely bare
now. I had a whole wall full of pictures by friends but that's already been
packed away. It's as though I'm divorcing myself from Edinburgh bit by bit.''
Her large canvases were shipped home in the summer - before she was offered her
current farewell show. However, she had plenty of smaller abstracted paintings
and some large banners - plus her kitchen chair. I first saw her Chair of
Endless Wandering in her solo exhibition at Demarco's Festival show. On the
seat is a circle of chains. ``It's a rest-less chair, with no place to just sit
and be.'' Written all over it in white on black in tiny obsessive handwriting
are the words: ``Nowhere to call my home. My feet need to sit and rest''.
Although she is known as a painter, she began by studying photography at
Canberra's National Art School, so, coming full circle, she installed and
photographed the chair in Gullane; at Glasgow's St Mary's Cathedral during
Mayfest, at Edinburgh's 369 Gallery, and in her back garden among the autumn
leaves. ``In early 1996 I will photograph it under an olive tree in Trevi, at
my new home in Umbria. It will bridge the gap.''
Izzo's travels started young. Her fluent Italian dates from primary school days
in Rome when her father worked there. Diplomacy has connotations of the exotic,
of parties and high life, of jetting across the world to be met by stretch
limos and bouquets. Yet it does have its down-side. Although it would be wrong
to use an extreme word like exile, since her time in Belgrade during
Yugoslavia's war-torn 1990s, Izzo's art has been preoccupied with journeying
and with ``those who cannot go home''.
Empathising with victims of the Balkans conflict, she first produced a volume
of sketches, Sarajevo: Book of Secret Entries; then a series of painted wooden
discs, one for each year of her life; and then at the Edinburgh Festival in
1993, Home Europe, an installation where she turned a small, stone,
barrel-vaulted cellar into a shrine as a homage. ``Shovelling out years of
rubbish in the cold and damp, I realised I was acting out what is reality for
so many in the Balkans - with the cruel difference that I could leave and take
refuse in warmth and comfort.''
Journeying, dislocation, dispossession, migration, boundaries, and sanctuary
have continued to be her main themes which she explores via a vocabulary of
motifs. ``I use a limited number of images: eyes, hands, footprints, flowers,
the outline or frame of a basilica, spirals, barbed-wire and silhouette
figures.'' Pattern and texture are important, and always have been. ``I also
studied printmaking and surface marks are integral to my work.''
If all this makes Izzo sound a too-serious-person, let me put you straight.
There's another side which artist Edith Simon caught ``to a T'' in her portrait
of her dancing. The Izzos give memorable parties, enhanced by Virginia's
ability to be formal - or to let her hair down. ``It's the Italian side of my
personality!''
Izzo also has the ability to jump in at the deep end and engage people in her
projects. In 1994 she decided to make a series (that word again) of
six-metre-long painted banners inspired by four poems from Klaonica, Poems for
Bosnia: laments for refugees, dead children and lovers, which express grief for
a devastated country.
These were shown during the Edinburgh Festival at the Tron Kirk. Adrian Henri
was one of the poets, so she wrote to him. The upshot was that Henri came to
read his poems in the kirk surrounded by her red and black banners with their
outlines of fallen bodies and confused patterns of barbed wire which can also
turn into a field of flowers.
Though phrases from the poems are incorporated into the banners. Izzo likes
text in her work: paradiso, power, fiume di sangue, tempesto, life, love, often
in Italian and English, some inscribed backwards as in a stream of
consciousness. ``I sometimes work to music. The text is like a mantra.'' The
banners are not literal narratives, but an artist's response to the elegiac
tone of the poems, each with its own visual force field. The central imagery is
fenced in by a border of tyre tracks or watchful eyes (derived from the
Egyptians' love of outlined eyes as a protective talisman) resulting in a
meditative rather than a terrifying or repulsive image. ``The frame is about
containing; not letting my world fragment or break,'' she explains.
Brooding - not screaming. That was Izzo's way in Yugoslavia - and as if not to
forget that strife in the calm of Edinburgh, her house is plastered with her
pictures from different periods, different countries.
The discs were a result of living in Brazil, seen partly as an autobiography or
diary, partly a tribute to the native people and the late rubber-trapper, Chico
Mendez. Called Foresta (The Forest) they contain animals, figures, hammers,
arrows, and pathways, painted in a pointillist method using decorative dots, in
the style of Aboriginal art. ``It's as though each dot tells a mysterious
story.'' The discs were also part of a musical collaboration with Nigel Osborne
and Edinburgh postgraduates.
Izzo began painting by default. ``My photography was always manipulated, always
hand-generated. I applied very thin veils or layers over the image. I suppose I
still paint that way. Anyway I was spending eight hours a day in the darkroom,
and I got ill. The doctor said `get outside' - so I did and till recently,
never went back!
``I'm no longer apologetic about my lack of academic training in painting. I
tend to learn by doing; by experience. It's taken 20 years and the longer I go
on, the more simplified my work becomes. I've never been particularly narrative
or figurative. The cross over into semi-abstraction was always there. A sense
of immediacy is my main concern. To feel something - in at the heart, down
through the arm and out on to the paper or canvas. To me, that's what it's
about.''
To see Izzo explain her art in these three short, swift gestures - incisive,
direct, determined, vigorous - is to know that she will continue with her
commitment to art, and store up her memories of her ``northern exposure'' to
enrich her work in years to come.
n Virginia Izzo's exhibition is at Edinburgh's Italian Cultural Institute,
Nicolson Street, till January 12.
Clare Henry meets a well-travelled artist whose work has become possessed by
journeying and images of those who cannot return home
</TEXT>
