<HEADLINE>AAA door closes to foreigners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864417</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS:
FOR more than 100 years the AAA Championships have been open to foreigners, but
in the interest of picking the best Olympic team, next year's event will be
closed.
Only athletes eligible for Britain and Northern Ireland in Atlanta will be
allowed to enter, the AAA of England said yesterday. The decision salvages the
credibility of Dave Cropper whose tenure of both the chairmanship of the AAA
and UK selection committee looked incompatible.
The presence of overseas athletes often prevented top Britons reaching finals,
denying them the chance of making UK teams.
q ONLY four of the original East team for today's Inter-area cross-country
match at Cumbernauld survive: Dave Ross, Ken Chapman, Peter Dymoke and Martin
Ferguson. Some defectors have joined Scott Cohen in a protest at the course,
deeming it dangerous.
Missing are last year's winner Dave Cavers, Glen Stewart, and Frank McGowan,
but Stewart McCrae, who sets the trail for Cumbernauld and Kilsyth Council,
denies rocks make the course hazardous. ``Heavy,'' he concedes, and will accept
adjectives such as ``relentless'' and ``challenging.''
In his day ploughed fields, raging burns and barbed wire fences were the norm.
``Athletes are not clones of some idealistic robolete . . . what's happened to
the men.''
West should take the men's title, but despite the West's defending Vikki
McPherson, East women may prove too strong.
</TEXT>
