<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Freeze frames</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864418</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE advent of the video recorder has enabled film lovers to indulge their
obsession more than ever. Not only does it mean that film fans can now possess
their favourite movies, but also it allows them to watch them when the mood
takes them, and not when the TV schedule dictates. Some of the best movies -
especially thrillers - never have the same impact as the first time they're
seen; others can withstand, and often benefit from, multiple viewings. This
guide lists 30 films which are essential to any self-respecting film lover's
collection. Two criteria qualify the movies for this guide: they are all
available to buy on video, and they're all wonderful.
n.Annie Hall: Hilarious Woody Allen film about a neurotic TV writer (Allen) and
his various relationships: especially with the title character (Diane Keaton).
(1977)
n.The Apartment: Perfect Hogmanay viewing. Jack Lemmon stars as a lowly
insurance clerk whose apartment is used by various of his superiors to
entertain their lady friends. Billy Wilder's film is touching, hilarious and
downright brilliant. (1960)
n.Arsenic and Old Lace: Two spritely old spinster sisters enjoy a quiet life
poisoning lonely gentlemen callers until two of their nephews gatecrash the
set-up. Frank Capra's marvellously manic comedy has a glorious cast of comic
characters led by Cary Grant. (1942)
n.Born Yesterday: Sparkling comedy about a would-be corrupt politician whose
dazzlingly dizzy girlfriend (Judy Holliday) falls in love with the journalist
(William Holden) he's hired to make her more ``couth''. (1950)
n.Breakfast at Tiffany's: Not a great film but one with bags (Givenchy of
course) of style - the super-sophisticated Audrey Hepburn, gorgeous George
Peppard, and a beautiful, Oscar-winning song - Moon River. (1961)
n.Casablanca: One of the most romantic movies ever made. Humphrey Bogart and
Ingrid Bergman try to sort out their love lives while Sam plays As Time Goes By
(again). (1942)
n.Gentlemen Prefer Blondes: Glamour galore as Marilyn Monroe and Jane Russell
star as two girls on a manhunt in this often overlooked musical that features
songs such as Diamonds are a Girl's Best Friend. (1953)
n.Gigi: Delightful Lerner &amp; Loewe musical set in the 1900s, about a gauche
teenager (Leslie Caron) maturing into an elegant young woman - under the nose
of Paris's most eligible bachelor, Louis Jourdan. (1958)
n.The Grapes of Wrath: John Ford's beautifully filmed adaptation of John
Steinbeck's moving novel about Oklahoma farmers heading for California is one
of the greatest films of all time. Henry Fonda stars. (1940)
n.Great Expectations: David Lean's stunning film is the most atmospheric of any
version of the Dickens novel (largely because of Guy Green's cinematography),
and arguably the greatest example of British cinema. John Mills is the older
Pip, Alec Guinness is Herbert Pocket and Martita Hunt is an eerily memorable
Miss Havisham. (1946)
n.Hannah and Her Sisters: Mia Farrow, Dianne Weist and Barbara Hershey star as
sisters in this wonderful, warm Woody Allen film which is just the thing to
watch over Christmas since it's all about families. (1986)
n.Harvey: James Stewart stars as harmless dipsomaniac Elwood P Dowd, whose best
pal is a six-foot rabbit called Harvey, and whose mortified sister wants to
have the pair of them committed. (1950)
n.High Society: Frank Sinatra, Grace Kelly, Bing Crosby, Louis Armstrong and
the Cole Porter score are the reasons for investing in this remake of The
Philadelphia Story. (1956)
n.His Girl Friday: Frantically paced screwball comedy stars the acid-tongued
Rosalind Russell as an ace reporter who - at editor (and ex-husband) Cary
Grant's request - postpones her wedding for the scoop of the century. (1940)
n.It's a Wonderful Life: Capra's Christmas classic is guaranteed to warm the
coldest of hearts. James Stewart stars as a small-town businessman who wishes
he'd never been born when he finds himself on the brink of bankruptcy on
Christmas Eve. Step in his guardian angel, a gentle and simple soul called
Clarence Oddbody, who shows him how his town would have been had he never
lived. Remember: No man is a failure who has friends. (1946)
n.Manhattan: Black and white masterpiece from Woody Allen about (you've guessed
it) a neurotic writer's relationships: especially with the title character. And
it's all set to a glorious Gershwin score. (1979)
n.Meet Me In St Louis: Wonderful musical set against the St Louis World Fair of
1903 stars Judy Garland and is a joy from start to finish. Songs include The
Trolley Song and Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas. (1944)
n.Mr Smith Goes to Washington: Capra's joyous social comedy-drama about a young
innocent triumphing over corrupt senators. James Stewart and Jean Arthur top a
superb cast. (1939)
n.My Darling Clementine: Best western ever. Henry Fonda stars as the legendary
Wyatt Earp in John Ford's lyrical version of events leading up to the famous
gunfight at the OK Corral. (1946)
n.A Night at the Opera: The Marx Brothers wreak havoc over an opera company in
this, their most consistently funny film. Only the musical scenes drag, and
that's when the fast forward button comes into its own. (1935)
n.On Moonlight Bay: Doris Day stars as a tomboy in love with boy-next-door
Gordon MacRae in this charming, and wholly entertaining, piece of Americana.
Followed by the equally enjoyable By the Light of the Silvery Moon. (1951)
n.Pal Joey: All-star version of John O'Hara's book. Rita Hayworth slinks, Kim
Novak pouts and Frank Sinatra croons jazzily - the Rodgers and Hart score
includes Lady is a Tramp and Bewitched. (1957)
n.The Philadelphia Story: Sophisticated comedy about a spoilt divorcee
(Katharine Hepburn) on the verge of remarriage, who won't admit that she still
loves her dashing ex-husband (Cary Grant). Oscar-winning Jimmy Stewart also
stars. (1940)
n.Pride and Prejudice: Forget your busty BBC version, this is the best:
Laurence Olivier as Darcy; Greer Garson as Elizabeth and a gem of a cast of MGM
character actors. (1940)
n.Raiders of the Lost Ark: Fabulous, action-packed romp is the first and best
of the Indiana Jones trilogy. Harrison Ford stars as the
archeologist-cum-adventurer. (1981)
n.Roman Holiday: Lovely romance about a beautiful young princess (Audrey
Hepburn) who escapes her guardians while on a state visit to Rome, and winds up
falling in love with an opportunist American reporter (Gregory Peck). (1953)
n.Scrooge: Alastair Sim is Ebenezer Scrooge in this unsurpassable version of
the Dickens classic which should be required viewing for any potential humbugs
over Christmas. (1951)
n.Sleepless in Seattle: Charmingly old-fashioned comedy-romance stars Meg Ryan
as the girl who falls in love with a widower (Tom Hanks) after hearing his
story on the radio. (1993)
n.Some Like It Hot: Brilliant comedy from Billy Wilder about two musicians
(Jack Lemmon and Tony Curtis) who join an all-girls' band while on the run from
dangerous gangsters. Marilyn Monroe is hilarious as the band's singer, Sugar
Kane. (1959)
n.When Harry Met Sally: Another Hogmanay must-watch. Heavily influenced by
Woody Allen's Annie Hall (itself a recommendation), this is a romantic comedy
about a couple who can't stand each other. Meg Ryan was never kookier and Billy
Crystal was never so bearable. (1989)
The video is now a universal possession, allowing
movie buffs to wallow in the romance, the glory
and the adventure of their own must-see films.
Alison Kerr selects 30 of her all-time celluloid greats
</TEXT>
