<HEADLINE>Bid for funding to build tall ship</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864419</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS group is hoping to regenerate shipbuilding on the Clyde and create a
jobs spin-off for Inverclyde into the next century . . . by turning the clock
back more than 100 years.
The Scottish Maritime Sailing Trust is trying to raise funding for a
Clyde-built tall-masted ship and hopes that Operation Dreamboat, its submission
to the Millennium Commission, will get the project started.
Inverclyde District Council has given its support in principle to the trust's
bid for #3.5m - half of the proposed cost - from Millennium fund chiefs.
If the ambitious project succeeds, it could give a welcome long-term jobs boost
to the Greenock area.
The trust, in partnership with Renfrewshire Enterprise, has approached the
commission to seek funding, and been asked to submit more detailed information
on the proposal.
The Scottish partnership wants to build a vessel in the biggest of the tall
ships classes, along the lines of the Winston Churchill and Malcolm Miller,
accommodating up to 40 trainees and 10 full-time crew on each voyage. It hopes
to build it in time for the 1999 Tall Ships Race.
With all of the required expertise available locally, the hull could be built
at the Ferguson's yard and fitting out completed at either Scott's dry dock or
the East India harbour.
In a report on the proposal to be discussed by councillors in Greenock next
week, recreation services chief Ian Douglas says there could be a long-term
jobs spin-off if the scheme was approved.
He said: ``Initially, the project would offer training opportunities and, once
built, the vessel could be used as an ambassador for Inverclyde. It would also
be a visitor attraction when in dock.
``The trust is confident there will be ongoing work if a new ship-building
facility is developed.''
Trust members are now involved in a major fund-raising exercise in a bid to
show the Millennium Commission that they can match the money sought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
