Skiing
GERMANY'S Katja Seizinger recorded her first World Cup downhill victory in
almost two years yesterday, ending American Picabo Street's streak of
consecutive wins. Olympic champion Seizinger collected her eighteenth career
victory in the World Cup and her first downhill win in 21 months in St Anton,
Austria.
Over the two legs of the downhill, a format forced on the organisers by lack of
snow at the top of the Kandahar slope, Seizinger recorded a combined time of
2min.6.68sec.
Fastest in the first leg, Seizinger carried an advantage of 0.20 seconds over
Heidi Zurbriggen going into the second run. The German posted the third-best
time on her second trip down the 1700m course with 1-03.46, and that was enough
to leave her comfortably in front of Zurbriggen.
Golf
ANTHONY Gilligan and Shane Robinson, of Australia, shared the second-round lead
in the Coolum Classic in Queenland yesterday after the big names crashed out.
Ian Baker-Finch, Peter O'Malley, Lucas Parsons, and Terry Price missed the
halfway cut of 148, while Craig Parry survived by one shot. Leading scores
(Australian unless stated):
138 - S Robinson 69, 69; A Gilligan 67, 71. 139 - S Leaney 72, 67. 140 - J
Evans 71, 69; S Alker (New Zealand) 70, 70; B Jackson (England) 70, 70.
SCOTLAND'S Simon Yates shot a second-round 73, one over par, for a halfway
aggregate of 149 to lie 11 adrift of Indian leader Jeev Milkha Singh in the
$200,000 Philippine Classic.
Tennis
STEFFI Graf has been ruled out of next month's Australian Open after having
undergone an operation for a chipped bone in her left foot.
ROSS Matheson beat Tom Hand 6-3, 6-4 to reach the last four of the Reebok
British Tour event in Corby. The Scottish No.2 then went down 6-2, 6-3 against
Paul Hand, who faces British No.3 Chris Wilkinson in today's final.
IVAN Lendl, who never won Wimbledon during his 18-year career, has been made an
honorary member of the All England Club.
Boxing
GARY Jacobs has been given the chance to win back his European welterweight
title. The Glaswegian gave up the belt to concentrate on winning the WBC title,
but was beaten by champion Pernell Whittaker in August.
Now the European Boxing Union have ordered their champion, Patrick Charpentier,
to make his next mandatory defence against 30-year-old Jacobs, with February 24
set as the closing date for purse bids.
MAURICE Core's bid to join the elite gang of three Britons who have won
post-war world light-heavyweight titles has been scuppered by flu. The
30-year-old Manchester fighter has been unable to shake off the bug, which has
forced his withdrawal from tonight's Hamburg meeting with Germany's unbeaten
WBO holder Dariusz Michalczewski. No new date has been set.
Meanwhile Commonwealth light-heavyweight champion Nicky Piper will replace Core
as challenger for Crawford Ashley's British title, with both fighters' belts at
stake. The British Boxing Board of Control have sanctioned a second meeting
between the pair, with a purse bid deadline of January 5, following Core's
withdrawal last month to concentrate on the now postponed Michalczewski clash.
Equestrianism
LUDGER Beerbaum warmed up for a repeat raid on the Olympia championship's big
prizes with a second-day victory at the London show. But the Olympic champion's
triumph in the Christmas Stocking Stakes with the nine-year-old, Avion, owed a
lot to a crucial mistake by Michael Whitaker on his first-day winner, My
Mesieur.
Whitaker clocked the best time in a contest decided by the fastest clear. But
he just clipped the first section of the two final doubles to rule himself out.
Beerbaum, with his inexperienced young partner, avoided errors to claim the
first place.
Brazilian Rodrigo Pessoa picked up the biggest prize of the first two days as
British riders missed their chance last night.
The 23-year-old Pessoa, riding Loro Piana Rose Garden, won a nine-horse
jump-off to collect the #5000 prize in the Eurosport Christmas Pudding Stakes.
He had the fastest of three clear rounds, but his time was beaten by all three
British riders - Nick Skelton, Robert Smith and John Whitaker - who each had a
fence down.
Curling
Greenacres. Henderson Bishop: Final - R Biggart 10, S Loudon 5.
Summit Centre. Glasgow Ladies Curling Club Pairs Final - Mrs A MacDougall and
Mrs W McCallum beat Mrs C Kerr and Miss A Calder 4.
Rugby league
SCOTLAND'S students were beaten 23-6 by France at Meadowbank Stadium last night.
