John Linklater sighs
deeply over the loss to moviemaking of Louise Brooks, the star who was too big
for Hollywood
AS a movie actress Louise Brooks was a wonderful aberration. Even more than
Garbo, whom she comprehensively out-Garboed, her face is recognised today
mainly from still photographs; familiar through her black-bobbed hairstyle more
than her features, beautiful though they remain. She has an incandescence that
far outlasts her career.
All but a few of her 24 films are lost forever. Only two deserve mention,
Pandora's Box and Diary Of A Lost Girl, both made with director G W Pabst in
Berlin in the late 1920s. They were silents. The sound of her voice is only a
matter of conjecture, alongside the testimonies of a select few who actually
knew her before she became a recluse, particularly lovers from Charlie Chaplin
to Humphrey Bogart and John Wayne.
This appears to present her as the ultimate groupie, yet nothing could be
further from the truth. She detested Hollywood. Anita Loos said, with as little
trace of bitchiness as understanding of what gentlemen genuinely admire, that
Louise's favourite form of exercise was walking off a film lot. Sometimes with
her favourite stuntman. Yet had Louise acceded to the casting couch manoeuvres
routinely proposed by producers and directors, her career would have been
easier. It might not have extended much beyond 1929 when, at the age of 23,
Louise more or less told the industry to stuff itself, but at the level of
personal politics she would have suffered less acrimony.
Had she chosen, Louise could have gone on to become as big (except that she was
five foot two, and wore six-inch heels to shoot scenes) as her direct
contemporaries Joan Crawford, Bette Davis and Katharine Hepburn. There are only
two years separating their birth dates between 1906 and 1908. This comes as a
shock, because the surviving photographs of Louise seem to quarantine her as a
silent goddess, a gagged flapper never heard in the talkies. That was her
choice. Compared to female product leads of the 1990s, identikit babes on
screen, interchangeable, unmemorable and depressingly unerotic, Crawford,
Davis, and Hepburn seem to represent an era when women stars were defiantly
their own women. Alongside Louise they were three amenable pussycats.
When in 1978 Kenneth Tynan tracked her down in Rochester, New York State,
Louise claimed never once to have seen any of her own films, or at least never
seen one sober. By then she was crippled by arthritis, zimmer-bound, never
venturing out of her flat, her hollowed face ravaged by an assiduous
partnership with gin, and her mind still sharp from a lifetime reading Proust,
Dostoevsky and Schopenhauer, a literary taste confirmed long after it had been
queried as a mere publicity stunt. In his essay Tynan is flattered enough to
divulge that Louise made a spirited pass at him, and dutifully reports that her
favourite lovers were English. Tragic that even such an experienced beauty
should reveal so culturally stunted a preference.
When Louise died 10 years ago a strong cult had already formed around her name,
at least partly encouraged by Tynan's efforts on behalf of her critical
rehabilitation. Certainly, little from her own. To the end, nobody was less
interested in the success of Louise Brooks than Louise herself. The only dream
she had ever entertained was to become a great dancer, for which she had been
training since childhood in south-east Kansas.
It was to improve her dance stage appearance that her mother had supervised the
cropping of her long black braids into the pair of sleek parentheses that
contained her still freckled face. Dance had secured her escape from Wichita
and brought her to New York. She was a speciality dancer with the Ziegfeld
Follies in 1925 when she signed her first film contract.
Louise had not been seeking a movie career. So unestablished was the industry
that she, in common with many, dismissed ``the flickers'' (``the movies'' only
caught on later) as an ephemeral sideshow. Paramount was still conveniently
based at its Astoria Studios on Long Island, otherwise she would never have
agreed to the capering diversion with which she treated her screen test. It was
her fate to possess a genius of which she, and anybody else, could not possibly
be aware up until that point. ``She is the intelligence of the cinematic
process, the perfect incarnation of that which is photogenic,'' Henri Langlois,
director of the Cinemathque Francaise, would describe it decades later. Louise
had stumbled into something she would never understand, or forgive.
``Pawed and applauded by millions of idiots,'' was H L Mencken's caustic
valediction on Rudolph Valentino, an unhappy man bewildered by an adulation and
success that he felt was controlling him. His sudden death in 1926 might have
confirmed all of Louise's instinctive distrust of this strange new phenomenon
with which she was cohabiting, but her exposure to Hollywood itself was delayed
until 1927, by which time she was being heavily promoted as one of Paramount's
``university'' of rising stars. The ``younger degeneration'', she called it.
Louise's problem in Hollywood was her fierce intelligence. She had a loner
streak. Strong independence had been encouraged by a mother who, frankly, had
made it clear she never intended to be over-burdened by her children. Louise
grew up feisty, speaking her mind. And her mind was ill-disposed to fools,
fawners, corporate bullies, see-through blouses of either sex and the
collective miasma of an industry geared to the mass-production of dreams.
Temperamentally, she was strictly and disdainfully insomniac.
``Hollywood is like floating through a sewer in a glass-bottomed boat,'' she
wrote half a century later. Even so, she survived three years of a five-year
contract with Paramount. In later life she had difficulty even remembering some
of the correct titles, but she made 14 films by 1928. She had also made a name
and created an image. She was the ``girl in the black helmet'', and her
trademark bob was discussed in film and fashion magazines. It was a hairstyle
for fast living. Not every single little breeze might be whispering ``Louise'',
but there was enough word out on her for the public to imagine it was Brooks
that Maurice Chevalier was singing about when Innocents of Paris was released
in 1929. That was also the year she got herself abruptly blacklisted by the
studios.
The final confrontation was Louise's giving Paramount the silent treatment when
they wanted to talk sound. She had co-starred with William Powell in making a
silent detective mystery, The Canary Murder Case, which the studio wanted to
commercialise by grafting on a soundtrack. It was at that stage in the history
of the movies when the talkies had arrived to stay. To everyone's astonishment,
Louise refused. She had previously been in dispute over a proposed cut in her
contract (in common with most studio stars as the talkies arrived), but now
every increased offer from Paramount was rejected. ``Come back, or you'll never
work in Hollywood again,'' was the final ultimatum. That was too leading a
cliche to resist. She was Louise Brooks. She was virtually programmed to reply
as she did: ``Who wants to work in Hollywood?''
She cut off her tongue to spite her face. The short-term satisfaction might
even have been worth the consequences, but there would be no way back. Critics
ridiculed the clumsy dubbing of Louise (by Margaret Livingston) for the release
of Canary, and Paramount retaliated by planting damaging stories that Louise's
voice was no use for the talkies. There was no truth in this, except Louise had
made herself non-negotiable. Tynan is among those who insist that her voice was
as melodious and true as a bell. She was obviously speaking nicely to him.
So Louise Brooks voluntarily joined the group of film actors assassinated by
the advent of sound. Clara Bow, the ``It'' girl of the 1920s, was made to feel
washed up with a Brooklyn accent. John Gilbert, MGM's box-office hearthrob of
the silver screen, was ridiculed for an allegedly high-pitched voice that did
not match his physique (although technical sabotage with the treble control
turned up was later revealed as the real culprit) and he died broken at the age
of 36.
Louise was 12 years younger. Contempt was her ultimate form of self-protection,
better than reliance on fashion and approval. In Louise you might call it
nihilism if you believed that it was herself, rather than an artificially
manufactured self, that she set out to destroy. In a new age that worships
ambition, her motives might appear incomprehensible. But Louise had values as
well as a dangerous talent. True artists are rare, and there is no place for
them in a competitive industry. Besides, she had another continent to try.
Europe wanted her.
The story goes that German director G W Pabst, who previously gave Garbo her
first lead outside of Sweden, had lined up an untried Marlene Dietrich for the
part of Lulu in Pandora's Box. Louise had been his first choice, but she was
contracted to Paramount. Dietrich was in his Berlin office ready to sign the
contract when Pabst received the cable breaking the news that Louise had quit
Hollywood and was available.
In later life mere mention of her rival actress, who would go on to make The
Blue Angel two years after losing Lulu, would prompt Louise into one of her
less charitable testimonials: ``Dietrich! That contraption!'' To think that
Louise left the bitch market open to Crawford and Davis. She could have walked
over them. We have to content ourself with what Louise achieved in Berlin.
If there is an argument about what was lost by the passing of the silent era,
the universal illusion sacrificed to the bland, the private trance of the
viewer rudely disturbed by scriptwriters' banalities, the active imagination
rendered passive, it finds its most persuasive illustration in Pandora's Box.
Dietrich, too worldly, too sexually ingenuous, too burlesque, too careerist,
would have been wrong for the role of the kept woman/lover/prostitute Lulu
committed only to momentary fulfilment, exploited sexual naif rather than
calculating man-eater. Pabst wanted the character as the ``personification of
primitive sexuality, who inspires evil unawares''. Brooks, his first choice,
was made for it. She was brilliant. Her performance was not just the triumph of
her own brief career, but one of the miracles of twentieth-century cinema.
It took 25 years to recognise this. Initial critical reaction was unfavourable.
German reviews, unable to accept an American actress in a part that had been
widely debated in advance, wanted more moral censure than Pabst's subtle
directing levelled at Louise. Americans were too caught up in the talkies to
have much time for such a mesmeric anachronism, and that has continued to
devalue the film outside of the film theatres. It doesn't even get television
showings. Louise would have approved.
She made another silent film for Pabst, Diary of a Lost Girl, and went on to
Paris to make Prix De Beaute in Paris, later dubbed in French, before returning
to America to face the music. She was ready to accept her film career as a
failure. Another project with Pabst fell through, and she sank into isolation.
There were some desultory efforts before she finally called it a day. As she
fell into poverty the studios were ready to give her humiliating bit parts as a
revenge. Her last picture credit was in 1938, a dismal cowboy effort called
Overland Stage Raiders with John Wayne. Wayne, after making 64 films, was just
about to make his breakthrough with Stagecoach. If that's what it took to make
a success in Hollywood, it must have represented the ultimate in unacceptable
compromise to a still defiant Louise. After her last test for a movie role she
was told: ``It stunk''. That was enough.
Louise slumped pretty low. After the failure of a dance school she set up in
Wichita, and an attempt to establish a career in radio soaps (if they got her
voice she was witholding her presence), she actually held down a job for two
years as a department store salesperson in New York, which must have been the
hardest role of her life. There were two broken marriages. In the index of her
biography, under love life, it is painful to monitor her decline. It goes
through film stars and directors, wealthy bankers and brokers, then gives
entries for ``hotel barman'' and ``Don the marine''. She would say that Lulu
was the story of her life, but she never quite added prostitution to her
problem with alcoholism. Friends eventually organised a small annuity to be
granted to her.
Her resurrection came through an unexpected medium, but it should have been
obvious all along that she could write. She liked to call herself ``the
best-read idiot in the world'', but as early as 1925 she had made a literary
debut in the New York Times. She had gone to the Broadway opening for No, No,
Nanette on the arm of Herman Mankiewicz, the second-string theatre reviewer of
the Times. Before he had fallen into a drunken sleep he asked Louise to keep
some notes of the show. She ended up filing a review under his name. ``A highly
meritorious paradigm of its kind,'' she opined elegantly.
The essays that Louise wrote a full 30 years later gave an outlet for her venom
on Hollywood. Portraits of Humphrey Bogart and W C Fields display an intriguing
mixture of savage insight, affection, much more technical understanding than
anyone would have believed into the mechanics of film acting, and sheer writing
craft. She writes about Garbo and Lillian Gish and Pabst. And she writes about
her own career, without vanity or pity. She was a survivor.
She was a terrible loss to Hollywood, because if it could not contend with a
Louise Brooks, a big part of its investment would never recover: its soul would
always be suspect, its intelligence unchallenged and its artistry corrupted by
the system. Louise's final words in her essay on the ``bloodless exile'' of
Greta Garbo might have been applied equally to her own dismissal: ``Hollywood
producers were left with their babes and a backwash of old-men stars, watching
the lights go out in one picture house after another across the country''.
