<TEXT>
GLASGOW has a tiger by the tail. The golden boy of British architecture and
design, ironically with the deeply foreign and oh-so-difficult-to-pronounce
name of Deyan Sudjic, has got the #65,000 job as director of the #10m Glasgow
UK City of Architecture and Design 1999. A unanimous choice. Definitely the
best man for the job. Brings international clout. That's the consensus of
experts and city fathers. Above all, the appointment shows Glasgow is serious
about 1999.
Reaction to the news has been little short of euphoric - and that in a city
noted for its cynicism - sighs of relief and smiles all round, as spirits rose
and the appointment was greeted with open arms.
For Sudjic, aged 43, is well respected for his intellect, energy, and
progressive, uncompromisingly modern taste and for an overall grasp of both
architecture and design. ``He's quite a polymath'' says Blueprint's editor,
Rowen Moore. ``I imagine that's why he got the job.'' Of particular relevance
is Sudjic's questioning attitude. He's interested in the bigger picture; at
looking beyond the building or object and its aesthetics, to the whys, hows and
wherefores; to what caused the recent profound changes in cities worldwide; and
what the future holds.
Neither is his internationalism in doubt. Currently visiting professor at
Vienna and orchestrating the 1996 Design as Identity exhibition for Copenhagen,
European City of Culture 1996, he travels widely and left Glasgow after
Monday's anouncement for a week abroad in those two cities.
Charming, erudite, articulate, with a track record of quality journalism,
exhibition organisation and numerous books to his name, he can also be
hard-hitting and does not suffer fools gladly. Dealing with the demands of the
different civic authorities - the district council, region and the GDA, who
currently make up the triumvirate in charge of 1999 - it won't get any easier
come unification. He will need teeth and determination to battle through local
authority red tape. Sudjic is no pushover and will stir things up for sure; no
bad thing after the 14 months of inertia following Glasgow's surprise win of UK
Capital of Architecture and Design.
Much rides on Glasgow's ability to make the most of this opportunity, yet the
city has been painfully slow in finding a strategy, and antagonised many who
were previously very committed to the project. Two years of volunteer labour
and goodwill, followed by a long lull, is bound to exhaust even the most
dedicated.
Alastair MacDonald, Janice Kirkpatrick, David Page and Per Kartvedt are just
some disillusioned key players.
``Architectural events take years to organise and there's a stop, slow, no-go
civic attitude. Once the private sector pressure group disappeared, so did the
action. There's no forum; no response; no momentum. It's as though we're losing
the very thing we worked so hard to win; knocked our pan out to no avail. We're
sick of contributing to things which become a bureaucratic disaster
orchestrated behind closed doors - when, ironically, Glasgow won the accolade
on its grass-roots empowerment!'' says MacDonald.
Sudjic must dispel this disquiet. Despite a reputation for arrogance, he would
be well-advised to listen to these very real complaints.
But already Sudjic's appointment has assuaged fears that the design element of
1999 was not being taken seriously, for he has a passion for innovative design,
spending a year as deputy editor of Design Magazine, then a decade as editor of
Blueprint, making it Britain's leading architecture/design magazine.
``At last we have someone who understands about quality; who knows good from
bad, and is completely aware of what's going on worldwide,'' says Kirkpatrick.
``He'll send out the right signals. Not parochial! We've got some hope now. I
just trust he'll be allowed to do the job.''
So who owns him? To whom is he responsible? Significantly, Monday's event was
moved from 1999's Princes Square base to the City Chambers at the last minute,
depriving everyone of a view of the excellent GSA MA Design exhibition there.
So will Pat Lally and Stuart Gulliver pull his strings? ``No-one owns me,''
Sudjic told me on the telephone from Vienna, his voice sharp and to the point.
In fact, he's responsible to the board of the new 1999 charity ``company Ltd by
guarantee'', as yet not formally constituted but including Lally, Gulliver,
Wright, Dugald Cameron, Conran, and others.
So why on earth move from sunny London to rainy Scotland? ``I'm always looking
for new challenges. I'm doing this because it should be fun. I've got a lot to
give, too. I see the job as workable and liveable. If I thought it was an
impossible job, I wouldn't have taken it.''
Sudjic was born in 1952 in London. His Yugoslav parents came to the UK in 1938.
His mother did post-graduate English at Edinburgh University while his
journalist father worked for the BBC World Service. They went back to
Yugoslavia in 1948 with two sons (one now a Kirkcaldy lawyer, also trained at
Edinburgh; the other a dentist) but communism palled and they returned in 1950.
``I had a London childhood; went to Latymer. It was rather theatrical. Hugh
Grant went there!'' In 1959 he took to journalism as one of the Oz school kids,
``Truly!'', then to Edinburgh University to read architecture 1970-76.
``I'd been making houses out of cardboard since I was 10. And I didn't want to
be a journalist. Edinburgh was a fantastic, beautiful place - though the pubs
closed at 10pm. The teaching was less inspired. Our first project was to draw
the drawing board! The second to design a car park.''
Contemporaries included John McCaslan of Canary Wharf fame. While editing the
student newspaper (and campaigning for Gordon Brown) he discovered he loved
writing.
A year in the GLC's architecture office (jobs included the Barbican) made him
``hopelessly impatient, frustrated and depressed. I really admire people who
have the range of skills needed: the sheer neck to get your ideas through and
the practical on-site skills when building. I had a narrow escape''.
His writing covers Architects Journal (``I learned more about architecture in
three years there than at Edinburgh''), Building Design, Sunday Times 1981-5
(``When Andrew Neil arrived I was ordered into the news room where I sat beside
Andrew Jaspan''), Guardian architecture critic - which he still is - but by
1983 he was keen to work for himself.
``About 1980 I became a workaholic. I was fairly relaxed before but then I did
a series of books (the first was Cult Objects in 1983, interpreting the
messages things have: Levis, Sottsass's Valentine typewriter, the Filofax,
Ray-Bans and the joys of matt black) as well as my Times job, plus setting up
Blueprint with a few chums.
``We published every three weeks, doing the whole thing including paste-up over
one weekend. We expected it to last six issues!'' Blueprint went on to win
major awards for editorial and design quality, setting new standards of
excellence. The business grew into Wordsearch Publishing, with a turnover of
#2m pounds a year and 25 employees. Wordsearch also produces Tate, and has a
graphic design service.
In 1993, he decided to step back. ``Ten years is enough.'' Now managing editor,
he still writes for Blueprint and has responsibility for financial planning.
Books include monographs on Ron Arad, Kawakubo, Expo 92, English Extremists,
Pawson, Rogers and Foster, with his 1992 book, The 100-Mile City, well known.
``It was an absurdly ambitious project showing how cities changed in the 1980s
into a completely new species; how five world cities - Paris, Tokyo, London, LA
and New York - are fighting it out when an urban soup now regularly stretches
for 100 miles. I saw the early warning signals. The book took two years;
exhausting but satisfying!''
He sees Glasgow as ``remarkably focused'', a natural partner to Barcelona,
Chicago, Helsinki, Vienna, and Prague.
``Glasgow has got itself on to the international circuit. It has a critical
mass and knows how to use design and architecture to express its identity. And
it's big enough to be surprising!''
Architecture was passion number one; then design and cities. But another of
Sudjic's talents is exhibition organising. I well remember the opening of the
1986 Foster, Rogers, Stirling show at London's Royal Academy - a stunning event
which attracted more than 100,000 visitors. He has also co-curated shows at the
ICA, RIBA and Italy on Nigel Coates, Paulson, Farell, Gough, the Chair, and the
Public Realm.
``I feel it's very important that 1999 shows be originated in Glasgow.
Architecture exhibitions should not be books on walls; they need exciting stage
management and must be aimed at people who would not know what architecture was
if it came up and bit them.''
Sudjic will live in ``urban Glasgow'', starting his four-year contract on
February 1. His wife and seven-year-old daughter arrive ``at the new term''.
His office will be in Princes Square's 1999 shop, later moving to the
Lighthouse Building. He will not share offices with Mike Hayes in the planning
department. ``We felt 1999 should stand on its own,'' Hayes told me.
``Glasgow is a stunning, exhilarating city,'' Sudjic says. ``The quality of
architecture is tremendous!'' He admits to no experience of housing
associations, but has help on hand as Pauline Gallacher of Share has been
appointed to Sudjic's 1999 team.
``I'm not a design dictator; I want to learn where the currents flow and asked
for someone to show me. I'll provide the seed but not work in a confined box. I
want to do things the Glasgow way.''
His immediate three-point plan is ``to get to know all the players in the city;
to see the venues and to produce a timetable. My role is to harness and focus
energies......''. He says his job is ``the best challenge since the Festival of
Britain 50 years ago''. Aware that Glasgow's bid was not about ``grandes
projects'', he proposes ``making the best of what you have, with consolidation
in the centre of the city'', but cites Barcelona's ``peripheral squares and
cheap interventions on the edges'' as something that could profitably be
applied to Glasgow.
Gulliver, one of Sudjic's selectors, along with Lally, Gould, Hayes, Bob Palmer
and architect Andrew Wright, refutes criticisms about delays in 1999's
progress. ``Until the conductor arrives the orchestra can't play.''
He also assures me: ``Yes, we've got to give him his head.'' Likewise Sudjic
has a reputation for appointing the right people and letting them get on with
it.
Sudjic was chosen from an initial application of 70, including 10 headhunted
names, three of whom (Sudjic, Victoria Thornton and Rory Coonan) made the
finals along with Scots Neil Baxter and Frank Binnie. Sir Terence Conran
endorsed Sudjic's appointment: ``Terrific. Good news. He has an eye, contacts
and knowledge, the abilty to give intellectual leadership and is in tune with
Glasgow's politics.''
Andy Harold of Nice House says: ``He has world stature. Whether he's an
organiser remains to be seen, but he's got my vote. He should enjoy himself
here, and Nice House will throw the party!''
As a welcome, you can't say fairer than that.
CLARE HENRY
</TEXT>
