<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Galloway stirs up Labour's Govan vote racism row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPLAINTS about ineligible voters were far more extensive than the 52 papers
rejected in the disputed Glasgow Govan selection process, The Herald has
learned.
As many as 180 votes were questioned at the count to select a candidate for the
new constituency, before 52 were rejected because of doubts over authenticity -
fuelling complaints of racism by supporters of Mohammed Sarwar.
The row within the Labour Party escalated last night when Hillhead MP George
Galloway added his voice to the claims of racism. He denounced the election at
a meeting in Yorkshire, where he shared a platform with the Pakistani High
Commissioner.
He told guests at the Bombay Brasserie in Bradford: ``This debacle represents a
shameful injustice to Mohammed Sarwar - an elected councillor and member of the
party's national executive in Scotland - to the many thousands of Pakistani
voters in the Govan constituency, and to the two million Muslims living in
Britain.
``It is a decision that has no credibility and one which must not be allowed to
stand.''
It was, he claimed, a breach of natural justice which would not stand up in
court.
The party hierarchy in London has resigned itself an inquiry - not yet formally
announced but bound to have damaging fall-out when, as expected, it reports
next month. Mr Sarwar told The Herald he was confident that any inquiry would
exonerate any of his supporters of wrong-doing.
``I have nothing to fear,'' he said last night. He pointed out that ballot
papers had been sent out for a postal ballot, making a nonsense of the
suggestion of false names or fake identities.
Glasgow Central MP Mike Watson won by a single vote on a count-back procedure.
The 245 for Mr Watson were matched by an identical figure for Mr Sarwar. Of the
18 voters for candidate Margaret Curran, 17 had expressed a preference and when
these were redistributed a dead heat came about. The rules were then invoked to
go back to the first ballot, in which Mr Watson had won by 237 to 236.
By then 52 votes had been ruled ineligible - a majority of them supporters of
Mr Sarwar. However, The Herald understands that there were around 180 voting
forms questioned by the scrutineers.
Ms Lesley Quinn, Scottish Labour Party organiser, was asked to rule on these
and allowed all but 52 to stand. Three were unsigned, and therefore
automatically barred, and 49 were deemed to be clear cases where signatures
failed to match.
Mr Sarwar said he would give the party the weekend to consider his request for
an inquiry and, failing that, he would make a further announcement - a
reference which may be taken as a threat of legal action.
Scottish general secretary Jack McConnell was in London yesterday, but for a
strategy meeting which did not discuss the Govan issue. However, the issue will
come before the NEC on January 24 - a meeting which will also be dominated by
the party's inquiry into the Monklands saga.
That meeting will have a straight choice before it - to call a rerun of the
Govan count, or to reject Mr Sarwar's complaint.
Last night, the SNP, which once captured the old Govan constituency, moved to
make capital from the row. Mr Bashir Ahmed, convener of Scots Asians for
Independence, said the unedifying spectacle would worry many in his
constituency and contrasted with his experience in the SNP.
``There was a wonderfully warm reception extended to us when we launched Scots
Asians for Independence at the SNP conference. We are delighted to be playing a
full part in the activities of the party as we work with our fellow Scots to
build a new Scotland. Our message to all Asian people in Scotland is to come
and join us.''
</TEXT>
