<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hampden Park nets #23m award from the lottery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAMPDEN Park has been awarded a grant of up to #23m by the Millennium
Commission, which will help turn it into one of the finest stadiums in the
world.
By far the biggest single National Lottery award made in Scotland, not only
will it help complete the redevelopment of the national football stadium but
will also create a centre of excellence for players and spectators.
The redevelopment, which has a total cost of #51m, will increase Hampden's
capacity from 34,000 to 52,000.
The Millennium Commission grant will be used towards the building of a new
south stand, which will house facilities for players, officials, and
supporters, and eight dressing rooms. The structure will have a 50-metre roof
span and is expected to be the biggest of its kind in Britain.
It will also include an international media centre and a museum of football.
Queen's Park Football Club, which set up the National Stadium Committee (NSC)
in conjunction with the SFA to oversee the redevelopment of the 92-year-old
ground, said that with funding totalling almost as much again in place, it was
``very confident'' the redevelopment would be completed by early 1998.
Announcing the grant at Hampden Park yesterday, the Earl of Dalkeith, the only
Scottish member among the nine on the commission, said its decision was based
on the fact that the project was bigger than Hampden Park alone and would be
``available to all''.
He added that ``we were convinced by the evidence produced by Queen's Park and
many other people that this would genuinely be appreciated by the people who
buy lottery tickets in Scotland. That is very important because it is their
money.''
</TEXT>
