<HEADLINE>Health-or-job bargain priced by judge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WORKER forced to make a ``dreadful bargain'' between his health and keeping a
job was yesterday awarded damages of #37,000.
Mr Thomas Bonar, 36, has worked as a painter for Trafalgar House Offshore
Fabrication at its yard in Methil, Fife, since May 1990. He contracted
occupational asthma as a result of his working conditions. Trafalgar admitted
liability.
Assessing damages at the Court of Session, Lord Gill said Mr Bonar, of
Ochilview Drive, High Valleyfield, Fife, had worked as a spray painter since he
left school 20 years ago.
He began to use a new type of paint in 1993 which caused him acute discomfort.
He coughed uncontrollably, his throat became irritated, and he had nose bleeds.
He was no longer working with the paint that had caused the problem but still
suffered from breathlessness, coughing, and disturbed sleep. He tired quickly
if exerted and could not walk for any great distance.
Lord Gill said: ``Mr Bonar is a hard-working tradesman who is enthusiastic
about his work. He says that painting has been his life.
``He has not given in to his condition. He has continued at his work and has
done as much overtime as is available to him. To his credit, he has maintained
this effort despite his symptoms, which make his work more difficult and
arduous.''
He now also had a ``considerable burden of medication'' to take and attended
hospital every four months.
Dr Gavin Petrie, a consultant chest physician with Fife Health Board, described
the condition as incurable and said Mr Bonar would need continuing supervision,
advice, and treatment, perhaps for the rest of his life.
Lord Gill added: ``If he continues in his present working conditions, there is
a material risk that further respiratory irritation may cause his condition to
deteriorate. A further deterioration could lead to a severe and irreversible
airflow obstruction.''
Lord Gill said doctors recognised the dilemma that had been created for Mr
Bonar. ``The best clinical advice would be that he should give up his present
employment but, as he is a committed and energetic worker and has no other
qualification or skill, such advice could well lead to long-term unemployment.
``Dr Petrie has aptly described Mr Bonar as having a dreadful bargain to make
between present employment and future health. He has made the dreadful bargain
to which Dr Petrie referred.''
</TEXT>
