<HEADLINE>SCOTTISH CUP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q.IT is not often that a team visits Albion Rovers in the hope of an upset, but
that is the case today when the Highland League's Deveronvale travel to
Coatbridge for a first-round tie in the Tennents Scottish Cup, one of the three
matches postponed last week.
An upset success would mean an all-Highland tie in the second round, as Keith
visit the victors.
Rovers have been taking no chances and Deveronvale have been watched by the
backroom staff at Cliftonhill.
One non-league team is sure to progress, as Edinburgh club Spartans visit
Glasgow University at Westerlands.
The team who were the main giant-killers last season, Stenhousemuir, have a
busy weekend, beginning with today's league match against Gordon Dalziel's Ayr
United.
'Muir will celebrate their more recent giant-killing act, which earned them
this season's Challenge Cup, with a gala night for the fans tomorrow in the
town's Dobbie Hall. The Warriors also have a video and a book about their
Challenge Cup win.
East Fife's impressive away record will be tested by Clyde at Broadwood, while
Stirling Albion's unbeaten run could be under threat from Queen of the South at
Dumfries. Berwick should keep the points at home against Montrose and Stranraer
are hopeful of victory at Forfar.
The third division's top two meet at Brechin, with Livingston's unbeaten away
record under threat. But Jim Leishman's men will be boosted by last week's cup
win at Stranraer.
</TEXT>
