<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Second boy in hospital dash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEN-YEAR-OLD boy with serious head injuries had to be driven 45 miles to
hospital because of a bed shortage, just a week after another child died making
the same journey.
Christopher Satterthwaite was hit by a car in Salford, Greater Manchester, on
Thursday night, but there were no intensive care beds available in the county's
two children's hospitals.
An ambulance had to drive him to Leeds General Infirmary, where yesterday he
was described as ``stable'', with a broken pelvis and elbow.
A top-level inquiry has already been ordered by the North West Regional Health
Authority into the death of Nicholas Geldard, 10, who collapsed with a
suspected brain haemorrhage at his home in Stockport last week.
He was taken to three different hospitals in the area before being driven to
the same Leeds hospital. He was dead on arrival. His parents are now
considering legal action.
A consultant said Christopher was the 31st child, since August 1, who had been
moved to a hospital outside Greater Manchester because of a shortage of beds at
the Royal Manchester Children's Hospital and Booth Hall Children's Hospital.
Labour health spokeswoman Harriet Harman has called on Health Secretary Stephen
Dorrell to investigate.
</TEXT>
