<HEADLINE>All-party talks by February is aim, as three-man commission starts its work in Belfast Talks on arms impasse begin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INTENSE pre-Christmas political activity over the Northern Ireland peace
process began yesterday, with the first formal meeting in Belfast of an
international commission bidding to resolve the row over arms.
The three-man body, established by the British and Irish Governments, and
chaired by former US Senator George Mitchell, hopes to pave the way to
all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland by February.
Yesterday, the group opened its behind-closed-doors work by hearing a
Government submission from a team led by Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick
Mayhew.
Belfast-based politicians, including fringe loyalist groups associated to
para-military organisations, will outline their views today.
Afterwards, the commission - also including former Finnish Prime Minister Harri
Holkeri and Canadian Defence Forces Chief General John de Chastelain - moves on
to Dublin.
There it will hear from the Irish Government and political parties, including
Sinn Fein.
Mr Mitchell and his colleagues went into yesterday's opening meeting stressing
that they had no preconceived ideas about overcoming the problems confronting
them.
He told journalists: ``We enter the process with open minds.......motivated
solely by a desire to make a constructive contribution.''
More seasonally, Mr Holkeri pointed out that while he came from the home of
Santa Claus, he was not a political Father Christmas for Northern Ireland's
peace process.
Meanwhile, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams signalled that the commission would
face no easy task in solving the arms controversy.
Commenting in Dublin, he underlined his party's continuing resistance to
British demands that the IRA had to move towards decommissioning weapons before
its Sinn Fein allies could join any all-party talks.
Mr Adams also said his party could talk authoritatively about IRA arms, while
holding out few prospects of advancing the peace process until Britain relaxed
its stance on the weapons.
Soon after the international body completes its first session in Dublin, the
Irish capital will stage, on successive days, a meeting of the Anglo-Irish
inter-governmental Northern Ireland Conference, and a prime ministerial summit.
Wednesday's conference will set the stage for visits to Belfast and Dublin by
Prime Minister John Major, 24 hours later.
In Dublin talks with Irish counterpart John Bruton, Mr Major will attempt to
boost the whole peace process.
Yesterday, a senior colleague of Mr Bruton's, Social Welfare Minister Proinsias
De Rossa, urged Mr Major to take advantage of his trip to Ireland to have a
face-to-face meeting with Mr Adams.
Last night, the Rev.Ian Paisley's Democratic Unionist Party defended its
decision not to meet the arms commission.
The party had new talks in Belfast with the Ulster Unionists, who are to make a
submission to Mr Mitchell today.
Former Belfast Lord Mayor Nigel Dodds said he viewed with ``extreme distaste''
what he regarded as an attempt to internationalise the situation in Northern
Ireland.
He told BBC Radio Ulster: ``We have an issue which goes to the very heart of
security of part of the UK, where vast stockpiles of arms and ammunition are
being held by terrorist organisations. That's a matter for the Government.
``We deplore the fact that a very influential American politician is being
brought in to deal with this issue. If it's okay to deal with this issue, then
the question has to be asked: Why could the same sort of internationalisation
and externalisation not take place in relation to other matters which should be
within the Government's domain?'' said Mr Dodds.
</TEXT>
