<DOCNO>GH951216-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Islanders thrown out of water meeting</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of the public who turned up for the fifth meeting of the West of
Scotland Water Authority on water charges last night expressed their outrage at
being thrown out.
The authority's four previous meetings ended in chaos after demonstrations by
members of the Hands Off Scottish Water campaign and the West of Scotland
Campaign Against Water Privatisation.
Yesterday, the authority met on Bute to discuss the Scottish Office move to cap
water charge rises at 6%, declaring it was confident that it could contain
water rate rises close to the level set by the Scottish Secretary.
However, members of the public who attended the meeting after seeing an
advertisement in the local newspaper said they were disgusted at being asked to
leave.
Mr Gerry Chambers, manager of Rothesay's Winter Garden complex, was talked down
by the authority's chairman, Mr John Jameson, when he rose to ask a question.
Mr Chambers said: ``This is a complete travesty and I am very disappointed that
the public are not being given the opportunity to question the water authority
at a public meeting.''
Concern was also expressed by the chairman of the Isle of Bute branch of the
SNP, Mr Donnie McLeod, who described the running of the public meetings as
completely undemocratic.
``The members of the board should at least be prepared to listen to what people
have to say. There was no attempt to disrupt this meeting today. Reading out
the minutes of a previous meeting and then calling the proceedings to a close
is a complete sham,'' he said.
The meeting ended when a member of the West of Scotland Campaign Against Water
Privatisation, dressed in a Santa suit, presented Mr Jameson with a mock-up of
his P45.
The debacle came as Scotland's water watchdog announced it was to ask consumers
for their views on the quality of service offered by the three water
authorities and on how complaints were being dealt with.
Meeting in Stirling yesterday, the Scottish Water and Sewage Customers Council
also announced plans for a permanent headquarters to be based in Stirling's
Springkerse business park. The council is based in Edinburgh at present.
While not revealing how much money would be spent on the countrywide customer
survey, the council's chairman and SNP member, Mr Dick Douglas, said its
purpose would be to establish what the public felt about the water authorities,
charges and services by March next year.
``What we want to establish is a base line on what people think of water
service. I can't say how much the questionnaire will cost but it will be a lean
and mean exercise. We are not in the business of throwing away money.''
</TEXT>
