<DOCNO>GH951216-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jackson scare
NEW YORK: Singer Michael Jackson may have been within 15 minutes of dying when
he collapsed last week, his doctor told the New York Post. ``Michael was
acutely and dangerously ill for hours,'' Dr Allan Metzger said. Jackson, who
was rehearsing for a television special when he collapsed on December 6,
suffered from low blood pressure and a dangerous loss of electrolytes, Metzger
said.
Collapse kills six
BOMBAY: Rescuers worked desperately yesterday to free 27 people trapped in the
ruins of a partly-completed block of flats which collapsed at Mumbra near
Bombay, killing six people. The four-storey block collapsed as the builder was
showing visitors around the site, police said. He was one of those killed.
Nuclear row
NEW DELHI: India is preparing for its first nuclear test in 21 years in a move
some see as muscle-flexing to impress neighbouring Pakistan and keep the
current Indian government in power, it was reported yesterday. The United
States is trying to dissuade India from carrying out the test, fearing it could
trigger other tests among the world's nuclear powers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Loganair moves its headquarters to the Isle of Man</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOGANAIR, ``Scotland's Airline'', is to be run from the Isle of Man.
Managing director Scott Grier confirmed yesterday that ``up to a dozen''
accounts and administration staff at Loganair's Glasgow headquarters had been
offered the choice of a move to the Isle of Man or redundancy.
Mr Grier denied the ``rationalisation'' amounted to a take-over of the Scottish
commuter airline by Manx Airlines. Services would be unaffected and the
travelling public would not notice the difference, he said.
``For the past 16 months, we've been operating in parallel with Manx,'' he
said. ``We're both British Airways franchise holders and there's some
duplication. The board feel it's time to rationalise.''
Flying operations and most of Loganair's 200 staff would stay at Glasgow
Airport. The company had no plans to change its services to Orkney, Shetland,
and the Western Isles, or the vital air ambulance service.
Loganair, Manx Airlines, Manx Europe, and the much larger British Midland
Airways are all wholly-owned subsidiaries of the Airlines of Britain group, set
up in 1987.
Mr Grier said the three smaller airlines would share accounts and
administration under a new ``sub-group'' based in the Isle of Man: ``In effect,
we'll have one accounts department instead of three, but the activities of each
operator will continue to be accounted for separately,'' he said.
Loganair staff were called together on Wednesday this week and told of the
plans. Mr Grier said he was ``personally very upset'' that some employees who
were not able to move to the Isle of Man would become redundant. However, he
believed staff in general were ``very pleased'' because the decision ``put an
end to uncertainty''.
``There's no question of a Manx takeover,'' he said. ``Loganair will retain its
separate identity. We knew when we became a British Airways franchise operation
that it would bring many benefits but we did give up our identity to a degree,
in that we lost our own livery and uniforms.''
Loganair also lost some of its larger planes to Manx but Mr Grier hoped ``in
the fullness of time'' to have access to bigger aircraft.
Mr Trevor Booth, Loganair's engineering boss in Glasgow, is leaving the company
to join British Midland, Mr Grier said.
</TEXT>
