<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major's condolences at birth of EuroG</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIME Minister John Major yesterday criticised the Euro, the proposed name for
the EU's single currency, as uninspiring, unimaginative, undignified, and the
lowest common denominator - even before it was born.
He then agreed to European economic and monetary union, which will lead to the
new money, on its scheduled date of January 1, 1999.
Tory Euro-sceptics are certain to be enraged by Mr Major's decision. Their mood
will hardly be helped by pro-European Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's statement
that he did not expect his party to include a pledge to keep Britain out of a
single currency in the General Election manifesto.
Mr Clarke also predicted that a British decision on whether to join a single
currency is now most likely in March 1998, when the first wave of eligible
countries is due to be selected if the current timetable is kept.
If all goes to plan, Europeans whose countries adopt the new coinage, will
begin jingling Euros in the pockets and purses in the year 2002. About half of
the EU's 15 member states are on course to qualify for membership of the single
currency, including Britain which has negotiated the right to opt out.
A decision on whether to use the opt-out must be taken by the Government which
wins the next election - expected by spring of 1997 - in the early part of 1998.
No symbol for the new money has been created so far to rival the American $ or
the Japanese Y. The currency will be decimal but no decision has been taken on
the name of the 100 units making up the Euro.
Mr Major's lack of enthusiasm for the new money was fuelled by suspicion of its
effects on currencies which do not join the process. He foresaw the Euro being
too strong for its rivals.
He told the BBC: ``Then there is a danger of competitive devaluation and
retaliatory protectionism across the community. And the self-evident worry
about that - a very real worry - is that the single market itself could become
damaged, if not destroyed.''
Nevertheless, his party Euro-sceptics are bound to give him a hard time over
agreeing a name calculated to raise the hackles of the dedicated sceptic Tory
back bencher.
Euro-sceptic Tory MP Bill Cash said: ``The proposal to go ahead with monetary
union and with the so-called Euro will go down as a complete disaster in
British and European history.
``We must resist this mood and I am amazed that we did not take further steps
to oppose it.''
The name was chosen against the favoured option of French president, Jacques
Chirac, who wanted the denomination to be called the Ecu, the EU's nominal
currency. He was supported by President Jacques Santer of the European
Commission.
Both pleas were steamrolled by German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who backed the
Euro and won.
There was no formal vote, in keeping with all summits.
Chancellor Clarke had suggested florin, shilling, and crown as possible
alternatives.
Four member states, including Ireland, supported the florin and there was
backing for several other names but none proved as uncontentious as the Euro.
Those currencies most likely to disappear first are the Deutschmark, the
Austrian schilling, the Dutch guilder, and the Belgian and Luxembourg francs
which are a single currency already. These countries represent the hard
currency states of the EU who are expected to form the core group of Emu
founders.
They could be joined by the French franc if France meets the so-called
convergence criteria demanded by the Maastricht treaty for economic and
monetary union (Emu). Britain and Denmark will also probably qualify although
both are undecided on whether to invoke the opt-out when the time comes.
Mr Major showed most interest in the effects of Emu on those countries which
remain outside it. His particular concern is that a small group of EU single
currency member states could begin voting as a bloc on political issues, thus
undermining the consensualist tradition of the European Union - and possibly
damaging British interests.
At Mr Major's insistence, the Spanish prime minister, Felipe Gonzalez, who
chaired the discussion, agreed to pass on to the Italians the responsibility
for investigating the effects of Emu on non-single currency member states.
This will give Mr Major more time to put off making up his mind on whether
Britain should join the single currency which represents the EU's most
ambitious scheme in its four decades of existence.
He can also go to next spring's crucial Maastricht II conference in Turin in
the knowledge that the single currency issue should not cramp his style. Emu is
not on the formal agenda of that meeting.
Britain is expected to spend millions of pounds familiarising the public with
the Euro.
Comparisons are being drawn with the publicity blitz which lasted for seven
years in the run-up to decimalisation of Britain's currency in 1971.
A blueprint for the European-wide campaign was produced recently by the
European Commission. It wants the community's member states to pick up most of
the cost of educating the public.
