chaired the discussion, agreed to pass on to the Italians the responsibility
for investigating the effects of Emu on non-single currency member states.
This will give Mr Major more time to put off making up his mind on whether
Britain should join the single currency which represents the EU's most
ambitious scheme in its four decades of existence.
He can also go to next spring's crucial Maastricht II conference in Turin in
the knowledge that the single currency issue should not cramp his style. Emu is
not on the formal agenda of that meeting.
Britain is expected to spend millions of pounds familiarising the public with
the Euro.
Comparisons are being drawn with the publicity blitz which lasted for seven
years in the run-up to decimalisation of Britain's currency in 1971.
A blueprint for the European-wide campaign was produced recently by the
European Commission. It wants the community's member states to pick up most of
the cost of educating the public.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Still managing to cope despite the adversity McLeish reckons all will  be 'Well</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>this sporting life </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORDS from his mentor and former boss, Alex Ferguson, helped Alex McLeish
appreciate that life is never going to be quite the same as it was in his
playing days. ``You didn't think it was all going the be plain sailing all your
life, did you?'' said Ferguson, as he chatted with the manager of Motherwell.
There was no need for an answer.
Fergie's fatherly intervention reinforced the realisation that, while his
playing career that brought every kind of prize and accolade with Aberdeen and
a record number of caps for his country, it did not necessarily provide
precisely the experience needed to understand the vicissitudes of managership.
McLeish's worst days as a player were soon after Ferguson left and Aberdeen
finished something like fifth in the table. For them that was failure, although
later they came very close to the real thing.
Now as a manager in his own right, McLeish has to confront a numbing sensation
as a bottom-of-the-league man. That might have been less daunting if he had
suffered such a fate in his first season, but it has come following a
marvellous opening year, during which Motherwell finished second in the premier
division and were justifiably lauded for the quality of their play.
``In fact, we would have been top of the table at one point had Dundee United
not equalised against us in injury time when we were heading for our sixth win
on the trot,'' recalls McLeish with understandable nostalgia.
There is a very simple, maybe simplistic, answer to the difference between the
Motherwell of last season and of this. They can't score goals and, no matter
how hard any team or manager tries, success in the game is a tough exercise if
no-one can put the ball past the opposition's keeper.
McLeish had thought he might have improved the performance level by switching
personnel, bringing in new players like Shaun McSkimming, Eddie May, and
Dutchman Mitchell van der Gaag, and letting Steve Kirk and Paul McGrillen go.
All his new men have been injured, two of them, van der Gaag and McSkimming,
missing out for lengthy periods. In fact, the Duchman has not yet got his
career in Scotland moving, and a variety of injuries, most notably to Chris
McCart and Tommy Coyne, has further depleted the manager's selection choices,
and in the end left what was a confident, resourceful side struggling without a
win for their last eight matches.
McLeish remembers thinking of McCart as a serious challenger to his own
position in the Scotland team, but his progress has been halted because of a
succession of injuries.
``At this time last year we had scored 31 goals,'' says the manager, ``compared
to 13 this year. If we had scored even a third of the 18-goal difference we
would probably be in about fourth place.''
McLeish, as a player earning a record for a defender of 77 caps, was not the
type to search for excuses, and is no different as a manager, but he puts
forward these statistics as evidence that the line between high and low in this
league is thin indeed.
``I had a friend over from Belgium recently who had no knowledge of our league,
but he pointed out within a short time of being here in some amazement that two
wins can take a team from the relegation zone to a place in Europe. That is
just the way it is and the only way out for us is to be ruthless in front of
goal.
``Coyne is very badly missed because he is a natural goal-scorer, a `sniffer'
in front of goal. The lads we have here have been playing well enough but are
inclined to want one more stride before shooting, but if they can't do the job
soon then a new striker will be essential. I have a list as long as your arm,
but I am sizing up two or three on a regular basis, all of them British.''
McLeish invariably gives the impression of being so laid back that football
set-backs are merely lines interfering temporarily with the picture. That would
not be an entirely accurate version of the situation, because McLeish hurts,
but mostly inside.
``Nobody enjoys criticism and I am no different, but I was getting stick from
some supporters last season when we were finishing second, so it was bound to
be worse now. The most disturbing thing is that the crowds have begun to
dwindle, although we have a tremendous hard core who are immensely supportive.
``I did feel a lot of negative vibes in myself early on in our bad run, but I
think that was because I had not experienced it before. I felt rock bottom when
we lost to Partick Thistle and I was really down for the next few days. I
wondered if I really showed it, but one or two people pointed out that I
shouldn't let the players see that. I realised they were right and decided:
bugger it, I won't be like this again. Now I am upbeat about our chances of
getting out of trouble.''
It was about then that Ferguson offered his advice, adding: ``You don't
appreciate what it can be like until it happens, do you?'' Now he does, and
believes he is the better for it.
``I believe I am a stronger man because of it and will be a better manager as a
result. I used to see it happening to managers and think: that must be
terrible, but you can't really understand it until you experience it.''
He has made up his mind that, when confronted by media questions that may be
loaded towards a pessimistic answer, he will respond as positively as he can.
``Of course, deep down this is hurting me and I am embarrassed, but the minute
we turn the corner and the lads relax and play as they can, they will start to
move up the table. There is a lot to play for yet but our target now must be
consolidation in the league.
``The `fan' letters are coming in at a faster rate these days, of course, but
not all of them condemnatory. ``Actually it is quite surprising how many
letters of support I am getting, telling me to stick with it and try to keep
the team playing the way we want. That means a lot.''
He admits that one of his problems is transmitting a mental toughness to
players, the kind of resolution that helped Aberdeen win games when they were
not playing well.
A couple of decent scorelines could make a lot of difference, but in the long
run Motherwell will have a man with a tougher hide and an even tougher mind
ready to lead them back to the higher echelons of the game.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
