<HEADLINE>Register of interest in modern mapping system</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>trailblazers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN 1996 the Registers of Scotland Executive Agency alters its character: it
acquires trading fund status. And so now, at last, it will reap the rewards of
five years of trailblazing activity - work which has culminated in the
implementation of an innovative system of digital mapping for the Land Register
of Scotland.
So successful has this system been, that the Land Register of England, which
years ago abandoned the process of converting its registers to digital mapping
because it was too difficult, is once more considering the same step.
The Registers of Scotland Executive Agency was until 1990, a part of the
Scottish Office. It is responsible for a number of registers: sasine, land,
personal and deeds among others.
The Sasine Register was established in 1617 to provide for the recording of
deeds as evidence of title to land or property. But the recording of a deed in
it does not mean the Keeper of the Registers certifies its validity. The
disposition which gives details of buyer and seller and a description of the
property, the documents which create securities or burdens on it, and the chain
of former deeds must all be examined before a good title can be established.
This repeated examination of numerous titles in every transaction is expensive
and time consuming. So in 1979 the Land Register of Scotland was set up. This
provides a system of registration of interests in place of the recording of
deeds in the Register of Sasines, and it gives guaranteed titles to land or
property. Unlike the Sasine Register, it is based on a title plan, which is
derived from the Ordnance Survey map.
And this is where the digital mapping comes in. By the early nineties Ordnance
Survey maps were being produced digitally. At the same time, the Registers of
Scotland had undertaken a strategy study to examine its future.
It was clear the Land Register (which is progressively replacing the Sasine
Register) could gain enormous benefits from the increasingly popular geographic
information systems. Land registration procedures could be vastly speeded up,
much more information could be stored, and access           to it could be
immensely improved.
Steps towards the installation of the Land Register's computerised mapping
capability began in 1993. The aim was to acquire a system which could load from
the Ordnance Survey map, produce an index map, check boundary lines, confirm
title positions in relation to surrounding titles, then draw a new, accurate
and detailed title plan.
Fife was the first county to go on-line with the completely computerised
system. Since March this year, every time     a property there changes hands,
the digitised mapping process allows the automatic retrieval of the right
section of the map. Then the boundaries can be ``lassoed'', further details and
measurements drawn in, boundary lines coloured and information highlighted
where necessary. Finally, grid references and all the information, along with
the textual title, are stored in the data base for instant retrieval.
This computerisation has involved an immense amount of effort as each property
changes hands for the first time. Gradually, however, the replacement of the
laborious hand-drawn mapping methods, the extension of digitised titles to the
whole of Scotland, and the eventual transfer of all properties from the Sasine
Register will result in a thoroughly efficient service. This will benefit
everyone with an interest in land or property.
The goal of the Land Register team is to have the whole of Scotland digitised
and transferred by 2003. However, long before then, with its new freedom to
trade and to keep its profits, rather than hand them over to the Treasury,
Registers of Scotland has plans to market its services more widely.
A project called Scotlis - Scottish Land Information System - is investigating
various commercial options. The vast amount of land information relating to
ownership, planning, local authority orders and so on which it possesses could,
for example, be combined and made available. There is the possibility of
producing an on-line reference service for solicitors.
Meanwhile, as more properties come on to the data base, the immediate benefits
of the new system are enormous and obvious. They include speedy access to
information, the sophisticated mapping functions which allow alterations, and
the fact that the contents can be examined by a number of people at the same
time.
And for weary conveyancers, the colourful computer screen could not represent a
more dramatic alternative to the tedious examination of dusty bundles of deeds.
The award and how to enter
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon on the right.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner will be presented with an award certificate and will be
featured in an article.
The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company specialist on an agreed
specialist management training course at the renowned Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
