<HEADLINE>Baboon marrow transplant for Aids man</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864436</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
San Francisco
A MAN dying of Aids went past the point of no return today, receiving an
experimental baboon bone-marrow transplant that might save his life.
Jeff Getty received the baboon marrow during a half-hour infusion, the
culmination of a two-year legal battle for permission to become the first
person to undergo the procedure.
``He's doing very well, feels very good, is up and talking and actually is
making jokes,'' Alice Trinkl, a spokeswoman for San Francisco General Hospital,
said after the operation.
Earlier, 38-year-old Getty underwent a final round of radiation treatment that
knocked out what was left of his immune system. ``It's about time,'' Getty
said. ``I'm lucky to still be alive.''
Getty, an Aids activist and former policy analyst at the University of
California, had fought to win permission for the highly experimental surgery.
The transplant was carried out by researchers from the University of California
at San Francisco and the University of Pittsburgh, as a group of supporters
kept vigil outside the hospital.
In August, the US Food and Drug Administration approved the surgery despite
warnings from scientific advisers that the procedure would probably kill Getty
and could spread baboon diseases to humans.
Human bone marrow contains stem cells that manufacture disease-fighting immune
system cells. The Aids virus destroys this system. The transplant idea arose
because baboons, for reasons that scientists do not understand, do not get
Aids. The theory is that the Aids-resistant baboon stem cells will take root in
Getty's bone marrow and produce immune-system cells that can fight the disease.
Getty underwent drug and radiation treatments this week to destroy virtually
all of what is left of his own immune system to prevent it from attacking the
bone marrow, which otherwise would be perceived as an invader.
Those radiation treatments all but ensure that he will die from Aids-associated
infections if the transplant fails.
The results of the transplant will not be known for several months. Jerome
Zack, a virologist with the University of California at Los Angeles Aids
Institute, is concerned that the treatment could potentially spread baboon
diseases to humans. Aids, for instance, is believed to have originated in
monkeys and mutated into a virulent human disease.
The Humane Society of the United States condemned the surgery. The baboon that
supplied the bone marrow was killed because scientists monitoring the
transplant required a large number of samples.
``Baboons, who are highly intelligent, social and emotional animals, should not
be killed for such highly questionable experiments,'' said Dr Martin Stephens,
vice president for animal research issues.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
