<HEADLINE>Hampden set for new millennium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAMPDEN Park, the old ground which hosted the greatest ever European Cup final,
between Real Madrid and Eintracht Frankfurt in 1960, is all set to take its
place again among the great stadiums in the world.
The biggest step of all came yesterday when Hampden was given a #23m Millennium
Commission grant, thus turning on the green light for the completion of a #51m
redevelopment of Scotland's national stadium. When the Hampden plan is
completed in two years' time, it will be given five-star status by UEFA and
again be eligible to stage matches of the highest calibre.
The latest move also opens the door for the SFA to move from their present
headquarters at Park Gardens to the new Hampden, a move which has already been
discussed - and for the Scottish League to ``flit'' from their premises at West
Regent Street in Glasgow. Queen's Park, however, will remain the owners of the
stadium.
Hampden's traditional south stand is to be demolished and replaced by a 16,000
state-of-the-art stand by 1998, and it is there that the men who administer the
game in this country are expected to base themselves.
The new work will raise the capacity of Hampden to 52,000 and will include a
museum, media centre, and sports injury clinic.
The Earl of Dalkeith, the Millennium Fund Commissioner who announced the grant,
said: ``This is tremendous news for the people of Scotland. The new national
stadium will envelope the rich heritage of Hampden Park with an unrivalled
range of modern facilities for sporting events and gatherings of all types.
``We have no doubt it will become a potent symbol of pride for Scotland's
national sport for the twenty-first century.''
He added that the #23m grant was ``the largest single lottery grant in Scotland
so far.''
Austin Reilly, of the Hampden Stadium Committee, said: ``This is a marvellous
gesture of support for the national stadium and we can only thank the
Millennium Commission.''
Reilly said that funding to take the project up to #51m would come from the
Scottish Office, the European Commission, the Football Trust, and the local
authorities, Stratchclyde Region and Glasgow District. A debenture scheme is
also to be launched for supporters.
He added: ``I'm very confident the whole financial package will drop into
place. We have only to clinch deals to match what the Millennium Fund is
putting in.''
Jim Farry, chief executive of the SFA, said: ``Scotland and Hampden are
definite success stories these days, particularly at a time when we have so
much negative news around.
``We cannot expect to please all of the people all of the time, but the
Millennium commissioners and others associated with this project deserve a
sincere thank-you from all sporting-minded Scots for this confident investment
in our sporting future.
``Also a thank-you to all those who purchased Lottery tickets and those
responsible in the Government for ensuring the successful introduction of the
National Lottery.''
The Hampden project is expected to be completed early in 1998 in time for
Scotland to stage the European youth championships at under-16 level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
