<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monktonhall miners meet to decide the future of the pit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE workforce of the troubled Monktonhall pit will gather in a miners' club in
Midlothian today to secure their jobs and end the uncertainty that has
surrounded their pit since they each invested #10,000 to re-open it three years
ago.
More than 90% have already intimated support for a #15m lifeline from Waverley
Mining Finance which will see the miners' consortium pass control to the
Edinburgh-based company.
The buy-out, expected to be rubber-stamped today at the Dalkeith meeting, will
mean new equipment committed to the colliery, allowing the opening of a new
coal face and the creation of around 80 new jobs.
The miners will each get a shareholding which they must retain for three years.
Mr John Richards, chairman of Monktonhall Mine-workers' Ltd, said after a press
conference, at which Waverley Mining released details of a statement issued
earlier to the London Stock Exchange, that the mood of the workforce was ``very
positive''.
``Of course they're sad but that's an emotive remark. They're sad because they
wanted it to be their own company,'' he said in Edinburgh.
Two years ago, he stated, he had spoken of two great resources - one being the
coal and the other the men.
``The third ingredient we required was money. Now I think we have all three
ingredients together - natural resources, human resources, and cash - in the
pot together.''
Mr Richards agreed it was ``with the gift of hindsight'' a lost cause from the
outset because they never had the required capital.
``If it had not been for Waverley Mining, the company would have been sunk
without trace and so would have all the coal, resources, and the employment.''
Waverley Mining Finance chairman Roy Shephard said they were giving the
workforce a great deal of dignity back.
``There is dignity in being at work and almost none in being out of it. They
can boast to their friends and colleagues on Monday that they are now
shareholders in a gold mine.''
British Coal closed Monktonhall in 1987 but the miners' consortium reopened it.
However, it quickly ran into financial problems and Waverley came in with a
rescue package in 1993.
Now, with this share offer about to be approved, it will be investing about
#15m in the mine.
Mr William McLucas, Waverley Mining Finance chief executive, said: ``The
company expects to receive the funds on Monday at which time they will be
making investment in Monktonhall and committing to buy the new equipment
essential to achieve two-face operation at the pit.''
``We wouldn't be there to invest in Monktonhall had it not been for the efforts
of the mineworkers to get the pit started,'' said Mr McLucas, who spoke of
accumulated losses of around #11m.
``Mining is about large-scale investment. It's not about small-scale equipment
when you are operating in a large and complicated colliery. We would not be
spending #15m if we didn't think it was worth it.''
He said the scale of resources at Monktonhall, in which 30% of the company's
total mining assets are now invested, was very substantial.
``It will see me past my sell-by date. We intend to be in business a long time.
What we need to be able to do is to supply the coal at a competitive price.''
</TEXT>
