<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What's in a name?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DR Guthrie's call (December 14) for uniformity in naming one's offspring
recalls the Victorian approach where the first son was named after his paternal
grandfather, the first daughter after her maternal grandmother, etc.
This meant that a couple had to have a number of children before being able to
name one on the basis of personal choice.
The alternative was to call the child by a different name from that registered.
In three generations of my late mother's family there were four Helens
christened who were known as Annie, Daisy, Nell, and Eleanor.
John F Crawford,
74 Drumsmittal Road,
North Kessock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
