<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Born-again baby Jesus takes his place in Nativity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW yesterday witnessed the second coming of Christ.
It was truly a historic occasion, and not without a touch of Glaswegian
malapropism. As the new glass-fibre baby Jesus - cost #600 - laid down his
sweet head, one young voice began singing ``A wean in a manger''.
Glasgow's original baby Jesus was stolen more than a week ago from the city's
George Square Nativity scene. The theft was not an opportunist prank as the
glass-encased scene is kept locked and the thief must have used heavy-duty wire
or bolt cutters to cut the lock.
The figures in the Nativity scene, which originally cost #16,000 when
commissioned in 1988, were made in clay and then cast in bronze-effect glass
fibre. The thief may have thought it was valuable bronze but would have
realised his mistake when he lifted the life-sized sculpture.
The theft allowed newspaper headline writers a field day of dreadful puns,
which included ``Jesus Heist'' and ``Halo, halo, halo''. Despite the continuing
publicity, there has been no trace of the original model.
Even an impassioned plea for information from no less a figure than Mr Pat
Lally, the council leader, failed to move the stony hearts of the culprits.
And lo, it came to pass yesterday that the second Jesus was laid in his manger,
again completing the Nativity scene which includes Mary, Joseph, the three wise
men, three shepherds, a donkey, ox, sheep, and an angel.
Glasgow Lord Provost Tommy Dingwall said: ``It was very disappointing to learn
that someone had been so mean minded as to steal the original baby Jesus
sculpture and sad that despite all the publicity we were unable to recover it''.
However, seasoned Nativity watchers will have noticed that the born-again
Christ looks slightly different.
``He looks completely different this time round because we couldn't remember
the first design we used six years ago,'' said the original creator, sculptor
Andrew Scott.
This time, the council is taking no chances. A security camera of the type used
to watch errant motorists is being trained on the manger night and day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UN hands Nato Bosnia role</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864442</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
United Nations
THE UN Security Council tonight authorised Nato to take over peacekeeping
operations in Bosnia.
The council's move legally allows Nato to deploy the new 60,000-strong
Implementation Force, known as IFOR, in its peace mission code-named Operation
Joint Endeavour
The Nato command had been waiting in Brussels for this green light from New
York to start pouring the troops and tonnes of weapons and ammunition into
Bosnia in the biggest military movement in Europe since the Second World War.
They are expected to start moving within days.
The resolution includes ``all necessary measures'' to ensure the peace
agreement'' signed in Paris on Thursday and negotiated in Dayton, Ohio last
month. This is UN shorthand for use of force.
However, the resolution does not explicitly call for Nato to arrest those
indicted by a war crimes tribunal.
Meanwhile, winter weather in Bosnia is seen as a mixed blessing.
It will make deployment of troops much harder, but at the same time fighting
has faded over the past three winters so the troops have less chance of walking
into a fresh flare-up.
Troop contributions range from 20,000 from the US, to 13,000 from Britain and
10,000 from France to 2000 from Russia and just 22 from Luxembourg.
Other countries such as Poland, Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Hungary, the
Baltic states, Malaysia, Pakistan, Egypt and Ukraine will among them provide
around 10,000 troops.
Alliance diplomats said Nato's 16 member states had learned some hard lessons
from the Bosnian conflict, which had forced it to reinvent itself in the
aftermath of the Cold War.
Britain's commander of Nato ground troops in Bosnia said he expects peace but
is prepared to fight.
``We are not going to war. We are going to implement a peace. We are going
there to implement their peace,'' Lieutenant General Michael Walker told a news
conference at ARRC - Allied Command Europe Rapid Reaction Corps - headquarters
in Germany.
The general said he expected to be in his new headquarters in Sarajevo by early
next week if ordered to move this weekend.
Gurkhas will fly to Bosnia in their first operational deployment since the
Falklands conflict. An advance party of the Nepalese troops will leave on
Sunday to be followed shortly afterwards by the remaining 100 soldiers whose
task will be to provide security and protection for divisional
headquarters.-Reuter/PA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FOREIGN DIGEST</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864443</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nigerian gas
deal signed
LAGOS: A consortium of four foreign companies signed a contract yesterday to
build a huge liquified natural gas plant in Nigeria despite the controversy
over the hanging of nine minority rights activists in the area.
Nigeria LNG Ltd said in a statement that with the signing of the contract the
final phase of the $4 billion project to utilise Nigeria's vast gas reserves
had started. Anglo-Dutch giant Shell and Western oil firms involved in the
project have rejected worldwide pressure to abandon the scheme in protest over
the hangings last month of writer Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight others in the
Movement for the Survival of Ogoni Peoples.
Simpson claim
LOS ANGELES: O.J Simpson's former girlfriend Paula Barbieri claimed that she
called him to break off their relationship only hours before his ex-wife and a
friend were murdered last year, a lawyer said yesterday. The model made the
claim during a pre-trial deposition in the wrongful-death lawsuit filed against
Simpson by the families of murder victims Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald
Goldman, according to Michael Brewer, a lawyer for Goldman's mother.
Salinas move
GENEVA: The sister-in-law of former Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
was freed from a Swiss jail yesterday after being arrested in a multi-million
pound drugs probe. Paulina Castanon, wife of Salinas' brother Raul, and her
brother Antonio Castanon were arrested on November 15 after allegedly trying to
use false documents to withdraw funds from her husband's #55m Geneva bank
account.
Dini survives
ROME: Italian Prime Minister Lamberto Dini survived two nail-biting confidence
votes in his drive to force through a deficit-cutting budget for 1996, but he
faces yet another test next week. ``I hope everyone calms down and that reason
prevails on Monday too,'' the technocrat premier, who was in Madrid at a
European Union summit, told reporters after yesterday's votes.
Bodies found
SANTIAGO: Chilean police yesterday dug up the bodies of two men believed to be
left-wing activists kidnapped after a 1973 military coup. They found the bodies
buried together after receiving an anonymous phone tip that workers kidnapped
after the 1973 coup were killed and buried at the spot in the northern city of
Copiapo, local radio reports said.
Whitewater vote
WASHINGTON: Setting the stage for a constitutional confrontation, a United
States Senate committee voted yesterday to go to court to obtain Whitewater
notes as the White House denied any similarities to Watergate and vowed
President Bill Clinton would fight the issue on principle.
</TEXT>
