<HEADLINE>Not so Gay Paree for Scottish exiles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are roughly 2000 ex-patriot Scots living in and around Paris. Precisely
seven of them, out of the 91 who had paid #60 for tickets, struggled in their
tartan finery through many miles of traffic jams and crowded pavements on
December 1, to the Caledonian Society's St Andrews Night Dinner in the centre
of town.
Some of them took as long as five hours. Unfortunately, the man due to address
the haggis arrived last of all - so late, in fact, that the haggis had all been
eaten. Indeed, it was in the early stages of digestion, so just before the
sweet course a spare beastie had to be ceremoniously presented for a recital of
the Burns poem and the ritual stabbing.
As a few Metros and even the occasional mainline train took to the tracks
yesterday, marking, perhaps, an end to a conflict which has paralysed France,
exhausted and harassed Scots have begun looking back over a whole month without
public transport.
Second last into the St Andrews dinner, for example, around 10pm, after four
hours in traffic jams, was 41-year-old accountant from Hamilton, Tom Dowie.
This former Glasgow Academy man, who has worked in Paris for 15 years, has
spent up to 90 minutes driving a few miles to and from work every day - modest
enough suffering and frustration by recent standards. His English wife Pru,
anxious to get her Stripping of the Willow and other numbers into shape for
December 1, had walked for two hours to a training session with the French
Scottish dance group, Chardon d'Ecosse, only to find herself locked out of the
building, and obliged to walk back again.
Some have been suffering less than others. Printer Willie MacGillivray, 53,
from Brodick, Arran, lives near his work, a business in the southwest Paris
suburb of Boulogne, puts a small bicycle in the boot of his car to get around
on occasional trips into town. His wife walks to work, three of their five
children use the bicycle, moped and lifts in a boyfriend's car, while daughter
Fiona has been staying with a friend near her school and the youngest son,
Andrew, walks to primary school.
``There's a bit of Dunkirk spirit. Because things are difficult, people are
determined to resist. My wife and I come into town every Sunday for church and
attendance at the Scots Kirk, which has around 90 members, has actually been
about 25% higher than usual since the strike began,'' Mr McGillivray said.
Investment banker Ian McLeod, 49, from north Ayrshire, who lives in the
southern suburb of Clamalt with his Glasgow-born wife Marion, has been taking
over two hours for the seven-mile drive to work. One evening, they even spent
half an hour driving the first 150 yards out of his bank's garage.
``Some colleagues have been spending up to four hours each way, every day, but
attendance among staff has been excellent,'' he said. ``The strike has had a
disastrous effect on productivity in secretarial work, with people having to
leave mid-afternoon in order to get home and look after children. ``I set off
around 7am and drive back at 8pm. It's a lottery every day as to how bad the
jams are. Christmas shopping has obviously been postponed,'' he added.
One of the angriest Scots in Paris is George Mutch, 48, from Keith, who has
worked in Paris for 24 years and teaches English in Paris Lycees to academic
high fliers preparing university entrance.
``I have trudged hundreds of miles over the past month,'' he said. ``I'm on my
fourth pair of Westons, and I feel like sending the bill to union leader Marc
Blondel. He ought to be the most hated man in France.
``Monday, with three hours walking for four hours teaching, is the worst day.
But I feel my life is in danger - kids on roller skates and motorised scooters
on pavements have been the biggest hazard, but I refuse to be beaten. Why
should we give in? We're being held hostage for a strike which is unjustified
and unjustifiable.''
Wouldn't a bicycle have made things easer? ``There are no bikes to be had in
the shops in my area. The best they could manage was a build-it-yourself kit
from Italy. I had no intention of turning my house into a construction yard''.
A 43-year-old Inverness-born painter, Mr Fred Crayk, who has been working in
Paris for a year, has found the strike exciting. ``The sense of stress is
incredible,'' he said. ``This strike brings out the primitive extincts from
under the civilisation. I witnessed a medieval style battle between cars at a
street corner yesterday and people slamming into each other, getting out and
hurling abuse.
``I have been walking miles to appointments in galleries and getting there
late, and paintings I have been posting to London have been taking ages to get
there. I nevertheless support the workers 100%. It's interesting, in these
post-industrial times, that there is still a spirit among working people to
preserve their basic social rights.''
Fellow artist Calum Fraser, 39, from Edinburgh, whose studio is in the flat he
shares with his girlfriend Sophie, is philosophical.
``I walk a lot anyway, and Sophie teaches at a school within easy walking
distance, so the strike has not been much of an inconvenience, although it is a
bit of a drag.
``Everybody seems to be enjoying it in a way, leaving work after lunch and
putting signs in shop windows saying they're closed because of the strikes. The
chaos on the streets is almost theatrical. Red lights used to be more of a
suggestion than order for Paris drivers. Now they don't give a damn.''
</TEXT>
