<HEADLINE>Recognising the parental role</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864445</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I READ with regret about the imminent departure of Frank Pignatelli from the
service of Strathclyde Education Department coinciding with the inception of
the new unitary authorities in April, 1996.
As a school parent in Strathclyde, I would commend the director for the many
noteworthy contributions he made in order to effect improvement in the quality
of education offered in our schools.
I would single out in particular his initiative in setting up the Parents'
Consultation Group on the Curriculum of which I am a member, after being
successful in the ballot necessitated by the high level of interest amongst
parents.
Mr Pignatelli recognised the fact that parents are the prime educators of their
children and have unique views on the way they are being taught and cared for
in our schools.
The group meetings afforded ordinary parents the opportunity to discuss their
views and concerns with Mr Pignatelli as the most senior manager of the largest
education authority in Europe. It may surprise most parents to note that their
children spend only one-ninth of their time during the year at school and Mr
Pignatelli always emphasised at the PCGC meetings that parental input was
essential to enable all youngsters to acquire literacy skills and achieve their
full potential.
I would also like to mention the director's commitment in ensuring to the best
of his ability and with the resources available that all children were able to
have access to the education system regardless of their parental social status
or home address, with particular reference to children having special
educational needs.
I am in no doubt that wherever Mr Pignatelli's future lies his reputation will
go before him guaranteeing happiness and success.
Rita Smith,
10 Hunting Lodge Gardens,
Barncluith, Hamilton.
</TEXT>
