<HEADLINE>Labour calls on watchdog to rethink plan for lifting restraints on charges BT on line for dearer phone bills</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864446</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WATCHDOG's plans to allow BT to raise bills by as much as it likes were
yesterday condemned as ``astonishing'' by Labour.
Shadow Consumer Affairs Minister Nigel Griffiths said millions would be
``horrified'' by proposals from the regulator, the Office of Telecommunications
(Oftel).
The Consumers' Association also said it was very concerned at the idea.
Oftel director general Don Cruickshank, however, defended his plans. He said BT
was facing increasing challenges from cable firms and argued that competition
would be enough to keep prices in check.
``I feel . . . it is now an appropriate time to lift the constraint,'' he said.
At present, BT has to limit any increases in its exchange line rental charges
to the inflation rate plus 2% a year.
Mr Cruickshank went on: ``This would give BT freedom, if they chose, to adopt a
much more imaginative approach to the way they price services, particularly for
residential customers.
``I believe BT would use this freedom to introduce a family of price packages
and customers would choose which package suited them best.''
Mr Griffiths was far from convinced. ``This year, Oftel allowed BT to increase
its line rental charges at nearly double the rate of inflation,'' he said.
``The millions of senior citizens and others will be horrified at the prospect
of unlimited increases.
``Yet again, the regulator is giving the green light to BT to increase this
very profitable element.''
CA officials have long complained that competition has failed to dent BT's
domination of the domestic market.
Senior researcher Colin Meek said: ``We are very concerned that BT might use
this opportunity to increase line rentals, which for many consumers is the
largest part of their bill.
``Any increased freedom for BT must be matched with greater responsibility to
ensure that no consumers lose out. BT is already in a position to offer far
more and far better packages to the public.''
BT had been asking for some time for more flexibility in charging packages to
allow it to tailor bills to customers' needs.
A BT spokeswoman said: ``We welcome the fact that the regulator recognises the
range and scope of competition that is now in the market place allowing him to
relax controls.''
Oftel's plans will be subject to consultation before they become reality.
</TEXT>
