<HEADLINE>Police checks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIGURES issued yesterday by the Association of Chief Police Officers in
Scotland show that there is a drop in the percentage of drivers who failed or
refused a breath test over the first 18 days of the latest drink-drive campaign
(December 13).
This is splendid, but are the figures true? How are they compiled?
At 8am on December 7 I was delayed at the Bearsden end    of Maryhill Road by a
long  tail-back of cars caused by a police check at the roadside.
They were not checking for exhaust emissions; unpaid road tax; or stolen goods.
They were stopping drivers of cars and buses in the morning rush hour, midweek,
on their way to work for signs of drink.
One report said the police had breathalysed 267 drivers, none of them positive.
Just what they expected?
Is this really in the public's best interest? I think not, but it could well be
an easy way to massage the statistics in order to achieve a favourable result.
Marjorie F Fairley,
12 Birkhall Drive,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
