<HEADLINE>Tories try to seed rural partnerships Village halls to turn into power house</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE underlying aims of people, prosperity, and partnership, set out in the
White Paper on Rural Scotland, echo the Scottish Secretary's promise to empower
local people.
The proposals were widely welcomed yesterday.
Critics, however, asked where the resources were to turn them into action, in
the light of budgetary cuts this week to Scottish Enterprise, Highlands and
Islands Enterprise, and Scottish Natural Heritage.
Lord Lindsay, Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries, and the Environment, wants a
Scottish Rural Partnership to provide the tools for communities to work towards
realising their ambitions. Its main components would be partnerships to bring
together at local level all the agencies with responsibilities in rural areas;
a National Partnership Group to co-ordinate support and assistance to the these
local partnerships; and a #2.5m fund made up of #1.5m existing grant assistance
schemes and #1m of new money.
Other features of the White Paper include a scheme to reduce the burden of
rates on shops servicing isolated communities, new research on rural crime, the
management of small schools, the use of the planning system to open up new
business opportunities, reviews of indicative forestry strategies, and natural
heritage designations.
Rural Forum, Scotland's alliance of rural communities and organisations,
welcomed the document. Its chairman, Ms Deirdre Hutton, said: ``Rural Forum has
always argued that the challenges facing rural Scotland could only be addressed
effectively if rural people were given the lead, supported by public
authorities working closely and properly co-ordinated.''
However, she warned: ``The White Paper does not itself address issues such as
poor transport provision, rural homelessness, access by rural communities to
the land and local natural resources, low incomes and social exclusion, lack of
access to opportunity for young people, and the many other problems confronting
rural Scotland.
``It does, however, provide a mechanism that should make this easier. The key
to the success of this new mechanism will be the commitment of the local
partnerships.''
Mrs Ray Michie, for the Scottish Liberal Democrats, said: ``It gives no
indication as to how local authorities are going to pay for the promised access
to woodlands and no immediate methods for tackling the housing problems which
are as acute in rural areas as in the towns.''
The SNP's rural affairs spokesman, Mr Rob Gibson, said that until Scotland's
feudal landholding system was swept away, Scots would have no influence on what
happened to their land.
The Scottish Landowners' Federation welcomed the emphasis on the need for
economic prosperity in rural areas, and the recognition of rural areas as a
working landscape, and the NFU in Scotland welcomed plans to simplify natural
heritage designations.
Mr Stuart Housden, the RSPB's director in Scotland, said: ``The proposed
agricultural conservation scheme, if suitably targeted and funded, could help
meet biodiversity conservation objectives, launched earlier this week by
Ministers. However, the White Paper is vague as to the resources available and
scope of the scheme.''
Power to the people?...................13
Leader comment...........................14
</TEXT>
