<HEADLINE>Pregnant woman attacked with bat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864452</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PREGNANT woman and her two-year-old child were attacked in their car as they
waited at traffic lights, a court heard yesterday.
Stirling Sheriff Court was told the attack, on September 18, happened at a
junction on a main road in Stirling's Raploch area, which has one of the
highest crime rates in Central Scotland.
Procurator-fiscal John Miller said Paul Rothwell, 25, appeared to be crazed by
drugs when he staggered into the road as the woman and child, who cannot be
named for legal reasons, waited for the lights to turn green. He was shouting
and swearing and he stepped in front of their car and raised a baseball bat as
if he was going to smash the windscreen.
Mr Miller said a passer-by distracted Rothwell and the woman managed to get her
car into gear.
She ignored the red light in her panic and started to drive off while trying to
shield her child who was fastened in the front passenger seat.
As she did so, Rothwell struck at the passenger door next to the child and
again at the rear of the car, before running after the car as the woman drove
away. A car behind had to drive round Rothwell, who flung his bat after it.
The court was given no explanation for the attack.
Rothwell, of Weir Street, Raploch, admitted vandalism, placing the mother and
child in fear, and resisting arrest.
In a separate incident, he admitted assaulting his father at his home at Weir
Street on December 11 and punching him repeatedly about the head and body. He
also admitted causing a breach of the peace outside Stirling Sheriff Court.
Sheriff Robert Younger remanded him in custody for reports until January 5.
</TEXT>
