<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The pressure game</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PREMIER ROUND-UP:
CELTIC hope to continue their recent impressive form when Falkirk visit
Parkhead today as the premier division reaches its half-way stage.
``We have the chance to put some extra psychological pressure on leaders
Rangers if we win,'' said Celtic assistant manager Billy Stark. ``If we collect
three points we would be just one point behind them when they play Motherwell
next week. It may only last a couple of days but we would like to do that.''
Celtic's play has been impressive of late and, as Stark added: ``It will be
difficult for us to improve on the performance the team gave against Hibs last
week. Tom Boyd has been suffering from a touch of flu but he has been training
over the past few days and we're hopeful that he will be able to face Falkirk.''
Malky McKay will continue as the replacement for the suspended John Hughes.
John Lambie, the Falkirk manager, returned from Spain to Brockville yesterday
still involved in negotiations to bring a player from there to join his club.
``I am still involved in negotiations about a player in Spain,'' said Lambie.
``That's all I can tell you. We're still hoping to do something but it would
have been good if we could have brought him back and played him in this game.
We will have the same squad as last week with big Kevin James added to it.''
Another man who could be joining the ranks at Brockville is Partick Thistle's
Albert Craig. The 33-year-old was club captain when Lambie was in charge at
Firhill, but appears to have fallen from favour under new Thistle manager,
Murdo MacLeod.
Now Lambie was said to be keen to take Craig to Falkirk and MacLeod admits
there has been contact. ``There is an ongoing situation with Albert,'' said
MacLeod. ``He's not in the team at the moment and a swop deal has been
mentioned. We'll have to wait and see what develops.''
Thistle travel to Rugby Park today to face Kilmarnock and MacLeod knows what to
expect. ``Killie had a great result against Falkirk last week. They are a team
capable of causing problems and Tom Brown is playing well.''
Another club playing well is Aberdeen, who take on Hearts at Pittodrie. Manager
Roy Aitken, seeking a third successive home victory, admitted: ``Hearts have
changed personnel by adding a cosmopolitan touch which has strengthened their
squad.
``However, it is what we do which concerns me. I have been happy with the
progress we have made this season. I have set a pattern of play but it is not
rigid. They are allowed to express themselves, show flair. But there is
improvement still to be made, particularly in off-the-ball situations. I want
us in possession as often as possible.''
``We need a third win to consolidate our league position and must produce the
right attitude and determination again for it will be a tough match.''
Captain Stewart McKimmie is suspended along with transfer-listed midfielder
Peter Hetherston. Striker Scott Booth is again missing with a thigh injury and
Brian Grant will take over from McKimmie at full back.
The last time Raith Rovers played Hibs, Jimmy Nicholl's side won 3-0 and it is
for sure that Hibs will be out for revenge at Easter Road this afternoon.
Success would take Raith to within three points of Hibs, who sit above them in
fourth place in the premier table.
Raith are the surprise packets of the division so far this season, their
impressive form having taken the Kirkcaldy team into the top half of the table
following promotion.
</TEXT>
