<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Destructive pupils are the major problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHENEVER politicians talk about education they seem to do so as if it were a
commodity produced by investment that could be bought with money, and as if
schools consisted only of teachers and officials.
Recent reports on the extent of smoking, drinking, and drug-taking among school
children are surely enough to remind us that schools are largely what their
pupils make them.
Neither money nor legislation can make all schools equally effective so long as
the homes and communities from which their pupils come vary as drastically as
they do.
Neither paying teachers more nor sacking them as inefficient can alter the
truth recently pointed out by a parent and teacher: ``The biggest single factor
in pulling down educational standards is not underfunding, but the millions of
teacher hours wasted on destructive pupils''.
I have yet to hear of any politician usefully addressing that problem.
Norman M Bowman,
2 Bute Terrace, Saltcoats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rangers lose '96 final to hearts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864455</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS have been prevented from hosting a European football final because
there is no room at the inn.
Ibrox had been in line to stage the European Cup Winners' Cup final on May 8
next year but a lack of available hotel beds in the Glasgow area for the match
led UEFA yesterday to award it to Brussels.
A spokesman for Greater Glasgow Tourist Board and Convention Bureau said last
night about 2000 beds had already been booked for a cardiologists' convention
in the city between May 7 and 9, taking up nearly two-thirds of the 3000 four
and five-star rooms the city has at the moment.
He said: ``May also tends to be a traditionally high-occupancy period for
hotels in the city, with the rate running at about 70%.''
Mr Campbell Ogilvie, secretary of Rangers, said the club was obviously
disappointed by the news, announced by UEFA in Birmingham.
He said: ``Last week, when we heard we were in with a strong chance of being
considered for the match, we contacted both local hotels and hotels within the
Scottish central belt as we were fully aware that it was imperative that a
maximum number of rooms in top-class hotels were required.
``We also heard last Friday that a major international convention was being
held in Glasgow between May 7 and 9, 1996.''
Mr Ogilvie added: ``We have been assured by UEFA that this was the only
stumbling block in our bid and that UEFA themselves are impressed by Ibrox and
the operation of the stadium.''
q.The Olympic Stadium in Rome will stage the European Cup final on May 22 next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SuspendedSole has few regrets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAVID Sole, the 1990 Grand Slam captain suspended from all involvement in rugby
until the end of the season for bringing the game into disrepute, does not
regret making the comments which led to one of the most severe bans handed down
by the Scottish Rugby Union.
``I certainly regret the furore that developed around my comments and the fact
that the whole issue seemed to get caught up in other people's agendas, but I
do not regret making the comments which were made in the heat of the moment
after a crucial game.''
Sole who retired in 1992 after having captained Scotland on a record 25
occasions in major internationals, later becoming assistant coach at Edinburgh
Academicals, is sorry for the inconvenience and embarrassment caused to his
club by his ``tantamount to cheating'' remarks.
Details of the ban were announced yesterday by the Scottish Rugby Union after a
disciplinary hearing at Murrayfield on Thursday night. The severity of the
suspension has taken many observers by surprise.
The affair has dragged on for five weeks since Sole made the now infamous
observation on the performance of Kelso referee Colin Henderson after
Academicals' premiership game against Melrose.
Henderson awarded nine penalties in succession against Academicals, and Melrose
won with an injury-time try which placed the now relegated Academicals deeper
into the mire.
The Union's initial attempt to stage a disciplinary hearing was sidelined when
Sole said he could not attend because he was babysitting. Club officials
appeared, and Sole made a written submission to Thursday's hearing whose
verdict, strangely, was predicted 12 hours in advance by a media report.
The SRU acted against a backdrop of a situation which was spiralling out of
control. Referees, with international official Ray Megson in the vanguard, were
threatening to boycott Raeburn Place until the situation had been resolved.
It is not the first time Sole has been out of favour with the SRU. In fact
there has been little love lost between the former Scotland captain and certain
members of the Union. His early retirement was precipitated by the comment by a
senior SRU man that he was a ``cancer at the heart of Scottish rugby.''
Yesterday's statement from Murrayfield declared: ``The sentence reflects the
SRU's policy of providing the fullest support for referees and the absolute
priority to promote good behaviour on and off the field. Concern was expressed
that, despite opportunities being given to appear at a meeting, and to
apologise to the referee, David Sole was unable to attend a meeting, but gave a
written explanation and has not apologised to the referee.''
Sole said yesterday: ``Nothing surprises me. At the end of the day, the
suspension hurts the club more than it hurts me, and that saddens me. I'm
involved not just with the 1st XV but with the under-21 side and the mini and
the midi-sections on Sundays. To that extent the decision is going to have a
significant impact on the club. I wonder if I'm still allowed to watch my son
playing mini-rugby.
``In my letter to the Union, I said I regretted that my comments had received
such widespread coverage in the media. The SRU say that I have not apologised
to the referee. Well, it's a small but significant point, but I was never asked
to apologise to him.
``I had an inkling that the SRU would do something rather small-minded and,
maybe, some people will think that their action comes into that category. Since
I retired as a player, I have tried to give something back to the game but I am
not going to be allowed to do that now.
The ban, which runs until May 11, means that Sole will not be able to coach
Academicals during their Cup campaign. He is banned from acting in any capacity
as player, coach, referee or touch-judge.
Privately yesterday, senior officials of the Academical club, one of the
founder members of the SRU, were furious at the severity of the sentence and
threatening resignation. They will respond officially next week.
Sole had disassociated the club from his comments and the club had told the
Union that they did not condone what their assistant coach had said.
Henderson, and Megson, who is scheduled to referee Academicals' game against
Edinburgh Borderers on Boxing Day, had no comment to make.
</TEXT>
