<HEADLINE>Scotland, the remake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alistair Richardson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT a year 1996 has been for movies with a Scottish theme! Looking back, 1995
was only the start - on the back of Rob Roy and Braveheart, Hollywood went
Scotland crazy . . .
Good news in January of 1996, with word that Braveheart Two: The Return was set
to go into production. Directed by James Cameron, The Return combines
thirteenth-century history with twenty-first century science. A scrap of
Wallace's DNA is found encased in aspic, scientists clone the DNA, re-creating
Scotland's greatest patriot. Using the technology of time travel, Wallace is
sent back, accompanied by his new best friend (Danny Glover) to change history.
The pre-release publicity for the movie says it all: ``They disembowelled him,
they chopped him into bits - but now he's back, he's pissed off and it's time
to kick some English ass . . .''
March - and Quentin Tarantino secured the option to remake Whisky Galore. In an
interview with Premiere Tarantino recalled: ``I just thought these Scottish
guys were so cool, heisting all that Scotch. But this time I figure we should
bring it up to date y'know. Less of that gentle teasing of authority shit, more
like the villagers really fall out over it y'know. And there's this big scene
where they cover each other with their shotguns and like, it's a stand off
y'know and then bang! And that guy, the butler guy in Upstairs Downstairs, well
he doesn't take all the shit his Mom's laying on him, he just takes his 44
magnum and she's history!''
The legend of Sawney Bean attracted the interest of Martin Scorsese. The
director, announced in April that he would produce the movie of the family's
story. Scorcese's favourite actor, De Niro, is already preparing for the role
of ``Pa Bean'' with his usual thoroughness.
Scorcese told the press: ``I was over at his house for dinner the other night
and the meat on the plate? I swear to God I thought it was pork, I tell you I
was shocked when Bobbie told me and y'know, Bobbie being Bobbie he just
laughed, the way he does.''
Few actors are bigger than Tom Hanks in Hollywood so his decision to star in
The Mike Forsyth Story came as a surprise. In May, on the Letterman Show, Hanks
explained what had attracted him to the story; ``Here's this guy OK? He's the
head guy for this political party that no-one in Scotland likes. And he goes to
England to help his new buddy, John Major, and then, one day, he says, `No
John, I gotta go back to Scotland, the people need me,' so Mike Forsyth comes
back to Scotland and he tries to be friendly with everyone and they all say `Go
Away! Get out of here!'
``Anyone else, they'd leave right? But not Mike, he smiles, he walks around in
public, he won't leave. I mean, Forrest Gump was just a story right? but this
guy's for real . . .'' John Major will be played by Michael Caine.
George Lucas is the prime exponent of the mythic hero genre in Hollywood. Think
of his Star Wars trilogy, the Indiana Jones movies, all with strong heroic
characters capable of transcending common sense notions of reality prepared to
risk everything in the pursuit of an impossible dream. Fergus McCann: The
Search for the Biscuit Tin began filming in June.
Keanu Reeves optioned Speed Two in July. This time he battles to keep the speed
of the bus up to 5mph on the M8 between Townhead and Charing Cross.
Finally, in September, Arnold Schwarzenegger optioned Gavin the Barbarian a
biopic based on the life of the erstwhile captain of our national rugby team.
Acting as consultant to the production, Gavin was characteristically effusive:
``I've read the script and it's really quite good . . .''
Alistair Richardson previews some
forthcoming attractions
</TEXT>
