<HEADLINE>Clan Ross seat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRUCE McKain, your Law Correspondent, is mistaken in his report on Mr Mohammed
Al Fayed's legal action relating to Balnagowan Castle in Easter Ross (December
12)
Balnagowan is most certainly not ``the seat of Clan Ross'', and has not been so
since a hereditary chief occupied it - and that was 1711 when the thirteenth
and last Baron of Balnagowan died. He, like myself, was a descendant of the
thirteenth-century Earldom of Ross.
While Mr Al Fayed's contribution to the preservation of Balnagowan as a
property is widely recognised, he most certainly has no connection whatsoever
with Clan Ross whose ``seat'' is where this Chief now is; and that is elsewhere
in Scotland, a country in which I am proud to live on a permanent and full-time
basis.
David Ross of Ross,
Chief of the Name and Arms of Ross,
Fettercairn,
Kincardineshire.
</TEXT>
