<HEADLINE>Court's confused signals Rail ruling fails to halt sell-offC</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent, DUNCAN BLACKe</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL privatisation will press ahead despite a court judgment which threw the
franchise plans for some services into confusion, the Government insisted last
night.
The Save Our Railways pressure group won a partial victory at the Court of
Appeal in London in its challenge to proposals for seven initial franchises,
including InterCity East Coast.
Campaigners said the ruling would force a rethink of the minimum levels of
passenger service required of franchises throughout the entire rail network.
Labour leader Tony Blair immediately issued a fresh call for the Government to
scrap rail privatisation.
He said: ``This is a hammer blow to the Government's plans. We have warned them
time and time again that this privatisation would not work, that the broken
promises would catch up on them, and the public simply would not tolerate the
destruction of the railways.
``Ministers should take the hint and admit defeat. They should realise that the
longer they press on the more damage they will do to themselves and the
railways.''
However, franchise director Roger Salmon insisted ``passenger rail franchising
is proceeding on schedule'' and was backed in this by Transport Secretary Sir
George Young.
The court ruling is complex but basically means that the Save Our Railways
(SOR) campaign has won part of its case. SOR had challenged the legality of
franchising proposals for the first three lines to be sold off: Great Western,
South West Trains, and LTS (London, Tilbury, and Southend) Rail.
It had also challenged plans for the next four: InterCity East Coast, Network
South Central, Midland Main Line, and Gatwick Express.
Last week, High Court judge Mr Justice Macpherson had cleared Mr Salmon of
accusations that he had unlawfully set minimum passenger service levels at too
low a figure.
Yesterday, however, three senior judges, led by Master of the Rolls Sir Thomas
Bingham, overturned the Macpherson ruling in relation to the second tranche of
lines. They ruled that Mr Salmon had failed properly to base minimum passenger
service levels for the sell-off on the current BR timetable, as he had been
instructed to do by former Transport Secretary John MacGregor.
On a technicality, the judges paved the way for Mr Salmon still to proceed with
the sale of the first three lines, ruling that there had been undue delay in
SOR launching its application for judicial review with regard to these.
The overall judgment left it clear for both sides to claim a victory of sorts,
though the balance of the argument seemed to lie with SOR.
Sir George Young said the court's rejection of the challenge to the first
tranche of franchises ``allows the franchise director to proceed with these and
I hope he will be in a position to do so.''
He added: ``So far as the other franchises are concerned, we will, of course,
be giving careful consideration to the court's judgment.
``This judgment does not affect the timing of Railtrack's flotation next
spring.''
The second set of franchises will probably now be sold off in the spring but
only after the minimum service levels have been revised.
Mr Salmon said: ``I welcome the Court of Appeal's rejection of the challenge to
the first group of three franchises. The decision allows me to proceed with
these sales and I expect to make announcements shortly.''
He said he was confident that the details on the first three franchises ``will
show the benefits that franchising will bring to passengers''.
He added: ``The court has given us leave to appeal against the decision in
relation to the further four franchises. We will be giving careful
consideration to this and to the other options available to us. Today's
judgment means that passenger rail franchising is proceeding on schedule.''
However, SOR secretary Keith Bill said: ``We have had a tremendous victory
today which will bring great benefits to rail passengers the length and breadth
of the country. The whole of the Government's rail privatisation process has
been thrown into chaos and they will have to think again.''
Mr Bill said SOR intended to take the matter of the LTS Rail ruling to the
House of Lords on Monday: ``We want the Lords to prevent any sell-off of LTS as
the Court of Appeal today said the line's PSR (Passenger Service Requirement)
had been formulated in breach of Government instructions.''
Shadow Transport Minister Brian Wilson called for the sacking of Mr Salmon and
said: ``The court ruling is wonderful news which confirms the reckless way in
which Ministers have been pursuing the dogma of rail privatisation. They should
now throw in the towel.''
For the Liberal Democrats, transport spokesman David Chidgey said: ``As
predicted, rail privatisation is proving to be the Government's poll tax on
wheels. It is time for the Government to think again, admit they are wrong, and
put the interests of the travelling public before party dogma.''
Mr Salmon had hoped to announce the names of winners of the bidding for both
South West Trains and LTS Rail last Tuesday. A separate announcement about
Great Western was due shortly afterwards.
The South West franchise is thought to have been won by Perth-based bus company
Stagecoach.
