<HEADLINE>Power to the rural people?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Elizabeth Buie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Elizabeth Buie examines a new initiative aimed at tackling the problems which
blight many rural areas
AT THE touch of a button yesterday, the Government's policy document for rural
Scotland was sent across the country on the Internet computer system.
Any villager, from the Borders to John O'Groats, could have read the Scottish
Office's new initiatives to solve the problems of rural unemployment, crime,
and conflicting land use 40 minutes after the White Paper had been presented to
Parliament - provided, of course, they had the necessary technology.
The Earl of Lindsay, Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and the Environment in
Scotland, had picked the ideal location for the launch. Strathyre, a few miles
north of Callander, had its own tele-cottage, an award-winning village shop,
charming hotel and pub, and fine landscape.
The problem in Scotland is, however, that not all rural areas are so fortunate.
Many, particularly the former mining villages, are blighted by unemployment.
Others have inadequate transport systems and are in danger of losing their
local schools.
Where jobs do exist, too often they are poorly paid and do not match up to the
educational qualifications or aspirations of rural dwellers. Communities such
as Assynt may have the enterprise and vision to invest in computerised links,
but many remain untouched by the technology revolution.
The new policy document Rural Scotland: People, Prosperity and Partnership has
as its main plank devolution of more power to local communities.
The Government hopes to achieve that empowerment of communities by establishing
another quango, the Scottish National Rural Partnership, and a number of local
partnerships whose membership and composition will reflect each individual
community's needs and interests.
It has also created a new Scottish Rural Partnership Fund to provide
pump-priming assistance to local partnerships. Its #2.5m budget includes #1.5m
of existing grant assistance and #1m of new money. Its objectives will be to
bring together a number of existing small-grant schemes relevant to rural
Scotland; to offer financial support to projects proposed by local rural
partnerships on behalf of communities; and to part-fund the initial costs
incurred in developing local rural partnerships.
While the initial funding level is acknowledged to be pretty frugal, Lord
Lindsay said he hoped that future spending rounds would release more money. And
it is on this thorny subject, money, that the Government's proposals attract
most criticism.
George Foulkes, Labour MP for Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley, pointed to the
fact that the Cumnock and Doon Valley area had suffered a 28% decline in
population between 1981 and 1991. Recent visits to Highland towns such as Fort
William and Strathpeffer had shown them to be relatively prosperous, largely
due to the Highlands and Islands' EU Objective One status.
With cuts of #33m to Scottish Enterprise's budget for training and employment
initiatives, how could towns in rural Ayrshire and Wigtown expect to revive
their fortunes, he asked.
``This will all be window dressing unless they have the resources behind
them,'' he says.
It was a comment echoed by the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations,
which, along with a variety of other organisations, agencies and quangos, will
sit on the new Scottish National Rural Partnership body.
SCVO director Martin Sime warned that the voluntary sector will be looking for
assurances that funding now available to rural charities and voluntary
organisations will not be lost through being redirected via the national
partnership fund.
There were some concrete measures outlined yesterday: a scheme to reduce the
burden of rates on the village shop; proposals for a Rural Business Use Class
in the planning system; changes in tax assessment for rural business units;
guidance on how to improve rural development and employment opportunities; and
a new duty on water authorities to take account of the interests of the rural
customer.
However, only time will tell whether the new partnership mechanisms are up to
the task of tackling the real countryside problems of transport, homelessness,
access to land and natural resources, low incomes, and social exclusion.
</TEXT>
