<HEADLINE>Yeltsin urges Russians not to vote for the past</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow
IN an impassioned appeal to the undecided, the indifferent and the angry,
President Boris Yeltsin today warned Russians not to vote for hardliners who
want to return to a totalitarian past.
``We don't appreciate what we have until it's gone. Freedom is like that,'' he
said in a nationwide television speech. ``It's like air. When you have it, you
don't notice it.''
Yeltsin's speech amounted to an 11th-hour attempt to prevent the expected
success of the Communist Party in Sunday's elections for the 450-seat State
Duma, the lower house of parliament.
``You should not allow the forces of the past to come to power again,'' he told
voters in a clear reference to the communists.
Although Yeltsin has stayed out of the election campaign, the results will be
seen as a rough referendum on his rule and a dress rehearsal for next summer's
presidential poll.
Russians are angry about the loss of their social safety net, at how inflation
has eaten up their savings and turned pensions and salaries into small change.
They are fed up with crime, corruption and Yeltsin's bloody war in breakaway
Chechnya.
q Russian troops today regained control of Chechnya's second city, Gudermes,
after Defence Minister Pavel Grachev threatened a ``no-nonsense'' response to
rebel attacks.
Russian forces all but sealed off the capital Grozny to ensure independence
fighters did not also infiltrate the battered Chechen capital in a campaign
apparently aimed at disrupting elections in Chechnya.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
