<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Herald's regular team of reviewers listen to the best sounds around
The Original American Decca Recordings, Ella Fitzgerald (MCA)
q If your finances won't quite stretch to Ella's four-CD, 80-track Ella - The
Legendary American Decca Recordings, then search out this single-CD
distillation. It covers the years 1937 to 1954, when she was working firmly
within the context of pop, and is an absolute stoatir. As well as being
accompanied by her own Famous Orchestra, the First Lady of Song is captured
with such notable sidemen as Louis Armstrong and Louis Jordan. Buy this and
then begin saving for the full works.
Pulp Surfin', various (Del-Fi)
q After having fallen in love with Dick Dale's awesome guitar-power on the Pulp
Fiction soundtrack, the rest of the world has at long last caught up with
Scotland's own Beat Poets, lone disciples of surf-rock toot'n'twang for almost
a decade. This collection will please California wave-catchers of all vintages,
whether they reside in California or, like the Beat Poets, Strathbungo. It
utilises classic tunes from Del-Fi's sixties archives - Pipeline by the Lively
Ones; Night Prowler by the Deuce Coupes; Link Wray's Rumble - as well as
offering new directions in beatily-poetic instrumentalising.
Dig the timeless sound of today's Insect Surfers! Marvel at the ongoing musical
rehabilitation of surf-guru Brian Wilson on In My Moondreams, in which the
erstwhile Beach Boy is assisted by Andy Paley. There's also a Frank Zappa
novelty track from 1963 (Letter From Jeepers) and the Bobby Fuller Four
performing the aforementioned Dick Dale's reborn hit, Misirlou. Tune in, turn
on, twang up!
</TEXT>
