<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tis the season to be strategic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Clay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE are coming up to the end of the year, the traditional time for investors to
look back on how their investments have performed and work out strategies for
the next 12 months.
This year was difficult to predict but turned out well. And the market tipsters
are scratching their heads again for inspiration about 1996. On the plus side,
we have inflation that is low and looking likely to stay that way. The world's
economies are slowing down but are still predicted to grow allowing company
earnings also to rise.
David Kern, chief economist at the NatWest Group, is looking for OECD growth of
2.4% next year, the same as this, and 2.5% in 1997, but he expects EU growth to
turn out at 2.7% for this year, down from 2.9%, and drop to 2.4% next.
The Chancellor has forecast the UK economy should grow by 3% next year, but
City economists are pitching their expectations below that - some even below
2%. All that should keep interest rates low. The crystal ball gazers at top
stockbroking firms have been predicting little change next year although the
end-year estimates range goes from 5.75% to 8%.
Given this relatively unexciting economic backdrop, the UK investor has to
recognise that sooner or later the home market will become heavily influenced
by politics.
Not even John Major can be sure of when the General Election will be.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's Budget last month seemed a clear indication the
Conservatives plan to hang on pretty much to the 1997 limit.
While the tax changes were seen by some as a move in the right direction, they
failed to stir the blood and must have been intended as no more than a curtain
raiser to a much more jolly affair next year. But this week has seen the
Government's majority cut by one through the death of a Tory MP.
Stockbroker Merrill Lynch points out that the Government could well lose its
majority towards the end of next year. Two to four Conservative MPs could,
statistics suggest, die every 12 months. That would leave Mr Major with little
choice but to have an autumn poll.
If, however, the Government still has a majority of two or more by then, the
broker expects it to soldier on, producing a tax-cutting Budget in November and
having a spring election in 1997.
In the short run, investors who have their money in shares probably need to
keep their eyes on the progress of the world's economies in case the slow-down
goes too far.
At some stage, it is logical to suppose the approach of an election must affect
decisions. Wholesale nationalisation of privatised utilities by a Labour
Government is highly unlikely, but there has been talk of a windfall tax on
electricity profits. The investment trust analysts at NatWest Securities
comment: ``The odds must be on higher personal taxation on higher earners.''
This has implications for the investment trust industry. The high earners are
the people most likely to be fuelling the rise in retail demand for investment
trust shares, so the industry needs to increase its efforts to ``package''
shares into tax-efficient products such as personal pensions.
The analysts also question whether a Labour Government would leave personal
equity plans intact. It is unlikely to abolish them retroactively, but new PEPs
could be abolished or, more likely, restricted.
Whether or not Labour does this, it would seem sensible to make sure you have
taken up this year's full allowance of #6000 for a general PEP and probably
also the #3000 for a single company version before the end of the tax year and
also take up the 1996-97 allowance as early as possible.
So far as investment trust shares are concerned, they comment: ``Investors are
likely to want to have more money overseas if Labour gets in. This will benefit
the trust industry since it will stimulate demand.''
They suggest buying the shares of large liquid overseas-based trusts should be
an excellent each-way bet.
Ken Clay
</TEXT>
