<HEADLINE>Germans seek ban on UK beef</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE upper house of the German parliament voted unanimously today for a complete
ban on imports of British beef because of fears it could be contaminated with
``mad cow disease''.
But Health Minister Horst Seehofer rejected the demand by the Bundesrat and
told it the issue might have to be settled in court.
The EU has ruled that British cattle born after 1992 are free of BSE, or bovine
spongiform encephalitis, and can be imported.
A temporary directive from the Bonn government implementing the decision
expires in February and needs Bundesrat approval to be renewed and made
permanent.
But the Bundesrat said today that it wants a general ban on British beef. In
addition, it said beef imports from other countries should carry a document
certifying them fit for consumption under German law.
``The Bundesrat emphasises that the recent development of BSE has shown that
the risk of BSE infection re-mains,'' the upper house said. Germany says there
is no proof that BSE cannot be transmitted to humans.
Seehofer warned members of the upper house that their move would result in
illegal actions which could be followed by compensation demands in the EU.
q.The European Commission tonight accepted a report on the welfare of veal
calves which damns the use of crates. EU Farm Commissioner Franz Fischler said
the report was aimed at allaying public fears.-Reuter.
Bonn
</TEXT>
