<HEADLINE>Royal composure over risk of being Shanghaied As rumours resurface of a takeover of the Royal Bank of Scotland, Kirsty Scott examines the prospects for this core financial institution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was no hint of turmoil, not even a frisson of ``what if'' emanating from
the stony, imposing exterior of the Royal Bank of Scotland`s Edinburgh
headquarters yesterday.
While the rest of the financial community buzzed with the unconfirmed notion
that the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation might be poised for a
takeover of the Royal, the bank issued a brief statement insisting, a little
ambiguously, that they were not in discussion with any potential bidders.
``We have made our position clear for a long time now,'' said a spokesman
later, ``and we believe the interests of our shareholders, our customers and
our staff are best served by our remaining an independent financial services
group headquartered in Edinburgh.''
That at least was welcome news for the many who believe the bank must stay at
the core of an independent Scottish financial sector.
Scottish National Party leader Alex Salmond, who was an economist for the Royal
when HSBC launched its first takeover bid in 1981, was suitably adamant about
what stance should be taken.
``A takeover of the Royal Bank would be damaging to Scotland,'' he said. ``I
don't think a takeover by HSBC would any more work in 1995 than it would have
worked back in 1981. The Royal, by and large, has been a success story,
certainly through the 1980s, and it should stay an independent Scottish
institution. I think Scottish opinion should be martialled in favour of
retaining the independence of our financial sector.''
Rumours have been swirling around the Royal for a number of months now, with
speculation that both it and the Bank of Scotland could be in line for a
friendly takeover. In 1981, moves on the Royal by both HSBC and the Standard
Chartered banking group were nixed by a Monopolies and Mergers Commission
inquiry.
Many believe a takeover would be an unfortunate transformation for a bank born
out of a spirited but flawed Scottish attempt to colonise Panama during the
closing years of the 17th century.
The new colony of Darien failed in 1699 with the loss of many lives and
one-quarter of Scotland's liquid assets, and the Royal Bank emerged from a
complicated system of compensation payments from the English, who had withdrawn
their support for the new community. The new bank officially opened for
business in Ship Close, Edinburgh, 268 years ago this month.
It has carried with it a reputation for innovation, initially inventing the
overdraft in 1728, and in the 1980s launching the phenomenally successful
Direct Line Insurance offshoot.
In the same decade, the bank diversified further by moving into the somewhat
dicey US market, buying the Citizens Financial Group of Providence, Rhode
Island. This year, Citizens saw its pre-tax profit increase by 57% to #107m.
The Royal Bank group's profit before tax last year rose by a total of 13% to
#602m, the highest in the bank's history.
Royal Bank spokesman David Appleton said yesterday that the bank was in a
strong position because it had diversified and gone for a range of different
business opportunities which had become significant profit generators.
However, industry analyst Chris Ellerton, of SBC Warburg, said he believed the
Royal was in a relatively difficult position in the consolidating UK market.
``The theory is that large-scale, high-volume, low-cost producers are going to
win the day and the Royal Bank is neither particularly high volume nor
particularly low cost. It is stuck in the middle ground. The outlook for growth
at the Royal Bank for the next year or two is not that exciting and a lot will
depend on Direct Line's ability to develop other lines of business outside the
insurance market.''
Alongside its drive to explore different options, the Royal has initiated a
major restructuring programme, Project Columbus, which earmarked a total of
3500 job losses in retail banking and brought them into direct conflict with
staff and unions. If the 80s were characterised by innovation, then the 90s
have been years of employee turmoil.
The banking union BIFU says the restructuring is savage and has targeted older
members of staff. Around 2000 jobs have already been shed within the branch
network.
``Quite frankly, I don't think the interests of the staff have been on the
agenda at all,'' said BIFU's Scottish deputy general secretary, Sandy Boyle.
``A recent survey shows that morale has totally collapsed. Only about 17% of
the staff believe in the executive. We're also seeing now quite blatant ageism.
As far as we're concerned, hardly anybody under 50 is getting a job. We're
looking at a workforce now where less than a quarter are 40 or over. That's
very, very worrying in the long-term.''
BIFU doesn't think any possible takeover would be good news for staff or
customers, but Chris Ellerton doesn't think anyone can view the bank as a
business waiting to be bought.
``It's not a lame duck; it's a very highly valued bank and before any bid
speculation was there it was a bank trading two and a half times its book
value. If someone wants to buy the Royal Bank of Scotland they will have to pay
a significant premium.''
</TEXT>
