<HEADLINE>The silent genius who could take life's falls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU can keep your Chaplins and your Harold Lloyds: as far as I'm concerned,
there was only one comic genius of the silent period of cinema - the great
``Stone Face'', Buster Keaton.
Keaton, the youngest of this trio, was born a century ago - in the same year as
cinema; the medium which offered his talents the chance to go far beyond
vaudevillian slapstick and which was repaid with some of the most memorable and
widely imitated sequences that have ever been filmed.
Keaton was born Joseph Francis in Kansas on October 4, 1895, to a vaudeville
act called ``The Two Keatons''; his parents, Myra and Joe. They worked as
members of the Mohawk Indian Medicine Company - a travelling vaudeville show.
At the age of six months he emerged unscathed from a fall down a flight of
stairs; a tumble that so impressed the legendary escapologist Harry Houdini
that he nicknamed the baby ``Buster'' - stage slang for a pratfall.
Before his first birthday, Buster got his first laugh, albeit inadvertently,
when - to the delight of the audience - he crawled onstage during his parents'
act. He didn't get the chance to perform in a theatre again until 1898, when
his mother finally, and reluctantly, agreed to allow him to join the act.
``The Three Keatons'' were hounded by the Gerry Society, an organisation which
aimed to protect children from exploitation, because their act depended on
Buster being thrown around and treated like a human punchbag. For the finale,
Joe would catapult his son, who was dressed as a miniature version of his
father, into the percussion section of the orchestra pit.
Through necessity and experience he trained himself to fall without seriously
hurting himself and learned how to prevent himself from registering emotion no
matter what disaster had befallen him, since he noticed early on that ``the
more serious I was, the more laughs I got''. So was born the frozen-featured
comic character that his name would come to represent in the movies.
In 1917, Buster broke up the family act, partly because he was now too big to
be thrown around and also because Joe Keaton had begun drinking and was
occasionally dangerous onstage. (On one occasion he misjudged a kick and struck
the back of his son's head. Buster was unconscious for 18 hours.)
Shortly afterwards, Buster - a dedicated movie fan - happened to meet Roscoe
``Fatty'' Arbuckle, at that time the second most popular comedian after
Chaplin. Keaton turned down a prestigious engagement worth $250 per week at the
New York Winter Gardens in order to work for Arbuckle's Comique Studios for
less than a fifth of that amount. The two men hit it off instantly, and proved
to be a perfect match onscreen in at least 15 films.
The first thing Keaton did when he began to collaborate with Arbuckle - whom he
later described as his ``greatest influence'' - was to take apart a camera and
figure out how it worked. After only two years in the film business, Arbuckle's
production supervisor, Joseph Schenck, bought Keaton his own studios and with
them went the unspoken invitation to let his imagination run riot. Keaton
proved to be a revolutionary, pioneering and downright classy filmmaker: his
production values were always high and he regularly, and flawlessly, made use
of innovations such as split screen in his short films, none of which were
based on scripts.
In 1923, Keaton made his first two feature-length films: Three Ages - a parody
of D W Griffith's Intolerance - and Our Hospitality. The latter featured the
kind of daredevil antics that would normally persuade a star to call on the
services of a stuntman, but Keaton insisted on doing all his own stunts. So
much so that in Our Hospitality he narrowly escaped being swept away by rapids
(the sequence is captured on film and his near-drowning can be seen in the
finished product). The following year, while filming Sherlock Jnr, he hit his
head on a railway track. More than a decade later, a doctor asked him when
exactly he had broken his neck.
Sherlock Jnr was described by a critic of the day as lacking in ``originality
and ingenuity'' - actually two of its strongest features. The story of a cinema
projectionist who steps into the screen while a movie is playing, it predates
Woody Allen's similarly-plotted The Purple Rose of Cairo by 61 years, and - as
a recent, rapturously-received, screening with live musical accompaniment by
the Paragon Ensemble in Glasgow testified - has not only withstood, but
triumphed over, the test of time.
Keaton's best-loved film was made in 1926. The General was his most spectacular
and costly work to date. It was the last movie over which Keaton had more or
less complete control. It went over budget and opened to mixed reviews, so
Schenck told him to work with a production supervisor on his next project. Just
before Keaton completed Steamboat Bill, Jr, Schenck advised him to join MGM.
This proved to be a catastrophic move which - in hindsight - heralded Keaton's
decline. Unfortunately, it was coincident with problems at home: his wife was
spending money faster than he was earning it, and she was trying to alienate
his sons from him.
Keaton's second movie for MGM, Spite Marriage, proved to be the last one with
any vestige of the ``Keaton touch''. The restrictions of working within, and
being answerable to, a tightly structured studio were stifling his creativity.
MGM committed a crime against comedy by effectively killing off the comic
personality that Keaton had taken a lifetime to establish. The studio forbade
him from carrying out dangerous stunts (crucial to his character); made him
abandon physical comedy in favour of spoken gags, and even subjected him to the
indignities of being a song and dance man (in Free and Easy).
Keaton had been sucked into the studio system which spat him out, drained of
originality. By 1930, personal and professional frustrations had led Keaton to
the bottle. Over the next decade, he made lousy films in a continuous drunken
haze; split up with his wife; married his nurse (without remembering he had
done so); became a gambler and - possibly worst of all - was forced to play
sidekick to comedian Jimmy Durante.
In 1937, faced with the choice of abstinence from alcohol or death, Keaton -
now on hard times - re-invented himself as a humble gag writer for the Marx
Brothers, again at MGM. But it was another marriage - in 1940, to a young
dancer called Eleanor - that probably prevented a relapse: ``It transformed my
life,'' he said. Over the next 26 years, Keaton gradually won back fans he had
lost and his silent comedies found new audiences as they were given a new lease
of life by film restorer and distributor Raymond Rohauer.
By the time of his death in 1966, Keaton's stone face had been re-established
as one of the cinema's true icons.
Alison Kerr makes a case for the brilliance of Buster Keaton, who for too long
has been in Chaplin's shadow
</TEXT>
