<HEADLINE>Scots forced to find snow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKIING:
WHEN the 1995 KPMG Scottish Ski team was launched two weeks ago on a tiny patch
of imported snow in the centre of Edinburgh, little did the squad of five
full-time skiers realise that their crucial pre-Christmas schedule would be so
hit by the lack of snow in Europe that they would have to fly to Canada to get
racing.
With the British National Ski Championships in Tignes, France, advanced by a
month from their usual April slot - to avoid a clash with the financial year
end of sponsor, British Land - the Scottish team need as many races as possible
before facing their fully-fledged British Alpine team rivals under the
selectors' intense scrutiny.
Rival skiers of the British Hanson &amp; Robertson FIS and Europa Cup Teams - the
squads to which the Scots immediately aspire - have been racing hard in
Scandinavia, completely filling the international quota of six starters which
Britain is allowed, thereby eliminating any Scottish team skiers.
The Scots have copied a coaching structure which cost the Canadians millions of
dollars to develop. Since adopted by the Scots, it has become the envy of the
UK, and is likely to be the blueprint when the current wholesale overhaul of
coaching throughout Britain is enforced at the end of this season.
These changes are predicted to bring a return to a system of a British Junior
Team and a British Senior team, and may bypass this current crop of Scottish 17
and 18-year-old Scottish team skiers. They could find themselves ``the lost
generation' - well short of the new qualifying standards for British team
selection, unless they can post some very inspiring results at the British
Championships, but too old for Junior team selection.
French-Canadian coach Chuck Auclair said: ``They are certainly the best
prepared, most hard-working team in recent years. When it comes to the British
Championships, that's when we have to make our mark and beat some of the better
British team skiers - selectors can never discount that.''
The leading Scottish team skiers have already had more than 50 days' on-snow
training, with successful summer and autumn camps in Chile and France - a
preparation which, according to Auclair, puts them on par with the leading
Alpine nations for the first time.
The whole Scottish team this season has been pared back to just 15 skiers,
fewer than half of what it was three years ago, with only five skiing full-time.
Scottish FIS TEAM: Ross Baxter, 17, Edinburgh; Michael Berkeley, 17, Forfar;
Paul-Anthony Cairns, 17, Telford; Ross Gardner, 18, Edinburgh; Ross Green, 16,
Falkirk; Derek McMillan, 18, Kilmalcolm; Finlay Mickel, 18, Edinburgh; Antoni
Pilarski, 20, Falkirk.
Scottish Home Based Team: Blair Aitken, 15, East Lothian; Lorne Noble, 15,
Edinburgh; Amanda Pirie, 15, Aberdeen; Pamela Robb, 15, Aberdeen; Gareth
Trayner, 15, Ladybank; Laura Westmacott, 16, Kirkliston.
</TEXT>
