<DOCID>GH951216-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>French railmen to end strike `Union leader claims victory as hopes rise that nationwide chaos will soon be over</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
STRIKING French rail workers voted to return to work today, opening the way for
an end to France's longest public transport stoppage in a decade.
The 22-day strike forced conservative Prime Minister Alain Juppe to scrap a
plan to streamline the loss-making state railway and promise not to touch
generous retirement schemes.
But he did not back down on his main welfare reforms, including new taxes and
controls of health service costs in a move to cut France's gaping budget
deficit and help it qualify for the single European currency expected in 1999.
Despite that Communist CGT union leader Louis Viannet insisted: ``The rail
workers' victory in imposing their sectoral demands on the government is a
textbook proof of the force which workers' unity and union unity brings.''
He called for further action but the signs were that the strike was crumbling
among Paris Metro and bus workers and in the state-run power and telecom firms.
The prospect of an end to the strike was greeted with relief by footsore Paris
commuters who endured three weeks of monster traffic jams and long walks or
bicycle rides to work.
Force Ouvriere, the other main union leading the wave of strikes, confirmed
that most of its members had voted to start work again on Sunday or Monday,
after tomorrow's planned mass protest against Juppe's welfare reforms.
The French franc was back up at its highest level since the start of the
crisis, but shares ended lower as investors fretted about the economic cost of
the long stoppage.
As the strikes wound down, rail chairman Jean Bergougnoux resigned, hours after
Juppe disowned him by criticising an absence of dialogue between management and
unions.
Even before the rail strikers voted, trains had resumed running in some parts
of the country and public transport was slowly coming back to life in the
French capital.
``Things are starting to roll a little bit. It's a positive sign,'' Transport
Minister Bernard Pons told Radio Luxembourg, predicting rail services would be
running across the country by Tuesday.
There were scenes of elation when one of the first Metro trains rolled into
Chatelet underground station.
``I never thought I'd be so happy to see a Metro. It's like a dream, a breath
of fresh air,'' said Scheherazade Boudard, 26. ``Paris without the Metro is
hell.''
Symbolising the beginning of the end of the rail stoppage, a high-speed TGV
train left Lille in northern France this morning carrying a mere 10 passengers
to Paris's Charles de Gaulle Airport.
The train arrived half an hour late after striking railway workers blocked the
tracks until police could clear them away.
Rail officials said it would take several days to clear rust from the lines and
get the network fully operating, and that die-hard strikers could still try to
disrupt services.
Trade unions said Juppe's plans to overhaul the indebted welfare system, as
well as European Union plans to open public services to competition, threatened
France's public services and working conditions as well as hitting workers in
their pockets.
French Transport Minister Bernard Pons tonight accepted rail chief
Bergougnoux's resignation, but asked him to stay on until a successor was
nominated.
A ministry statement said Pons thanked him and assured him that the government
did not blame him for the strike crisis.
Symbolising the beginning of the end of the rail stoppage, a high-speed TGV
train left Lille in northern France at 6am today, carrying a mere 10 passengers
to Paris's Charles de Gaulle International Airport.
The train arrived half an hour late after striking railway workers blocked the
tracks until police could clear the way.
In Paris, six Metro underground lines ran limited services, RATP said. About 6%
of buses were running.
Postal services were also improving, with just 2% of workers striking and
disruptions at 39 of 135 sorting centres compared to 46 yesterday, the post
office said.
The two main Paris airports operated normally despite a threatened strike by
air traffic controllers, officials said.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
