<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Obstacles on the rail track</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Garside recommends the service on the Anglo-Scottish motorway bus and
suggests the InterCity rail service has let him down because of the
fragmentation of the rail service due to privatisation (December 8).
It may also be that the bus operates almost track cost free, only paying a
reduced road fund tax and with a rebate on most of its road fuel tax.
InterCity, on the other hand, operated profitably without any subsidy
whatsoever until privatisation struck.
InterCity West Coast desperately needs its track upgraded but the Government
refuses because it will not provide a commercial return on investment. The
express bus would travel down the new M74 built at a cost to the taxpayer of
several hundred millions. No nonsense about commercial returns here.
The bus, and other road users, do not pay a penny extra for the benefit of this
investment. Elsewhere the Scottish Transport Minister gets excited about a road
bridge over Loch Creran. It will save the motorist 15 minutes. But the rail
bridge at Dornoch, even with mainly European funding, is ridiculed as
uncommercial.
A project to bring passenger train services back to Alloa was about to start
when Government departments decided another #1m was required to give extra
protection to motorists at level crossings. This made it uncommercial and the
project was scrapped.
But 100 yards away the Scottish Office found ``special'' funding of several
millions for a new Alloa road into Stirling. These are not isolated examples.
This is Government policy.
The train operators have to pay track access charges of a few hundred millions
(#170m from ScotRail alone) to Railtrack, which does maintenance which costs
only a fraction of this amount.
If better tracks or upgraded signals are required, then the train operators (or
local authorities) have to fund this themselves as extras. What happens to
those hundreds of millions that Railtrack does not spend on improvements? That
is the ``Profit''.
It is a wonder the trains run at all.
Ralph Barker,
The Knowe,
Crawford, Lanarkshire.
</TEXT>
