<HEADLINE>Value of a good clear out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E Dundas, Christopher Sims, Angus Gawn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance letters</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Your questions answered by R E Dundas, Christopher Sims and Angus Gawn
q My wife and I have a mixed bag of investments purchased over the years
through privatisation issues and new investment trusts coming to the market. I
am 59 and in early retirement with an index-linked pension of #20,225 per
annum. My wife is 55 and her income is #35.25 a week. There is no mortgage on
our #90,000 bungalow and we have no debts.
The following portfolio is badly in need of tidying up. It consists of 3000
Scottish Hydro, 425 PowerGen plus 220 part-paid, 695 National Power plus 330
part-paid, 1600 BT, 10,000 M&amp;G Income zero dividend Preference, 3000 Fleming
Emerging Markets plus 892 warrants, 3200 EFM Smaller Companies plus 640
warrants, 1200 Fleming Chinese plus 240 warrants, and 2500 Abtrust Emerging
Economies plus 500 warrants.
We save #100 a month with Foreign &amp; Colonial Investment Trust (#3800 now in
plan) and #30 a month with M&amp;G Recovery Unit Trust (Accum) (10,120 units
purchased to date). We have #9000 each in Tessas and #12,000 in an instant
access building society account in my wife's name with interest paid gross.
Your advice would be greatly appreciated.
n We would agree with your conclusion. Your portfolio needs tidying up. Overall
it is worth #56,000, and by the time the interest is added to your Tessas your
savings and investments will total around #90,000, a substantial sum by any
standards which should be well managed.
Even your privatisation portfolio is heavily weighted towards electricity
shares. New specialist investment trusts do not have the same attractions for
small investors as the more broadly based conventional trusts, where you picked
well with Foreign &amp; Colonial. M&amp;G Recovery is a highly rated unit trust.
You have a tendency to concentrate your fire power with nearly #20,000 tied up
in just two investments, Hydro and M&amp;G Income zero dividend Preference.
You are well placed with your substantial index-linked pension. Your
investments are there to provide you with the icing on the cake as well as a
bit of independence and security. It is for you to decide how much income you
would like from this source and, accordingly, the emphasis that should be
placed on capital growth.
We would suggest that you seek the advice of a good stockbroker who should be
able to provide you with a broadly based portfolio of equities and investment
trusts to suit your financial needs.
q I took out a Scottish Amicable Flexidowment Second Series policy in 1981 with
an earliest maturity date in 1991 and a latest maturity date of 2006. I have
been disappointed by its recent performance and requested a surrender value.
This turned out to be approximately 73% of the total sum of benefit and bonuses
from the bonus declaration of 1994.
It would appear that there is a penalty on the surrender of this policy despite
the fact that it was sold on the basis of having an earliest and latest
maturity date. Am I right in thinking the Flexidowment principle was a sales
gimmick with no particular advantage for the policyholder?
n These policies provided a guaranteed pay-out calculated from a specified
formula from the tenth anniversary onwards. As it happens the standard early
surrender values have not been any worse, but Scottish Amicable says they would
have been had the life fund under-performed.
From the perspective of today, when there are more competing products available
and there has been pressure to improve early surrender values generally, the
Flexidowment guarantee may appear a modest advantage. But in the context of
when you began the policy it was an advance on a standard one in at least
giving a floor to the surrender value. If it was marketed as the answer to the
inflexibility of the with-profits policy then this was an exaggeration.
q I would be grateful for your opinion regarding the Kvaerner offer for Amec. I
do not like the absence of a share alternative. In particular, I would like you
to comment on the cash offer of 100p per share and on the loan note
alternative. Do you feel the cash offer is fair and reasonable and is the
interest on the loan note worth considering?
n This offer closes on Monday and on balance it is worth accepting given Amec's
poor record and the outlook for its industry. While the bid may not be very
generous, Amec shares are likely to fall sharply should it not succeed. The
loan note alternative does not look attractive.
q I have my Tessa with the Dunfermline Building Society and it will mature in
January. The Dunfermline has recently written to me offering the chance to
reinvest the #9000 capital for a further five years at a fixed rate of 7.7%.
While it is unlikely that I will need access to the money, it is not totally
impossible and, of course, interest rates could rise substantially during the
next five years. The penalties which the Dunfermline will impose on early
withdrawal are severe and, in fairness, it says that anyone who is likely to
want to withdraw early should invest in a variable rate Tessa.
As a higher rate taxpayer I find the offer attractive and I'm tempted to take
the chance, but is it too much of a gamble on the interest rate remaining
competitive or could I do better elsewhere?
n No-one can predict what interest rates will do over the next five years but
as things stand, with both main political parties apparently committed to low
inflation and sound money policies, a return to high interest rates is
unlikely. It is more probable that they will fluctuate quite narrowly around
present levels. Based on past performance, Dunfermline's rates are highly
competitive and you are unlikely to do better elsewhere.
If you cash in the Tessa before the five years are up all the interest accrued
since the start becomes subject to tax. As you are a higher rate payer, the
7.7% would drop down to 4.6% net, and there would be the penalties. The current
variable rate is 7.2% which would become 4.3% net.
So the difference is not that great - approximately #27 a year - though the
latter rate would, of course, drop if interest rates in general fell. The final
decision has to be yours, but in your position we would agree with the
Dunfermline's advice.
