<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth accused in right-of-way row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs and the Ramblers' Association have accused Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth of hypocrisy over his policy on public rights of way.
Local residents yesterday staged a demonstration at Middleton Hall in
Midlothian, site of the Scottish Prison Service's abortive venture to set up a
training centre.
They walked through the grounds using ladders to overcome barriers to maintain
a right of way which they say has existed for 20 years.
The SPS, however, denies its existence and says no mention of it will be made
in the expected imminent sale of the mansion and its 113 acres.
The SPS is expected to lose around #1m on the sale of the property, which it
bought for #1.3m in 1989. RA Scottish officer Dave Morris said: ``It is
extremely irresponsible for the Scottish Secretary to be blocking this route in
this way.
``It sets an appalling example to all other landowners in Scotland and runs
entirely counter to his statements.''
Midlothian MP Eric Clarke said: ``What has happened is absolutely scandalous.
This is disturbing not only because of the huge waste of public money but also
the total inconsistency on the part of the Scottish Secretary.''
Labour's Treasury spokes-man, Mr Alistair Darling, said there was now a case
for referral to the Public Accounts Committee. ``The Government is saying one
thing and then doing the other by blocking off a right of way the public is
entitled to use,'' he said.
</TEXT>
