<DOCID>GH951216-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ashby libel case QC asks for `substantial damages'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE jury hearing the David Ashby libel case should award the MP substantial
damages in accordance with the need to vindicate him, the High Court heard
yesterday.
In a reference to this week's Court of Appeal ruling that judges and counsel in
libel cases can indicate to a jury the level of award they deem appropriate,
the MP's counsel, Mr Geoffrey Shaw QC, said in his closing speech that he would
not avail himself of his new liberty.
The 55-year-old MP for North-west Leicestershire, who is suing the Sunday Times
over allegations that he is homosexual, had been forced to speak about his
marital difficulties, his sexuality, his health, and even his impotence, as
necessary steps towards the vindication he sought.
He had waited almost two years for a courtroom battle with his estranged wife,
Silvana, pitted against him.
``I do say that, if you find for Mr Ashby in this case, it will be your duty to
award substantial damages in accordance with the need to vindicate him.''
He said the jury might have read in the newspapers of public concern about the
level of damages awards. ``But, as Mandy Rice-Davies said, `They would say
that, wouldn't they?' because it's them against whom large awards have been
made.''
Mr Ashby is claiming damages over a January 1994 article which said he shared a
double bed with a man friend during a holiday in Goa at the end of 1993.
Times Newspapers Ltd and former Sunday Times editor Andrew Neil deny libel,
although they accept Mr Ashby did not holiday with a man in Goa. They assert
that he was and is having an affair with 32-year-old Dr Ciaran Kilduff.
The newspaper's counsel, Mr Richard Hartley QC, said in his closing speech:
``It is our submission that damages do not arise. You do not get damages in
this country for an article which is true and it is our submission that the
evidence against the plaintiff in this case is overwhelming.''
Mr Hartley described the MP as arrogant and pompous - easily upset and hurt
over petty matters - who was misguided and illogical in his decision to sue.
Mr Ashby had said that he had never come across bigger hypocrites and more
dishonest people than the Sunday Times but the jury might think the MP scored
``near maximum points'' on the hypocrisy and lies scale.
The MP had maintained that people would have to have dirty minds to think he
and Dr Kilduff were having a homosexual affair just because they shared a
double bed at Chateau Tilques, St Omer, northern France, during a brief holiday
together in January 1994.
The QC asked the jury: ``I suggest it's an insult to your intelligence and
others to suggest you would have to have a dirty mind to come to that
conclusion.
``If you don't come to that conclusion, you are in the realm of people
believing in Father Christmas or that babies are delivered by storks.''
He added: ``It's clear on the balance of probabilities that he is a homosexual
and he and Dr Kilduff were having a homosexual affair.''
Mr Justice Morland will sum up on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
