<DOCNO>GH951216-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pay cut secures bulk of book jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at the loss-making HarperCollins book manufacturing plant at
Bishopbriggs, near Glasgow, have voted overwhelmingly to transfer to a new
company.
About 360 workers had been told the plant would close and that they would be
made redundant unless they agreed to accept changes in working terms and
conditions by 1pm yesterday.
The agreement to accept a 9.5% cut in wages and a compensation package offering
78 weeks of the difference between the old and new rate was put forward by Mr
Chris Hardie, the prospective owner of the plant, and Mr Eddie Bell,
HarperCollins's executive chairman.
Staff previously rejected a 25% wage cut proposed by Mr Hardie, who owns a
small Berwick-based company, Martins the Printers.
In addition to the compensation package, HarperCollins has made ``generous
subsidies'' available to Mr Hardie.
The Graphic, Paper, and Media union, which represents most of the workers,
confirmed that 337 of its members had agreed to transfer. The 20 who refused
would be made redundant.
Mr Hardie's company will take control of manufacturing from Monday, ending
Collins's 175-year association with book manufacturing in Glasgow. The plant is
understood to have lost more than #10m in the past five years.
Mr David Munro, GPMu Scottish branch secretary, said last night: ``While we are
not in favour of cuts in wages and do not believe that the failure of the
HarperCollins manufacturing business was due in any way to the working
performance of our members, we are happy that the employers have now agreed to
operate within legislation adhering to the transfer of undertakings.
``The net effect of the new proposals means that the reduction introduced to
the wage structure will not be felt by our members for 18 months. This now
allows the launch of the new company.''
The union said it was also pleased that book manufacturing would continue at
Bishopbriggs and said it looked forward to a ``long and fruitful relationship''
with Mr Hardie.
Mr Bell said: ``This terrific result has saved more than 300 jobs. We never
shirked from our responsibility to our people. I believe today that the staff
have made the right decision and I look forward to working with Chris Hardie in
the future.''
Mr Hardie was not available for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Borders crash kills two</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO men died and two other people were injured in a Borders road accident on
the A7 Galashiels to Selkirk Road, yesterday.
Police named the dead men as Mr Charles Clamp, 25, of Crumhaugh Road, and Mr
Christopher Muir, 24, of High Street, both Hawick.
The two people injured were taken to Borders General Hospital. Mr Paul Currie,
21, of Beattie Court, Hawick, received pelvic injuries and was ``stable''. Ms
Jennifer Bird, of Falside, Camptown, Jedburgh, had arm and leg injuries and was
``serious, but stable''.
The accident, near Glenmayne House, happened when the Austin Maestro the four
were travelling in left the road and plunged down an embankment before bursting
into flames.
Ms Bird, who was in the rear passenger seat, was thrown from the vehicle. Mr
Currie, who was sitting next to her, was rescued by a passer-by and police
officers.
</TEXT>
