<HEADLINE>Academy Brass, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Academy Brass, RSAMD, Glasgow
LAST things first. ``And now, the moment you've all been waiting for,''
announced Bryan Allen. ``The big band is unleashed.''
Strangely untrumpeted, the RSAMD brass department yesterday staged the official
debut of its latest creation at the climax of a superb lunchtime concert.
Formed only this term under the aegis of newly appointed head of brass at the
Academy, Bryan Allen, the big band is an 18-piece outfit that got off to a
storming start.
Stronger in ensemble than in solos, the band - powered by mental drumming from
Guy Rickarby - roared through a short series of big band classics: Count
Basie's Jumpin' at the Woodside, Neil Hefti's Cute, and Duke Ellington's
Caravan, among others.
Displaying the muscle of their classical technique, they made mincemeat of the
complexities of Don Ellis's The Last Tangle of Lord Boogie. To say it was an
auspicious start would be to understate.
The entire concert was a virtuoso display of the range of brass talent in the
RSAMD. The brass band played sections from Walton's original music for The
Battle of Britain and a bruisingly confident account of Thomas Wilson's bracing
Sinfonietta, while a sextet of leading players performed Leonard Salzedo's
Divertimento (which contains the Open University theme). The last might have
had a tighter edge if it had been conducted.
The brass department has been a core element of the RSAMD for years; Bryan
Allen has picked up a rich inheritance. The signs yesterday suggest exciting
developments; watch this space.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
