<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The lady for all seasons W</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile </ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell
enters the busy world of Stockard Channing
WHAT does an actress do after scoring the success of a lifetime both in the
theatre and on the screen? Stockard Channing, whose performance as Ouisa, the
New York society art dealer in John Guare's play Six Degrees of Separation, was
a sensation on Broadway and in London, has been busy ringing the changes.
Having played Ouisa so successfully she may have found herself facing the fate
of many actresses - being replaced when the play was filmed. But Guare had
written the play for her, and it was she who played Ousia in Fred Schepisi's
acclaimed film version.
In reality, Channing is svelte, dark haired, and as sharp as can be - nothing
like Ouisa. She followed her with the role of the tarty, down-on-her-luck Ruby
in Wayne Wang's Smoke, shown at the London Film Festival, which will open here
next year.
Ruby is completely her creation, because she was allowed the freedom to decide,
on the basis of the script, how she conceived the character. She is a classic
New York broad, a wasp-waisted woman of the world with blonde hair and black
roots.
She has come to New York to try to help her daughter who, she has discovered,
is pregnant, on crack, and living with a junkie pimp. She tries to persuade an
old lover, a corner store owner played by Harvey Keitel, to help, claiming he
is the girl's father.
``Ruby has been round the block,'' Channing says. ``In fact, Ruby has been the
block, there is no doubt about that, so I decided she had to look very bold.
When she walks into Harvey's cigar store she has to make a real impact. It is
an animal thing. She is a female animal in a male den.''
Keitel, who does not like to rehearse but to work straight on camera, was taken
aback when he first saw her. She was not his idea of Ruby. He pointed out he
had a line in which he told Ruby she ``looked like shit,'' yet here was
Channing in high heels and dressed to the nines. Channing insisted no man would
say something like that to a woman's face, although they might think it if they
felt threatened by her.
It is a striking part in an impressive film, and she has followed it with as
varied a selection of roles as any film actress could wish for. They range from
the battered wife, Carol Ann in the drag fairytale, To Wong Foo, to the English
keeper of a bawdy house in the latest version of Moll Flanders, made earlier
this year in Ireland.
While in London in Six Degrees she met Tom Stoppard who, having seen her as
Ouisa, decided she was just the person to play the title role in his espionage
play, Hapgood, in New York. That was a hit and she is now waiting for Stoppard
to come up with a screenplay which Renaissance Films and Channel Four will make
and she and Stoppard produce.
She notes she has gone from Ruby to Carol Ann to the head of MI5, to the keeper
of the whorehouse, finishing up with the part of a newscaster in Up Close and
Personal opposite Robert Redford and Michelle Pfeifer.
She is realistic about the vagaries of the actor's life. If something happened,
that was fine, but certain things were not meant to be.
``You have to let projects go,'' she says. ``As I get older, I realise that is
how life works. I don't talk about something until I am doing it, otherwise it
is just a fantasy. Why torture myself with things that may never occur? There
is no control over things like that. Why go round saying - What is the matter
with me? I never worked with David Lean. You can drive yourself crazy that
way.''
She knows she is lucky; she still has options as an actress, and there is work
lined up, including a film of a Horton Foote play with Mary Stewart Masterton
which should be finished by Christmas. There is also a film with Scott (The
Right Stuff) Glenn and Jennifer Tilly called Edie and Pen to come.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coroner's drugs plea to teenagers: `You don't know what you are putting in your body' Warning after death of boy, 15</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CORONER yesterday made a heart-felt plea to teenagers after the death of a
15-year-old boy who took an overdose of ecstasy tablets hidden by his mother's
boyfriend in their home.
Aaron Fairhurst died in hospital at Crewe, Cheshire, in May after being
discovered in his bedroom making grunting noises.
At an inquest in Crewe, coroner John Pollard said: ``I make a plea from the
heart to all teenagers and anyone else tempted to use ecstasy or any other
illicit drugs to bear in mind that you don't know where they were prepared or
how well or badly they were manufactured.
``Quite frankly, you don't know what you are putting in your body. It is a most
foolish and stupid thing to do.''
Aaron's mother, Lisa Fairhurst, 31, and her long-term boyfriend, Gareth
Charles, were regular drug users but have now renounced the habit and yesterday
backed the coroner's warning.
Fairhurst, who is divorced from Aaron's father, told the inquest her boyfriend
had bought the ecstasy tablets for their own use and hidden them in their house
in Davenham, Northwich.
On the night of May 25, she went to bed but heard a banging noise, as if an
object had been knocked over, and grunting noises coming from Aaron's bedroom.
``We saw Aaron with his upper body on the bed and his feet on the floor. His
body was rigid and his eyes were open but rolling back.'' She added: ``He was
soaking wet but very hot, and had all the classic symptoms of an ecstasy
overdose or reaction. I panicked and told Gareth to take him downstairs.''
The couple managed to get him to drink two pints of water and then a pint of
salt water in an attempt to make him vomit, but this did not work and they then
took him in their car to Leighton Hospital, Crewe.
Her boyfriend returned to the house from the hospital and found that his hidden
ecstasy tablets had gone. Aaron was pronounced dead soon afterwards.
Fairhurst said: ``Aaron was the happiest he had been in a long time, so I can't
understand what his motives were to sit in the bedroom and do that on his own
when it is generally classed as a social thing.''
She described how he had suffered from bullying at school in Manchester but
added: ``He was a happy, bright boy, a bit of an extrovert.''
Police Constable Kevin Chambers told the hearing in a statement that about five
ecstasy tablets were missing from the house.
Fairhurst and her boyfriend both pleaded guilty to charges of possession of
cannabis and ecstasy and were placed on probation for six months by Northwich
Magistrates' Court.
Consultant pathologist Dr Ann Nicol said Aaron died as a result of
cardio-respiratory arrest due to an MDMA overdose.
Recording a verdict that Aaron died through the abuse of a non-dependent drug,
Mr Pollard said there was no evidence to suggest that he had been depressed or
suicidal.
``He took the drugs because unfortunately he had grown up in a culture in
Manchester where drugs were frequently talked about.''
After the hearing, Mr Colin Downie, solicitor for Fairhurst and Charles, said
the couple had both renounced the use of drugs and urged all young people to
beware and not to be tempted into taking them.
``Drugs have wrecked their lives and they sincerely hope they will not wreck
the lives of any other unfortunate people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Counting the cost</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Murray Ritchie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE coming of the Euro as the EU's single currency means Britain - which is not
committed to it - is expected to spend millions of pounds familiarising the
public with the new money, writes MURRAY RITCHIE.
After yesterday's decision by EU leaders to move to monetary union in 1999 the
Government must now decide whether to exercise its opt out from the single
currency in 1998.
The new coins will be in circulation, if all goes as planned, in 2002 - by
which time every EU member state should have prepared its citizens for the
changeover through a vast multi-million pound publicity campaign. But Britain
appears so far to have no such plans.
Comparisons are now being drawn with the publicity blitz which lasted for years
in the run-up to decimalisation of Britain's currency in 1971. Almost seven
years was spent on that campaign.
Now the British appear destined to lag behind the rest of Europe because of the
Government's determination not to make up its mind on the single currency until
the very last minute.
A blueprint for the European-wide campaign was produced recently by the
European Commission. It wants the community's member states to pick up most of
the cost of educating the public on what the Euro will mean to them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Swimmer who thought she was selling ecstasy jailed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BRITISH international synchronised swimmer was jailed for two years
yesterday, for offering tablets she believed were ecstasy for sale at a
nightclub rave.
In fact, Louise Skidmore, 22, from Bristol - national champion in 1988, and who
took part in world championships and a pre-Olympic competition in Spain in 1991
- was selling pills which contained no controlled drug. Her co-defendant at
Plymouth Crown Court, Leona Nicholls, 23, who had been living in London, was
also jailed for two years.
Judge William Taylor said: ``I note you were not in fact selling ecstasy,
although you believed you were.'' He told the defendants, who he said were both
of previous good character and in all other respects hardworking and decent
young women, that he regarded the offence as so serious only a custodial
sentence could be passed.
Both women had appeared for sentence having pleaded guilty last month to
offering ecstasy tablets for sale at Oz's nightclub in Union Street, Plymouth,
in April.
Prosecuting, Mr John Bush said although they believed the tablets to be
ecstasy, forensic tests revealed they contained no controlled drug.
Judge Taylor said the pair brought the tablets from Bristol to Plymouth, having
accepted the drugs for sale on behalf of another person in a moment of
stupidity. He told Skidmore, against whom there was no evidence apart from her
admissions: ``Many youngsters look up to you to set an example.''
Mr Bush said the women were in the nightclub on the night of April 28 when, as
a result of something said by a client, two security guards approached them and
said a random drug search was being carried out.
Asked to produce their purses, Nicholls was found to have around #200, and
Skidmore about #100.
They both denied carrying any drugs and the police were called. Nicholls then
told a female security officer she had drugs on her and produced a bag
containing 43 tablets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man bets on fathering a child at 100</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BUSINESSMAN has bet #50 that he will father a child at the age of 100.
Mr John Richardson, 55, says it will give him something to live for and he will
have a lot of fun practising in the next 45 years.
The bet has been taken by William Hill bookmakers who have given him odds of
10,000/1 - meaning he will make #500,000 if he wins.
Mr Richardson says he will advertise for a woman aged between 25 and 35 to give
birth to the child in return for #250,000.
He says he wants the child to be conceived in the ``usual and enjoyable
method'' and is willing to have a blood test to prove it is his.
Mr Richardson, a toy importer, from Hatch End, west London, has four children
aged between 16 and 35, from three wives.
q William Hill yesterday opened its book on bets for 1996. They included one
million to one that Anthea Turner will win #1m on the National Lottery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish picks new managing director</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Television has designated Andrew Flanagan, its finance director, to
take over as managing director in May, writes ROBERT POWELL.
He will replace Mr Gus Macdonald who will become executive chairman of the
Glasgow-based ITV station.
Mr Bill Brown, the current non-executive chairman, is retiring.
Mr Flanagan, 39, will be mainly responsible for the day-to-day running of
Scottish Television.
Mr Macdonald, who has been managing director for nearly six years, will
concentrate on strategy and future planning. His promotion to executive
chairman was announced earlier this month.
Mr Flanagan, who comes from Glasgow, qualified as an accountant before working
for Touche Ross, the PA Consulting Group and a subsidiary of the US cable
corporation Nynex.
He joined Scottish Television as finance director in February 1994 and played a
leading role in negotiating its strategic alliance with the cable and satellite
television company Flextech earlier this year.
Mr Flanagan said: ``My time at Scottish has allowed me to appreciate the needs
of our programme makers and I will do my best to help them maintain our
position as Scotland's top television station.''
A new finance director is still being sought
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Setting targets for millennium</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUGH targets for education and training for year 2000 were announced yesterday.
The figures by the Advisory Scottish Council for Education and Training Targets
(Ascett), had been revised from those originally set in March 1994.
Mr George Kynoch, the Scottish Office Industry Minister, said higher levels of
achievement were needed to build well-educated and flexible workforce.
It would be a workforce which was not merely ready to cope with the increasing
pace of change in the economy and in technology, but well-placed to seize the
opportunities this presented, he said.
Professor John Ward, chairman of Ascett, said that although Scotland led the UK
in many of the measurements, she still fell behind many competitors abroad.
There was evidence of a flattening out in attainment.
The targets announced by Ascett were:
q.By age 19, 85% of young people to attain five Standard Grades or the
equivalent. (Position now 72.5%).
q.By 21, 70% of young people to attain three Highers or the equivalent. (Now
51%).
q.60% of workforce to be qualified to level of three Highers or the equivalent.
(Now 47%).
Mr Frank Pignatelli, director of education at Strathclyde Regional Council,
said the third target posed a problem because the annual increase needed was
2.6% and recent increases at 0.8% had been ``abyssmal''. The 13% gap which had
to be closed was equivalent to 253,000 employees.
</TEXT>
