<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Young Playwrights, Old Anthanaeum Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PART of Scottish Youth Theatre's Winter Festival, this one-off evening of four
rehearsed readings is the culmination of a two-year programme of local writers'
workshops and the rigorousness of this process is reflected in the quality of
the work.
Most impressive was James S. McNulty's The Sunmaid, which, while rooted in a
gritty contemporaneous world of urban alienation, is underpinned by the fairy
tale allegory of a maiden imprisoned in the tower. Beautifully scripted, with a
great ear for street-smart idiom, McNulty also shows an impressive grasp of
theatrics, with the building suspense heightened by Robin Wilson's understated
direction.
Wilson also directs Gavin Sayers' The Trouble With Mr Charlie, a short,
stylised evocation of the lingering effects of bullying. Sayers's work is
powerful and inciteful, boldy depicting the strange dependency of the tormented
on the tormentor.
Bram Gieben's Billy Joe is less subtle, with the young playwright over-egging
the pudding. A Scottish family sit down to a meal and in the course of it has
to digest adolescent anguish, suicide, murder, hints of incest and fatal
disease. However, like McNulty, Gieben has an assured grasp of dialogue.
Douglas Maxwell eschews a contemporary setting to opt for a period piece,
although he brings a Po-Mo sensibility to The Chamelion's Play, the tale of a
group of actors planning the assassination of Oscar Wilde. Again, the script is
highly literate and dramatically sophisticated, but is too self-conscious, with
an overuse of Wildean epigrams, to really succeed.
An invigorating evening, excellently performed by the second year students from
the RSAMD, who clearly warm to material they can directly relate to.
</TEXT>
