<DOCNO>GH951216-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth secures jobs pledge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As the Broadcasting Bill is published television companies are hit by takeover
speculation
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth has secured guarantees that a Scottish
production base will be protected no matter who owns Scotland's television
companies.
The assurance came as the Government published its Broadcasting Bill, the main
provision of which allows greater cross-ownership between newspaper groups,
television companies and radio stations at both national and regional levels.
There will be a public interest criteria by which the regulatory authorities
can assess and approve mergers or acquisitions.
In addition there will be more scope for digital technology, with provision for
the licensing of an anticipated 18 digital terrestrial channels.
Mr Forsyth has been engaged in Cabinet discussions to secure the future of jobs
in Scotland and to ensure that any takeovers do not damage Scottish interests.
It is understood that publication of the Bill was delayed by a week while Mr
Foryth was engaged in talks on the matter with Cabinet colleagues. Some 500 to
600 jobs in Scotland could be affected.
In a statement issued last night, Scottish Arts Minister Lord Lindsay welcomed
the inclusion of provisions in the Broadcasting Bill to safeguard regional
production on ITV in Scotland.
He was also pleased that Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley had agreed to
extend the scope of the Gaelic Television Fund to cover Gaelic radio, and that
she was prepared to consider including measures in the Bill which would improve
the scheduling of Gaelic radio.
Lord Lindsay said: ``From representations we received from Grampian TV and
others we were aware that the local input to these services might be put at
risk following any relaxation of the regulations governing television ownership.
``We are delighted that Cabinet colleagues have recognised the importance of
including provisions in the Bill which, if enacted, will ensure that,
irrespective of ownership, the quality and range of regional production on ITV
will be safeguarded.''
Mrs Bottomley said the Bill set out a proposed new regulatory framework to
allow the development of digital terrestrial broadcasting and amend existing
media ownership rules.
The proposals would give the UK a world lead in the development of digital
broadcasting technology services, and would help UK media companies compete
more effectively in overseas markets by allowing them to exploit opportunities
in the expanding global media market.
She said: ``A strong, diverse broadcasting market which reflects the national
and regional characteristics of the UK can only be achieved if our media
companies can compete effectively in the international market place. The
proposals I have set out today wil help UK companies compete effectively,
creating commercial and employment opportunities for the UK at home and
abroad.''
Labour, however, was more cautious. Shadow Heritage Secretary Jack Cunningham
said the Bill did not meet the challenges and opportunities offered by the huge
growth in multi-media services that was set to take place, describing it as a
Bill for the present, not the future.
On cross-media ownership, he said the new provisions would require very close
scrutiny. Mr Cunningham said: ``With the removal of the two-licence limit it
will be important to look closely at the ownership of regional ITV franchises
by national newspaper groups where the parent company also owns significant
numbers of local papers.
``I am concerned that it appears that the only newspaper group significantly
disadvantaged by these proposals is the Mirror Group.''
Leader comment 14
</TEXT>
