<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appeal over quango inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Frances Horsburgh, local government correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By FRANCES HORSBURGH
Local Government Correspondent
SCOTTISH local authority leaders have asked the Government to join them in
mounting an investigation into the role and powers of quangos.
Underlying the offer by Cosla is local government's desire to win back powers
from the bodies whose members are appointed by the Scottish Secretary rather
than directly elected.
Cosla vice president Councillor Keith Geddes reminded a full meeting of the
convention in Edinburgh yesterday that there were now more than 5000 members of
these appointed bodies compared to just more than one thousand councillors in
the new unitary local authorities.
In addition quangos controlled more than #5.5bn of public spending.
Council leaders have suggested that the current joint Scottish Office/Cosla
Task Force, which had been examining the rules governing the behaviour of
councils and elected members could be the right vehicle to examine the role of
quangos.
They made the offer at a meeting yesterday with Scottish Local Government
Minister George Kynoch at the Scottish Office.
The Minister has not yet responded to the suggestion, but Cosla will put its
proposal in writing and expect to receive a reply at a scheduled meeting with
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth in January.
</TEXT>
