<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>radio</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE White Settlers, (Radio 4) up for cultural discussion or, as Scottish Watch
would have it, claymore-dissection, this week are the English incomers to the
Highlands.
Taking all that Haste ye Back stuff seriously, admiring the peaceful empty
spaces, and noticing you can buy a friendly wee castle for the price of a
bedsit-sized bungalow in Sussex, many southerners have taken up residence among
the natives, and John Forsyth wanted to know the extent of ill-feeling they had
experienced, if any.
He figured a Catch-22 situation existed, whereby if the newcomers kept to
themselves, they would be accused of snootiness but if they got involved In the
Community, they'd be accused of taking over and their colonialist tendencies,
their oppressive Empire mentality, their offensive fantasies of fuedal
landlording would become manifest.
Well, take Pauline Catt for example. Were she my neighbour, my curtains would
be twitching like a midge-infested Scottie dog, my natural nosiness elevated to
Infiltration Investigator.
A doddle of an assignment this one would be, actually, for the aforesaid
Pauline is so blinded by her sense of racial superiority (letting slip that she
once lived in Nigeria as well as Kent) that she is becoming careless, almost
braggadocio in her activities.
She hardly keeps her imperialist intentions under her WRVS hat - Girl Guides,
Women's Guild, Cheshire Homes, church flower rotas and the Inverness flower
show. Need I go on?
Her husband, obviously cannier, wishes she would not go on. That Forsyth chap
failed to pick up on her revelation in the programme her spouse ``made her
promise'' not to get involved in any political arguments, but instead she waded
in, as if through the blood of my ancestors, and with chilling defiance Pauline
declared that since Scottish people didn't have to justify being in England,
why should the English have to feel defensive when they come to live here?
Forsyth pointed out, I don't think in front of Pauline, that fleeing Jacobites
probably ran through her back garden on their way back from Culloden moor some
time ago. I think the arrogant woman would have asked the ghosts in for a nice
cup of Scottish Brew, after deviously hiding the Earl Grey, and showed them a
framed wedding photo of her daughter.
Emma Wood is writing a book about the situation, and in her incomer-interviews
she worries that no-one mentions the historical reasons for the quietness; the
ethnic cleansing of the Clearances, and the murderous policies of the past.
English herself, she admitted to a feeling of being here on sufferance -
``though there's no reason to creep round in sackcloth and ashes''.
NOT an option considered for a second by Terry Butcher, former captain of the
English football team, who has lived in Bridge of Allan for nine years, runs a
hotel and has no problems enjoying playing at Chieftains now and then, while
admitting to his sense of English identity, which is fair enough.
The youngest of his sons is convinced he was born in Inverness (though his mum
says different) and he thinks the English are posh, and say ``I say'' a lot.
But his 12-year-old brother, Nicholas, says that the teasing can become nasty,
``more hate'', and at the rugby camp two boys from Newcastle were going to get
a right kicking before they were whisked off.
And there's the nice sounding Dr Hugh Jones, who was made to feel a southerner
when he lived in Yorkshire, who vastly prefers Scotland, appreciates his
children's good local school, mildly resented some sections of SNP
electioneering talk with made the incomers fell unsettled and undervalued, and
who works as a consultant at a hospital in Inverness.
But don't drop your guard, he's a consultant dermatologist. Don't say your
Agent didn't warn you - they are getting under our very skin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Relaxation boosts TV share prices</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE relaxation of restrictions on media ownership proposed by the Government
yesterday sparked off a wave of takeover speculation in the television industry.
All three ITV stations serving Scotland saw their shares boosted by speculation
that they would soon be gobbled up by larger media groups.
Carlisle-based Border, the smallest ITV company on the UK mainland, soared 27p
to 245p.
Scottish Television, in which Mirror Group and Flextech, the US-controlled
television programme commissioning company, each have a 20% stake, gained 22p
to 491p.
Grampian Television, which is 40% controlled by two Scottish fund management
companies - Abtrust and Edinburgh Fund Managers - rose 16p to 219p.
The Government's Broadcasting Bill abolishes the present restriction on one
company owning more than two ITV licences. Instead, the Bill says that no ITV
company should control more than 15% of the total television audience.
The change was welcomed by large media groups that are keen to expand further.
But many smaller players which fear losing their independence, expressed
reservation.
Grampian gave the Bill a very lukewarm welcome. ``We would have preferred to
see the retention of the two licence ownership rule, but are encouraged by the
success of the Scottish Office in having some regulatory protection for ITV
regional commitments included,'' said chief executive Donald Waters.
However, Scottish Television, which has often been mentioned as a potential
bidder for Grampian, welcomed the easing of ownership restrictions.
Managing director Gus Macdonald said it would ``allow terrestrial broadcasters
to keep pace with competition in the current rapid expansion of multi-media
activities''.
His view may well be coloured by the enthusiasm of Scottish Television's two
main shareholders for the relaxation of television ownership rules.
Mirror Group spokesman Nick Fullagar said: ``We are delighted that the
Secretary of State has seen our point of view that Channel 3 (ITV) must be
allowed to consolidate.''
``We have always aspired to have a significant holding in a bigger group of ITV
companies and this now makes it possible,'' he added.
Flextech chief executive Roger Luard meanwhile reiterated his company's
ambition to expand its interests in ITV. Flextech sees ITV broadcasters as
important sources of programming for its associated cable and satellite
channels.
The main hope of the smaller ITV stations is that the big boys will ignore them
as they struggle to buy up the larger English licences.
By the time those battles are over the heavyweights may be too close to their
15% audience quota to take on any more.
Two main ITV groups are widely seen as emerging to dominate the market.
Carlton-Central is tipped to merge with MAI, which owns Anglia and Meridian.
That would create a southern-based group with 14.8% of the UK television
audience.
Granada, which owns London Weekend, is meanwhile seen as a predator for
Yorkshire/Tyne Tees. That would create a group with a 13.1% share of the market
focused on the north of England.
Both blocks would be too big to take on Scottish, which has a 3.6% share of the
national television audience, once its 20% stakes in HTV and GMTV are counted
in.
``What you could end up with is two big blocks, one in the north and one in the
south, and the Celtic fringes,'' one Scottish Television official said.
Mr Peter Brownlow, finance director of Border Television, took a similar view.
``Border Television, because of its size, may be an easy target, but if another
ITV company wishes to buy a significant player it will look elsewhere,'' he
said.
Although the Broadcasting Bill will make it easier to develop cross-media
links, it will not not necessarily encourage Scottish newspaper and radio
groups to rush into television.
Scottish Radio Holdings - the owner of Radio Clyde, Radio Forth, Radio Tay, and
Northsound, said it had no plans to invest in television.
Caledonian Publishing, owner of The Herald and Evening Times, said the
Government's proposed relaxation of media ownership rules would not entice it
into broadcasting.
``We have no short-term ambitions to go into either radio or television,'' said
chief executive Liam Kane. ``The focus for our expansion is newspapers or
indeed magazines. I think we will stick to what we are good at.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saatchi rejects new Tory contract</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAATCHI &amp; Saatchi, one of the world's top advertising companies, is withdrawing
from the Tory Party advertising account, it was announced yesterday.
The decision follows the party's request to renegotiate its exclusivity
agreement.
The planned change would have resulted in Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Advertising working
alongside other agencies in future Tory campaigns.
Conservative Party Chairman Dr Brian Mawhinney said: ``We have been very happy
with the quality of work. Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Advertising have chosen not to be
part of this larger grouping we want to put together but we understand the
reasons for their decision.''
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Advertising's chairwoman Jennifer Laing said: ``This is a
professional decision that we should part company; as an agency we do not work
in a co-operative with other agencies.
``The coming campaign needs to be very single minded. We part on good terms and
with finances settled.''
The agency hit trouble early this year when Maurice Saatchi, who formed Saatchi
and Saatchi in 1970, was sacked in a boardroom coup. He went on to set up rival
firm M and C Saatchi with his brother Charles in January.
Yesterday's move could open the way for a return to the political frontline by
Maurice Saatchi, who is still a senior adviser to the Prime Minister and a
close confidant of Baroness Thatcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Chamber Orchestra, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAYMOND Leppard's guided tours of the main cities in Mozart's life have
provided the SCO in recent seasons with some cleverly compiled and beautifully
executed concerts, each of them stitched together with genial spoken
commentaries by the conductor himself. This week the subject has been Mozart in
Salzburg, scene of the wunderkind's first triumphs and launching pad for what
would become his great cycle of concertos and symphonies.
Thursday's programme in Edinburgh, repeated in Glasgow last night, displayed
Mozart's Salzburg style in four contrasted works, two of them diverting, one of
them flamboyant, and one - the sinfonia concertante, K364 - a masterpiece. With
James Clark as violinist, and Catherine Marwood as his viola-playing shadow,
this disguised concerto was performed with the right sort of tension, in which
light gleamed through darkness, and even the orchestra's introductory
flourishes sounded uneasy.
The effect was profoundly disturbing; music filled with questions,
undercurrents, and anxieties, in which the moments of virtuosity - such as the
hair-raising skyward leaps for the soloists near the end of the finale - merely
added to the sense of unrest. In such a context, even the brilliance of the
34th symphony at the end of the programme sounded less than usually
affirmative, more than usually ready to plunge into ambiguity.
Real brightness was reserved for the little string divertimento, K136, that
opened the concert, where Leppard drew charm from every phrase and every
rhythm. The bassoon concerto, K191, likewise gained from the conductor's
insight and from the delectably grainy tone brought to the solo part by Ursula
Leveaux.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Geologists rewrite the tale of Sodom and Gomorrah</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEOLOGISTS claimed yesterday that they had pinpointed the probable site of the
biblical cities of Sodom and Gomorrah and worked out why Lot's wilful wife
ended up as a pillar of salt.
It wasn't, as men over the generations have claimed, because she disobeyed
orders and dared to look back but due to the briny nature of the Dead Sea.
``This is an attempt to use modern geological perspectives to look into a very
racy story - the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah - and solve a fascinating
historical problem,'' said Mr Peter Styles, of the Quarterly Journal of
Engineering Geology.
The findings by two British geologists working in Canada were printed in the
journal yesterday.
While the rough location of the infamous cities has long been suspected, the
authors said they used the latest geological thinking to trace the cities to a
specific peninsula in the Dead Sea and work out the reason they vanished around
1900 BC.
Saturated soil and highly flammable bitumen, rather than God's wrath, was
apparently behind their demise.
``The area is made up of rock types which, when subjected to a large
earthquake, will actually liquefy - like shaking up a bottle of sauce,'' said
Mr Styles. ``Theirs is a great story but if, as they suggest, the whole city
was destroyed and collapsed into the sea, I don't know how much would be left
to dig up.''
According to the Old Testament, the cities were destroyed by fire and brimstone
in retribution for their sinfulness.
God warned Lot of the impending peril. However, his wife disobeyed the sole
condition of not looking back and was transformed into a pillar of salt.
Research shows it was more likely a case of mistaken identity, however.
Geologist Graham Harris said that the Dead Sea was full of salt floes that
might have been thrown up by surging water to resemble a female outline.
Mr Harris and fellow Briton Anthony Beardow analysed local soil and rock to
conclude that Sodom and Gomorrah were probably located on a peninsula that juts
out into the Dead Sea.
The sea, in fact a salt lake, is divided into two basins. The Lisan Peninsula,
where the team believes Sodom was located, separates the basins at the sea's
narrowest point.
Their analysis suggests it was a vibrant trading hub, used as a crossing point
to ship salt to the Mediterranean and Egypt.
Locals were also involved in risky bitumen mining, according to the Journal,
meaning fire would have been a constant hazard in what was an earthquake zone.
That would help explain the biblical references to the fiery destruction of the
two cities.
Mr Harris said it was impossible to tell if an earthquake set off the so-called
liquefaction process he believes swallowed up the cities but said
archaeologists and engineers should join forces to put the 4000-year mystery to
rest.
``Not withstanding the geological argument, the enigma will never ever be
resolved until artefacts can be rediscovered that can be positively identified
to those cities,'' he said. ``And I'm absolutely sure there's something left
down there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trading places</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Phil Penfold</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Douglas Hodge endured a traumatic sojourn in the Philippines to shoot his
newproject. He tells Phil Penfold about the trials of making Saigon Baby
HE reckons that he's a ``fairly tough cookie'', but actor Douglas Hodge admits
that making Saigon Baby for the BBC was ``one of the most harrowing assignments
I've ever done''.
Douglas, who has appeared in such TV classics as Capital City, Middlemarch, A
Fatal Inversion and in Bliss for the BBC, stars opposite Kerry Fox and John
Hurt in a searing indictment of the ``trade'' in young children in the Far East.
``I saw some sights that I would prefer to forget,'' he recalls with a grimace.
``We went to the Philippines to shoot, chiefly because the Vietnamese
authorities do allow filmmakers in, but they have the final say on what they
are allowed to film . . . if they don't like something in the script, out it
goes. So we went to Manila instead. And believe me, that place is the
playground for hell. Any sexual kink or perversion you want you can have.
``It's there, right on the street. You don't have to go looking for it, it's
offered to you. Children are told to go out and earn money by their families,
and they go and sell themselves.
``We also shot in some absolutely appalling slums - such as the back end of
Calcutta. In a lot of ways you feel very privileged to see the raw side of
life, but in a strange way, because no-one else ever goes there and it's not
exactly on the tourist trail. So we got a view that no-one else does. It's not
a place I would want to go back to or an experience that I would care to repeat.
``And the other sad thing is that while you're wandering around in the Far East
you realise how `same' the world is getting. The people wear the same clothes
as we do in Britain, the shops are the same, and that fast food chain is
everywhere. Whatever happened to the desire to be that little bit different
from the rest?''
But the plight of the children touches his heart. ``Especially when I thought
of our daughter, Mollie, who is now three. She has a charmed life in relation
to some of those children. When Tessa and I see pictures of the children in,
say Romanian orphanages, Mollie becomes all the more precious. But I guess that
all parents feel like that, don't they?''
Married to Only Fools and Horses star Tessa Peake Jones, Douglas says that,
``yes, we'd like to have more children. Being a parent has changed us both. You
see the world in an entirely new way, a different perspective, when you become
a mum or a dad.
``In a way, I can almost feel sorry for the couple in Saigon Baby, because they
want a child so much. They've tried for years, and nothing has happened. So the
last resort is - buy one. Money doesn't matter to them. They've got pots of it.
``But my character Michael Cooper isn't that sympathetic - he's a rich git
businessman, a real high-flier. What he discovers is that there's a huge trade
in babies, and that not all of them are perfect. There are ones with Aids and
others who are disabled. They have to get the papers together that allows them
to take the child out of the country.''
And yes, he says, he is a ``complete'' New Man. ``Whatever that is.
``I read somewhere the other day that women are getting more and more masculine
and going to football and rugby matches, while men are buying far more beauty
products. Where's the world going?''
Is he envious of the Michael Coopers of this life? ``Oh, God, no. Nothing is
any problem to them. People like that have a terrific life, and a baby is just
another thing they want. Another possession to play with. There's the argument
that anything would be better than the life the child might leave behind, but
it's a terribly complex moral problem. People who have it easy all the way, all
the time, never appreciate how nice it is when something wonderful happens.''
He has been filming in another ``glamorous, not'' location, Tooting Beck,making
a new Screen One film called It Could be You.
``Which is all about a Lottery winner who sweeps the jackpot with a win of #25
million.
``He's called Bob Whistler, and he's an electrician who lives with his wife
(Frances Barber) and child in a very ordinary house, living a very ordinary
life. Thing is, when he wins, he's got two problems. His mistress used his
money to buy his ticket, and he then loses the ticket that proves he's the one
who should get the money.
``It's a bit like a Feydeau farce, a bit like an Ealing Comedy. It's very light
and frothy, with an edge to it, great fun to do.''
Unless, of course, you've got a scene: ``running through East Street market,
where the genuine traders were getting a bit pissed off at our presence, and
then started asking for a bit more `convenience' money to keep them sweet. They
very soon got wise to the idea of a film crew making a movie!
``After Saigon Baby, I wanted to make something that was a bit off-the-wall.''
He feels the Lottery so far ``has really been only bad news, hasn't it. It
seems to corrupt people in seconds, doesn't it? And the worst thing for me was
that it seems to let the Government completely off the hook. They're now able
to crow about the `giving to charity' bit, without contributing anything
themselves. As far as I can see, it's just another invisible tax''.
He adds: ``But alright, I'll come clean with you. Although I'd never bought a
ticket before, all of us on the set subscribed to a weekly syndicate, using a
set of numbers . . . and we didn't win so much as a damn penny!''
Making It Could Be You was a blessing for Douglas and Tessa, ``because she was
working at night with the RSC in the play The Park at the Barbican, and I was
working through the day here in Tooting. So we could be with Mollie at
alternate times, which is great".
Hodge says: ``Tessa's play had incredible reviews, but there's hardly any
publicity budget! It was the complete opposite to Only Fools for her, and live
theatre which she really loves. It was great for home life because she could
get back every other night, since the play was in repertory. But that's not so
good for an actor, because you do the play once or twice a week, and go back to
it in another week, when it's like starting to learn it all over again!
``Tessa's always being asked if they'll be doing any more Only Fools and
Horses, and she keeps on saying that she really doesn't have a clue. My own
guess is that all the good storylines have dried up. But John Sullivan is such
a terrific writer and an inventive genius, so anything could happen.''
When It Could Be You finished, Douglas returned to the BBC to edit a film he
shot for the BBC's Education Unit, ``about conservation which is going to be
called The People are the Forests. I'd done all the major work on it -
directing 200 National Youth Theatre folk and three professional actors was
tremendously exciting - and had to go back and lick it into shape in the
editing process''.
He adds: ``There are a couple of future projects that may or may not come off.
The sort of thing that if I mention them now and they don't happen, I shall
look a total prat!''
Did he ever consider leaving the UK to work in the States? ``Tessa and I
thought of maybe going off to work in New York at one point. There were a few
interesting things offered that never seemed to quite get off the ground. And
then Mollie came along, which put paid to all that. I just love being a
father.''
Douglas and Tessa now live in Buckinghamshire. ``Which means that for It Could
Be You, I had to be up and out of the house by five in the morning to get to
the set!
``But the childhood in the Medway towns was useful in catching the South London
accent again - it's all too easy to drop into it. I rather like Bob Whistler,
for all his faults. He and his wife Wendy are, at the heart of it, honest and
they have no illusions. I think that they're as tough as old boots - she
certainly is. He's recognisable, a bloke that you can identify with.
``In fact, if we've got it right, then I reckon that there'll be a lot of men
sitting in pubs across the country, thinking `this is all terribly familiar'
and even `there but for the grace of God . . . '.''
In a lot of
ways you feel
very privileged
to see the raw
side of life
</TEXT>
</DOC>
