<DOCNO>GH951216-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Keeping officials on the move</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>westminster diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL FORSYTH'S great vision for the future of Scotland is causing
consternation among officials who actually have to operate the thing. In the
coming year he has tabled meetings of the Scottish Grand Committee in Stirling,
Inverness, Aberdeen, and all over the place.
The trouble is that this involves flying up to Scotland and providing hotel
accommodation for substantial numbers of people. The list is as follows: Four
Hansard reporters, a Deputy Sergeant at Arms, two Commons Badge Messengers and
a committee clerk.
In addition are the added expenses for MPs who normally would travel straight
from their various locations in Scotland to London, but will now have to divert
to Stirling, Inverness, Aberdeen, etc...
Then there are all the costs of paperwork, the labour costs of setting up the
meeting halls, and the telephone bills. One exhausted Hansard reporter told the
Diary  that she was not exactly relishing the prospect of belting up to
Scotland once a month and then belting back to Westminster to report a normal
day's business.
Forsyth, however, seems determined, and at least this week had the good grace
to pay tribute to the hours worked by his own staff. He acknowledged that they
sometimes are at their desks early in the morning and leave late at night.
One Forsyth aide, asked if  he thought his boss was a slave-driver, looked
about for a few seconds and then said: ``Well, it's challenging.''
Nil points
MR Martin Redmond, Labour MP for Don Valley, is rapidly moving up the ranks of
MPs who ask questions which, at great expense, produce answers in which no-one
has the slightest interest.
He recently asked the Secretary of State for Scotland if he would list, for
each of his executive agencies for the last financial year, in respect of
overseas travel by staff, the cost, the countries visited and the posts held by
the staff involved.
In came the replies, which showed that some organisations, such as the Scottish
Agricultural Science Agency, had sent people abroad, but the Scottish Office
Pensions Agency, the Student Awards Agency for Scotland and the Scottish Courts
Agency all said ``nil.'' As we have reported before, it costs between #250 and
#350 a time for this fascinating information.
MacKays and Mackays
HOW many MacKays/Mackays do you think are now operating in the House of Lords?
The answer is six. The new Lord Advocate, Lord (Donald) Mackay of Drumadoon,
sworn in the other day, added to the list which, of course, includes the Lord
Chancellor, Lord Mackay of Clashfern, and front bencher Lord MacKay of
Ardbrecknish.
However Tory peer Lord Reay is Hugh William Mackay, and his fellow Tory Lord
Inchcape is Kenneth James William Mackay. In addition, the independent peer
Lord Tanlaw is Simon Brooke Mackay.
Apparently, when the new Lord Mackay was introduced  there were some
mutterings. ``Another bloody Scot, and worse still another one called Mackay,''
came a comment from one front bencher.``Do you have to be a Mackay to get to
the House of Lords?'' Oh well, at least there is only one Baroness Gardner of
Parkes.
Back to school
STICKING with the Lords, we are indebted to the Earl of Mar and Kellie, who has
a novel view of how the proposed new nursery voucher scheme might work in
Scotland.
He told peers the other day: ``My nephew Euan currently attends a playgroup in
his home village of Kilmelford on two mornings a week and on two other mornings
a week my sister-in-law drives him to Oban to attend another playgroup.
``The distance between Kilmelford and Oban is a far from straight 20 miles. The
two return trips are a barely sustainable 80 miles. How will Euan administer
his nursery school voucher in those circumstances? Will he be able to use the
playgroup's safety scissors to cut it in half?'' Over to you, Euan.
Coat of office
WHO was that wearing Scottish Office Minister Raymond Robertson's coat as MPs
disembarked at Heathrow the other day? It was Monklands East Labour MP Helen
Liddell, who had picked up the wrong garment. We are told that some unkind soul
from the body of the aircraft bellowed: ``Helen, I didn't realise you were so
desperate to get into Government.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
