<HEADLINE>Born in a winter wonderland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor Madrid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNOW in Madrid? The Euro in your pocket? There seemed something not quite real
about the EU summit yesterday, especially one which is being billed as the most
important for years.
Outside the meeting thousands of bored policemen, looking more like terrorists
in their balaclavas and machine guns, stamped to keep warm as the snow turned
the city white.
John Major's jibe that the single currency could be akin to Alice in Wonderland
was slightly off the mark - the Euro was actually born in a winter wonderland.
The decision to baptise the Euro before it was born was taken with a remarkable
lack of enthusiasm, almost as though those responsible for this momentous
decision were embarrassed or perhaps in awe of their own responsibility.
They were, for once, doing something which will actually have a real, daily
impact on the life of every single European citizen - even those whose
governments can't or won't join the single currency from the start.
The deed was done quickly. In less than two hours the EU's finest political
brains and most powerful political leaders, in all their collective wisdom,
concluded that they could not come up with anything more imaginative than the
Euro. (They could have got that idea from this very newspaper which suggested
months ago it would be the boring Euro - remember you read it here first.)
There was none of the usual bragging afterwards by the various national
delegations who normally claim negotiating triumphs for themselves on such
occasions. Instead, the name was formally adopted with fearful lack of fuss.
To mark the occasion, there were - refreshingly - no champagne toasts and no
long-winded speeches of self-congratulation which normally mark such EU
occasions. The Euro's midwives merely went off for a long lunch with the King
of Spain who picked up the tab.
President Chirac of France had taken the huff when it became clear the name Ecu
was to be ditched. Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany then kicked him when he
was down by ruling out a public opinion survey so that the people could give
their views.
A British spokesman, annoyed at suggestions that John Major was grumbling about
the Euro but unable to come up with a more acceptable name of his own,
responded tartly that ``there were no weirdos - you know, like doubloons or
ducats...''
Jacques Santer, the European Commission president, voiced desperate support for
the doomed Ecu, but his views were also drowned as the Euro was swept to life
on the crest of a wave of ennui.
Policeman braving the snow outside the congress hall in Madrid where the EU
leaders were holding their summit.           Picture: JAVIER BAULUZ/AP
</TEXT>
