<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Worst day in the life of a police chief</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE soon-to-retire chief constable of Strathclyde, Leslie Sharp, yesterday
spoke of the worst day of his life when he learned that a young constable had
been stabbed to death.
He also reflected on his 4!s-year spell in charge of the UK's second biggest
police force, likening it to being captain of the Queen Mary.
Mr Sharp, 60 next May, made his comments shortly after he received a very high
commendation award at a Strathclyde Police long-service and good-conduct medal
ceremony in Glasgow.
The chief constable, who steps down on Hogmanay, said it meant a great deal to
him that ``ordinary bobbies'' had gone to such lengths to mark their
appreciation.
Asked to reflect on the highest and lowest point of his spell in Strathclyde,
he said the worst day of his life had been June 17 last year, when Constable
Lewis Fulton was stabbed to death in Glasgow.
Mr Sharp, who was in London at the time lecturing on the success of Operation
Blade, said the incident put him at his ``lowest ebb ever''.
Mr Fulton, 28, died after going to the aid of colleagues during a street
disturbance in Gorbals.
Mr Sharp said his appointment as chief constable was the high point of his time
in charge. ``It was quite unique for an Englishman to come up here and take the
top police job in Scotland,'' he said.
``Being the chief constable of a force like Strathclyde is like being captain
of the Queen Mary. It is a big organisation. It takes a little while to change
course. But once you change course it goes full steam ahead and gets there in
the end.''
He said he had no advice for his successor, Mr John Orr, who takes over on
January 1, other than to say the force was ``in good heart''.
Seven police officers who challenged three men after an armed robbery at the
Bank of Scotland in Brandon Parade, Motherwell, last September, were among 20
officers commended for bravery yesterday.
Sergeant Kenneth McIvor, 40, from Airdrie, received a very high commendation
after pursuing and apprehending one of the men, who had a handgun. He was also
promoted to inspector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
