<HEADLINE>CONSTRUCTIONAmec bid set to go to the wire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE #375m battle for Amec now seems likely to be extremely close by the time it
ends at 1pm on Monday with many surprised at the weakness of the share price
yesterday, writes ANDREW WILSON.
Against the 100p on offer and the level it has been trading at until Thursday
it fell 2!sp to 96p which seemed to indicate that the bid may fail.
Intriguingly, Norwegian shipbuilder and engineer Kvaerner has failed to reach
the 30% level which is the maximum number of shares it is allowed to buy in the
market.
By the close, its holding was only 26.1% and so everything now depends upon the
level of acceptances.
Kvaerner chief executive Erik Tonseth has threatened to sell the holding if he
does not win. He said that in deciding whether to accept or reject the offer,
shareholders should not assume Kvaerner will be either a supportive or a
long-term minority holder of Amec.
Failure could mean a substantial loss both in cash terms and of face.
Amec chairman Sir Alan Cockshaw accused it of high-pressure bullying tactics
and that it was trying to divert attention away from the real arguments on
value.
The crucial factor is whether shareholders are prepared to take the Amec vision
of the future on trust after the many disappointments of the recent past and
the huge damage to their capital values or take the cash on the table.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
