<HEADLINE>Pig appeal to arable farmers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dan Buglass</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE demand for quality pork is growing so rapidly that one leading pig-breeding
company is seeking to attract Scottish arable farmers into setting up
large-scale outdoor herds, writes DAN BUGLASS.
The rewards, according to Eric Oakes, who is the managing director of
Somerset-based Peninsular Pigs, can be very worthwhile with a return on capital
of ``20%-plus''.
Outdoor pig production in Scotland has expanded rapidly over the last ten years
and perhaps 25% of the national sow herd is now run on this
environmentally-friendly system.
The appeal for more farmers to start up herds is principally fuelled by Marks &amp;
Spencer which wishes to source all its pork from pigs born in the open air.
Mr Oakes commented: ``The pigs are produced to a relatively wide specification
on a contract price significantly above the average all pigs price (AAPP) for a
specific market. It's not a speculative business. We know how many pigs are
required each week and it's rather like being a member of an exclusive club.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baby born after 8000-mile dash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BABY born prematurely was recovering in Leeds General Infirmary yesterday,
after her mother was flown 8000 miles for an emergency Caesarean operation.
Chloe Anderson was born after the RAF made a 20-hour flight from the Falkland
Islands with her mother, Carol.
Mrs Anderson, who lives on the islands off the east coast of South America,
with husband Eddie, was suffering from dangerously high blood pressure and
would have died without treatment.
Her daughter, who was two months premature, would also have died without the
emergency mission, as the island hospital is not equipped to deal with the
problem.
Mrs Anderson's condition was diagnosed by Leeds infirmary-based consultant
obstetrician and gynaecologist Paul Vinall, who visits the islands each year to
give voluntary medical help.
He immediately called in the RAF, whose Aeromed team delivered the patient to
the hospital in four stages - involving a jet, helicopters, and an ambulance -
giving her intensive care all the way.
The baby weighed just 1lb 11ozs when she was born hours after her mother
arrived at the hospital. She is now three weeks old and is slowly gaining
weight.
Mr Vinall said Chloe, who is expected to remain at the hospital for several
months, is doing superbly well and is over most of the hurdles. He said she now
has a 95% chance of normal survival.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Beattie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS ironic really. Dr Kennedy, the heart specialist, used to play for
Stirling    County. I'd had a pain in my chest and so I was referred to him. It
was all going so swimmingly until he looked at the ECG trace and decided to
whisk me into hospital to have a wee look inside. So, as you eat your bran
flakes beneath your Herald, you lucky people, I am lying somewhere, hopefully
getting better. Whatever, it's time for me to relax, reflect, and get the
stress down at the tender age of 38. I've had this flaming virus you've all
had, so hopefully that's all it is.
I think rugby is careering mentally out of control with professionalism. It's
gone potty, and    the smile has gone out of the game. We have journalists
using players to slag off other journalists. Hey, I've done it myself, but it's
completely out of order. We have players saying things about other players, and
then saying they never said that. I don't think I've seen quite so many people
lie in such a short period of time.
We have an unhealthy fixation with money. And we have people on the periphery
looking for a way to make a buck out of it. In fact, we have a fixation now
about everything that surrounds rugby, rather than with the playing of the game
itself.
Rugby is a wonderful game. If you haven't played it then you can't know the
sheer unadulterated joy of wandering from lineout to lineout, on an autumn day,
with the smell of deep heat in the air and the sun poking between the trees,
just having fun.
A friend of mine reminded me recently that rugby is a players' game. Most of
the good folk in the world who play are doing it for fun. If you haven't played
the game you'll never know the thirst afterwards, the sore way your body felt
on a Sunday morning, and the deep sensation of being one of a pack of 15
people, sometimes more, who all have the same love of a silly game. The
memories of people who have played rugby are filled with the daft episodes, the
times of elation, the funny        stories, and the sad times.
I doubt if any player in the world thinks to himself at the end of his career:
``Yes, I remember getting a grand for that game.'' Not a bit of it. They
remember the tries, the way they won, and what they changed about the way they
went about playing their beloved game called rugby. They remember the moves
they dreamed up, the      tactics, the feeling sometimes of being backs to the
wall and loved by nobody when it got up a level. They remember the tears, and
the laughs. Most of all, they remember the laughs. Bloody hell, I do any way.
But here we are, absorbed by players' contracts and whether there is a win
bonus or not. And clubs squeal like stuck pigs to try to get a slice of the
action in Europe. They actually fool no-one, and a thing called self-interest
is very much to the fore.
But, there I go, getting side-tracked.
I've learned a lot this week. I've realised that I shouldn't have played
against Romania all those years ago, instead I should have stayed in bed with
the raging fever and given the body a chance.
I shouldn't have trained with all of those colds, and I         shouldn't have
played with them either. My last game of big-time rugby was at Twickenham with
antibiotics for tonsillitis and nursing a cold. Lunatic. I swam with this virus
a week ago. Idiot. I smoked for years. Chump.
I've also learned that, no     matter what, rugby may be only a game but it's a
good game. It's big time and it's fun.
Whatever, I am taking no more early-morning calls from Bill Hogg.
After all, rugby's recent changes seem to have been very bad for my
cardio-vascular system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MLC chairman paints positive picture of industry Beef exports rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VICTOR ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIVESTOCK farmers must continue to concentrate on efficient production but not
production on the cheap, said Don Curry, chairman of the Meat and Livestock
Commission yesterday.
They must also do everything they can to ensure consumers trust the production
process and feel good about the meat and meat products they buy.
In an end-of-year message delivered at the annual Cirencester farming
conference Mr Curry presented a very positive picture of an industry that has
been hammered by negative images in recent months.
The market demand for meat had remained remarkably stable at around 65kg per
head per year for the past 15 years, although the pattern had changed with
poultry and pig meat taking market share from beef and lamb, largely as a
result of product development and price.
``This may come as something of a surprise given much of the media coverage in
recent years that has tried to suggest otherwise. The perception sometimes
fostered by critics of the meat industry that there is a rising tide of
vegetarianism is clearly not supported by the facts.''
Despite various restrictions, British beef exports had grown strongly with 93
different countries taking almost 300,000 tonnes in the past year. Lamb and pig
meat exports were also buoyant and the home catering market increasingly
featured British meat.
``We clearly have a livestock and meat industry that is not in decline as some
might suggest. Quite the reverse. Ours is a dynamic industry prepared to
diversify to meet changing demands and claiming a greater share of our home
market and aggressively exploring all export opportunities.''
However, he admitted that ensuring consumers felt confident about meat and meat
products in relation to alternatives would be a major challenge in maintaining
and expanding demand in the future.
For farmers this meant efficient production. This did not necessarily mean
producing on the cheap; it meant producing the right quality of animal as
efficiently as possible using the technology now available to help deliver the
right product for the market.
``Up to now British livestock farmers have been very successful at improving
quality and reducing production costs. But not enough of us know precisely what
our production costs are, particularly in the ruminant sector.
In order to remain competitive against other meats, other foods, and other meat
producing nations, we need to become even more professional. It also meant a
greater emphasis on education ``so that ignorance is neither a barrier to
building trust nor something that can be exploited by unscrupulous critics''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Self-inflicted injury rules out McDowall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALAN McDowall has ruled himself out of tomorrow's important fight at Glasgow's
Moat House, and a likely British title challenge, after a hand injury in
training last night.
The Renfrew light welterweight was gearing up to meet Darlington's double ABA
champion Alan Hall when the mishap occurred.
The 28-year-old carelessly damaged his right knuckles after a playful smack at
a punchball in the Sydney Street gym.
But his manager, Alex Morrison, angrily said: ``He knew the stakes were high
for this one. What he did was completely stupid. Now he has blown it.''
Promoter Katherine Morrison has retained the services of Hall, who will now
meet Walsall warrior Peter Till.
Unbeaten featherweight Brian Carr, from Moodiesburn, bids to extend that run
against Abdul Mannon, from Bangladesh, and the Scot, a former ABA champion and
Olympian, should be too strong.
Edinburgh light-heavyweight John Wilson should also win when he takes on Barry
Beasam, of Plymouth, while Hamilton featherweight Scott Dixon, most impressive
on his debut two months ago, is fancied to beat another Devonian Martin Evans.
The card is completed by Glasgow super-middle John McAlpine against Burnley's
John Duckworth. q.FOLLOWING his 89-second appearance in August's fiasco against
Peter McNeeley, Mike Tyson continues his comeback tonight against Buster Mathis
in Philadelphia. If, as expected, Tyson sprints to victory, he will face WBC
champion Frank Bruno in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Branson to sue in bribe row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIRGIN tycoon Richard Branson said yesterday he would sue the American company
he has accused of making him an offer he had to refuse.
Earlier this week, Mr Branson claimed on BBC1's Panorama that lottery giant
GTECH, a major backer of Camelot, had tried to bribe him to pull out of the
race for the lottery operator's licence.
GTECH denied the allegation and said it was considering legal action.
Now Mr Branson has fired the first shot by claiming that GTECH has libelled him
by calling him a liar.
``They (GTECH) have accused me of being a liar and of having spread an `evil
smear','' said Mr Branson.
``Given the nature of the accusations that they have levelled against me and
their attack upon my integrity, and given the importance of the issues that
have been raised, I have no other option than to issue a writ for defamation
against GTECH.''
GTECH said later it had received a writ from Mr Branson and would be defending
it ``vigorously''.
Mr Branson said the controversy would now get the public airing it merited in a
court.
He added: ``The Panorama programme . . . raised a number of serious issues
concerning GTECH and claims that have been made relating to the operation of
their business.
``As GTECH are major shareholders in the company running the National Lottery,
those issues need to be addressed by GTECH in a serious and considered
fashion.''
Mr Branson told Panorama that he reported the alleged bribery attempt to
lottery watchdog Peter Davis.
Mr Davis, who says he has no recollection of being told and is also consulting
legal advisers, has launched an inquiry into the affair which will centre on
allegations that Mr Guy Snowden, an executive with GTECH, tried to bribe Mr
Branson out of the lottery race.
The waters were further muddied this week when Mr Davis said he had accepted
free flights in GTECH private jets - before awarding the lucrative lottery
scratchcard licence.
Mr Branson's idea for a non-profit making lottery had popular public support
but Mr Davis, who awarded the licence, said he thought Camelot would raise more
cash for good causes nominated by the Government.
</TEXT>
