<HEADLINE>Talisman setssights on Goal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864509</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Talisman sets
sights on Goal
CANADIAN oil explorer and producer Talisman Energy has been confirmed as the
bidder for Goal Petroleum, the Aberdeen-based oil minnow.
Talisman is making an agreed #131m offer at 97!sp cash per share, a premium of
43% over the market price before the bid talks were disclosed.
The deal has already been sewn up as institutional holders of 45.5% of the
shares, mainly Norwich Union and Mercury Asset Management, have given
irrevocable undertakings to accept.
Forte hits back
FORTE has taken the fight against Granada into the enemy's camp with an attack
on its trading performance and strategy in its latest document urging
shareholders to reject the #3300m bid.
Accusing Granada of not understanding Forte's business, Sir Rocco Forte says
his antagonist ``is driven by the need to make an acquisition to reverse its
flagging rate of growth. The slump in Granada's share price since the launch of
the bid shows that there are increasing doubts about the wisdom of its hostile
offer.''
Granada immediately slammed the latest defence document as ``pathetic''. It
contained ``nothing about profits, cash generation or dividend.''
Double money
STOCKBROKER Greig Middleton's profits more than doubled from #877,000 to #1.98m
in the six months to October, the results of its parent company, King &amp;
Shaxson, reveal. Group profits rose from #1.25m to #2.06m excluding
discontinued activities.
Havelock buys
STORE-fitting group Havelock Europa is set to expand its service and client
base with the #12.8m acquisition of retail graphics and display company
Showcard. Fife-based Havelock will pay an initial consideration of #10.2m for
the Hertfordshire company, with further payments of up to #2.6m dependent upon
Showcard's profits in the year to March 31 and the nine months to December 31,
1996. The deal is conditional, subject to approval from Havelock's shareholders
at a January 9 meeting.
</TEXT>
