<HEADLINE>Pressure group hails court ruling on rail sell-off as a `Christmas present for passengers' Campaign claims a signal victory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Duncan Black</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A pressure group yesterday won a crucial victory in the Court of Appeal in
London which will help protect the level of future train services. But they
were unable to push Government rail privatisation plans completely off track
due to a legal technicality. Duncan Black examines the ruling's implications
North of the Border
SCOTTISH campaigners against rail privatisation last night hailed the Court of
Appeal's judgment as a breakthrough in their long battle.
The court's decision was welcomed as ``the best possible early Christmas
present'' for passengers by the Save Our Railways pressure group in Scotland.
Secretary Richard Leonard said: ``This is a devastating blow to the
Government's plan to axe and sell off rail services.''
Not only did it mean that existing Anglo-Scottish services to King's Cross
would be protected, he said, it also set a precedent for other services. Cuts
proposed by the franchise director in the ScotRail Passenger Service
Requirement (PSR) would have to be reversed, giving an added safeguard for the
Fort William sleeper service and lifting the axe which had been hanging over
some Glasgow-Edinburgh services.
Mr Leonard said: ``Our understanding is that all the PSRs so far issued -
including ScotRail and InterCity East Coast - will now have to be rewritten.
That means all existing franchises will be delayed. The nearer the sale gets to
the General Election, the less likely it is that the Government will be
prepared to press on with this deeply unpopular privatisation.''
The judgment had two other important consequences, he added. It would force the
Government to find new cash for investment to maintain existing services, and
it would shake City confidence in the sale of Railtrack, planned for 1996.
Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson said: ``The whole thing is discredited
and should be abandoned.''
The court decision was a very substantial victory for the Save Our Railways
campaign and it was vital that Ministers now respect the spirit as well as the
letter of the judgment, he said.
``It would be ludicrous for the Government to press ahead with two or three
franchises which are marginally within the law while the remainder go back in
the melting pot. In particular, the court quite specifically ruled the PSR on
the LTS (London Tilbury and Southend) franchise to be unlawful. Surely the
Ministers are not so desperate that they will proceed in the face of that
rebuke from the court?''
Mr Wilson said: ``The InterCity East Coast line was on the next batch and there
were places on that line which were going to lose up to 50% of their services.
But all of that is now set back.''
The court ruling had implications for all of the proposed rail franchises,
added Mr Wilson. ``Rail privatisation is further discredited, and if the
Government has any sense it will throw in the towel. The franchise director
should be sacked for acting outside the law.''
The Scottish National Party said the judgment was a great victory for users of
the rail network across the country. Transport spokesman Keith Brown said:
``The Government's sell-off of Britain's railways has been declared illegal
before it has even begun.''
Mr Brown said the Government had repeatedly given hollow reassurances that
privatisation would not lead to cuts in timetabled services, yet the appeal
court had ruled that most of the initial sell-offs were illegal precisely
because of timetabling changes.
``It is an absolutely damning indictment on Westminster and the Conservative
Party that the country should have to use the courts to protect its
infrastructure from the actions of the Government.''
For the Scottish Liberal Democrats, Charles Kennedy said he was ``delighted''
with the court's decision. ``This ruling has dealt a body blow to the
Government's privatisation plans and represents a critical breakthrough for the
objectors to privatisation.
``Given the chaos now surrounding the Government's plans, rail privatisation
should be consigned to the dustbin pending a General Election.''
Meanwhile, a spokesman for the management-employee buy-out bidders for the
InterCity East Coast line said last night that they had no comment to make on
the judgment.
But he said: ``We are committed to run a timetable well in excess of the PSR as
it stands, and where possible it will exceed the current service. We cannot
speculate upon a court judgment involving other parties, but we can say that we
are still committed to bidding for the InterCity East Coast franchise.''
</TEXT>
