<HEADLINE>Couples putts his way to the top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864512</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Montego Bay, Jamaica
FRED Couples, who has turned post-regular season events into a lucrative
cottage industry in recent years, took significant strides yesterday in the
second round of the Johnnie Walker World Championship at the Tryall Club,
Jamaica, towards regaining the title he won four years ago by making birdies at
four of the last five holes.
That surge gave Couples a score of 67 and a total of 137, five under par, to
share a three-stroke lead with Fiji's Vijay Singh and Wayne Riley, the
Australian holder of the Scottish Open title, both of whom bogeyed at the last
hole after they had driven to the rough.
On another afternoon of hot sunshine and high humidity Couples, despite his
ailing back stiffening up, made seven birdies for the day's lowest score. He
made six of them with single putts on greens many of the 20-strong field found
difficulty in reading, and one with a holed chip shot. Two other putts saved
par.
Singh, who has won twice on the US Tour this sason, had three birdies and the
eagle 3 he made at the seventeenth, 524-yards long but downwind within range of
a short iron which he struck to within 20 feet, looked as if it might give him
the outright lead until he made his final mistake.
Riley, who led by three strokes from Singh overnight had lost it all by the
turn, but he counter-attacked with three birdies in six holes from the twelfth
and it was only when he compounded his driving error at the last by hitting his
second shot into a bunker that he, too, dropped back into a tie.
Loren Roberts, who lost to Sam Torrance in September's Ryder Cup singles, also
came to grief at the eighteenth but still held a two-stroke advantage over the
third American player in the first five, Mark Calcavecchia, whom many still
cannot bring themselves to believe won the 1989 Open Championship at Royal
Troon.
Certainly, the prospects of any of the four Europeans following Nick Faldo, who
won the event in 1992 receded almost into invisibility. Bernhard Langer was the
closest pursuer, but a distance of seven strokes away, and Colin Montgomerie,
Faldo and Torrance, respectively five, seven and 10 over par, are now playing
only for money.
