<HEADLINE>`Fatal dose' of alcohol consumed by crash motorist</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTORIST who crashed on the A9 should have been dead . . . not from any
injury but from the amount of alcohol in her system.
Housewife Wilma Taylor, 45, was almost six times the legal limit, which
medically speaking is a fatal dose, a court heard yesterday.
Fiscal David Hingston told Dingwall Sheriff Court: ``She was in danger of dying
from the amount of alcohol she had consumed.''
When motorists rushed to the crash scene near Evanton, in Easter Ross, they
found Taylor sitting in her car, polishing off a quarter-bottle of whisky.
Mr Hingston described how Taylor, of Wester Balblair, Beauly, first hit a kerb
and stopped. A passing driver, a Mr MacKenzie, went to her aid, only to find
her drinking out of the bottle.
The fiscal said: ``He had no legal right to remove her car keys but very public
spiritedly offered to drive her home. She refused. But he remained nearby to
keep an eye on her.''
She drove off. Despite an oncoming driver's attempt to avoid her, she collided
with him on the grass verge.
At this stage, Mr MacKenzie stepped in and took away Taylor's car keys.
Meanwhile, Taylor finished off her bottle of whisky while awaiting the arrival
of the police, and threw away the empty.
She also had to hang on to a policeman to stand up and, instead of blowing into
the breathalyser, she dismantled it.
Taylor admitted driving dangerously while unfit, refusing a breath test at the
scene, and giving only one of the two required breath samples at Alness police
station.
Sheriff James Fraser deferred sentence until January 8 for reports.
</TEXT>
