<HEADLINE>Crawley limps off as England slump</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864514</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLAN Donald tormented England in Durban with the bat then ruined their day
altogether in his more accustomed role as an innings-wrecker.
South Africa's brilliant fast bowler contributed 32 unlikely runs to a highly
damaging last wicket stand of 72 with new-ball partner Shaun Pollock.
But, having taken 103 minutes to steal the initiative away from England as a
No.11, Donald needed only two deliveries to complete a dramatic third Test
turnaround.
The first, at the end of his opening over, was snicked by Mike Atherton into
Andrew Hudson's hands no more than an inch or two from the ground at gulley.
The second, during Donald's third over, saw new No.3 Graham Thorpe edge another
low chance, this time to Daryll Cullinan at first slip.
From being up against the ropes only an hour into the second day's play, South
Africa were suddenly landing one telling blow after another. By the time bad
light brought a premature close, the home side were ahead on points with
England struggling at 123 for five, still 102 runs behind.
That, however, was only part of the problem for Atherton's men as an injury
jinx returned to haunt them again.
John Crawley, racing round the boundary in a vain attempt to stop the 4 that
registered the home team's 200, was no more than a couple of yards from the
ball when he pulled up in agony, clutching his left hamstring. The injury looks
like ending his tour and he must now bat with a runner.
Injuries were almost an everyday event in Australia last winter. So were
batting collapses and, in Durban, the two went hand in hand again.
Atherton, perhaps, had to fail because no-one can be a hero all the time. But
seeing the man who thwarted them in Johannesburg walking away with only two
runs to his name was just the boost South Africa needed.
Thorpe was forced to fill the No.3 spot after Crawley's injury - and became the
twentieth England player over the last 111 Tests to find it a jinxed position.
The spot has now produced just 10 centuries in 199 innings.
From 13 for two, Alec Stewart and Robin Smith steered England into slightly
calmer waters while adding 70 runs. But then up popped support seamer Craig
Matthews to give South Africa another lift just when they needed it.
Durban-born Smith, having struck six boundaries, pushed at one of several
deliveries that bounced more than expected and another low chance was snapped
up by Brian McMillan at first slip.
Stewart, meanwhile, looked on course to end a sequence of 13 Test innings
without so much as a half-century. But when nine runs short of that
mini-milestone the vice-captain sliced a back-foot force to Hudson in the
gulley.
Matthews had struck two key blows in as many overs and not even Jack Russell
could deny him a third success before close of play. The keeper, who kept
Atherton company so loyally during that unforgettable last day in Johannesburg,
knuckled down for another 42 minutes until being caught by the leaping Jonty
Rhodes at point.
Graeme Hick and Dominic Cork managed to see out the final two offers before
gratefully accepting an offer to leave for bad light. But a day that had
started so brightly for England was by now gloomy in more ways than one.
With Peter Martin completing a four-wicket haul when McMillan edged to Russell
and Mark Ilott removing Rhodes, Dave Richardson and Matthews in the space of
six balls, the tourists had enjoyed a golden first hour.
But their inability to shift South Africa's final pair until spinner Richard
Illingworth bowled Donald through the gate 35 minutes after lunch took the
shine of all that sparkling work.
