<HEADLINE>Hay and McMillan reach final hurdle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOTH Scotland teams won their semi-finals at the European Championships
yesterday here in Grindelwald, Switzerland, to qualify for today's finals.
The Scottish women - Katie and Edith Loudon, Karen Addison, and skip Kirsty Hay
- had two impressive victories. Having disposed of champions Denmark by 8-4 in
a morning quarter-final, they went on to beat Norway for the second time this
week with a 6-4 win last night.
Scotland took a single at the first end, Norway blanked the second, then
settled for a single, and stole another single at the fourth. In the fifth, Hay
had a chance to take the lead but had to settle for just one shot.
Norway went ahead again but Scotland's breakthrough came in the seventh end
when they scored 3. Norway ran out of stones in the tenth end.
Scotland's men - Roger McIntyre, Mike Hay, Norman Brown and skip HammyMcMillan
- dominated against surprise semi-finalists Italy to win 5-1. They now are only
one game away from retaining their European title.
McMillan won this game the hard way, scoring four of his five points when he
did not have last stone, including the first end. After steals in the sixth,
seventh, and eighth ends the Italians conceded. Results:
