<HEADLINE>Diana skips gym as `new man' takes heat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864516</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales broke with her routine by skipping her regular morning
work-out at an exclusive gym, where the alleged new man in her life turned up
for a fitness session yesterday.
Wealthy property developer Christopher Whalley braved a battery of cameramen to
train as usual at the Chelsea Harbour Club gym in West London.
He was named by two national newspapers as having struck up a secret friendship
with the princess after meeting at the fitness centre.
However, following his visit to the gym this morning, the man at the centre of
the latest royal speculation vanished.
He arrived at about 7.50am in a black J-registration Mercedes, accompanied by a
man who shielded him from the cameras as they walked in from the car park.
Later in the morning, other club members leaving the gym told waiting newsmen
Mr Whalley had already left.
At about 10am, a man drove the Mercedes to another area of the car park, took a
black holdall and black plastic bag from the car, and drove away in an orange
Golf, taking the keys to the Mercedes with him.
According to a report in yesterday's Daily Mirror, Mr Whalley, 40, began a
relationship with the princess 14 months ago, after they met at the gym.
The Cambridge-educated bachelor has met the princess for breakfasts and lunches
at Kensington Palace and in fashionable London restaurants, and is believed to
have spent weekends with her at his remote farmhouse in Yorkshire, according to
the newspaper.
He is believed to run London property development company Stemplace Ltd.
Staff at a firm of accountants at the offices in Battersea, south-west London,
where Stemplace is registered, said Mr Whalley would not be available for
comment yesterday.
Mr Whalley and the princess are reported to have met and began their friendship
after she stopped him on the stairs at the Chelsea Harbour Club and said:
``What does a girl have to do to get a coffee around here?''
Mr Whalley is said by friends to be ``the ultimate charmer''.
The Sun describes Mr Whalley as a ``dashing hunk'' and one of the most eligible
bachelors in London, and says the princess's friends have thrown a cloak of
secrecy around him.
It quotes one friend as saying: ``She never wanted this to come out. He's been
discreet and loyal and doesn't consider his friendship a big deal.''
Asked about the relationship, Mr Whalley told The Sun: ``I'm not one of her
regular friends. So she's phoned me a couple of times - what exactly is the big
deal?''
Asked if he thought it was bizarre that Diana should call him after meeting in
the gym, he told the newspaper: ``Of course not. Everyone's entitled to have
friends.''
