<HEADLINE>Mother shouts at accused</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN was led from a court yesterday after shouting at the man accused of
murdering her daughter.
Ms Dorothy Niven's mother shouted: ``I am doing a life sentence because of what
you did and my husband is dying in hospital.''
Salesman Richard Karling, 43, denies drugging and murdering Ms Niven after she
threatened to end their affair.
Mr Karling, of Bellview Crescent, Ayr, told the High Court in Glasgow he found
Ms Niven lying face down in her bed and thought she was ill.
However, advocate-depute William Totten, prosecuting, told him: ``She was a
young, attractive, and vivacious girl and you were obsessed by her.
``You gave her expensive gifts, a Rolex watch, a car, and holidays abroad, but
you had no more money and the good times were running out. If she had put you
out of her life, you would have been left sitting in your rented flat with
nothing and you could not accept that.''
Mr Totten said Mr Karling did not try to waken Ms Niven when he said he found
her in the bed, because he knew she was already dead.
Mr Totten told him: ``You killed her. You got her to her home by drugging her
with Temazepam and killed her.''
Mr Karling replied: ``No.''
He denies murder and claims Ms Niven led a double life working as a secretary
for the Students' Loan Company and as a sauna girl.
</TEXT>
