<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Editor attacks prince after contempt case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TODAY, the defunct newspaper, was fined #75,000 yesterday after publishing
extracts from a book on royal bedroom secrets.
After the case, the paper's editor, Mr Richard Stott, delivered a stinging
attack on the Prince of Wales.
Mr Stott, through his counsel, Lord Lester QC, had offered his ``unqualified
and sincere apologies'' to the High Court in London after admitting that the
article, taken from the book by the prince's former housekeeper, Mrs Wendy
Berry, had breached a worldwide injunction.
However, outside court after the verdict, Mr Stott said the whole action had
``a great deal more to do with who was involved than what it was about''.
He added: ``It is absolutely outrageous that the Prince of Wales would want to
consign people to prison for that kind of thing when he is prepared to go on TV
and talk about his relationship with Camilla Parker Bowles and other matters of
confidentiality.''
The prince had obtained a worldwide injunction banning Mrs Berry from cashing
in on her nine years' service with the royal family at Highgrove, which ended
in 1991.
However, the former royal housekeeper, now believed to be living in Canada,
went ahead and published in the US. In her book, The Housekeeper's Diary, she
claimed she was revealing the Princess of Wales's bedroom secrets.
Lord Lester had told Mr Justice Potts the Today article had been taken from a
book that was already in the public domain. and that the case bore parallels
with the Spycatcher saga.
The European Court of Human Rights had found that, because Peter Wright's book
had already been published abroad, all secrecy had been lost and
confidentiality could not be maintained by an English court.
However, Lord Lester said Mr Stott did not realise that the European court's
decision did not affect contempt of court orders made in English courts.
News UK Ltd, publishers of Today, was fined #50,000 and Mr Stott #25,000.
Lord Justice Potts said Mr Stott had received advice from leading counsel
before the book was published in the US and, if he had taken the same direction
after the book came out in the US, he would no doubt have been warned ``publish
at your peril''.
He said the case stemmed from an injunction issued in the High Court in January
this year, restraining Mrs Berry from publishing or revealing anywhere in the
world information which came during her employment in the royal household.
Mr Stott and News UK had admitted they knew of the injunction when they
published in July but were unaware it affected them because the material was no
longer confidential, unpublished information and was available everywhere.
Lord Justice Potts said both parties had committed a serious contempt of court
but he accepted that the editor acted on mistaken advice from his own house
lawyers and, for this reason, he was not committing him to prison.
Mr Stott said outside court: ``At least I am not in the Tower. We were never
served with this injunction - a wide-ranging injunction which should have been
served to everybody.
``This was information I suggest was in the public domain and this is not the
sort of situation where you try to put someone into prison.
``This area of the law is a complete muddle. No-one knows where they are going
on this. It is complete and utter nonsense for Buckingham Palace to serve an
injunction which does not state clearly what we are supposed to do.''
</TEXT>
