<HEADLINE>Teaming up for success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT that he would admit it, but if anyone on the Goldenacre pitch today has
greater reason for nerves than the title-chasing Stirling County players it is
Heriot's winger, Elliot Bunney.
One feature of being an athletics star - and Bunney certainly was that with a
record six Scottish senior 100 metres titles, one more than Scotland's only
Olympic sprint champions, Eric Liddell and Allan Wells - is that failure lets
down only one's self. Team sport brings corporate responsibility, of which
Bunney, making his first XV national league debut, is aware.
``It's a team game, and I don't relish all this personal hype,'' insists the
28-year-old, who last season returned to the game after a 12-year absence.
Perhaps the fact that his most significant track honour was Olympic relay
silver hints that Bunney is at heart a team creature. Inevitably, however,
those with a sense of history dwell on the prospect of his following Liddell on
to the wing for Scotland.
Bunney won't entertain such talk. ``I started playing for fun, and that's still
what this is about for me,'' he says.
Though he has quit the track, Bunney still works at sprint drills twice weekly,
not least to support internationalists Jamie Henderson and Doug Walker, who are
preparing for the New Year Sprint at Meadowbank. Bunney, alloted joint back
mark beside one-time Heriot's winger Walker, does not wish to make a fool of
himself and will not race.
The conditioning, however, has kept him sharp, and his pace should not surprise
Stirling. After all, his best times put him ahead of Welsh winger Nigel Walker,
the former international hurdler generally acknowledged as the world's quickest
wing.
With Livingston last year, Bunney scored with his first touch, then seven tries
in eight games. He had one try in his only Heriot's first XV appearance, a
friendly against Preston Lodge.
Appetite for the physical          aspects has been lacking in most of those to
have made the transition from track to rugby. By all accounts, Bunney has not
been found wanting.
q.ROB Andrew has predicted a bright future for Newcastle after the threat of
relegation from Division 2 was lifted. The RFU's competition sub-committee,
handed the task of increasing the second division from 10 to 14 members,
decided there would still up a two-up, two-down passage betweens divisions one
and two but opted against a play-off between league two's bottom club and the
fifth-placed in three.
Now Andrew, Newcastle's rugby director, sees the decision as a major step
towards Newcastle becoming one of the giants of the English game.
</TEXT>
