<HEADLINE>Councils pledge a Burns festival lifeline</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE International Burns Festival has been thrown a lifeline just weeks before
it is due to get under way.
Local authorities in the South-west of Scotland have pledged a further #169,000
to save the bicentenary celebrations from collapse.
A last-ditch plea to the councils and enterprise companies - which have already
pledged #260,400 - was successful, and first priority for the organisers will
be to pay for the festival brochures, which they could not afford to send to
the printers.
However, Cunninghame District Council stood out among the nine principal
backers, when it refused to give the festival more money.
Labour MP for Cumminghame South, Mr Brian Donohoe, said: ``I am not surprised
at the decision. The festival has been so badly marketed that it causes me
nothing but despair.
``It is a total and absolute shambles and those people responsible for its
organisation must bear the consquences.
``They have lost a golden opportunity to attract tourists to Ayrshire. I don't
believe they have harried people as much as they should to back the event.''
He added: ``There were 30,000 people at Burns's funeral. They will be lucky if
they get a few thousand at next year's event.''
Among responses from other core funders of the festival, only Kyle and Carrick
District Council have yet to decide on a request for a further #45,484 grant.
It wants talks with the organisers next month before making its decision.
In Cumnock and Doon Valley, councillors agreed to a #10,000 grant, only two
thirds of the amount requested.
Mr Stuart Finlayson, acting chief executive of Kilmarnock and Loudoun District
Council, said: ``If additional financial support is not generated, then the
festival will fold.
``If the festival folds, there will be no economic or other benefits for the
area and the council will have to make a contribution towards wind-up costs.''
Mr John Struthers, festival director, said: ``Despite considerable efforts, it
has not proved possible to recruit a main sponsor.
``Our current cash-flow projections show that by the end of the festival, in
March 1997, it is likely there will be a deficit of some #235,000.
``We have considered the possibility of cutting some of the programme but even
cutting all of it would only reduce the risk of financial exposure marginally.
``Furthermore, reducing the number of key events would seriously jeopardise not
only new sponsorship but also the sponsorship already pledged.
``We believe we are on the verge of putting in place a viable and successful
festival.''
It has emerged that the only sponsorship obtained includes #25,000 from Tennent
Caledonian Breweries, #20,000 ``in kind'' from Dalblair Motors of Ayr, and an
estimated #80,000 from the Bank of Scotland and United Distillers.
Mr Struthers said they had five other firms who could be described as ``strong
leads''. They were also holding fresh talks with Strathclyde Regional Council
and the Scottish Tourist Board about finance.
</TEXT>
