<HEADLINE>Service for flu victim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCHOOL friends and teachers paid their last respects to flu victim Stephen
Mackenzie at a special church service yesterday.
The eight-year-old from St Mary's Roman Catholic Primary School, in Paisley,
collapsed from the illness last weekend and died at the town's Royal Alexandra
Hospital.
Classmates joined a large gathering of family and friends for a funeral Mass at
the town's St Mary's Catholic Church.
Parish priest Father Tom Jamieson said Stephen was a star pupil and added:
``Boys and girls in Stephen's class said Stephen always made people laugh.''
Referring to the youngster's classmates, Father Jamieson said: ``He was always
a friend to all his brothers and sisters.
``If any child was in the playground with nobody to play with, Stephen would be
the one to go over and play with them. He was a friend to anyone.''
Parents Thomas and Jacqueline followed their son's tiny white coffin as it was
carried out of the church to Woodside Cemetery nearby.
Stephen, who had been off school with flu, collapsed and died in the family
home in Broomlands Street, Paisley, on Saturday morning.
His mother had found him lying unconscious in the hall. All efforts to revive
him failed.
Doctors said it was extremely rare for flu to be a killer.
</TEXT>
