<HEADLINE>NO BUSINESS LIKE FOOTBALL</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gavin Kennedy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>the herald essay</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Why does football bring out daftness in otherwise sensible people?
Gavin Kennedy ponders the folly of businessmen and football financing
BEING ``fitba daft'' is relatively harmless. It is an affliction found to
varying degrees among football supporters and among certain businessmen (and a
few business women) who run football clubs.
With few exceptions, owning a football club is just plain daft in business
terms. Hard-nosed business folk, who can smell commercial follies at Jodrel
Bank distances, can go weak in the head whenever that folly is a grass pitch
with wooden rectangles at each end.
The businessman fan has only to sniff a chance to realise their childhood
dreams and they throw their hard-earned cash at debt-ridden, hopelessly
loss-making, non-commercially run outfits, against which, no amount of sensible
advice can deter them.
If they count their spare cash in millions - Walker of Blackburn, or Hall of
Newcastle, even Murray of Rangers - their follies are their own. They can
afford to lose it all. But when they count their cash in hundreds of thousands,
or less, their follies can have consequences well beyond themselves.
Why does football bring out daftness in otherwise sensible people? Re-living
Saturday's matches on Monday morning with your mates - even mates from rival
tribes - is one thing, but putting real money into controlling a club merely to
end up with a free seat and a hot pie in the director's box is another. Sure,
that is not how they see it when they commence their folly but as surely as
linesmen punish your team with outrageous offside flags, a free seat is all
they will end up with, until, that is, the brute course of financial disaster
forces them out.
The dreadful tragedy of Hillsborough has had an enormous effect on all clubs by
its rulng that to play football at the highest level the clubs must accommodate
the spectators in modern and safe stands. Progress has been spectacular. What
commercial sense failed to impose, the deaths of fans made obligatory.
Football in the ``good old days'' was watched in wretched conditions. Yet you
can still hear fans deep into nostalgia for the camaraderie of the chanting,
singing, swearing, and occasional sweet banter of the dirty cages they stood
in. One radio commentator, bemoaning the lack of passion in a recent game,
blamed it on the ``impossibility of seriously singing sitting down''.
Why did the owners not invest years ago? Simply put, the answer must be, with a
few honourable exceptions, that they did not have to invest in their stadia
because their customers were willing to put up with unplumbed depths of filth
just to see their team playing and, if they were not willing, they could stay
away for all the controllers of clubs cared or noticed.
The economics of football are as lunatic as the Common Agriculture Policy.
Football depends on the willingness of its customers to pay to see their team
defeat another team for ``points''. The winning team takes the points and goes
home happy; the losing team gets nothing and goes home bitter. The team with
the most points from the scheduled number of games wins a league championship
and gets a shot at the bigger money available in European football. And, to
maintain the interest of the weaker teams, they have other chances to win a cup
competition.
But, as night follows day, the impossibility of satisfying everybody is
obvious. If some teams win, other teams must lose. A sense of crisis is
inevitable whenever one's own team loses. Heads are called for: the manager's,
the players', and the owners. To avoid the consequences of these inevitable
fates, the managers, the players, and the directors play a game called
``Survival at all Cost''.
Team managers demand money from the owners to buy new players, who, in turn,
demand more money to move to clubs that are desperate for their services;
owners throw what money they can at buying solutions and, when this does not
work, or if they have no money, they resort to bank borrowing. They might
persuade the bank to lend them money or, as dangerous, they might resort to
pledging the club's assets to the bank, including the stadium and land, the
players' registrations, and any ancillary assets associated with the club's
past. In doing so, the club's future earnings are pledged in a desperate effort
to climb up the league table or to win a cup. But if they succeed other clubs
must fail in a vicious circle.
The bottom teams borrow to get back up and the top teams borrow to stay up -
thus the endemic financial problems of football are fully explained. That is
why almost all clubs are in debt to some extent, with many in debt to
horrendous levels. The million or more that they borrowed to buy a player, who
was intended, nay certain, to be the club's salvation, imposes mounting
repayment costs whether they save the club or sink with it. When what has to be
paid back exceeds what can be financed out of the club's actual earnings, the
club sinks into a debt swamp, against which selling assets brings only
temporary relief.
Borrowing to punt for glory is a hit-or-miss affair. That million pound-plus
player can be crippled for life three minutes into his next game, and thereby
be a worthless asset on the balance sheet. Fortunately, that does not happen
too often, but injuries just less than career-breaking do occur regularly,
which raises issues about the relatively poor treatment in Scotland for
prematurely retired players compared to the more generous treatment they
receive in England, courtesy of the efforts of the players' union. A proportion
of the television and transfer monies should be used to fund a players'
benevolent scheme. The Scottish football authorities, however, have declined so
far to discuss this proposal seriously with the Scottish players' union and
meantime the victims of occupational injuries must rely on the benevolence of
their clubs).
Managers can have a short club life too. Declarations of confidence from
chairmen are usually a prelude to an abrupt sacking. But managers do not come
or go cheap. They can cost as much as top players, even in modestly successful
clubs, and where they cannot expect large salaries they go for long contracts,
and sometimes both, as a bargaining hedge against abrupt dismissal.
Having borrowed to the hilt, sold and bought players, and changed managers,
probably more than once, the only people left to blame are the owners. This is
less frequent in football than is common where lenders and shareholders have
greater powers. Football clubs lead charmed lives in this respect. Companies
making similar losses, with a deteriorating risk-reward ratio, would be on a
bank's ``watch list'' shortly before intervention. Of course, the banks make
good money from their indebtedness and there is no need to feel sorry for any
bank's plight.
As long as the tangible assets of the club can cover the debt, the bank may
continue to help beyond the patience it shows to other customers. But to
liquidate the club's assets and realise the money the club owes, would
automatically liquidate the ability of the football club to function. Showdown
would mean shutdown.
That this does not happen too often (eg Third Lanark) is a testimony to the
folly of football financing. There is always somebody around who will try their
luck at owning a club. That somebody can come from anywhere. In Celtic's case,
Fergus McCann crossed back over the Atlantic on the back of golfing holidays.
Some of these saviours save their clubs permanently, others do so only until
financial imprudence catches up with them. Still others make things only worse
than they were before they got notions well beyond their personal means
(consider the history of Hibs before the current owners fortunately stepped in).
Football is unlike other business sectors. In the normal market, each firm
competes for the customers of other firms and their strategies of success are
underpinned by a determination to drive the weaker firms out of business.
Success is measured by profitable performance. Those firms that succeed pay
high salaries to those in charge of their success. The weaker firms cut costs,
and therefore rewards, to their failing employees. The richer firms can
innovate or copy at their discretion.
In football, failure leads clubs to bid at ever higher prices for ``better''
players and managing staff. The imperative is to invest from a narrowing asset
base, probably already mortgaged beyond the hilt. But they must either borrow
to invest or face the ignominy of retreating to a lower division; hence pride
overcomes prudence. It takes three or more years to turn round an ailing
business in a normally competitive market, but in football, a 10-month season
is long-term. Often, the owners have only a few months to get it right again
and that is why the bank is resorted to so recklessly.
No football club has any business incentive to drive another club out of
business (I exclude the aberration of Wallace Mercer's bid for Hibernian FC).
If football clubs competed to drive their rivals out of business, against whom
would they play on a Saturday? Ever-weaker teams from impoverished lower
divisions would not fill large stadia with paying customers for too long. Even
the legendary ``never-bored-with-winning'' Rangers fans would soon tire of 20-0
victories over ``Auchindinny United''. Competition in football takes place on
the pitch between the teams and not in the form of products in a general
market. Both groups of customer consume the product - the same game - at the
same time. Each club, therefore, needs credible rivals to survive so that they
can succeed when they beat them. That is what the customer pays to watch.
Clubs arose from local communities a hundred years ago and some small number of
them regard their place in the sun as an inheritance and fiercely defend their
right to the top spots.
Team competition on the field is the foundation of the financial follies of
most clubs. The noisy exhilaration of scoring a goal and the silent despair at
losing one, drives owners, managers, players, and customers to want someone -
usually the bank - to spend money they have not got themselves to keep their
team scoring goals, or stop letting them in.
Everything is fired by the need for a winning result. Each round of competition
leads to more and more expense and, ultimately ineffective, attempts to improve
performance. The sensation of the first #1m player shrivels in wonder against
today's sensation of the first #8m player - how soon before the first #50m
player? The richer clubs raid the poorer clubs for the best players; the poorer
clubs turn out team the ``B'' teams of the richer clubs, because they can
afford to buy only what is off-loaded by them. What will happen to this fragile
financial merry go round when transfer fees are abolished, or radically amended?
This is not all. Football is a regulated business sector like few others.
Professional football is governed by the administrators of the Scottish
Football Association and the Scottish Football League. These bodies are elected
from individual clubs and area associations across the country and they set the
rules, decide the changes, impose the fines, and maintain the discipline of all
players, professional and amateur.
It is possible, thereby, that people can rise in the game's convoluted
structure to the very top and end up controlling a multimillion-pound business
sector, even though they have never played or managed at the highest (or any)
level of the game, nor ever run any sizeable business, nor sweated over meeting
a weekly payroll out of diminishing earnings with their homes in line for
repossession, nor been noted for very much (not a sin, mind you, but neither is
it a qualification). They can rule over those who have done it all and more,
and they can enforce the fiercest discipline, including incredible fines that
would embarrass an vengeful judge.
Football recently has discovered new and vast sources of income in the global
entertainment business. The World Cup and the various regional cups (of which
our own European Champions' League is but one) are firmly under the financial
control, not of the clubs, whose employees, the players, create the
entertainment the world willingly pays to see, but of the national, regional,
and world governing bodies, from the SFA, through UEFA, to the very top at
FIFA. The clubs and their employees do not get a look in. They must obey all
the decisions of the governing bodies, right down to height of their socks, and
submit unconditionally to their jurisdiction.
This rich seam of income - we are talking about hundreds of millions -
strengthens the governing bodies over the clubs and the players by an
ever-greater degree. The clubs, heads down, have not noticed or, if they have,
cannot do anything about it, the significance of the strategic shift from club
football, with its myriads of little dramas and petty personality clashes and
crises, plus financial lunacy, to football as a global entertainment business,
with its TV, sponsorship, and mass merchandising mega-bucks deals. The game's
administrators, by default perhaps, by sheer good luck of being in charge of
the beautiful game, have found themselves beyond the reach of the most
ambitious of club chairmen (any of whom they can, and occasionally have,
slapped down for daring to stick their heads above the parapet).
The consequences of the Bosman case for transfer fees (a source of income, as
well as a major expense, for cash-strapped clubs) are not fully understood just
yet but serious change is one consequence we can be sure of even now.
n.Gavin Kennedy is professor of management at Heriot-Watt University Business
School, and founder and managing director of Negotiate Ltd, a company which
advises on negotiating strategies and techniques. He is a shareholder and
long-standing (and long-suffering) supporter of Hearts.
</TEXT>
