<HEADLINE>Joining the best-tressed set</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
To be the belle of the Christmas ball, you have to be head and shoulders above
the crowd. Prepared to put up with almost anything, Anvar Khan goes in search
of the perfect party hairdo
TRIED &amp; TESTED
n The styles on this page are representative of the range of results you may
expect when you have long hair and ask a reputable Scottish stylist to dress it.
I gave no instructions, other than I was going to a party and the stylists were
not allowed to pick up their scissors. This may seem somewhat cruel, like
asking a mechanic to work without a spanner, but I deemed it a fair challenge.
Hairdressers are notorious for wanting to cut hair. So what happens when they
can't snip? How do you glamorise someone then? The point system is subjective,
and suggestions for where-to-wear-it are pure speculation.
TOTAL 17/20
nCharlie Taylor, 20-28 South Methven Street, Perth, Telephone: Perth 33221
Price: #40
Originality: 8/10, Enjoyability: 9/10
Time: 2 hours
The office was divided on this style, as I walked the lonely corridor from the
paper's fashion studio, where Charlie did her work, to my desk. ``Oh, what have
they done to you?'' said a female colleague. ``Well, at least we're honest''
said one of the cheekier wimps, after he entertained a savage chortling at my
expense. ``Oh,'' I sneered, ``what a saving grace that is.'' ``But it's braw,''
said another, ``Oh, it's gorgeous.''
Charlie Taylor is Scottish Hairdresser of the Year 1995. She's been a
hairdresser for twenty years, studied under Trevor Sorbie and got broody,
though not necessarily in that order. She has two babies, one adopted girl, who
is half-Ethiopian, the other, all of 23 months, her own. Her husband, Alastair,
is the practical side of the partnership. He's very big, a rugby player-type,
she told me (we'll get to the hair later), and he organises her. Charlie is
slim and petite and very glamorous. Hubbie may be physically stronger, but
psychologically, she's a bison. Charlie built her team and her Clarins Gold
salon from scratch, at the age of 34, she now employs 27 staff.
There was immediately the unspoken agreement that she would not put my hair up,
as she was certain that's what the others would do. Instead, she used Babyliss
professional tongs and a technique she recently learned from a session stylist
who dresses the tresses of big cats such as Marie Helvin, Jerry Hall, and
Joanna Lumley. However, I'm sure you already made that connection, when you
looked at the photo. ``It's very John the Baptist,'' offered my neighbour. For
budding musketeers, perhaps.
nRegis Hair and Beauty, Debenhams, Argyll Street, Glasgow, Phone: 0141 204 1036
Price: #10
Originality: 8/10
Enjoyability: 8/10
Time: 1 hour
IT was only when we were half way through the styling process that Shona Miller
confessed she had been worried about doing a reporter's hair. She said she'd
been uptight all morning in case The Herald was doing some kind of survey in
which she failed; forgive me, I couldn't disillusion her. I couldn't tell her
there was a judging format, because I didn't want to make her more
uncomfortable. And anyway, given what she was doing with my tresses, I knew she
was going to come out tops. Regis also score high marks for being the only
salon not to ask me about my holidays.
The Regis salon is tucked away on the third floor of Debenhams department
store, and here you can be sure you're paying for the service and styling
rather than the decor. There are no leather suites to be paid off, no unctuous
bowls of fresh lilies or sunflowers, just light inches of flyaway hair
electrocuted on to white, emulsioned customer stations, and trolleys of rollers
and combs. This is a working salon, a wide space which is sometimes full, but
never full of it.
Shona washed my locks, put them in a dozen large rollers (my hair, I now
understand, has the volume of a church mouse) and sat me under the dryer. She
told me she'd been working for Regis for a year, but was still learning. She
said hairdressers swapped tips, and in that way they are a very generous
profession. Indeed, even I could see how her styling advice was being
photocopied and filed by colleagues. Shona then spent 30 minutes pinning
ringlets to my scalp after smoothing and backcombing each section. She went
straight for it, under pressure of time, and never had to undo a pin. This is
definitely a party hairdo, shapely and sleek. She's a star.
Regis are offering a Top to Toe treatment for #55, which includes a facial,
manicure and pedicure, back and shoulder massage, cut, shampoo and set/blow dry.
TOTAL 16/20
nAlan Edwards Salon, The Briggait, Glasgow, Phone: 0141 552-8131
Price: #25.50
Originality: 8/10, Enjoyability: 6/10
Time: 2 hours
MY hair was put once again in velcro rollers, and a pleasant, cocky young chap
by the name of Ross did the honours. After asking him about conditioning
treatments for hair (I thought I might need one by now), he rattled on for
about 15 minutes about what I could do to keep it healthy. (Avoid doing hair
features for a start). I was warned off when I said I liked using shampoos with
a natural not a chemical smell.
``You don't want stuff that smells nice,'' he said, irritably, ``You want
products which are good for your hair.'' I forgave him on the grounds that he
was a man.
My hair was dried by a space age silver tadpole. The tail attached to the hood
was secured on to a hairdryer nozzle. Ross advised me on how to conduct
temperature changes in case I overheated, then flicked the hairdryer on full
blast. The tube erected with wind, and suddenly I had a hat like the body of a
puffa jacket from Cape Canaveral. Senior Stylist Carmen Little, however, was
determined to apply the personal touch.
Kissing plays a huge part in the exuberant, laddish, atmosphere of the Alan
Edwards salon. Carmen saw off a customer with a friendly peck, but couldn't
remember his name. But while there were mouths in motion, there were too few
hands. The salon was busy. Carmen needed someone to press a knot of hair, so
she could knit a chain up the back of my head, so I had to oblige. It's not
quite as bad as having to hold the needle while a nurse takes a blood sample,
but helping out any professional always makes you feel superfluous rather than
cared for. I did like this hairdo, the detail; links and pineapple tufts, were
very futuristic. Carmen also wins the prize for using the most hairgrips. I
counted out 52 when I got home.
TOTAL 14/20
n Taylor Ferguson, 106 Bath Street, Glasgow, Tel: 0141 332-0397
Price: Hair #25, Make-Up #13.50, Nails #13
Originality: 7/10, Enjoyability: 7/10
Time: 2 hours
TAYLOR Ferguson is a ubiquitous chap. He is at everyone's beck and call: the
wife, the customer, the staff, the press. His salon life would be made easier
with a pair of skates, but he is too much of a gentleman to look as if he's
thinking of himself.
My hair was sprayed with a light hairspray and set in velcro rollers. I was
then seated under a hooded drier, or ``the pod'' as I call it, for a blast of
hot air. The Fergusons insisted I had my nails and make-up done too. They
wanted me to enjoy my visit. Debbie, the beauty therapist, was very amenable.
She gave me a relaxing facial massage and coloured me in.
At one point I had three people around me, Taylor undoing rollers, Debbie
scrabbling at my cuticles, and an assistant passing the hairgrips. I actually
felt embarrassed for causing so much trouble. Anne told me she thinks Scottish
women are happy to get their hair done, but don't take to being made-up because
they see it as unnecessary pampering.
Determinant on your social life and circle, the word ``party'' conjures up
various expectations. Some dress down, so they don't ruin their best gear
during the inevitable journey to drunkeness. Others presume canapes and olives
and men with husband potential. Taylor set me up with a hairdo which would have
seen me through an interview with a UN Ambassador, shopping at Harvey Nicks, or
picking at a moonlit dinner on a fabulously expensive Mediterranean cruise
liner.
``It's very posh,'' said a friend. ``It's a bit Imelda Marcos,'' said another.
Personally, I thought I looked sensibly square, like a solicitor (the legal
kind) who's keeping her wild side under expensive wraps for the right man with
the right wallet.
Taylor Ferguson are currently offering their party makeover - hair, nails and
make-up - for the special price of #45.
TOTAL 14/20
</TEXT>
