<TEXT>
q ROUGH Quest, in front too long when a legless second to Couldnt Be Better in
the Hennessy Gold Cup, can exact sweet revenge under a tighter reign in the
Betterware Cup at Ascot today, Terry Casey's nine-year-old, ridden by Jamie
Osborne at Newbury, went to the front at the tenth and his supporters could
allow themselves a modest grin as he galloped towards the third last with a
clear advantage over his rivals.
However, the picture had changed dramatically within barely half a minute, as
Rough Quest could summon nothing when passed approaching the last, eventually
going down by 14 lengths.
Although he was anything but discredited by his performance in the Hennessy,
there is every reason to suggest that he is capable of better.
All his previous best efforts had come when produced late on, and the way he
finished the race at Newbury - hardly able to lift his legs out of the mire -
suggests that too much use was made of him.
Even Osborne, a pilot on a par with the best, admitted subsequently that the
tactics had not worked, and expect to see today's rider Mick Fitzgerald holding
Rough Quest in something resembling a half nelson during the early stages.
</TEXT>
