<HEADLINE>Hill lose court battle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOOKMAKERS William Hill failed in the High Court yesterday to stave off a
tripling of the fees they must pay for using Tote odds.
They had claimed that the fee increase from #2 to #6 at each of their 1600
betting shops was an attempt to pressurise them into taking part in a joint
venture between the Horserace Totalisator Board and arch rivals Bass Leisure
Group, who own Coral's network of 750 shops.
William Hill did not want to take part in the joint venture, Tote Direct, which
Mr Justice Macpherson said appeared to have lost money in each of its three
years of operation.
But he said he could see ``nothing arbitrary or unfair'' in the Tote's
decision, which will mean Hill's must pay another #340,000 a year.
Tote Direct enables punters to place their bets directly into the Tote pool,
but bookmakers have to pay #1500 for computer terminals at each of their shops.
The Tote announced earlier this year that bookmakers who had the terminals in
at least 80% of their shops would have their fees frozen for seven years.
The judge said William Hill had ``comprehensively lost'' their judicial review
challenge and must pay the costs of the legal action.
q STABLE lads' wages will rise by 3% from next year after their representatives
reached a ``realistic'' settlement on pay and working conditions with the
trainers. From February 1, 1996, the minimum rate for the most experienced lad
will rise to #164.83 with the most junior taking home #76.76 for a 40-hour,
five-and-a-half-day working week.
q DOPE tests on Dancing Dove, second to Chadwick's Ginger at Carlisle on
October 6, and High Five, tailed-off last behind Unchanged at Folkestone on
September 7, have proved positive.
Dancing Dove, trained by Gordon Richards, was found to have isoxsuprine in its
urine and clenbuterol, another prohibited substance was found in High Five's
urine.
Inquiries will be held by the Jockey Club's disciplinary committee in due
course.
</TEXT>
