<HEADLINE>Scottish banks' share prices surge as takeover speculation in the sector rises to fever pitch Royal plays down HSBC bid rumours</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEVERISH speculation that Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation was poised to
bid 750p-a-share for Royal Bank of Scotland yesterday set shares in the
perceived bid prey alight.
However, what was hailed by one senior dealer as ``a good rumour for a Friday''
appeared to have lost much of its credibility by the end of the session and, in
percentage terms, Bank of Scotland made greater gains.
Shares in Royal Bank surged to an intra-day high of 658p, soaring 72p from
Thursday's close. By the session-end they had fallen back to 608p, up 22p, in
hefty volume of about 10 million shares. Bank of Scotland, which gained 12p on
Thursday, leapt 16!sp to another all-time high of 306!sp.
It was rumoured that Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation (HSBC) would offer
0.46 of its own shares and 300p in cash for each Royal Bank share, valuing the
Edinburgh-based bank at a weighty #6100m.
This level of detail, which has been absent in other recent instances of bid
speculation surrounding Royal Bank, lent credence to the rumour early on.
One market-maker said of Royal Bank's 658p intra-day high: ``When the stock is
going hell for leather some people make stupid prices and people deal on them.
There wouldn't have been much volume at that level.''
Royal Bank said it was not in ``any discussions with any potential bidder'' and
a hostile bid by HSBC, whose shares were off 6!sp on 998p, would certainly mark
a sea change in its philosophy.
The rumour appeared to cut little ice with the managing director of Royal
Bank's corporate and institutional banking division, Iain Robertson.
Mr Robertson took profits on 80,000 shares, more than half his entire holding,
selling them at 620p.
Royal Bank chief executive George Mathewson has said it would be extremely
unusual for a business with the bank's track record to be the subject of an
``unwanted'' bid.
Comments by HSBC chairman Sir William Purves, which indicated his regret that
Clydesdale Bank had been sold by Midland before HSBC took over the ``big four''
bank in 1992, have added fuel to rumours that HSBC is seeking a foothold north
of the Border.
An HSBC official, who would not comment on whether the group would or would not
bid for Royal Bank, said she did not think too much attention should be paid to
the ``Scottishness'' of Sir William in the context of what HSBC would like to
do.
The official emphasised that HSBC did not have a ``shopping list''.
She added: ``We are a very liquid company. We do see many opportunities of
acquiring companies, sometimes up to about 10 a week. We haven't done anything
this year. That doesn't mean we are not poised to do something next year.''
Senior HSBC executives have said repeatedly in recent months that they were in
no hurry to buy banks at current price levels.
BZW banking analyst Hugh Pye said that, on paper, HSBC and Royal Bank might be
a good fit.
But he added: ``The fact of the matter is that the Royal Bank chief executive
has stated very firmly that he is not interested, so that rather puts paid to
it.''
</TEXT>
