<HEADLINE>Hussain bats his way back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<FLAG>cricket round-up</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NASSER Hussain struck a brilliant century in Pakistan yesterday before
confirming that 1995 has seen him hit new heights as a batsman.
Hussain's England A team remain unbeaten seven weeks and nine games into their
Pakistan tour after a remarkable one-run victory against Pakistan A at Peshawar.
Yorkshire all-rounder Craig White was the other hero, conceding just three runs
from an inspired final over as England A went 1-0 up in the three match one-day
series, which ends their trip.
White also made a sprightly 39 not out to help Hussain (100 not out) put on 81
in the last 10 overs of the England innings. Yet afterwards skipper Hussain was
the first to admit that it was the Pakistanis who should have won.
He said: ``They are a better one-day side than a Test side, but we did not bowl
as well as we can. We were definitely below par today and I'm sure the lads
realised that.
``But they kept fighting and Craig White and Dean Headley bowled really well
during those last three overs. No side should lose when they have only to make
15 from the final 18 balls, and with wickets in hand.
``In the end I think it was our determination not to be beaten that probably
saw us through.''
He continued: ``We are all very aware of our unbeaten tour record. Now we have
just two more games to win to make sure we go home with that record intact.
That would be a fine achievement.''
Hussain, who has played seven Tests - the last two years ago - must now come in
back into the senior England reckoning.
England A 225-5 (N Hussain 100no), Pakistan A 224-6 (Shahid Anwar 100no).
England A beat Pakistan A by one run. Limited overs international in Peshawar.
q INDIA'S women cruised to a seven-wicket victory over England in the deciding
one-day international in Madras yesterday.
England, who went into the match with high hopes of scoring a double success
after their 1-0 Test series victory, struggled to 146 for nine from their 50
overs, with captain Karen Smithies top scoring with 38.
India were always in control in their reply, Anjun Chopra smacking an unbeaten
57 to guide her side to 149 for three with more than five overs to spare,
clinching a 3-2 series victory.
</TEXT>
