<HEADLINE>Cover up before you slope off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Helen Pridham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT this time of year many people are not so much looking forward to Christmas
or even Hogmanay as to the period after that when they can get away for some
skiing.
For those venturing overseas, choosing a resort which offers good snow
conditions at a reasonable price will be top priority. But making sure you have
adequate insurance cover is also vital.
Most tour companies now make travel insurance a condition of booking. But you
do not have to take the cover in the brochure. Indeed, your travel agent will
probably try to persuade you to take out its policy instead. But compare the
cost and the cover before you decide.
A cheaper way of buying travel insurance nowadays is to choose an annual
policy. These are offered by larger building societies and banks, such as the
Royal Bank of Scotland. They normally include up to 17 days of ski insurance as
well as cover for other holidays throughout the year.
A family policy from the Royal Bank, which includes cover for up to three
children aged 18 or under, costs #130.
Naturally it is important to compare not just costs, but what the insurance
includes. If you want to be adventurous and ski off-piste, check the terms.
Some insurers exclude off-piste skiing, others will only cover you if you are
accompanied by a guide, while some do not impose any restrictions.
Snowboarding is also becoming increasingly popular. It is expected around 40%
of skiers will try it this season. But some insurance contracts exclude it as a
dangerous sport.
One annual travel policy which covers both snowboarding and off-piste skiing
(with the need for a guide) is WorldCover Direct (0800 365121). It provides 21
days ski insurance a year. The cover can be used for any number of trips (some
policies allow only one ski trip per year) so it could be used for, say, three
one-week holidays. If you are a real ski addict, you can extend your cover to
up to three months a year.
The cost of WorldCover Direct's basic annual policy is #75 for an individual,
#110 for a couple, and #120 for a family, which can include children up to the
age of 21 in full-time education. A big advantage for families is that children
are still covered if they travel separately.
WorldCover Direct's Jonathan Biles points out: ``The vast majority of travel
insurance policies insist on the family travelling together. There is no such
restriction with WorldCover Direct. Children living at home or in full-time
education are covered for all their holiday travel and school trips up to the
age of 21, even if taken without their parents, and partners can travel
independently.''
Another useful feature of the policy is that it covers travel in the UK more
than 25 miles from home. So if you intend to swan off to Aviemore for the odd
weekend, you will have the comfort of knowing you are insured for loss of ski
equipment and have such things as public liability cover.
--
IF you are going abroad, you will also need to consider your currency
requirements. An increasing number of travellers are opting to use credit
cards. Fiona Wilkinson of Visa UK says: ``As well as convenience for hiring
skis and paying for lessons, cards also tend to give better foreign exchange
rates.''
Before you go away, however, check whether your issuer provides a 24-hour
replacement service in case it is lost or stolen. Visa UK (0800 106030) is
offering a free wallet-sized ``ski pass'' which gives emergency telephone
numbers to contact if this occurs, along with useful information on the UK's
most popular holiday destinations. It also contains safety advice from the Ski
Club of Great Britain for skiers and snowboarders.
According to leading travel insurer Home and Overseas, though, most accidents
do not occur on the slopes. Spokesman Martin Mills explains: ``More injuries
happen when people are walking around a resort because they slip on an icy step
or someone ploughs into them.''
You have been warned!
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A media distress flare full of sound and fury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>television</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT least among life's mysteries is Janet Street-Porter. Her very existence
begs you to wonder if the invention of television was not perhaps humanity's
biggest mistake after the walking erect game became fashionable.
If the medium is the message, Street-Porter is a distress flare, flashing
Chanel red, from an industry fresh out of ideas.
She is, in her much parodied way, the epitome of a certain kind of telly
person, what with her essentially juvenile faith in ``yoof'', her apparent
belief that history began with rap and the hand-held camera, her nerveless
smile and her verbless sentences. Street-Porter's mission, whenever she pops
up, seems to be to prove communication without content is not only possible but
desirable.
Splendid, then, to see her flounder and drown amid the banalities of Live TV in
Robert Thirkell's Nightmare at Canary Wharf (BBC2, Monday). Hired by the Mirror
Group's unlovable David Montgomery to create a 24-hour cable station that would
be bright, innovative, entertaining and, above all, cheap, Street-Porter had
her six months of pre-lauch hell captured for posterity, perhaps as a warning
to all those inclined to believe that quantity in television is next to quality.
What was most fascinating about this fly-on-the-wall was the internal politics
of Live TV. Hardly surprising, perhaps, what with participants as egregious as
S-P, Montgomery, and Kelvin MacKenzie, a man once feted in this industry for
reasons that remain mysterious. But the fabulous fun of the piece lay in the
fact this unlovely trio fell out only over entirely trivial matters. There was
no dispute over whether or not they should be producing tat; it was the nature
of the tat, its primal tattiness, that alone counted.
S-P, as acolytes know her, wanted more yoof-friendly stuff, that being the only
idea she seems to have. Kelvin fancied a spot of topless darts (the players,
not the darts) as an avant-garde challenge to the cultural hegemony and elitism
of, say, snooker. S-P swore a lot while Kelvin did a lot of smirking, as though
entirely confident that when it came to bare-knuckle boardroom bitching it
would, of course, be the man from the Sun Wot Won It. And he did.
Clive James, suddenly back on form, won nothing but amiable scorn from the folk
in Nashville when he went country (ITV, Monday) and tried to make a hit from
the sow's ear of a song he claimed to have written. It may all have been a
gentle satire on the quality of compositions emanating from Music City, but
given that this presenter's ego is equivalent to a major landmass, it was hard
to be sure. Clive has literary gifts, does he not? He has said so himself.
Either way, it was a lot of fun. We got to hear Chet Atkins play for a brief,
dazzling moment. We were given to understand that even the production and
guitar of Mark Knopfler couldn't make Clive's turkey fly. And we saw an entire
city obsessed in its every waking moment with its industry. If Hollywood is
movies, Nashville is music, another place where each year thousands of aspiring
stars go to build, or more often to bury, their white American dreams.
Jonathan Ross has a dream, we may guess, and it is a humble one: he wants to be
loved and he wants to be taken seriously. The trouble is, one wish militates
against the other. It's hard to take seriously the man who said recently that
Batman Forever is ``the best movie ever made'' but it is near-impossible to
love a personality who is, beyond question, the biggest fan Jonathan Ross will
ever have.
In Search of James Bond With Jonathan Ross (ITV, Sunday) - note the ``with'' -
was in essence yet another shameless plug for a new movie disguised as a
documentary precisely as convincingly as Sean Connery's dome was disguised by
his hair-piece. Ross interviewed various screen Bonds, pretended to drive an
Aston Martin, and invited Hugh Hefner to applaud his own lecherous appreciation
of the so-called ``Bond girls''.
It was only funny when you stopped to remind yourself that someone had paid a
great deal of money to put this slice of schoolboy wish-fulfilment on the
screen.
Someone at ITV Network Centre, or whatever the gloomy name of Channel Three's
command-and-control operation is these days, has also laid out big money on
Jack Dee, and you can't entirely blame them. He is a very funny, very talented
man, who will doubtless one day host a hit prime-time show - but not this week.
Jack Dee's Saturday Night (ITV) is one of those attempts to be all things to
all couch-potatoes. It combines a hot, young comedian new to the mums and dads
with hot, young bands, more familiar older acts, and even, as last week, a
couple of superannuated Coronation Street stars. Did someone think this would
work? Did someone imagine that the best way to promote a relatively new act was
to keep him off the stage for most of his own show? You can only wonder, come
to that, if Dee's lugubrious material will withstand the scrutiny of a mass
audience. To begin with a routine about cat's vomit might seem brave and quirky
on paper; on-stage it looked and sounded like a mess on the carpet. Even Dee
seemed to sense it wasn't working. How he will cope with a bill like tonight's,
which manages to include both Freddie Starr and Paul Weller, is a thought that
offers its own, horrible fascination.
No such surprises were offered in the two-part An Evening With Sir Peter
Ustinov (BBC, Sunday and Tuesday) and it did not matter at all. The veteran wit
has trucked his trunkful of anecdotes and memories around every major city and
most major chat shows on the globe but the brilliance of it all remains
undimmed.
Ustinov tells a story as though he were playing all the parts, including the
animals, in a big-budget epic; his jowls alone express more with a joke than
most actors manage with Hamlet. Someone, somewhere, should give him the sort of
time and space for an autobiographical documentary that is presently being
squandered on the likes of Jonathan Ross. But we should be so lucky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court jester should be nobody's fool</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WORRY about Prince Charles. He strikes me as serious minded, well-intentioned
and hard working. Qualities which would make him an excellent King.
Unfortunately, he has a serious, possibly fatal, flaw - his navete. The
tabloids were right this week to mock the photograph on his Christmas card
which shows him perched uncomfortably on a stone garden seat with Wills and
Harry emerging from two huge urns like flowerpot men. It begs the question: is
he the little weed in the centre? Any toddler would have asked that, nevermind
a cerebral organ like The Sun.
Why then did one of the expensive chinless wonders who parade themselves as
``aides'' not point this out to him? It is bad enough that he is a
self-confessed talker to plants, an adulterer, and has friends like ``Bunter''
Soames. These alone offer countless opportunities to poke fun and not just from
anti-monarchists or cynical commentators.
Last week a former member of the Palace staff told me the Prince had called up
his lawyer and told him he is suing for divorce. ``On what grounds?'' the
lawyer asked. ``Can you believe it,'' the Prince replied. ``My wife says I'm a
lousy lover.'' ``That's why you are sueing?'' the lawyer retorted. ``Of course
not,'' said the Prince. ``I'm suing because she knows the difference.''
And, as Frank Carson would say - there's more. Apparently, days before the
wedding the young Diana had whispered to the Prince: ``Will you still love me
after we are married?'' ``Probably even more,'' he replied. ``I have a thing
about married women.''
The company I was in, which, with me as the exception, could be categorised
fairly as part of the Establishment, was howling with laughter. Each could not
wait to tell their royal joke.
But this, of course, is not unusual. Subjects have tended to mock monarchs and
their families since time immemorial. However, presenting yourself as a figure
of fun as Prince Charles is inclined to do is harmful to the very institution
he represents. It seems astonishing at a time when spin doctors abound and
every two-bit actress has a street-wise publicist, the Prince of Wales should
depend on advisers who would be better qualified writing scripts for Have I Got
News For You.
Even his wife, the Princess of Wales, with all the brain power of a spent
battery, has out-manouvered him. She is a woman who proves Ken and Barbie did
have a love child. Whatever she says is fatuous. In her Sloaney world people
don't have weaknesses and failures - only maladies. Gluttony followed by
vomiting she dignifies as an illness. For her ``love'' is not a difficult and
painful experience but a cure-all for the world's ills. She makes Tony Blair
sound sincere.
With supreme coaching from Clive James she has ambushed the Royal Family, yet
she has her title solely by virtue of being the wife of the Prince of Wales.
She may be beautiful but this does not qualify her as an ambassador abroad. It
is a truth universally acknowledged that such a woman on the loose must be in
want of a lover which is why, the nation's wives, being more calculating
creatures, distrust her more than their husbands who are easy prey to a pretty
face.
The personal life of these two individuals would not matter were it not having
an adverse affect on the standing of the British monarchy and posed a threat to
its very existence. The monarchy helps sustain in the British people a belief
in the legitimacy of constitutional, democratic government. It is difficult to
keep this in mind when the only aspect of the Royal Family discussed is who is
sleeping with whom.
Bagehot was right when he said a system of government based on rationality
alone would leave people feeling there is something missing. We need only look
across the Atlantic to see how the world's biggest democracy is desperate for
an emotional attachment to one family, hence the obsession with the Kennedys.
The monarchy not only offers a symbol of continuity and tradition; it plays a
pivotal role in our liberty. Hitler came to power in Germany by democratic
means then abolished elections. Winston Churchill and Lloyd George both
observed that had the Kaiser been there Hitler would not have got away with it.
In Italy, the King was unable to stem the rise of Fasciscm but played an
important role in re-establishing democracy. And who would argue that in Spain
the monarchy has not protected the democratic institutions from right and left
wing insurgency?
The worst excesses in the modern world have taken place in republics whether in
the communist bloc, Africa, or the Middle East. As Henry von Blumenthal of the
Monarchist League has remarked: ``Where autocratic monarchies have been
overthrown as in Iran, Iraq, Libya and Cambodia, the result has been an even
worse republican substitute.''
Bagehot warned ``we must not let daylight in upon magic'' but this is
impossible to sustain in an age when society seems hungry for scandal. What the
Royal Family needs, and Prince Charles in particular, is good PR. For instance,
the Prince's Trust is a remarkable achievement and thousands have benefited
from training and jobs under its auspices. It has aided those who found
government agencies wanting.
Add to this the tremendous job the Royal Family has done in promoting British
industry and trade abroad due to the personal touch and the close ties which
bind the commonwealth, despite differences. A realisation of this by the public
would take the monarchy out of the pages of Hello magazine and back to the
centre of our constitutional debate.
The Prince of Wales is a sensitive man but the way to the nation's heart is not
through vulgar populism or school-room humour. Leave that to the Princess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenny Logan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPPORTUNITY knocks. As big games go, they don't come much bigger than today's
spellbinder at Goldenacre. If we beat Heriot's by 43 points we retain the
championship, if we beat them by 42 points a play-off with Melrose is on the
cards, and if we lose we finish fourth in the title race.
To put 43 points between ourselves and Heriot's is a mighty tall order, but
nothing is impossible. Stirling County are certainly capable of scoring the
points required, but you would have to reckon, too, that by       the law of
averages Heriot's wouldn't finish with a blank scorecard.
Our first priority is to win. Secondly, we have to score a minimum of 43 points
and, thirdly, we have to make sure that we don't leak points at the other end.
That should make for an interesting afternoon's entertainment!
Of course, the ideal scenario from a marketing man's point of view would be for
us to finish level on points and points differential with Melrose, then the
whole thing would go to a play-off. It's happened before, away back in 1977,
when Hawick beat Gala in a winner-take-all game at the Greenyards.
It would be brilliant for the fans if it happened again, but I'll bet Melrose,
just like us, are rather hoping that it's all done and dusted today.
One guy who won't be on       parade with us today is John Manson. The prop was
sent off last weekend while playing for North and Midlands against the South. I
wasn't at the game, so I can't comment on the circumstances of the dismissal.
What I can say, though, is that John feels he has let himself and the club
down.
It's not just County. He was desperate to make his mark with Scotland this
season and, until his sentence is known, that hangs in the balance too.
I've had to sit out the inter-district championship so far because of a knee
injury, but I have gone along as a spectator to Glasgow's games against North
and Midlands and the Exiles. The fans are still voting with their feet. There
were only 500 or so at Burnbrae last Sunday for the Exiles game and I'd bet
that West of Scotland attract more for a premiership match.
There really does have to be more of a marketing effort and, certainly if
district or provincial sides are to be in the European Cup next season, then
there will have to be a    marketing blitz. If you look at how the likes of Sky
TV push football, then you see the kind of campaign that we need in rugby. Use
the players, focus on the internationalists.
TV can make Falkirk v Raith sound as appetising as Rangers v Aberdeen. You
really do need to get some hype going and that's what's going to be required
next season.
So far as participation in the European Cup is concerned, I can understand why
my own club, plus Melrose, Watsonians and Boroughmuir, for instance, want to be
involved, but for the good of the game as a whole I still think that district,
or provincial sides, should be involved from Scotland.
Three super clubs dominating the Scottish scene wouldn't be good for the
long-term future of Scottish rugby.
I do think, though, that whatever three sides we enter in Europe, we should
make use of all the top players. This would mean creating three provincial
sides from the five districts currently playing in the inter-district
championship.
I made my after-dinner speaking debut at West of Scotland last weekend. Those
who were there may well have witnessed a unique occasion. I've retired hurt
after just the single outing.
</TEXT>
