<HEADLINE>CHEMICALS Meconic profits grow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH-based fine chemicals manufacturer Meconic has more developments under
wraps, managing director Dr Marshall Smalley said yesterday,
writes ANDREW WILSON.
These are in addition to galanthamine which Shire Pharmaeuticals is in late
stage testing as a treament for Alzheimer's Disease and more information should
be available with Shire's flotation prospectus.
So far Meconic has used about 100 tonnes of daffodil bulbs which are the
natural source of galanthamine and is talking to growers about large long-term
contracts.
It already has a detergent to clean the lungs of new-born infants and a control
for Parkinson's Disease as well as two pain relievers.
All these are more for the future but the capital expenditure programme is
being stepped up rapidly to add about 30% capacity over the next two years. In
the first half-year as a listed company, Meconic increased operating profits by
23% to #2.5m.
The impetus came from the opiates where the Macfarlan Smith subsidiary is the
sole legal supplier in Britain - these include the active ingredient in codeine
and so as a listed drug has to be bought over the pharmacy counter and will not
be affected by any Asda-inspired price war in the supermarkets.
Speciality chemicals such as Bitrex, which is added to household chemicals as a
bittering agent, saw strong export sales as did the aloin intermediate used in
an anti-arthritis drug in France.
Full-year pre-tax profits seem set to rise from #4.7m to about #5.5m which
would leave the shares trading at around 18 times likely earnings. There is an
interim dividend of 1.65p.
Meconic is the outcome of a management buy-out from Glaxo and with the shares
at 201p, compared with the issue level of 135p in June, the original backers
have made an excellent return on their money.
New investors will benefit from the publicity from the Shire issue.
Meconic may get up to 10% of the product wholesale price and if the Alzheimer
tests are successful in what is obviously one of the leading pharmaceutical
growth markets, then there could be considerable progress in the share price.
