<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Baby dies of meningitis</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864533</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BABY has become the latest victim to die in an outbreak of meningitis which
in the last month has claimed four lives in the north-east of England.
The baby, who has not been named, was seven weeks old when the disease took
hold. Doctors were astonished at the speed of the child's death from the
disease, meningococcal septicaemia.
The youngster was taken to North Tyneside General Hospital's casualty
department on Thursday morning, and transferred to Newcastle General Hospital
when the disease was diagnosed, but died that afternoon.
Earlier yesterday, a five-month-old baby boy from Weymouth, Dorset, was
reported to have died at West Dorset hospital.
The number of cases of meningitis in Dorset has increased by more than 50% in
the past year.
Parents who notice any symptoms are advised to contact the nearest accident and
emergency department, if their GP is not available.
Meningitis is a bacterial infection which causes inflammation of the brain
lining.
Reece McCawll, four, of Middlesbrough, died on December 1 and, last week, the
disease killed a 16-year-old Bishop Auckland girl, and seven-month-old Mark
Casey, from Sunderland.
</TEXT>
