<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Telephone banking is not new but with the Halifax joining in, it is set to become far more widespread Dial M for money</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Gillian Barton</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BAITING the banks has been a popular sport for many years, but the development
of 24-hour telephone banking opens up a brand new dimension for
misunderstanding and confusion.
At best, I like to imagine customers ringing to check their current account
balance in the middle of the night only to hear the sound of gentle snoring. At
worst, there is potential for a whole new area where things can go wrong.
Judging by the latest report from the Banking Ombudsman, there are still plenty
of problems with the banks' traditional services. So he must be quaking in his
shoes as he views the imminent expansion of finance by phone.
Telephone banking has been around for a decade or so, but now that the giant
Halifax is to join the fray it looks set for a much higher profile. Around a
million of its customers can now use the new Halifax Direct service which has
been running as a pilot scheme for the past couple of years.
The building society, which plans to become a bank in 1997, admits it is late
on to the scene, but it believes the delay means it has got the technology just
right.
Presumably though even it hasn't figured out a way of actually delivering dosh
to your doorstep or of transmitting cash and cheques back down the telephone
line to credit your account.
Both these basic everyday needs still involve customers in a trudge to their
nearest branch or cash dispenser - or a drive or bus trip if, like me, closures
have left you without an easily accessible local branch.
Once all you needed to operate a bank account was a pair of legs, a pen and a
cheque book. Now you need a car, a telephone and, maybe, a special tonepad or
personal computer as well. That's progress.
While telephone banking first came on the scene in 1986, it was another three
years before First Direct became the first bank to offer a 24-hour service. Now
there are a dozen or so banks with telephone services for customers. There are
two main types, although the addition of banking through your personal computer
is waiting in the wings.
First, there are the stand-alone services including First Direct, the Bank of
Scotland's Banking Direct and NatWest's Primeline. These tend to offer the
largest range of options and customers can usually find out their account
balance, request a statement and order a new cheque book, set up a standing
order, arrange to pay bills, transfer money between accounts, stop cheques and
arrange overdrafts.
A smaller number of options may be available from the support-type services
which back up a branch network. These include the TSB's Phonebank, Clydesdale
Telebank and services from the Royal Bank of Scotland and Abbey National.
The Halifax's Maxim current account customers have already had access to a
limited range of telephone banking services through a computerised system. With
the new service, they'll be able to talk to a real person on the other end of
the line.
``Before Halifax Direct customers could arrange to pay bills, but these had to
be set up by the branch first. Now they can simply phone our new service and
ask for particular bills to be paid,'' the society says.
Banking services at Halifax Direct should be quickly followed by general
insurance and, later, life insurance and mortgages by phone.
Meanwhile, the latest report from the Banking Ombudsman highlights the problems
that can occur when banks move into new areas, and it has some sensible advice
for fans of phone finance.
``All customers, whether using telephone or branch banking, should be cautious
. . . and ensure they are speaking to an official of the bank before giving
confidential information about their financial affairs,'' the ombudsman,
Laurence Shurman, says.
The report shows that for the first time mortgages topped the list of
complaints investigated by his office. Among other things, he believes the
problems stem from the complexity of mortgage products and packages now on
offer.
One home owner was awarded more than #8700 by the ombudsman after he complained
about a remortgage on his home in Perthshire.
He had been told by the bank that the new repayments would be just over #650 a
month when, in fact, they turned out to be more than #775.
The ombudsman also turned the spotlight on mortgage indemnity guarantees (MIGs)
- policies that are paid for by home buyers, but designed to protect lenders
when a home is repossessed and sold for less than the amount needed to clear
the outstanding mortgage.
Mr Shurman says borrowers have been kept in the dark about the true nature and
cost of these policies and calls on banks to refund some of the premium if a
borrower pays off a home loan after only a short while.
Complaints about another modern trend in banking, cash machines, dropped back
into second place on the list last year.
``It is worrying, though, that there should still be as much fraud as there is
(and perpetrated with such apparent ease), when the cost of reimbursement will
inevitably be passed back to the general body of customers,'' Mr Shurman says.
</TEXT>
