<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fancier who drank his wife's divorce payment will have to sell loft or face going to jail Judges home in on pigeons</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN, Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PIGEON fancier who drank away an #8000 pay-off, which should have gone to his
wife as part of a divorce settlement, will have to sell his birds to help
settle the debt.
The sale of the pigeons and their loft is part of a bargain Thomas Robertson
hopes will keep him out of jail.
An interim interdict was pronounced against Robertson, of Cleveland Drive,
Inverkeithing, Fife, when he was divorced in 1992.
The court order in favour of his wife, now Mrs Sandra Fairley, banned Robertson
from getting rid of any money which he might receive as a result of his work at
Rosyth Dockyard.
The divorce settlement included a #7980 payment to Mrs Fairley.
Robertson received a payment of #8206 from the Ministry of Defence but when his
former wife took him to Dunfermline Sheriff Court he admitted he had spent it.
It was explained on his behalf that he had simply drunk the cash away over a
year in full knowledge that there was a court order against him.
Sheriff Ronald Alexander took the view that this amounted to a particularly
serious and flagrant contempt and jailed Robertson for 60 days. He was released
immediately pending an appeal to three judges at the Court of Session.
In a written judgment issued yesterday, Lord Ross, Lord Justice Clerk, who
heard the appeal with Lords Prosser and Mayfield, said the court had been
presented with a letter from Mrs Fairley saying she still had received no
payment of the divorce settlement.
Lord Ross added: ``It was also stated on her behalf that Mr Robertson, who is a
pigeon fancier, has recently purchased a pigeon loft and has several pigeons.''
There was also a letter from Robertson's solicitors offering to pay #150 a
month towards the divorce settlement.
Lord Ross said Mrs Fairley had made it clear she was interested in receiving
the money and that if it was paid she had no wish for her former husband to be
sent to prison.
The judge added: ``Mr Robertson informed us that he deeply regretted what he
had done. He stressed that he was prepared to make this monthly payment.
``He also stated that he would be prepared to sell the pigeon loft and his
pigeons, which could raise several hundred pounds, and that he would do so as
soon as possible.
``He explained that he had exhausted the gratuity which he had received from
the Ministry of Defence over a period of approximately one year.''
Robertson also informed the court that if he could get another job he would be
able to increase the amount payable to his former wife.
If he had to serve the 60 days, he would be less likely to find other work.
Lord Ross said that anyone who knowingly breached a court interdict would
normally be dealt with severely and in a case like this, a 60-day sentence
would not normally be regarded as excessive.
However, Robertson had adopted a very reasonable attitude and the main concern
had to be to ensure that Mrs Fairley received the payment to which she was
entitled.
The court had decided that the appropriate course was to continue the appeal
for six months so that Robertson could show that he was prepared to comply with
the order to pay the #7980 to his ex-wife.
The judge added: ``We have done so upon the understanding that Mr Robertson
will make payment of sums of at least #150 of month towards satisfaction of the
capital sum awarded to her in the decree of divorce.
``We also expect him to make further payments to Mrs Fairley in respect of the
proceeds of the sale of the pigeon loft and the pigeons.''
When the case came back to court in June next year the court would expect to be
told what payments Robertson had made to his former wife.
The court would decide what to do in the light of what happened over the next
six months.
</TEXT>
