<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protesters' journey to the courts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE partial victory by the Save Our Railway campaign yesterday marks the latest
in a series of moves by protesters to take their battle to the courts.
Earlier this year, Highland Regional Council secured an interdict at the Court
of Session in Edinburgh which prevented British Rail from withdrawing the Fort
William-London sleeper service until full public consultation had taken place.
That decision effectively saved the ``Deerstalker Express'' service. Franchise
Director Roger Salmon subsequently included a modified version of the service
in ScotRail's seven-year Passenger Service Requirement for the network.
Yesterday's success came after the Save Our Railways campaign appealed against
a High Court ruling last week which had cleared the franchise director of
accusations that he had unlawfully set minimum passenger service levels at too
low a figure.
</TEXT>
