<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIKE Ramsay was the first player to claim a place in the quarter-final stage
when he defeated local club player Richard Campbell in yesterday's first round
of the Scotish championships at Heriot-Watt University, Edinburgh.
Ramsay won a close first game 10-8 against the former Scottish junior
internationalist, but then cruised home 9-1, 9-2.
Cumbernauld's Peter O'Hara also went through to the last eight following a 3-1
win against Scottish junior champion Colin Hamilton.
O'Hara, a member of the Scottish senior squad, took the first two games 9-1,
9-6, before Hamilton staged a comeback to take the third 9-6.
However, it was the more experienced player who always held the upper hand in a
close fourth game, and he went through 9-1, 9-6, 6-9, 9-7 and now looks likely
to face former internationalist Graeme Sword.
Martin Heath, the No.1 seed, faced a worrying start to his bid for a first
title. The Oban player, with his brother and fellow competitor David as a
passenger, arrived over an hour late for his match after his car broke down.
However, the organisers showed leniency in rescheduling both ties for late in
the evening.
The women's joint top seeds, Claire Waddell and Senga Macfie, received
first-round byes and so begin their campaigns in today's quarter-finals.
