<HEADLINE>Singh in hot pursuit of Riley</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Montego Bay, Jamaica
ON another afternoon of hot sunshine and high humidity, Wayne Riley, the
Australian holder of the Scottish Open title, clung tenaciously to the lead
yesterday in the second round of the Johnnie Walker World Championship at the
Tryall Club in Jamaica. But he was strenuously pursued by Vijay Singh and the
two American Ryder Cup players, Loren Roberts and Fred Couples.
Riley had lost his three-stroke overnight advantage on Singh by the turn,
having had two bogeys to Singh's two birdies, the second of which gave the tall
Fijian the lead for the first time. But when Singh bogeyed the tenth and Riley
made his first birdie of the day at the twelfth he had resumed his leadership.
Roberts, beaten by Sam Torrance in the singles at Oak Hill in September after
having won his first three matches, moved into third place on two under par,
one behind Singh. Couples, the winner of the first championship four years ago,
was a stroke behind his compatriot with five to play.
Meanwhile, Colin Montgomerie and Torrance, the Scots who finished first and
second on the 1995 European order of merit, continued to starve themselves of
birdies. Montgomerie, who had two in the first round, had the same again and
Torrance's drought also reached parched-earth proportions as he made only two
gains in 36 holes.
Torrance again compromised his fortunes with a depressing start, a double-bogey
6 at the second, and after Montgomerie had hit a fine shot at the short third
to five feet for a 2, his inspiration dried up just as completely as his
compatriot's. About most of the field there was strong evidence of post-season
ennui syndrome.
