<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Franchise verdict means no hold-ups for Stagecoach</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STAGECOACH declared it had no plans to cut rail services on any network
post-privatisation, as it emerged that the South West Trains franchise which
the Perth-based bus company should now be awarded next week was one of only two
deemed by the Court of Appeal to be legal.
As a result of a challenge by pressure group Save Our Railways, the Court of
Appeal ruled that five of the seven franchises it considered were unlawful in
terms of minimum passenger service requirements.
The other franchise adjudged to be legal was Great Western Trains, which
franchising director Roger Salmon is expected to award to a consortium
comprising FirstBus, formed by the merger of Aberdeen-based GRT and
Weston-super-Mare-based Badgerline, investment capital group 3i, and the
existing management of the Welsh and West of England network.
Although the London, Tilbury and Southend franchise was considered illegal, the
challenge probably came too late to prevent the Office of Passenger Rail
Franchising (Opraf) also signing this contract next week.
Opraf said last night it was aiming to let the first franchises next week. Had
it not been for the appeal court action by Save Our Railways, Stagecoach would
probably have been awarded the South West Trains franchise this week.
Stagecoach last week attributed a newspaper report claiming it had won South
West Trains to the ``failed'' management buy-out team, apparently indicating
the Stagecoach bid had been successful.
However, the Perth-based company is prevented from making any specific comment
on South West Trains as a result of confidentiality undertakings.
Executive chairman Brian Souter said yesterday: ``It was in the public domain
that we were one of two preferred bidders for South West Trains.
``If South West Trains has been cleared, obviously we would be happy about
that.''
Declaring Stagecoach's strategy, Mr Souter said: ``Our bids are quality bids,
they are comprehensive bids and we have no plans to cut rail services in any of
the bids (for networks) that we are looking at.''
Referring to busy networks with little subsidy, Mr Souter added: ``Some of
these big commercial franchises have got very low PSRs (passenger service
requirements) but nobody in their right mind would cut the service. It would be
commercial suicide to cut some of these services.''
Mr Souter said Stagecoach was ``piggy in the middle'' in the argument between
the Government and Save Our Railways but the company is undeterred by the
pressure group's victory in the courts.
He added: ``Our appetite is there for rail franchises. We are interested in
them all and will bid for them all as it happens.
``If there is a delay with a court, we will stick with the process. It is an
inconvenience but has no impact on our view of railways.''
FirstBus, which has a 24.5% stake in the the consortium which is the sole
preferred bidder for Great Western Trains, yesterday declined comment on the
Court of Appeal judgment.
South West Trains, which operates the regional and commuter network out of
London's Waterloo, is the biggest of the 25 franchises being privatised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McKenzie haunted by Milne's shadow Stirling intend to build on victory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974864542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE task in hand for Stirling County today at Goldenacre is to put 43 points
between themselves and Heriot's, which would mean a successful defence of their
championship crown, with Melrose consigned to second place.
But for County captain Kevin McKenzie there is a target beyond today's
crucially important SRU Tennents Premiership encounter - the resumption of his
quest to make the Scotland hooker's berth his own.
For McKenzie, who has lived in the shadow of Herioter Kenny Milne - the game
does have a habit of throwing up these interesting ironies - the chase for the
Scotland No.2 shirt had taken on something like the pursuit of a holy grail.
Milne retired after the World Cup with 39 caps in the bag. McKenzie was the
heir apparent but then he got injured and missed Scotland's first outing of the
season, against Western Samoa.
The knee-ligament damage has taken nine weeks to heal and, aside from a bounce
game at stand-off last weekend, today marks McKenzie's first real outing since
a stamp on the knee put his plans on hold.
The occasion also will mark Milne's retirement from the game after 14 years in
the Heriot's first XV.
Yesterday, McKenzie, who has four caps but none against the major nations, was
wanting to concentrate on the game, but needed no reminding that today
represented the first day of the rest of his rugby life.
``Being up against Kenny doesn't enter into the equation for me. We've played
each other often enough in the past, so we both know what to expect. He has
done everything that there is to do in rugby and so he's got nothing to prove.
``For me, though, there are certainly things beyond this game. I have to play
well and make sure that the knee holds out. I don't think there's any doubt
that if I had been fit then I would have been in the Scotland side which played
Western Samoa. I like to think that, anyway. I look upon that as a cap lost.
``Yes, the injury was a bit of a killer. I had hung around for long enough
waiting for the opportunity to show what I could do. Kenny retired and then I
got injured, but you have to show the strength of character to come through an
experience like that.''
However, back to the business in hand. ``The main thing is to win the game
today and then the points will, hopefully, come. If we win, we can finish first
equal and if we lose on points difference, then so be it.
``Even if that were to happen, I reckon we would still have had a good season.
The problem has been losing to teams that we should have beaten. We've beaten
all the top sides and I still reckon that we're the best side in Scotland.
``To beat Heriot's by 43 points isn't impossible and we'll die in the attempt,
but you would have to say if you were being honest that it's improbable. We can
score 43 points but, by the law of averages, you would expect   Heriot's to
score some as well.''
Heriot's FP director of rugby Fraser Dall said yesterday that his side would
certainly not lack motivation. Heriot's would not be running on to their own
Goldenacre patch simply to make up the numbers.
But the hosts will be missing three leading players. Full back Stuart Lang
damaged his collar-bone at an Edinburgh squad session but is included in the
Edinburgh side to play South tomorrow; winger Cameron Glasgow has a hamstring
strain; and captain and tighthead prop Stuart Paul is also on the injury list.
Stirling are at full strength, with the exception of prop John Manson, who was
sent off last Sunday following a stamping incident in the South v North and
Midlands district championship game at Murrayfield.
Heriot's FP - C Aitken; D Fowler, D Stoddart, D Officer, E Bunney; P Smith, F
McMillan; M Livingstone, K Milne, A Binnie, P Young, J Turnbull, S Elliot, T
McVie, G Dall.
Stirling County - C Sangster; A Turner, I Jardine, M McGrandles, K Logan; M
McKenzie, K Harper; J Gibson, K McKenzie, B Robertson, S Hamilton, M Norval, G
Mackay, G Flockhart, B Ireland.
.ALL 21 England players in the squad for today's match against Western Samoa
have signed contracts with the       Rugby Football Union, which will bring
regular internationalists a guaranteed #36,000 this season.
Will Carling led the way by being first to sign the new deal, and now he wants
to concentrate on the Twickenham showdown, as England attempt to arrest a run
of three successive defeats.
``Nothing else will come to us unless we perform on the pitch and it is on
Twickenham rather than the team-meeting room that I am concentrating,'' said
Carling.
The captain is already impressed by newcomers Matt Dawson and Paul Grayson,
both winning their first caps, and Graham Rowntree, who is chosen on merit at
loose-head prop for the first time.
England beat Western Samoa 44-22 in the World Cup Group matches - but
weaknesses were revealed in England's defence.
``Western Samoa tried to hit the ball-carrier at the point where he is carrying
the ball, that means around chest high,'' added Carling. ``We must ensure that
our ball-retention stands up to their unusual tactic.''
</TEXT>
