<HEADLINE>DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIALS Trafalgar pledges quick turnaround after #321m loss</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BTRAFALGAR House shook the City with full-year losses nearly twice some
estimates at #321m as new chief executive Nigel Rich discovered a virtual can
of worms as contracts were put under the microscope and major assets were
written down to more realistic values.
Put more formally, chairman Simon Keswick blamed inadequate leadership, lack of
operational control and weak financial disciplines but added that he is
confident of making real progress this year.
However, the belief that the #204m of exceptional costs are truly the last
after the 1993 total of #397m written off helped the shares recover part of
their initial 3!sp fall to close 2p easier on the day at 24!sp.
That capitalises the Ordinary shares at #263m to leave Trafalgar in that
unhappy category where the market value is less than the losses.
A renewal of support came from 26% shareholder Hongkong Land which so far has
invested almost #600m in Trafalgar as well as the prestige of the Keswick
family.
But given the size of the order book which rose #500m year on year to #3300m
and the high skill levels in the engineering and construction divisions, many
believe the shares could be an interesting speculation on a medium-term view.
Although there will be a seasonal increase in debt in the first six months to
next March, debt is not a severe problem, particularly if more assets are sold
off such as the US property and housing activities. But those who stumped up
for the #425m Preference share funding at 100p in the beginning of 1994 are
feeling pretty sore with the stock now trading at 48!sp and seeing the dividend
being passed and with little real hope of receiving anything for perhaps three
years. In any case there are no distributable reserves with there being a total
net loss of #382m.
Mr Rich, who bought 500,000 Trafalgar shares at 78p and so has a string-vested
interest in recovery, said that Cunard was going nowhere when he arrived. It
was also hit by the disastrous QE2 refit which resulted in #8m of passenger
compensation claims.
The ships were unable to meet their targets and the value of the brand name was
being wasted so that there was a #16m operating loss before the compensation
compared with the 1994 profit of #8m. The fleet is being written down by #79m
with another #31m being taken for restructuring costs.
Consultants were put in late last year and by April were able to clarify the
position on the leading engineering and construction contracts.
The lack of controls under previous managements seems to be breathtaking with
Trafalgar having 700 operating subsidiaries, but it was impossible for top
management to discover how they were performing.
John Brown power engineering was hard hit by the problems of the Keadby plant
where the General Electric turbines had a large design fault. These had to be
returned to the US for re-engineering and the subsequent six-month delay on the
#250m contract where there appears to have been no recourse to suppliers helped
push the division from #13m profit into #69m loss.
The Clydebank-based operation is now much less ambitious, going for lower-risk
and smaller contracts which have reduced its order book while 23 supervisory
managers have departed.
Davy had a similar tale of woe with a deficit totalling #84m including #20m of
contract losses.
But there are bright spots such as the John Brown chemical engineering
activities where expansion in Asia is paying substantial dividends and at Ideal
Homes which doubled its profits to #19m and is a nice little nest egg for
future disposal.
However, there are more job losses to come in addition to the 620 already
announced and Trafalgar is going to be an unhappy place as the remedial surgery
begins.
