<TEXT>
PETER Wright, Boroughmuir's international prop, who has now completed the
six-week ban for verbal abuse of referee Kenny McCartney during his side's
premiership clash against Gala, comes straight back into the Edinburgh side to
play South of Scotland at Meggetland tomorrow.
Wright comes into the side which lost to the Exiles but which defeated Ulster
in last weekend's friendly. Wright's Meggetland team-mate, Scotland under-21
scrum half Graeme Beveridge, is on the bench, with Graham Burns of
Stewart's-Melville in the side. Team:
N Mardon (Boroughmuir); F Henderson, S Hastings (both Watsonians), D Wyllie
(Stewart's Melville), S Lang (Heriot's FP); A Donaldson (Currie), G Burns
(Stewart's Melville); G Wilson (Boroughmuir), G McKelvie (Watsonians), P
Wright, D Burns (both Boroughmuir), S Murray (Edinburgh Academicals), C Mather
(Watsonians), B Ward (Currie), D Clark (Stewart's Melville).
Replacements - R McNulty (Stewart's Melville), D Lindsay (Musselburgh), M McVie
(Edinburgh Academicals), G Beveridge, D Laird (both Boroughmuir), A N Other.
q.THE senior clubs pressing for club participation in next season's European
Cup, as opposed to the SRU plan for Districts to fly the Saltire, have been
further angered by the Union's statement this week that the district route is
now a ``decision'' and not a ``proposal''.
An official challenge leading to an extraordinary general meeting of the Union
looked even more likely last night as Boroughmuir secretary Norman Bryson
declared: ``We will have to examine the SRU constitution to determine whether
they have the power to make such a decision.''
