<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J.P. Leach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE phrase ``Christmas is a time for remembering'' becomes truer every year, so
much that it now has official cliche status. If there's one thing that
Christmas does not stand for at this time, it's worshipping. Born-again
Christians, for a change, are absolutely right in this respect.
Compared to America, BACs are very much a minority, and you have only to look
at America to know that this is a good thing. Their lack of insight into world
events is similar to their lack of fashion sense, and could be inferred about a
group of people who can believe that the meek should inherit the earth while
simultaneously demanding the right to carry a sub-machine gun in self-defence.
Despite all this, Christians are right about today's pagan approach to
Christmas. Their ``original message of Christmas'' (ie that stables aren't such
bad places after all) has been buried under a mountain of crass commercialism
and syrupy emotion.
Come midnight next Sunday, church pews will be full of shell-suited infidels
and, instead of hymns that ring emptily, there will be gutsy, beery breathed
renditions of the old Christmas favourites. Songs so good they're almost worth
sitting through a sermon for.
``Real'' Christians can get their parkas in a twist about it, but it's a fact
of life that Joe Soap is happy to hang around for a yuletide fix of religion,
as long as that's where it stays. As soon as the last strains of Silent Night
have died out, Joe will be off down the road with the rest of the Soap family,
looking forward to a day off work spent in front of the telly.
This is a time of year packed with emotion, more usually excruciating
embarrassment which surfaces every time the kids yell ``Daddy, when am I
getting another present?'' every time a visitor calls. Even back in the
seventies, when an opulent Christmas meant getting Mousetrap and Cleudo, the
world was full of killjoys sanctimoniously intoning that ``kids nowadays really
get too much, don't they?''
As I've got older I've realised that these are usually the people who feel
outdone on the present front. Having spent twice as much on your kids as you've
suggested, their faces fall when they see your living room looking like a
Fisher Price toy graveyard. Having, in their eyes, been outdone they can only
grab the moral high ground while inwardly resolving to start saving for next
year.
Tradition is the main driving force in Christmas festivities. Why do something
you enjoy, when you can instead do something that you've always done? This
slavishness to custom is what makes us eat certain foods, drink mulled wine,
and it can be the only credible reason why they buy records by Cliff Richard in
great quantity.
Religious people can moan about the syrupy sentimentality of Christmas, but
that's what keeps the collection plates full: religious observance is all part
of the Christmas package - albeit a minor one. It doesn't matter that no-one
goes to church any more; come the school nativity plays, every dad in the
country will have a lump in the throat.
Men who haven't seen the inside of a church for years will be close to tears
when they see their kids acting out a Bible story. Never mind that
baby-in-the-hay nonsense: look, there's our Kelly-Marie dressed up as a tree!
This has more to do with a worship of our past than a worship of God. These
guys don't care about any religion, they're too busy remembering their own
childhood.
For them, the real meaning of Christmas is nostalgia: glorified, sugary, sickly
nostalgia. If they weren't so busy getting into debt in order to create
Christmas nostalgia for their own kids, they'd stop and wonder what the hell
they were doing. Some sociologists think that this whole midwinter madness is
just a traditional Celtic way of trying to forget that it's been dark for the
past two months. I don't believe this.
Christmas is a time for remembering. No matter how bad things are now, we can
all remember at least one childhood Christmas when we had more toys, food, and
sweets than we could have dreamed possible. To make things even better, we
thought that it was a happy, unconditionally loving Santa that was setting all
this up.
In our subconscious, the Scalextrix and the Tiny Tears dolls were signs that a
higher force not just existed, but cared about each one of us. If you could
always believe in Santa, you really wouldn't need a God. If you can't believe
in him, then the next best thing is to watch your kids revel in their belief.
</TEXT>
