<TEXT>
YORKSHIRE Electricity, one of the dwindling number of English electricity
companies (RECs), has received a number of approaches but no actual bid talks
have taken place, according to director Brian Morgan.
The group would be prepared to talk to a potential bidder but did not believe a
merger could be justified.
``The sort of savings we anticipate you could obtain from a merger with another
REC or a water firm doesn't seem to us to justify the 30%-type of premium you
would anticipate having to pay,'' Mr Morgan commented.
Yorkshire yesterday confirmed its second massive dividend bonus this year. It
is to pay shareholders a special 100p-per-share bonus on top of its normal
interim payout of 11.88p, compared with 7.92p in the corresponding period last
year.
The announcement of the second special bonus was first made in October,
although it still has to be approved by shareholders. Pre-tax profits grew to
#110.6m for the six months to September, from #97.6m. Earnings per share jumped
10p to 45p.
In January, the Leeds-based group paid a 90p-per-share bonus dividend, which
cost it #188m, while the latest payout will amount to #184m after a recent
share consolidation programme.
Yorkshire chairman Christopher Hampson said the results demonstrated an
excellent performance in the face of a tightening regulatory regime.
``Our strategy is clear, namely to continue to build an efficient and
profitable energy business which will benefit both investors and customers.
``Accordingly, we intend through our performance to demonstrate the strength of
the company as an independent Yorkshire-based business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
