<HEADLINE>A host of angels, and a popular prime minister  Continuing our year-long harvest of the best of literary talent, Herald writers and critics select the reading material which stood out from the rest of the crop.</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILLIE ANDERSON
Snow Falling on Cedars, David Guterson (Bloomsbury, #5.99),
The Moor's Last Sigh, Salman Rushdie (Jonathan Cape, #15.99)
BOOKSELLERS are in a privileged position to choose from a wide variety of
immediately available books, but this does not protect them from the increasing
dross that some publishing houses are foisting on the public. Dross most
certainly cannot describe Snow Falling on Cedars by David Guterson, which is
one of the most accomplished first novels I have read in a long time. His
language and his powers of description to evoke the still pervasive sense of
mistrust in the States towards their citizens of oriental extraction make this
a book to be enjoyed by all.
The Moor's Last Sigh by Salman Rushdie is a novel by an author at his best. It
should have won this year's Booker Prize. It will certainly last longer in
people's memory.
HUGH BARNES
The Creature In The Map, Charles Nicholl (Jonathan Cape, #18.99)
So I Am Glad, A L Kennedy (Jonathan Cape, #9.99)
Son To The Father, Tony Peake (Little Brown, #15.99),
THE best non-fiction book I read this year was The Creature In The Map by
Charles Nicholl which marvellously reconstructed Sir Walter Raleigh's 1595
journey in search of the lost golden city of El Dorado.
In fiction, I enjoyed A L Kennedy's So I Am Glad for its mixture of love story,
allegory, fantasy and satire, and for the transforming enchantment of its
Glasgow streets, as well as Son To The Father by Tony Peake, a brilliant and
rapturous book about human relationships. This is a political novel in the best
sense: it's about the moral considerations at the root of political ideas, and
about chapter as an embodiment of moral nature.
IAN BELL
Dirt &amp; Deity - a Life of Robert Burns, Ian McIntyre (HarperCollins, #20)
The Letters of Robert Louis Stevenson - Volume Eight (Yale, #29.95)
The Moor's Last Sigh, Salman Rushdie, (Jonathan Cape, #15.99)
Tom Paine - A Political Life, John Keane (Bloomsbury, #25)
Paul Celan - Poet, Survivor, Jew; John Felstiner (Yale, #19.95)
IN a thin year full of tired gambits and dull writing I admired Ian McIntyre's
sane and clear-sighted Dirt &amp; Deity - a Life of Robert Burns. Simultaneously I
was awed, yet again, by the art and energy of RLS in The Letters of Robert
Louis Stevenson -Volume Eight and cheered (though this country barely deserves
him) by Salman Rushdie's superb The Moor's Last Sigh.
Two other books which left me just a little richer for the experience of
reading, meanwhile, were John Keane's Tom Paine -A Political Life and John
Felstiner's Paul Celan -Poet, Survivor, Jew. Each, in their different ways,
proof of the endurance of ideas.
STEVE BRUCE
Whit, Iain Banks (Little Brown, #16)
Scotland - the Brand David McCrone, Angela Morris and Richard Kiely (Edinburgh
University Press, #12.95)
Farmer's Diary Volume IV, Charlie Allan (Ardo Publishing, Methlick, #11.95)
IAIN Banks just gets better. Whit is humorous, humane and, considering it is
about a sheltered young girl coming of age in a religious commune, something of
a thriller.
With tourism soon to become our largest industry, David McCrone, Angela Morris
and Richard Kiely's Scotland - the Brand is timely. A study of ``heritage''
producers such as the National Trust and Tourist Board, it broadens into
provocative reflections on the link between Scotland's lack of a state and its
representation as a product for paying customers.
The Herald's Charlie Allan has long entertained ``toonsers'' who dream of the
rural idyll and farmers who can read with his weekly accounts of a small
farmer's working life. Farmer's Diary Volume IV is now in the shops or
available by post (as are the first three collections).
DEIRDRE CHAPMAN
Shards of Memory, Ruth Prawer Jhabvala (John Murray, #15.99)
Eveless Eden, Marianne Wiggins (Flamingo, #12.99)
Wonder Boys, Michael Chabon (Fourth Estate, #15.99)
THE books that impressed me this year all had a wide canvas and an offbeat way
of attacking it. Ruth Prawer Jhabvala's Shards of Memory is an untraditional
dynastic novel about an American/European/Indian family, living lives of
freedom and creativity, drawing on all these sources.
Marianne Wiggins's Eveless Eden made use of the catacylsmic news events of the
years 1986-91 to turn a powerful love-story-cum-thriller between a foreign
correspondent and a photographer into a metaphorical warning about our
emotional values.
And Michael Chabon's Wonder Boys, a tale of life glimpsed through dope and
chronic detachment, was the funniest book I've read in years.
JULIE DAVIDSON
Edith Wharton Abroad, edited by Sarah Bird Wright (Robert Hale, #15.99)
Leading the Blind: a Century of Guide Book Travel 1815-1914, Alan Sillitoe
(Macmillan, #15.99)
TRAVEL literature broadens the mind. The genre has a distinguished pedigree -
from the seventeenth century onwards it was de rigueur for peripatetic
belletrists to include travel writing in their canons - but today the challenge
is coming up with an angle.
Someone has been everywhere and everyone has been somewhere, so it's no longer
enough to visit and describe, as in Edith Wharton Abroad (edited by Sarah Bird
Wright), unless you have a fashionable name. A century on, however, the elegant
prejudices and controlled enthusiasm of Wharton's selected travel writings
(1888 to 1920) reveal more than the guide books she despised.
But look what she missed by neglecting the mighty Baedecker: a seam of social
history and polemical geography which has been mined by Alan Sillitoe in
Leading the Blind: a Century of Guide Book Travel 1815-1914. Sillitoe is a
collector of early guide books, and his creative excavations make an angel of
an angle.
MICHAEL FRY
Max Havelaar, written under the pen-name of Multatuli by EW Dekker, (Penguin
Classics #7.99)
FOR me the most intriguing new novel was an old one, originally published in
1860, but out this year in Penguin Classics. Max Havelaar, written under the
pen-name of Multatuli by E W Dekker, is intriguing because it is Dutch, and we
do not get to read too many Dutch novels. It is autobiographical, and concerns
the downfall of a young colonial official, a tearaway with a heart of gold. It
has a splendid villain, Batavus Droogstoppel, working within a complex
structure where he never actually meets the hero.
What struck me most, however, was its uncanny resemblance to George Douglas
Brown's The House with the Green Shutters, in showing a society where all hopes
are blighted by narrow provincial complacency. In this respect, Calvinist
Holland of the nineteenth century seems to have been much like Calvinist
Scotland.
CLARE HENRY
Art is the Flower, Pamela Robertson (Pavilion, #14.99)
Whistler: Drawings, Pastels and Prints (Yale UP, #95)
Angels, Archangels and all the Company of Heaven, Gottfried Knapp (Prestel,
#9.95)
ART is the Flower is the whimsical title of an excellent, beautifully
illustrated book on Charles Rennie Mackintosh's botanical watercolours. These
are his most popular images and a firm favourite of mine too. The book is by
Glasgow Hunterian's resident Mackintosh expert, Pamela Robertson. Another major
artist with Glasgow links is Whistler whose archive and bequest of pictures is
based at Glasgow University. Margaret MacDonald, a world expert, has spent 25
years on this irascible, eccentric, notorious but giant figure and distilled
her knowledge into the catalogue raisonne: Whistler: Drawings, Pastels and
Prints from Yale UP at #95. Comprehensible but readable.
Looking for an angel? Then Gottfried Knapp's Angels, Archangels and all the
Company of Heaven, with its glossy images from great paintings from Raphael,
Botticelli, Velasquez and Rubens to Rodin and Klee, is great value and just
right for a sentimental, frivolous Christmas.
ALEXANDER LINKLATER
The Crossing, Cormac McCarthy (Picador, #6.99)
Morvern Callar, Alan Warner (Jonathan Cape, #9.99)
Bunkerman, Duncan McLean (Jonathan Cape, #9.99)
CORMAC McCarthy's The Crossing did more than just survive the critical acclaim
which attended its predecessor, All the Pretty Horses. It made praise
superfluous. The near-biblical rhythms of his prose, the pounding dialogue, and
McCarthy's lonely picture of the world's enmity and darkness set it beyond the
reach of its commentaries. Alan Warner's Morvern Callar was the year's most
impressive debut. Morvern is a superbly cool and resourceful character. Her
expedient morality suppresses a despair which is given form in Warner's
entirely original picture of a grim West Coast of Scotland and rave-coast of
the Mediterranean.
And Duncan McLean has done something equally new to the Scottish North-east. In
gradually pushing its janitor protagonist towards psychosis, Bunkerman takes a
brilliantly unflinching, wrong-way look down the telescope of male sexuality.
JOHN MACLEOD
Rose Madder, Stephen King (Hodder Headline #15.99)
Virtually Normal: an argument about homosexuality, Andrew Sullivan (Picador,
#14.99)
The Missing Days, Kenneth C Steven, (Scottish Cultural Press, #4.95)
GRIPPER of the year: Stephen King's Rose Madder. I'd never read anything by
King, the world's best selling writer. I don't think you could dismiss his work
as pulp fiction; it is far too well written, and hard to despatch in a hurry.
Still, it is King: very dark, very chilling. When I reviewed this I said I'd
never read another Stephen King. I lied. I've since read two.
Best non-fiction: Andrew Sullivan's Virtually Normal: an argument about
homosexuality. Sullivan is working-class, right-wing, Roman Catholic and gay.
Confused? Maybe, and I couldn't agree with his conclusions, but his essay is
tightly reasoned, beautifully penned, and marked by a rare tolerance.
Kenneth C Steven's 1995 anthology of poems, The Missing Days is a delight.
Every one a gem, and for 56 poems a bargain at the price.
GEORGE McKECHNIE
Gladstone, Roy Jenkins (Macmillan, #20)
ON November 24, 1879 as he approached the age of 70, Gladstone began the first
of his legendary Midlothian campaigns progressing by train from Liverpool to
Edinburgh with intermediate station speeches at Carlisle (an audience of 500),
Hawick (4000) and Galashiels (8000).
It was dark when he reached Edinburgh, but ``the scene even to the West End of
the city was extraordinary both from the numbers and the enthusiasm''.
In his massive biography Gladstone, Roy Jenkins vividly captures the towering
magnetism of the great Victorian statesman and leaves us in little doubt that
by comparison the leaders of today are but political pygmies.
Jenkins recalls that during his first Midlothian adventure it was calculated
that Gladstone had addressed ``in 30 speeches and over a 15 day circuit the
precise figure of 86,930 people''.
A century on it is almost impossible to comprehend the prodigious energy,
output and oratory of Gladstone but Jenkins does manage to reduce him to the
status of mere mortal as he explores Gladstone's personal and family life, and
the anguish he had with his social and moral crusades.
HARRY REID
The Siren and Selected Writings, Giuseppe Tomasi di Lampedusa (Harvill Press,
#14.99)
The Masterless Men, J K Mayo (Macmillan, #14.99)
Ringan Gilhaizie, John Galt (Canongate Classics, #6.99)
FIRST, The Siren and Selected Writings by Giuseppe Tomasi di Lampedusa. The
Sicilian aristocrat Lampedusa wrote The Leopard, a powerful elegy for his
island, and the finest European novel of the century. He didn't produce much
else of note - but some of his better bits and pieces have been gathered in
this collection, intelligently introduced by his biogra-
Continued from Page 19
pher, the Scottish writer David Gilmour. A thin book full of fat pleasures.
Sicily also looms in The Masterless Men, the fifth and best of J K Mayo's Harry
Seddall novels. This thriller is a little cruel, unremittingly readable, and
imbued with a terrific sense of place.
Finally, Canongate Classics have issued a good, no-nonsense paperback edition
of Ringan Gilhaizie, John Galt's turbulent tale, written in 1823, of the
Scottish Reformation. This gutsy novel manages to be cerebral, tempestuous and
shocking all at once.
WILLIAM RUSSELL
Konin, A Quest by Theo Richmond (Jonathan Cape, #18.99)
Writing Home, Alan Bennett (Faber and Faber, #7.99)
MOVING, beautifully written, Theo Richmond's account of the life and death of
Konin, the small Polish town from which his Jewish ancestors came, puts the
Holocaust in its human context. We know how the Jews died, this shows the
centuries-old way of life the Nazis destroyed with them. Richmond's parents
emigrated to Britain before the First World War and he had never been to Konin
until he started searching for his roots. His discoveries in Konin, A Quest by
Theo Richmond bring home the full horror of the Nazis' crimes against humanity.
One of the most endearing collections of memoirs and assorted writings ever
made, Alan Bennett's Writing Home is sad, funny, outrageous, opinionated and
provocative. His memoir of the Lady in the Van, who camped in squalour in his
front garden for years, is masterly, but it is the diaries which delight most.
JOHN RYAN
Donkey's Years, Aidan Higgins (Secker &amp; Warburg, #14.99)
Byrne, Anthony Burgess (Hutchinson, #14.99)
The Collected Nature Stories, Henry Williamson (Little, Brown and Company,
#12.99)
AN autobiography, funny, sad and so brutally truthful that it reads like
fiction was a revelation; Donkey's Years by Aidan Higgins spares no one from
his eccentric family in the impoverished Big House as he grows up in Ireland
and beyond. From the days when families spent much time together, everyone will
recognise an oddball relative here.
A previously unpublished novel (his word) from the late Anthony Burgess turned
out to be a ribald tale in verse; Byrne, a down-at-heel poet, romances his
unholy and unorthodox way across the continents. Not for the politically
correct.
In large paperback format, The Collected Nature Stories of Henry Williamson
brings together evocative tales of wildlife from three earlier volumes written
just after the First World War when there were still some animals around.
Illustrated with the superb woodcuts of C.F Tunnicliffe from the first
editions, this delightful book is worth buying for these alone.
ANNE SIMPSON
Independence Day, Richard Ford (Harvill, 14.99)
Mr Ives' Christmas, Oscar Hijuelos (Bloomsbury, #15.99)
The Alienist, Caleb Carr (Warner Books, #7.99)
AT odds with all those who damn fathers as useless rogues, two powerful novels
from America remind us of life beyond man-hating agendas. Both Richard Ford's
Independence Day and Oscar Hijuelos' Mr Ives' Christmas transport us through
emotional frailties and confusions to arrive at a point of self-discovery which
is dazzling in its perception and hope. Ford's Frank Bascombe, a puzzled
divorcee with a light-fingered son, has the literary stature of Updike's
Rabbit, but warmed by punchy compassion and fast wit.
Hijuelos' Ives is riven by grief for a murdered son, but his embattled ascent
from melancholy realism to restored belief in humankind is a modern parable;
troubled, tender, angry, a marvellous affirmation of decency in the hades of
New York. Also Caleb Carr's stupendous thriller, The Alienist. Three great
story-tellers at the lyrical summit of imagination.
GRAEME WOOLASTON
The Ghost Road, Pat Barker (Viking, #15)
Not Drowning but Waving, Peter Adam (Andre Deutch, #20)
AT first Pat Barker's The Ghost Road seemed a disappointing conclusion to her
First World War trilogy, with an over-elaborate symbolism surrounding
psychiatrist William Rivers's earlier career as an anthropologist in Melanesia.
But then the book moves to the Front itself, and what had previously been
unconvincing came together as profoundly moving. An immensely deserving Booker
prizewinner. Barker's account of the psychological after-effects the war left
on individuals makes it easier to understand why at least one European country
collapsed into collective madness, and Peter Adam's autobiography Not Drowning
but Waving begins there, with his childhood as a Mischling, a half-Jew, in Nazi
Germany. His story then ranges over a vast sweep of European culture, following
his career as a BBC documentary producer, but always chronicling with almost
painful honesty the lifelong uncertainty about his own identity which sprang
from that childhood.
KENNETH WRIGHT
The Borough, Danny Cannon (Serpent's Tail, #8.99)
Lost In Music, Giles Smith (Picador, #12.99)
White Chappell Scarlet Tracings, #5.99; Radon Daughters, #5.99; Downriver,
#6.99; Iain Sinclair (all Vintage)
THE best Glasgow novel in years is Danny Cannon's The Borough, a haunting tale
of small, quiet lives in the streets and bars of Partick, free of condescension
and of pseudo-proletarian bluster. The closing leap into fantasy is audacious
and achingly moving.
Giles Smith's Lost In Music, confessional of a lifelong affair with pop as
consumer and performer (please welcome The Cleaners From Venus!), is funny and
wistful. If you ever played air guitar or measured out your life in album
sleeves, this is the story of your life.
Iain Sinclair's phantasmagorical London trilogy White Chappell Scarlet
Tracings, Radon Daughters, and Downriver, is a fearfully strange voyage through
underground folklore and urban decay that reads like a Hammer film scripted by
the Kray twins on drugs. If these books were people, they'd be in Broadmoor.
</TEXT>
