<TEXT>
Scotland has a creditable part in the movie pantheon. William Russell reports
on events planned for
the centenary
THE Flickers, the Movies, the Talkies, the Video! Scotland will celebrate the
centenary of the cinema next year with a series of splendid events - the
precise nature of which is not quite clear yet, because the Scotscreen 100
programme will not be officially launched until spring and most of the events
have still to be finalised. But, as they say in showbusiness, it is bound to be
all right on the night.
The English end of the festivities, Cinema 100, of which Scotscreen is an
adjunct, held its launch last month and announced one nationwide event. On the
great National One Pound day, Sunday, June 2, everyone can go to the pictures
for a pound a head. This has to be a bargain, although how good a bargain will
depend on what films the exhibitors are showing.
The London launch, chaired by Lord Attenborough, who presides over Cinema 100,
left the Scots organisers somewhat taken aback since, not only were they not
ready to do the same, they had not been warned what was coming in time to
cobble anything together.
The choice of 1996 for Britain's celluloid annus mirabilis - the rest of the
world celebrated the birth of the cinema this year, except for America which
did it two years ago - looks like rampant jingoism. There is no reason why
everyone could not have agreed on the same year, except amour propre - and a
desire not to let the French monoplise things.
Who actually invented moving pictures is open to dispute - the American Thomas
Edison, our own William Friese Green, not quite immortalised in a pretty
terrible British movie called The Magic Box; and one Max Skladanowsky can all
lay claim to have been the founding father - but the French, naturally, brook
no such nonsense. As far as they are concerned the answer is les freres Lumiere
who showed their films for the first time in the Salon Indien of the Grand Cafe
on the Boulevard des Capuchins in Paris on December 28, 1895.
As a result they have been celebrating like mad all year across the Channel, as
indeed have the BBC and many British newspapers. Somehow Cinema 100 failed to
get them to stay their hands. We picked 1996 because on March 7, 1896, films
were shown in Britain for the first time in the Alhambra, Leicester Square,
albeit films made by the Lumiere Brothers.
The first thrash organised by Cinema 100, the imaginatively titled Premiere of
the Century, will be held in London, naturally, and on March 7. It will, we are
assured, be attended by stars past and present, national and international -
and, of course, Lord Attenborough, the sine qua non of British cinema. A major
new film will be screened, although it is not yet decided what it will be, but
there are some British films in the offing which would be ideal. If it is an
American one then we know where we stand.
Whether there will be regional, provincial and Scottish versions of the
premire is yet to be decided, but the likelihood is that we, at least, will
wait for our own first screening dates and try to get something new and special
to show then.
As far as the celebrations here and south of the Border are concerned, one
cannot help feeling it is all a bit late in the day for so much to be still pie
in the sky. The main attractions which have been revealed do not, on the whole,
sad to say, actually thrill the blood. Cinema is nothing if it is not exciting,
innovative, controversial and entertaining, and the programme, while manifestly
worthy, is seldom any of those things individually or collectively.
First off the mark, however, with a really good idea is the Glasgow Film
Theatre. It is showing two silent films on December 28, Jean Vigo's portrait of
the high life on the Riviera, A Propos de Nice, and Rene Clair's comedy about a
mad inventor who attempts to place the French capital in a state of suspended
animation, Paris Qui Dort, to mark that first Lumiere Brothers performance.
It will be an occasion not to miss because the silent cinema, which has much to
offer, does not translate well to the television screen and opportunities to
see silents properly projected and with the right musical accompaniment, an
essential element for their enjoyment, are rare. The music will be provided by
Adrian Johnston, described by GFT as ``a one-man band,'' for which relief from
the ubiquitous Carl Davis we should all be grateful.
The two key Scottish dates are April 13 and May 26, when the films were first
shown in Edinburgh and Glasgow respectively. The Edinburgh screenings were held
in what is now the Festival Theatre, Nicholson Street - then the Empire Palace.
In Glasgow they were shown in The Skating Palace, Sauchiehall Street - now the
MGM multiplex. It was to become, over the years, the home of the Panorama,
Hengler's Circus, the Waldorf Dance Hall, the Regal Cinema and then the ABC
cinema.
One plan is that on April 13 every cinema in Scotland will show a film with a
Scottish connection, a worthy aim, except that the majority of feature films
about Scotland are probably best forgotten, the historical ones in particular
being mostly claptrap and good only for a laugh.
A Scottish Screen Festival, the first-ever devoted to Scottish film in
Scotland, run in conjunction with Bafta Scotland, is being held in the
MacRobert Arts Centre, Stirling, from April 18 to 21. Dame Diana Rigg is chair
of the committee organising the junket - just the job for a great Mother
Courage - which will end with what Linda Pearson of Bafta described as a
Scottish parliament. This gathering, it is hoped, will try to chart the way
ahead for film in Scotland.
The Edinburgh International Film Festival celebrates its 50th anniversary this
year and its programme will tie in with the centenary. The director, Mark
``gorgeous'' Cousins, as he is known in London film circles, is planning to run
a section called ``Films that Changed the World''. He also wants to transform
Edinburgh Castle green, making it into the Emerald City in Oz, to mark the
anniversary. Somehow one cannot see the city fathers falling for such an
innovative idea. For starters, it would kill the tartans at the tattoo! But
Mark is on the right track. A few more daft, amusing and provocative ideas like
that are needed.
Also in August, one of the blatant gaps in the film book market should be
filled when David Bruce's Scotland, The Movie Book is published by Polygon to
coincide with the Film Festival. In the form of a gazetteer, it will be a
personal view of the history of the first hundred years of cinema in Scotland.
There are also 31 Centenary Plaques being put up throughout Scotland, marking
places associated with great Scottish filmmakers, performers, exhibitors and
cinemas.
The stars, at least a couple of whom are still alive, include Donald Crisp
(Aberfeldy), Jack Buchanan and Deborah Kerr (Helensburgh), Sean Connery (The
Conference Centre, Edinburgh), Duncan Macrae (Maryhill) and Finlay Currie
(Inveraray). The institutions include the New Picture House, Campbeltown; the
Synod Hall, Edinburgh; the Glen Cinema, Paisley; and the Capitol Cinema,
Aberdeen.
The great Scottish film exhibitor families will be marked by plaques to George
Singleton and the Cosmo (GFT) and the Pooles of Synod Hall fame (Saltire Court,
Castle Terrace, Edinburgh). Among the directors, Alexander Mackendrick, will be
commemorated by one at Castlebay, Barra; Bill Douglas by one at Newcraighall,
and the filmmaker Norman McLaren by one at 21 Albert Place, Stirling, or
possibly the Glasgow School of Art.
A new tourist map showing where films made in Scotland were shot is planned in
conjunction with the Scottish Tourist Board. You can see where the Maggie
puffed, whisky was galore, Liam Neeson went skinny dipping in Rob Roy and
Margaret Leighton and David Niven went over the sea to Skye among other things.
Among other events:
n.Bafta is planning a series of master classes on film which will be held at
universities and other institutions of higher learning.
n.Scotland is to film Scotland. Scottish Television is asking people to send in
videos of their lives on centenary day, April 13, which will then be shown on
the telly.
n.In October, if the National Lottery money turns up in time, the cine-deprived
people of the Highlands will be provided with the UK's first Cinemobile which
will tour the region, bringing movies to the people.
n.There is to be a touring exhibition round the cinema foyers of Scotland which
will reflect the experiences of those who worked in cinemas from the pioneering
days up to the age of the multiplex.
n.The Scottish Film Archive is plundering its treasures and sending out a
series of films from the silent era showing events of the day which were filmed
by local cinema managers - who thought the video was something new? - which
will be shown round the commercial circuits.
The Flickers went down a bomb with Scots right from the start, and a
cinema-going tradition was established which has survived the onslaught of
television. Today Scotland is still the UK's major market for films outside
London. Going to the cinema proved more popular in Scotland than anywhere else
in Britain and by 1920 there were 557 cinemas showing films.
By 1930 Scotland had 634 cinemas, of which 127 were in Glasgow, 39 in
Edinburgh, 27 in Dundee and 15 in Aberdeen. They did not all flourish, however,
because competition was fierce and the coming of sound was to spell the end for
many of them. In Glasgow alone, in the immediate aftermath of its arrival, 15
cinemas closed, unable to afford the new equipment. Glasgow was the first place
to get the talkies when on January 7, 1929, The Singing Fool was presented at
the Coliseum in Eglinton Street.
By 1937, Glasgow had 98 cinemas with a seating capacity of 133,659, 12 theatres
and three music halls. So it continued, more or less, until the 1950s when the
arrival of television drastically reduced their number. Today Glasgow has 24
screens, although not in 24 individual cinemas, while Edinburgh has 29 screens,
and Scotland as a whole, at a rough count, has 152 screens in some 60 sites,
housed in the new custom-built multiplexes or old picture palaces which have
been subdivided.
The first film review appeared in 1907 in The Scotsman and people like me
started to earning a living. It has, some would say, been downhill ever since.
Scotland had some glorious picture palaces, of which Glasgow's Green's
Playhouse, with its legendary golden divans where many a romance bore fruit,
was probably the finest. But everyone brought up in the years when the cinema
was the principal source of entertainment has their favourite picture house.
Today's bright young cineastes who enthuse about old movies only know the half
of it. You have to have seen them where they were meant to be shown to fully
appreciate them. In the 1930s, Lanark, with a population of around 7000, had
three cinemas, which gives some indication of the thrall the medium held the
population in.
One, the Electric, was burnt down before I was of a cinema-going age in the
1940s, and was only remarkable for the fact that its ruins still stood and the
general belief that the fire had been an insurance job. The others were the Rio
in the Castlegate, the local fleapit, and the Regal at the top of the town,
which was posh and had a cafe attached. In those days the manager wore evening
dress at night and the usherettes, who showed you to your seat in the stalls or
the circle, wore smart claret-coloured uniforms, while similarly clad doormen
prowled the foyer keeping the queues in order.
Carluke had a splendid pile called The Windsor, owned by the family who owned
the Rio. It had a fantastic facade made of orange brick which looked like
something out of the Arabian Nights, or, to be more accurate, the Arabian
nightmare. The theme did not get beyond the foyer.
Some palaces are derelict, others have been cruelly subdivided into shoebox
auditoria, others replaced by supermarkets, filling stations and video stores.
Today's multiplexes have their good points, but they have no character, one is
the twin of the other.
What seems to be missing from the celebrations is a major exhibition devoted to
the glories of the picture palaces, to the costumes they wore and the dreams
they conjured up, and a really splendid party at which we could all dress up as
our favourite film fantasy - I'm going as Fred Astaire, while the office is
full of would-be Cruella de Villes and Big Men longing to put on a raincoat and
say Play it Again, Sam. So sit back, fasten your seatbelts and let's enjoy the
ride.
</TEXT>
