<TEXT>
Gary C Buchanan visits a romantic retreat in a silver sea
APPROACHED from the air, Mauritius, with its rings of reefs, lagoons and white
beaches looks extremely like an oyster. Actually it is much bigger than the
largest-known oyster, being around 38 miles long by 29 miles wide.
No traveller flying over this giant oyster can remain insensitive to the blue
and green summits of the mountains that rise from the emerald plains. Legend
has it that a colony of giants who inhabited the great crescent of Lemuria
were
roaming the Capricorn Sea in search of the land of Paradise. They found
Mauritius, a magnificent land freshly built from the depth of the sea by
Vulcan.
Today, as you are driven to your resort hotel from the modern airport, bearing
the impossible name of Sir Seewoosagur Ramgoolam, it becomes immediately
apparent that the island grows sugar cane as its main business in life -
tourism comes in third, after manufacturing clothes from imported textiles.
Every available square foot of land is planted with the profitable weed, and
the 10-foot-high canes are to be found on every flat inch of the island,
except
for your hotel, the larger roads and the airport runway.
The road journey seems long after the 11-hour flight (non-stop with Air
Mauritius, one-stop with British Airways) but it provides a good glimpse of
Mauritian life in microcosm. Most of the population seems to tend the sugar,
living in little villages strung along the roads. The roadways have no
pavements but they do have storm gutters at the sides, consequently the entire
population walks, chats, snoozes and generally spends its time in the middle
of
the road.
Other hazards are brakeless bicycles (which have no lights at night),
bullock-carts full of cut cane, also with no brakes, ``biketiques'' - complete
shops piled on to the back of Hondas which always include a two-foot wide
glass
case displaying their wares - and few road signs.
Another, more subtle hazard to driving is the sheer beauty of the Mauritian
mixed population. The sudden entry into the field of vision of a saffron sari,
a graceful swaying walk, a pair of eyes smiling out at the world from beneath
the balanced bucket, is enough to cause the unwary traveller to steer into the
village banyan tree.
As you progress along the network of undulating roads you start wondering
which
continent you have actually travelled to. Lurid Hindu temples covered in
writhing psychedelic deities rise out of the sugar cane, around the next
corner
there is quite likely to be squatting a dour Presbyterian church more suited
to the Outer Hebrides, while on the corner itself is a Roman Catholic shrine -
with a grimy plastic Madonna peering through the tangled vines. Just to add to
the confusion, English is the official language, but everyone speaks a French
patois - and pay in rupees.
There is a charming blend of five different ethnic groups and it is this
surprising cultural mix that saves Mauritius from being just another idyllic,
but insipid holiday playground.
The island was first explored by Portuguese sailors during a spell of good
weather in 1505, but they didn't know quite what to make of it so they sailed
away again. According to another legend - Mauritius is full of them - they had
mistaken basking dodos for swans and called the place Island of the Swan, but
Portuguese sailors could hardly have been that stupid, could they?
The next wave of visitors were the Dutch, who began a modest settlement in
1598. They went in for dodo-bashing in a big way with wooden sticks, to such
an
extent that by 1680 there were none left - anywhere in the world. By 1710 the
Dutch, having named the island after their Prince
Maurice, decided it was time to leave and enjoy their new acquisition instead
-
the Cape of Good Hope.
In 1715 the French arrived, drums beating and claiming the island as theirs,
renaming it Ile de France. With Gallic shrewdness they built their main
harbour
on the calm side of the island, and Port Louis (from a king of the same name)
became a very important port, particularly with pirates, smugglers and slaves.
Then in 1810 General Abercrombie invaded the island and claimed it for
Britain;
and British it remained until 1968, enjoying all the benefits of English
grammar, dressing for dinner and driving on the left hand side of the road. In
1968 Mauritius was granted independence. Today Mauritians prefer speaking
French to English, but they do still drive on the left - except round corners.
Strict planning controls introduced by the government ensure that Mauritian
hotels blend in with the local surroundings without so much as a penthouse
peeping above the canopy of the tallest palm. So after the colourful drive
from
the airport your hotel creeps up on you as it emerges from the undergrowth.
Andrew and Fergie chose to party in paradise before the parting of their ways
-
their choice was Le Touessrok. Designed by a Mauritian architect to look more
like a Mediterranean village than a hotel, this little gem now boasts a York
beach and a York suite - may the memory linger on.
Le Touessrok has 200 whitewashed rooms and suites, more reminiscent of Mykonos
than Mauritius. Many of the rooms with white shutters and thatched roofs open
on to shaded alleyways in the peaceful solitude of their own island, joined to
the main hotel by a southern seas' version of the Rialto Bridge.
A little further north, but still on the east coast, lies a legend in southern
hemisphere hospitality - Le Saint Geran Hotel, Golf Club and Casino. This
deluxe retreat follows the Mauritian formula of merging the interior and
exterior. The elegant white hall of impressive height is awash with fresh
flowers and bids an almost Moorish welcome to its much-vaunted clientele of
royalty, celebrities and football stars.
Set in 35 acres on a beach that appears to go on forever, La Pirogue
accommodates its guests in bougainvillea-clad thatched cottages, each
positioned to capture the glorious sunsets across the Indian Ocean.
Life at La Pirogue revolves around its beach that meanders into infinity
between the horizon and the mountain as well as the crystal clear waters, just
teeming with big game fish. Enthusiasts return year after year to this part of
the world where experts can guarantee some of the biggest catches.
Smoked marlin, the Mauritian answer to smoked salmon - and the infinite range
of seafood, including fresh water Camarons, not to mention Chinese, Indian and
Creole dishes as varied as the islands population, feature prominently on the
lavish buffets which accompany a performance of the Sega, the national dance
of
Mauritius. This throbbing rhythm of drums and voices tugs at your hips and
heels - evoking the pulsebeat of the island as no other can.
With a climate of wraparound sun, the occasional short sharp shower to bring
out the smell of frangipani and stephanotis, a diet of the freshest fruits and
salty seafood, not to mention the delicious local rum, Mauritius has all the
ingredients for serious lotus-eating. Little wonder that the island is
attracting the cupid market - couples are happily trading aisle for isle and
choosing the giant oyster in the Indian Ocean.
Mark Twain wrote: ``God made Mauritius first, and then he made Heaven.'' For
weddings or honeymoons, Mauritius is not just another insipid playground - it
is isolated splendour. This island, 1000 miles south of the Seychelles, is the
latest topic of conversation in the ``honeymoon to beat all honeymoons''
circuit.
But you don't need the excuse of marital bliss to visit this model for heaven.
Truly Mauritius is delicious - if only they would drop the dead dodo.
</TEXT>
