<HEADLINE>Dark magic sadly gone</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Frank McGroarty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra a century of cinema</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OF all the mediums, the cinema has an atmosphere that is totally unique. Since
the early days of the twentieth-century there was no bigger treat for a child
than a visit to the local ``flicks''.
Whether it be at the local flea pit, or the luxurious picture palaces, the
children from all walks of life would be greeted by the manager and his staff.
The moment the lights were dimmed a cheer would raise the roof because they
were about to be taken on a journey into a different world where the goodies
would always triumph over the baddies.
1934 saw a new landmark in Scottish cinema watching when the first Mickey Mouse
Club, a Saturday show specially designed for children, opened at the New Tivoli
in Edinburgh. It did not take long for the other cinema chains throughout the
country to realise the potential of the idea and start up their own clubs or
run their own special matinee programmes.
The menu would consist of the usual mix of cartoons for starters. There would
also be comedies from favourites like Laurel and Hardy or the Three Stooges.
The main course would usually be a Western. Stars like Hopalong Cassidy and Roy
Rogers were just two of the cowboy matinee idols.
The biggest cheer would be when the bad guy got his just deserts or when the
seventh cavalry arrived at the very last minute to save the day. If however the
hero was in any danger, a common occurrence would be - horror of horrors! - the
projector breaking down. The eventual cheer signalled that it had been fixed
and the hero lived to fight another day.
Apart from the main feature, there were competitions. Popular examples were the
talent shows where the winner was decided on the strength of the crowd's
applause. These contests not only heightened the involvement of the audience,
it also gave the projectionist ample time to load the next film.
The final course would usually consist of a serial where the audience was left
on tenterhooks, having to come back the next week to see if the hero escaped in
one piece.
Two men who are well acquainted on the subject are filmmaker/historian Ian
Rintoul from Edinburgh and his colleague, Jack Pottage. Both promote the golden
age of the cinema in the shape of film shows and talks at venues around the
country. Ian also stages exhibitions on the subject of the cinema.
``Going to the cinema was such a special event for the children,'' he said. ``
You have to remember that in those early days there was no television and very
few children had a radio,'' added Pottage.
The cinema clubs, decline started during the 1960s because of competition from
television and a bigger demand for full-length feature films. A lot of the
smaller cinemas closed as a result. ``They did have morning matinees for the
kids in the big cinema chains like the ABC minors. Unlike the other children's
shows they had a set programme that travelled the circuit, whereas the small
individual cinema could not afford a different programme every week.''
A child's quest for action and adventure has been just as great since those
early days when pioneers like J J Bennell first launched his B B (Bright &amp;
Beautiful) Pictures. Today it is down to filmmakers such as Steven Spielberg
and George Lucas, whose blockbuster trilogies, such as the Star Wars and
Indiana Jones films have helped to lure children back to the cinema.
If only they could couple that special dark magic these films created alongside
the unique atmosphere and format the cinema clubs had to offer. Children would
encounter an experience that was so special, the memory would stay with them
for the rest of their lives.
Frank McGroarty laments the loss of   Saturday morning
children's clubs
</TEXT>
