<HEADLINE>Space station parking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Donnelly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARKING in space is no easy matter, as the recent rendezvous of the space
shuttle with the Russian MIR station showed, but a team of Glasgow specialists
led by aerospace expert Dr Colin MacInnes are putting their brains to the
problem to help prevent mid-orbit shunts.
Space enthusiasts held their collective breath as the shuttle carried out the
tricky manoeuvre to dock safely with the large platform without breaking
anything.
As the shuttle approached MIR it had to follow a carefully planned path to
avoid damaging the station's solar panels or impacting on the station's docking
port at too high a speed. The catch as catch can manoeuvres are planned well
before launch and have to be implemented to a strict timetable once in orbit.
These problems, however will be even greater when the huge International Space
Station Alpha begins construction in 1997. Then American, Russian and
eventually European spacecraft will have to intercept the station and lock on
to Alpha's many docking ports and berthing points.
To overcome these difficulties the European Space Technology and Research
Centre, part of the European Space Agency, has funded a two-and-a-half-year
study at Glasgow University's Department of Aerospace Engineering to develop a
new automatic rendezvous and docking system.
The European Automated Transfer Vehicle (ATV), which will transfer supplies to
space stations, will be able to use the new system to approach and dock largely
unaided. In addition, it will be a relatively easy matter to change the ATV
flight plan once in orbit.
The new system being developed uses a ``potential field method'' where
obstructions, such as the station's solar panels provide a virtual force,
pushing the ATV away. The ``virtual forces'' only exist in the flight computer,
but have proven to be a simple and extremely effective way of controlling
rendezvous and docking manoeuvres.
Joe Donnelly looks to the race to dominate the skies
</TEXT>
