<HEADLINE>Wounds remain for female carers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE stress of caring for chronically ill relatives could be a health hazard. A
new study of women carers is showing that psychological stress can slow the
healing of wounds by as much as nine days.
The findings could be important in improving the recovery of patients following
surgery and lessening the chances of developing some post-surgical infections.
The research team led by Janice Kiecolt-Glaser, professor of psychiatry and
psychology in Ohio State University, compared how well skin wounds healed in a
group of more than two dozen older women. Half of the women were the principal
carers for relatives suffering dementia. The remaining women served as a
control group for the study.
All of the women were asked to complete a questionnaire which rated how
stressed they considered their daily lives. A sample of blood was also taken
from each woman at the beginning of the study and analysed to determine the
levels of Interleukin-1, an important blood factor involved in immunity.
A biopsy of a small piece of skin was also taken. The wound was then cleaned
and re-bandaged every day for the first week. After that, the women returned
every few days so that their wounds could be cleaned and photographed to
provide a record of healing.
At the end of the study, the carers' wounds took an average of nine days longer
to heal than did those of the women in the control group. The blood analysis
also showed that they also produced less Interleukin-1. The study also showed
that the changes in the rate of wound healing among the stressed women were
most apparent in the first two weeks after injury.
``That's very important,'' says Kiecolt-Glaser. ``If a patient is going to get
infections or other problems following surgery, that two-week period is when
you'd expect the worst to occur.''
</TEXT>
