<HEADLINE>Hold on, here's the future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra a century of cinema</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE Omar Sharif's entrance in Lawrence of Arabia, the future of cinema is now
shimmering upon the horizon. But desert landscapes have been replaced by
sprawling screens the size of tower blocks, seats which rock'n'roll, deafening
sound, and a picture quality to rival reality. It is the final form of the
future that now remains a blur. Sharif's Ali may have been a dot of sand and
dust, yet in tomorrow's world what is certain is that the pixels in each
picture will be polished to perfection.
If only the performances could be so digitally enhanced. We've already had
Humphrey Bogart advertise a soft drink he wouldn't have wasted on his whisky 30
years after it killed him. Why not resurrect a golden age of movie stars who'll
show them how it's done? Or are they already doing that with Clint Eastwood? In
the future - 10, 20, 100 years along the spool - will a bit-part actor off a TV
show become a legend?
In fact next year a digital double of Denzel Washington will perform all of the
most dangerous stunts in a film called Virtuosity. His images were scanned and
then manipulated to perform the more outrageous stunts - which a $7m star would
balk at.
And so to Britain where talents such as Alan Parker, Daniel Day Lewis, and John
Boorman burn brightly then are quickly shipped off in crates to stoke the big
pot-boilers in Hollywood. Could we see a day when Colin Welland's comments that
``The British are coming!'' upon collecting an Oscar for Chariots Of Fire could
be seen as a promise rather than a punchline?
If the Brothers Scott have anything to do with it, a fierce British film
industry will be reborn. Tony Scott, director of Crimson Tide, and brother
Ridley, director of Thelma and Louise, bought Shepperton Studios for just such
a purpose. And when will we establish a Scottish film school to nurture talents
who'll produce a churchyard of Shallow Graves?
Just who will these talents be? Flicking through the television channels are a
million actors who just might make it, thousands of writers and megaphones-ful
of directors. But to predict the future you can onlypeer into the past and then
work forward.
If Quentin Tarantino worked in a video shop and achieved Oscar-winning success
with Pulp Fiction, will the bubbly girl at the Azad store on Great Western Road
now win one for a remake of One Flew Over The Cuckoo's Nest?
A more reliable form of shaping the future is for executive number crunchers to
peer into the swirl of old cinema ticket stubs. In America, where the
entertainment industry is the second biggest export, ticket sales are dropping.
Figures released by the National Association of Theatre Owners illustrated that
in 1991 and 1992 sales dropped below 1000 million for the first time since
1977.
The blame is stapled to the success of home entertainment systems; video,
CD-Roms, and laser discs which offer superb pictures and sound quality. The
release of Jurassic Park in 1993 forced ticket sales back up and executives to
realise that special-effect blockbusters will make people leave home.
And ever since Cinemascope was invented to beat off the fifties threat of
television, the cinema has been about the big-screen experience. So screens are
going to get bigger, much bigger. At the moment three companies are engaged in
a Godzilla battle over giant movie screens. Digital technology has revived the
spirits of Samuel Goldwyn and Louis B Mayer as movie moguls come out fighting.
In the right corner is the Imax Corporation - this Toronto-based company are
investing in giant-screen theatres such as the 650-seat theatre being built in
New York which will use a state-of-the-art 3D film process.
Viewers will strap on a lightweight headset with electronic glasses and tiny
speakers. The films shown on the giant multi-storey screens will be specially
shot but it is expected that in the future special prints of blockbuster movies
will be made available in such a format.
In partnership with Imax is special effects wizard Douglas Turnball who was the
designer and director of Universal Studios' Back To The Future ride and also
the mind behind the 2001: A Space Odyssey effects. Talking about the new style
of cinema images available with Imax he says: ``Imax is almost the real thing.
I was at a private screening for Destiny In Space where I spoke with some
astronauts who were on the Nasa mission which serviced the Hubble Telescope.
``They said that the Imax experience was so close to reality. In some respects
it was better because there weren't any restrictions such as helmets which
impair vision. They said the Imax film was replacing their visual memories of
what they saw in space. That's a pretty profound statement.''
And in the left corner limbering up is Iwerks Entertainment. The firm launched
by two former executives at Disney - Stanley B Kinsey and Donald W Iwerks - has
a slightly different market strategy. ``If you can excite them with rides and
special effects, they'll still come out,'' says Kinsey. In January 1994 they
launched the Cinetropolis complex at Foxwoods Resort Casino in Connecticut.
The idea is a series of small cinemas with 48-motion-base seats which move and
tilt to films like Supersonic Flight through a breakneck ride with Robocop and
an underwater adventure called SOS. Also in place is the Iwerks Fox Theatre
which has 60ft high images perfectly projected and a Cinedrome 360, a disco
with a video ``wallpaper''.
In The Loch Ness Experience, as the paying public explore the depths of the
Scottish waters from the comfort of Connecticut, Iwerks are attempting to
remove the word ``virtual'' from the development of ``virtual reality''. They
have teamed up with Ivan Sutherland, the father of VR, to develop a sensory
experience akin to the movie Lawnmower Man - except that no-one goes mad and
murders.
While both Iwerk and Imax battle for supremacy, tucked in another corner is
Showscam. For this firm the image is all. The Showscam film process creates an
astonishing level of quality which, as yet, nothing else has matched. Sharpness
is created by matching the speed of the film frame to the human eye. It is said
that the human eye perceives the world as if it were running at a film speed of
approximately 60 frames per second.
Conventional motion pictures operate at 24 frames per second while special
formats rise to 30 frames. Showscam projects 70mm film at an accelerated rate
of 60 frames per second which adds depth, clarity, and realism to the image.
The catchphrase is ``Don't Just Watch Movies - Experience Them''.
Pacific Bell has already invested millions in digitised movies. The company
hopes to beam digital flicks by fibre-optic lines to between 2000 and 3000
theatres, juggling eight trillion bits of data which are then reassembled and
projected by a high-definition ``film'' projector. This could eventually cut
$300m from distribution costs.
But what of the software which tomorrow's hardware will project or beam? A
generation of filmmakers on the fringes of the future now exist. Included are
Steven Spielberg, James Cameron, and George Lucas.  All three have now broken
away from the studio system to form their own companies. Cameron pioneered the
system of computer morphing, first in The Abyss then later in Terminator 2. It
was, however, pushed even further by Spielberg's Jurassic Park.
George Lucas is also at the vanguard, ironic for a man who has not directed a
movie in the 20 years since Star Wars. Production of Star Wars IV is expected
to begin in 1997. The reason for the delay was his decision to wait until the
computer effects could conceive his extraordinary vision. Such a time now sits
on a keyboard at his fingertips.
The new generation of action movies are set to achieve the effects of Jaws. In
1977, Steven Spielberg showed us what we had never seen before - the terror
caused by a giant shark. Sure, today it looks clockwork, but racing across the
expanse of the cinema screen it appeared lethal. In 1993 Spielberg showed us
dinosaurs as man had never seen them. More is set to come.
A slate of big-budget action movies based on the exploits of America's
biggest-selling comic characters are planned. James Cameron and his company
Digital Domain are working towards bringing Spiderman to the screen.
The very nature of the new computer effects is suitable for bringing comic
books to life. Richard Donner, director of Lethal Weapon, has plans to make a
movie based on The X-Men.
But while blockbuster movies will be adapted in the future to fit in with
movable seats, the majority of people will still prefer to sit in silence with
their eyes superglued to the big(ger) screen. But then, whose eyes will they
stare into?
Alicia Silverstone, the star of Clueless, has been granted a multi-picture deal
and a $10m pay packet which indicates Hollywood has faith in its dithery young
star.
It remains to be seen if she will go the way of Molly ``who the hell is she?''
Ringwald who graced the cover of Time magazine before diving into the fog of TV
movies. Leonardo Di Caprio has already demonstrated his acting credentials and
will win Oscar after Oscar, after Oscar - unless he does a River Phoenix.
In Britain the brightest young lights include Scots actor Robert Carlyle who
continues to illuminate everything he does. The release next year of
Trainspotting can only push him, and those behind the scenes, further. It would
be fantastic if writer John Hodge, producer Andrew McDonald, and director Danny
Boyle could add Oscars to a mantlepiece weighted with Baftas.
The shortest movie genre in history may well be the techno-thriller such as The
Net as more people transfer over to more sophisticated machinery. An evening at
the movies watching somebody struggle through the same process is like night
school.
Yet the movie genre which will ride ever onwards towards the sunset will be the
Western. Though critics have been ringing its death-knell since Clint Eastwood
first forgot his character's name, quality movies continue to mosey into town.
And it's because men still run Hollywood and men love Westerns. But the women
are working their way up too.
Alicia Silverstone this year joined Demi Moore, Jodie Foster, and Sharon Stone
at the Power Shower. Hollywood's female elite have recently begun using baby
and bridal showers to network. This year the number of female-driven dramas
increased. The number of female directors, executives, and writers in Hollywood
may still be negligible but it is now on the rise.
So, change hangs in the air like the dust clouds stirred up by Omar Sharif's
Ali more than 30 years ago. Change is said to be the only constant. But there
is another where the cinema is concerned. Regardless of new technological
experiences, dynamic new film stock, rising young stars, and fast-paced movies,
people will still remain in the dark.
The cinema is a communal experience - but with some chomping audiences you
might wish they were gagged - and that will never change. Regardless of
innovations to tempt cinemagoers to stay home alone with only cable, satellite,
and sound-systems for company, the big screen lure will win out.
As Douglas Turnball says: ``The traditional film theatre is an important social
phenomenon. I don't expect it to go away. It's an important component of our
culture. I expect it to be augmented by alternative forms of entertainment.''
Yes, but will any of them be as good as a bright screen light in the dark?
Stephen McGinty slips on his 3-D glasses to take
a look at developments in entertainments as movie
executives vie to build ever bigger thrills
</TEXT>
</DOC>
