<HEADLINE>The gang's still all here</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rainy camping trips and working for the strangest badges imaginable are a thing
of the past. The approach of the Scouts and Guides has changed, discovers Ann
Donald, even if the principles behind the movements have stayed the same
THE Scout master was well prepared to answer any criticism of his organisation.
``People are still under the misconception that we wear funny hats, long khaki
shorts and march up and down in draughty church halls reciting `dib dib dob
dob'.''
Mike Walker is Convener and Assistant Area Commissioner for The Gang Show. For
those who seek to criticise what is, outside religious organisations, the
world's largest organisation - a new member joins every five seconds - The Gang
Show, like other aspects of this near century-old movement, is an easy target.
Certainly in recent months there has been no shortage of anti-Brown Owl or
Bob-a-Job jibes.
Back in July there were murmurings that Scouts may cease swearing allegiance to
the Crown. A few months later the unwelcome glare of publicity honed in on
Scout leader Peter Atkins who was convicted of molesting teenage boys on camp.
And only last week a Channel Four documentary alleged that founder Baden-Powell
was a sadist, repressed homosexual and fascist sympathiser. Is it any surprise
then that numbers, currently at 650,000 and 750,000 for Scouts and Guides
respectively, have been falling off since the late 80s and both associations
are struggling to recruit volunteers?
Look no further than these negative facts and figures and of course it's easy
to understand the premature media-led demise of a movement that is seen to
personify the anachronistic elements of God, duty to one's country, discipline,
order and all the old-fashioned fun of a sausage sizzle. Why on earth would the
Nintendo  generation want to align themselves with these old duffers straight
out of a golly gosh Enid Blyton book?
Well maybe it's time to wake up and smell the campfire coffee because all these
years we've been sniggering at the woggles, knots and ging-gang-goolies, the
Guiding and Scouting movements have been quietly evolving and trying to adapt
to the needs of the Nintendo generation.
Certainly if the fresh-faced troop of Guides and Scouts I encountered at the
Edinburgh Gang Show are to be believed, then the movement has made a serious
dent in the stuffy middle-class image of previous decades.
Backstage at The King's Theatre, among the clutter of the orchestra's changing
room and in between the bursts of show songs and excited screams and yelps
emanating from the make-up room, a steady stream of teenagers confound my
cynical preconceptions regarding the relevancy of such uniformed youth
movements.
``If someone called the Guides naff I'd say you don't know what you're talking
about,'' says Laura from the 191st Corstorphine. Her friend Christine, fresh
from the world jamboree in Holland, joins in. ``It really is what you make of
it,'' she says. ``Now we sit down with our leader every month and tell her what
we'd like to do to get more out of it.'' And she proceeds to rattle off an
impressive A to Z of decidedly un-naff sports, outdoor activities,
international trips, community projects and badges relevant to computing,
conservation and the community.
``I used to get hassle and get called a `saddo','' confesses one lad before
adding triumphantly, ``then I told them all the things we do and they wanted to
join up too!'' Another Guide chips in enthusiastically about the difference the
1991 Jeff Banks-designed uniform has made. ``You're not embarrassed to wear it
now,'' she says. ``Because you can choose from a denim shirt, trackie bottoms,
or blue culottes, a sweatshirt and a sash to sew your badges on.''
For Gang Show co-ordinator Mike Walker it's a case of facing up to reality.
``The movements have to adapt to the times because if we don't give the kids
what they want then they'll walk away,'' he notes matter-of-factly.
This is confirmed by Elma Tait, County Commissioner for Edinburgh who has been
involved with the movement since joining the Brownies almost 40 years ago. Like
the majority of female leaders I observed in the Gang Show audience, she
appears to have less in common with the bygone breed of buxom, hale and hearty
Brown Owls and more in common with groovy youth club leader.
Listing the pivotal changes over the last decade she says: ``The new uniform
helped and there are far more outdoor activities now. The girls have more input
in the programme and there's more opportunity for international travel. We
really are trying very hard to get this image over to the general public,'' she
stresses.
``They still harbour an image of us circa 1966. Many people don't know that
since 1991 girls could join the Scouts and that the Beavers and Rainbows were
set up for the five-year-olds almost 10 years ago.'' Mention the topic of class
and Tait sighs. ``It's a very unfortunate misconception. You name any area in
Edinburgh and I'll show you guiding going on. We don't have class structure and
that's why we have the same uniform. There are no designer labels.'' Echoing a
fundamental BP belief she adds: ``We're all equal here.''
However much the movements doth protest their evolution and nineties image
change, there is no denying the fact that membership is falling steadily with
the majority dropping out post Brownies and Cubs age group. Out at the Scouts
Scottish HQ at Fordell Firs near Dunfermline, chief executive David Shelmerdine
attributes this bleed to the dropping birth rate and the fact that an
increasing number of recreational youth groups are having to share the same
children. He also cites the role of the parent.
``You have to understand who decides you become a member. For the under-10s
it's usually the parent, over that age and it's the child who decides what they
do with their spare time. It's true of all youth organisations,'' he reasons.
``Once they become independent they go off and do their own thing.''
Another problem the associations face is the public perception of a movement
geared to producing thousands of good little Christians. Not so, says
Shelmerdine, before going on to espouse a philosophy that sounds as if it's
been lifted straight from a new age bible.
``We are and always have been a multi-faith movement. We don't have a strong
religious but rather a spiritual dimension to our work which is summed up by
the acronym SONG. S is for Self relationship. Do I feel good about the way I
live my life? O equals Others. How do I develop my relationship with others; my
peers, community and those less fortunate than myself. N is for Nature. How I
live and my relationship with the world around me. And G is God in terms of
searching for a relationship with a higher being. We never say that to be a
Scout you have to be a true believer. When you make that promise `to do my duty
to God' it means you are promising to explore that relationship with a higher
being. It's all part of your own development.''
It is this framework and value system that differentiates Scouting and Guiding
from all other youth movements, with a continually reassessed programme that
cherishes the somewhat grandiose aim of ``promoting the development of young
people in achieving their full physical and spiritual potential as individuals,
as responsible citizens, and as members of their local, national and
international communities.''
For some this aim is to be commended as the panacea for a secular society's
ills, for others it is an impossible task in an era defined by video games,
child abuse, Lottery greed, street fashion, and every other facet of modern
living. For those involved with the movement though there is no doubt about the
enduring relevancy of this aim and indeed the movements themselves. ``We've
been around for nearly a century now,'' notes Elma Tait. ``And I'm sure we'll
still be here in another hundred years. You can't get rid of us that easily,''
she adds with a defiant smile.
</TEXT>
