<HEADLINE>A leap for mankind</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE SANDISON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUR boy done good this year. Jonathan Edwards, Britain's world-beating, triple
jump champion, with a leap of historic proportions, went straight into the
record books. And he wasn't being chased either, I thought, as I looked at
``Randolph Leap'' near Relugas on the river Findhorn.
Randolph, it is alleged, was fleeing from a posse of his peers who were intent
upon his murder, which added greatly to the spring in his step.
It is remarkable what the prospect of an imminent interview with St Peter can
do for a man's confidence. We find within ourselves previously unknown reserves
of strength. As happened to the government soldier fleeing after a debacle of
the Battle of Killiecrankie, hurling himself over the river Garry; and
Macgregor, leaping to safety across the river Lyon in Perthshire.
The river Findhorn in Morayshire is one of Scotland's most dramatic and
attractive streams, from its source in the grey Monadhliath mountains, to the
cold waters of the Moray Firth by Culbin Forest near Kinloss. The most
spectacular aspect of the river is a 20-mile long, deep gorge, which begins at
Dulsie Bridge, on the line of the old military road between Lochindorb and
Cawdor, and then continues downstream to the famous Sluie salmon pool, east of
the town of Forres.
The lower levels are known as the ``Meads of St John'', after the Victorian
writer and naturalist, Charles St John. St John, who was born in 1809 at
Chailey, Sussex, lived most of his short life in Moray. In 1834, whilst
visiting Rosehall in Easter Ross, St John met and married Miss Ann Gibson, the
daughter of a rich Newcastle banker.
St John's most famous book, Wild Sports of the Highlands, is often referred to
as 101 Ways to Shoot an Osprey. Nothing furred, finned or feathered which ever
flew, swam or stalked the moors and rivers of Moravia, were safe from his
administrations. St John's stories first appeared in the Edinburgh Quarterly
Review, edited by John Lochart, the son-in-law of Sir Walter Scott, who was
himself a keen sportsman.
There is a variety of pleasant, undemanding, walks along the banks of the
Findhorn Gorge, the sides of which are 200ft high in places. The scenery is
spectacular: woodlands of larch, pine, birch, oak and beech; heather tussocks,
juniper, forget-me-not, primrose, wood sorrel, wood vetch and violet; wren,
thrush, blackbird, blue tit, great tit, tree creeper, chaffinch, and
best-bib-and-tuckered dipper.
n One of the most easily accessible Findhorn walks starts at Sluie (OS Map 27,
Nairn, Gd Ref 27/013524), four miles south of Forres along the A940 Grantown to
Forres road. A roadside sign, on the left, is marked ``Sluie Walk.'' Turn right
here, and drive past Sluie Lodge to reach a car park and picnic area. Walk back
to the lodge and follow the track downhill. Take the right-hand fork at the
first junction.
Within a few minutes, at the Mains of Sluie, you reach a long row of five
deserted cottages. The path along the edge of the gorge gives magnificent views
of the rushing river below. The track is well-marked but great care is required
on this section. After a mile there is a notice warning you to go no further.
Follow the track left, back through the wood to the car park.
``Randolph's Leap'' is three miles south from Sluie. Turn right at Logie
(27/010504) and park on the B9007 at Gd Ref 27/001497.
</TEXT>
