<HEADLINE>Definitely a dead parrot fish</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Adrian Robertson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS my first encounter with a parrotfish. Aptly named, they are, with their
iridescent blue mouths and ridge of mini teeth, razor sharp for nibbling at the
coral reef. It was dead. Definitely an ex-parrotfish.
Craig, our guide from the Biological Station in Bermuda, hauled it from the
water's edge and radioed for help. It was not an urgent ``bring your
resuscitation gear'' demand. Merely a request to bring a bodybag (fish
wrapper?), perform an autopsy, and find out why it died.
The parrotfish is one of the protected species which lives on the reef, and if
anything is damaging the ecosystem then the Biological Station staff want to
know about it. In these Greenpeace times many independent organisations monitor
the health of the planet. Bermuda's official Biological Station is one of only
two such government-funded establishments in the world, the other being in
Hawaii monitoring the Pacific.
Bermuda. Laid back. No, relaxed would be a better description. A mixture of
sunshine-induced lethargy and colonial correctness. Heady stuff, as heady as
the rum-based ``dark and stormy'' cocktails designed for the unwary tourist. A
genuine tourist trap, so to speak, but not altogether an unpleasant experience.
The colonial presence is still strong, despite the fact that the Royal Navy
officially left its magnificent dockyard almost 50 years ago. Premier John Swan
made independence a referendum issue last summer, but got a resounding ``No''
for his troubles. The tax haven status of Bermuda had more to do with the
result, I suspect, than the Bermudians would care to admit.
They pay no income tax. Local services are financed to a great extent by
tourism (tourist tax, airport tax, hotel tax). The British Treasury looks after
major expenditure, but independence would cut the apron strings.
The locals would then have to pay to support embassies and consulates around
the world, pay to establish their UN voice if desired, pay to promote their
Olympic ambitions, even. The thought of all this taxation must have frightened
off a lot of people who are doing very nicely, thank you, the way things are.
Money makes the world go round.
Some others bore a grudge against Swan. He enlisted the help of Scotland Yard,
in the form of a couple of boys from the Met, to take over the running of the
colony's police force when they were faced with a particularly difficult murder
a few years back. They stepped in over well-respected ``15-year'' men, so the
story goes. In a small community that doesn't go down too well. Neither does a
referendum that wasn't in the manifesto.
Not quite British.
The dress code is British, however, with a naval-colonial input. Cut-off suits
(shorts to you) are a common sight in town. A bit odd at first, when you see
some upright-looking chap emerging from a bank clutching a briefcase but minus
his trousers.
On the double-take you realise that he's wearing a short-trousered pinstripe
suit. When you see similar grown-ups-in-shorts in the discos, you realise that
this is like nowhere else on the planet.
On arrival, visitors must show their return ticket and their hotel booking or
they don't get through immigration. Simple as that. No open-ended holidays, no
beach bums. You could, though, come for a fortnight, fall in love with the
place, and buy a house. The only problem is that it'll set you back at least
#1m.
The island government has a simple policy on house purchase. It may be a tax
haven, but no incomer is allowed to buy a property under a certain value. This
protects the housing stock at the lower end of the market, and ensures that the
Bermudians themselves always have affordable housing.
The gap between what Bermudians pay for a humble dwelling and what the incomers
fork out is considerable. One entertainer's hideaway was for sale when I was
there in early summer. Do you have a spare #12m?
But back to the ex-parrotfish, or rather, the reef. Bermuda is a collection of
islands sitting on a volcanic plateau which is in many places just 25-30 feet
below the surface of the Atlantic. The outer limit of the plateau forms a
treacherous reef on which countless ships have perished. Beyond it is the full
depth of the Atlantic, but within is a haven from the worst excesses of its
storms. Early sailors risked everything, on their journey from the old world in
search of the new, for a safe anchorage. The reef itself is one of the islands'
main attractions. Glass-bottomed boats let you view the magnificent corals and
exotic marine life. A two-hour trip from Hamilton, the capital, to the wreck of
HMS Vixen will set you back about #20 or #30. It was scuttled 99 years ago to
block a channel during troubled colonial times, and the turquoise waters have
long since claimed it and covered it in coral.
Fishing near the wreck is strictly prohibited. The fish are so used to the
tourist boats that the water positively boils when food scraps are thrown
overboard. The nearest thing to tame fish I've seen, outside of a fish supper.
Some of the boats will take you seven miles to the outer reef, a day trip where
you can scuba dive. It costs about $85 for a four-hour lesson over a shallow
wreck, but experienced divers can save considerably on that. Snorkelling is
very much cheaper.
There's also a 48-seat submarine, the Enterprise, which dives 60ft down the
reef, the ultimate experience if you want to see fish and stay dry. You reach
the submarine via a tender from the Royal Naval Dockyard. It may be called the
Enterprise, but the real Captain Kirk runs a rival operation.
The dockyard itself should be at the top of any visitor's agenda. The sprawling
site has been turned into an attraction in the true meaning of the word.
It charts the ascent of western man, from the discovery of the New World,
through the ensuing colonial struggles and the strategic importance of a
western Atlantic base in the Second World War, to its use as a tracking station
down range of the Cape Canaveral Nasa launch site.
It also, by default, charts the decline of the British Empire. This was, after
all, of major strategic importance to what was once the world's greatest naval
power. Viewed from the stern of the ferry as we departed, it was quite majestic
in its redundancy.
The magnificent buildings, apart from the museum, house a cool shopping mall
(coolness being a welcome respite from the summer sun's scorching heat)
complete with bars, restaurants and discos.
The best beaches are along the south coast, some merely rocky coves, others
long and curving and palm fringed. My hotel was on the other side of the
island, but since it is only about 1!s miles at its widest point, that wasn't
too much hassle. In fact it prompted me into trying out one of the best way of
seeing Bermuda.
I hired a motorbike. More of a moped without the pedals, actually. To be
recommended, but remember to wear your helmet. The police are pretty slick at
the on-the-spot fine routine.
There are also deep-sea fishing trips. This politically correct paradise has
taken steps to maintain its placing on the conservationist's list of desirable
holiday resorts.
Ernest Hemingway could never have had it so good. Go deep-sea rod fishing,
catch a marlin, have it weighed, and go home with the aching muscles - but with
the satisfaction that your worthy opponent will live to fight another day.
Returning the catch is the name of the game, but that policy didn't quite
square with the dolphin on the menu in a couple of the restaurants I visited. A
bit of double checking confirmed it was dolphinfish. No need for Greenpeace to
worry. The food is good, especially if you like fish. The fish chowder, a very
thick and spicy broth, is positively addictive. Ever tried a fish steak
sandwich? A wahoo steak washed down with a glass of the local beer or even a
dark and stormy, makes a very satisfying lunch.
One of the best ways to appreciate the island's beauty is to take a stroll
along part of the old Bermuda railway. Like many sections of post-Beeching
track in Britain, the rails have long gone and all that remains is a very
easily negotiated footpath (motor-bikes prohibited).
The railway was built between 1922 and 1931. The entire route covered a mere 21
miles and being Bermuda required 33 bridges, 16 of them over water. The rate of
construction, at 2!s miles per year, made it the slowest on record and the most
costly. It operated for only 17 years before being sold in its entirety to the
then British Guyana.
Its legacy is the the most breathtaking of holiday walking routes.
I covered a several short sections (no more than a couple of miles at a time)
and found that the east end section the most spectacular in a wild and rugged
sort of way.
Craig, our guide, led our small group along with a lively commentary. We left
the Biological Station, itself worth a visit, and walked along the road a few
hundred yards to the start of the path.
The railway path passes one of the old cedar forests, reduced by disease many
years ago to a collection of withered stumps (one of the reasons why Bermuda
cedar souvenirs are so expensive). The calabash tree has replaced it to a great
extent, its gourds making ideal nests for the bluebirds.
Further along you pass an old cemetery where lie some 100 or so victims of the
yellow fever epidemic that ravaged this paradise 150 years ago. The view along
the coastline is spectacular in a rugged sort of way, and as you rest for a few
minutes you can watch the longtails swoop low over the ocean in search of a
morsel. Whalebone Bay, where we found the parrotfish, is the ideal spot for
some snorkelling. A couple of yachts bobbing at anchor complete the tranquil
scene.
Apart from water sports, Bermuda's other major sporting attraction is golf.
Bermuda must boast the world's most spectacular course where you can tee off
towards a pin on the other side of the Atlantic. OK, it's only an inlet but
it's still the Atlantic.
And rugby. There's the annual classic which attracts the most famous names in
the game. Old sportsmen never die. They sip rum cocktails in Bermuda.
If you're not feeling up to a round of golf, a trip to St George is worth the
effort. Take a bus, even. They run every 15 minutes; the drivers could give
some of ours a lesson in manners. St George is exceptionally pretty, with its
marina and replica of the Deliverance, the ship that was built by survivors of
the shipwrecked company of the Sea Venture in 1609 to carry them on to
Virginia. Many ships were lost on the reefs in those days, none more famous
than the Sea Venture.
The replica, plus a ducking stool, stocks, and whipping post for snap-happy
visitors to pose at, make St George a bit of a tourist trap. Enjoyable,
nevertheless, if you take the time to stroll along the side streets.
The capital, Hamilton, has an impressive frontage. It's called Front Street and
is on the waterfront. The cruise ships tie up here, at the pavement's edge
almost, right across the road from the gaily painted shops and restaurants with
their high balconies. The bigger ships, like the QE2, anchor in the Great Sound.
Bermuda has the usual mix of hotels, half a dozen or so five-star international
types and many smaller ones. Officially, nothing should be built higher than
the cathedral in Hamilton, but some of the five-star jobs appear to flaunt the
convention. The smaller ones expand in a lateral fashion. That is, they have a
central building with dining rooms, bars, and a few bedrooms. Then they build
blocks of bedrooms a few feet away. All very tasteful, of course.
A grander version of this is the ``cottage colony'' hotel, which are best
described as exclusive intimate properties with prices to match. One in
particular, the Lantana, boasts what the owner describes as an open air museum
where the grounds are dotted with statues by local and international sculptors,
and the main building is festooned with paintings and artefacts from around the
globe. The prices vary accordingly, as you might imagine. There are also guest
houses and self-catering apartments.
Finally, if you want a souvenir to take home, then remember that almost
everything has to be imported. It does fly the British flag (even if the
currency is the Bermuda Dollar and is pegged 1:1 with the US dollar) and even
has a Marks &amp; Spencer.
To tell the truth, the souvenirs ain't up to much. Cheap T-shirts, very
expensive Bermuda cedar, and booze. In reverse order, the rum is tasteful, the
cedar is tastefully carved, and the T-shirts are as tasteless as anywhere else.
The Americans love the place and despite their influence, or perhaps because of
it, the shops flaunt their Britishness and even their Scottishness. There's the
Pringle shop and an Archie Brown with its giant tartan-clad teddy bear outside
to usher in the customers.
I couldn't say farewell to Bermuda without mentioning its very own Mr Happy.
Johnnie Barnes used to work in the local bus garage, and at lunchtime he would
pass the hour eating his sandwich on the wall outside waving cheerfully to
passers-by.
He's now retired, and you'll pass him on the main roundabout east of Hamilton
where he spends eight hours a day, five days a week, waving to passers-by, and
preaching to them if they stop long enough to strike up a conversation. He's
now such a fixture that he features on the postcards.
My taxi driver gave me Johnnie's history. ``Some people reckon he's lost his
marbles,'' he said. ``I just think he knows something that the rest of us have
forgotten.''
Adrian Robertson looks into the Atlantic depths and discovers Bermuda, a haven
for natural beauty as well as the tax-shy
</TEXT>
