<HEADLINE>A place for the spirit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARL MACDOUGALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mr IVES' CHRISTMAS
Oscar Hijuelos
Bloomsbury, #15.99
EDWARD Ives had no beginning. He was left on the steps of a New York church and
raised in a foundling home - ``as cavernous and haunted as a cathedral''.
Contemplating Baby Jesus made him sad. Jesus was perhaps the most wanted child
in the world, while he had been abandoned.
But his faith sustained him. As a young man he almost wept when he entered a
church at Christmas. He was uncertain of many things, but the fact that he
could contemplate timeless images that seemed to speak especially to him was a
source of inspiration and pleasure.
It had nothing to do with decoration, the cheery wreaths, the bows of pine
branches, the ivy and flowers, but rather about the Christ child, ``whose
meaning evoked for him a feeling for `the beginning of things,' a feeling that
time and all its sufferings had fallen away''.
Ives was a successful commercial artist, who received a note of encouragement
from Walt Disney when he was 13, and made enough money to own, among other
things, a Drer etching. He met his wife in a life drawing class. Annie was a
vivacious woman who could barely stand her family's meddling ways.
She was pregnant when she married Ives. They had two children, Robert and
Caroline, who were raised in an open, fair-minded way. Ives taught his son
about religion and its imagery, how tongues of fire and soaring doves
represented the human spirit and of Christ's desolation when he felt forsaken
in the wilderness.
Ives knew nothing of his ancestry but was drawn to the Spanish cultures that
flourished in 1950s New York city. Even when he became his agency's
vice-president, he continued to live in upper Manhattan, where he felt at home,
in a multi-ethnic community. He helped many local Hispanic families find work
and his best friend was an immigrant Cuban barman who became the children's
godfather.
Oscar Hijuelos has constructed his story beautifully, replacing the exuberance
of The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love and The Fourteen Sisters of Emilio Montez
O'Brien with great warmth and tenderness.
His small chapters are layered with meaning, so that the reader is hardly aware
of absorbing the details, rather sharing the meditation on how peace can come
after a shattering crisis; such as that which befalls Ives' family shortly
before Christmas 1967 when his son is killed.
The value of this novel lies in its truthfulness. Ives is desperate to regain
spiritual peace, but can neither forgive nor understand God for pointlessly
turning against him. Neither can he accept what he sees as the haphazard
rejection of his life and belief.
It is a powerful testament on the need for a spiritual dimension in a society
where it is undervalued or seen as a weakness, and an affirmation of the power
of love and forgiveness in the face of human frailty.
CARL MACDOUGALL
</TEXT>
