<HEADLINE>Romance is for the birds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra particles</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n No matter what they say, it's tough being a bird, and tougher if you're a man
bird. The things you have to do to attract a lady bird's attention! Throughout
the animal kingdom, males have come up with inventive ways to catch a gal's
eye. The methods are as varied as the number of species, but generally there's
one common rule - other males are your competition.
But not if you're a ruff, says David Lank, a biologist from Simon Fraser
University in California who's been studying the little wader's mating habits.
Lank found that there are two genetically different types of male ruff, each of
which has its own strategy for courting females. This alone is unique, but just
as astonishing is the fact that these two male types don't compete directly
with each other. Instead, they work together as a team to attract females, much
like two lads on a night out.
The studies show that while this is very strange behaviour because these males
are competitors they both benefit by pulling in more females than they would by
themselves.
Male ruffs display to females on communal dancefloors, or ``leks''. Most of the
males are independents who strut their stuff in their own court which they
defend against others. A small number are ``satellite'' males which hang about
the leks cruising the courts of independents, who actively try to woo them into
staying and sharing in the matings.
``What we have is a kind of singles bar,'' Lank says. ``With both the males and
the females looking for one-night stands,'' explains Lank. ``A female, it
seems, prefers to do one-stop shopping where there are a lot of males
together.'' A bit like the aforementioned clubs.
Apparently both males do equally well in the mating game. This peculiar mating
system is likely driven by the choosiness of the female, who shows a preference
for male cooperation. If she didn't, the males would all compete directly, and
one or the other type would become extinct.
Further studies have not determined whether ruffs decide which gets the ugly
one or whether they have the phrase: ``Don't like yours much''. It's possible
they take the rough with the smoothie.
n BABIES can recognise their mothers' faces by the age of six months, but their
brains perform the task differently depending on whether it's hard or easy. The
work, carried out by a University of Minnesota graduate student has
implications for how facial memory develops.
n EXPERIMENTS that may result in cars powered by hydrogen fuel are under way at
Sandia's Livermore Lab in California. The lab is leading research with other
institutions to improve an engine that would use hydrogen as part of its fuel
supply. The group envisions creating a hydrogen-fuelled engine to drive a
generator, which would then power electric motors to turn the car's wheels.
Hydrogen, the most abundant element in the universe, creates little more than
water and a small amount of oxides of nitrogen when burned correctly in an
engine.
n A PURDUE University researcher has discovered a bed of ancient bones that may
contain the first fossilised evidence that some species were wiped out when a
giant extraterrestrial object hit the Earth 65 million years ago. William J
Zinsmeister, professor of geosciences, discovered the fossils during a trip to
Antarctica early this year. The fossil bed includes various species of fish and
occurs just above the iridium layer, an unique deposition in the rock record
worldwide that is suspected to have been created by a catastrophic event, such
as the impact of a giant asteroid or meteorite.
n AUSTRALIAN doctors have developed a microprocessor syringe for anaesthetics.
The computer-driven drug delivery system for use in operations can precisely
match the level of anaesthetic with the levels of stress suffered by patients
under surgery. The team at Adelaide developed complex mathematical models which
can predict how drugs perform and the computing software controls the syringe,
allowing the surgical team to concentrate on monitoring the patient.
</TEXT>
