<HEADLINE>There's always a guy who knows the score</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Allan Laing</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It started with a pianist masking the whirrs and clanks of the old projectors,
but cinema music developed until some houses had
their own orchestras. Allan Laing listens to the soaring strings
MORE years ago than I care to remember, I went to see a movie called One Flew
over the Cuckoo's Nest. And something wonderful happened, right at the end. You
may recall that marvellous final scene. The mighty Chief Broom smashes the
window, picks up McMurphy's lifeless body, and runs off, almost majestically,
towards a sunset over those dark remembered hills.
And all the time there was the achingly beautiful sound of Jack Nitzsche's
haunting score. It was inspirational. Moving. Perfect. That was the first time
I noticed, I mean really noticed, the music in a film. It was as if a new door
had opened in my mind.
It is an indisputable truth that music is a prerequisite for a film. Without it
movies simply wouldn't work. Together they form the perfect marriage between
the visual and the aural images. You need a score to provide a sense of
continuity. It heightens the emotions of a scene.
We are inclined to forget, as we sit there munching popcorn in the dark, that
what we see upon the screen is a two-dimensional art form. It is music which
magically transforms it into 3-D.
A film score is probably at its best when it provides a narrative to those
dramatic moments (and every movie has them) of utter silence on screen.
The scenes where actions, rather than words, tell the story. Two perfect
examples. Janet Leigh in the shower scene
And yet, despite all that, film music is a highly sophisticated art form. At
its best, it can stand alone without its celluloid partner. Good music is good
music; simple. It can be sparse, minimalist; such as Ry Cooder's slide guitar
work in Paris Texas. Or it can be huge and symphonic; like Maurice Jarre's
anthems for Lawrence of Arabia and Dr Zhivago.
And to think it all started 100 years ago with a wee man at a piano, playing
along to silent movies. His job, not to thrill the audience, but to mask the
sound of the primitive film projector. Airs have graced the motion picture
industry from its very inception. Every cinema in every town in America had a
picture-house band. New York's Paramount Playhouse even boasted a symphony
orchestra. Those Hollywood pioneers soon discovered that music could actually
do something for a movie. It could set its tone and its mood.
It could, almost, tell the audience how they should feel about a particular
scene. For instance, would old romantics have been moved to tears by Rhett and
Scarlett if they'd parted in silence and not to the throat-lumping sound of Max
Steiner's famous Gone with the Wind theme. Probably not (though, frankly my
dear, I don't give a damn).
Still, enough melodrama. Back to the wee man at the piano. When the talking
picture - and the ability to mix sound and vision - arrived it is estimated
that some half-a-million musicians in America were thrown out of work as the
industry moved from live accompaniment to a recorded score, specially written
for the film.
In the early days the music was usually borrowed from the shallow end of the
classical pool. Anonymous, formulaic, and pretty boring, frankly. However, as
technology improved in the 1930s, major studios such as Warner Brothers and
MGM, set up their own music departments. This coincided with the arrival in
Hollywood of an army of hugely talented composers and arrangers, refugees who
had fled Europe in the build up to the Second World War. Unlike many of their
American-born contemporaries, they were all classically trained with a
background and a tradition of either symphonic or operatic work.
Among them were the aforementioned Mr Steiner (Now Voyager, Treasure of the
Sierra Madre, and, of course, Gone with the Wind), Franz Waxman (Sunset
Boulevard and Rear Window), Dimitri Tiomkin (High Noon, Dial M For Murder, Rio
Bravo, 55 Days in Peking, The Alamo), Erich Korngold (Anthony Adverse, The
Adventures of Robin Hood), and Miklos Rozsa (Spellbound, Ben Hur, El Cid).
They took their movie music seriously, these chaps. Thanks to their efforts,
the composer's role was accorded greater status. They even got their names
mentioned in the credits. Movie soundtracks began to be issued on gramophone
records.
In the 1950s a second generation of composer appeared, most of them
American-born this time. There was Bernard Herrmann, with his idiosyncratic
scores for movies such as Citizen Kane, Vertigo and, of course, Psycho. The
versatile and prolific Elmer Bernstein who scored The Magnificent Seven and The
Great Escape and, more recently, Ghostbusters, My Left Foot, and The Age of
Innocence.
A little later came composers such as Lalo Schifrin (Bullitt, Dirty Harry, The
Eagle Has Landed) and Jerry Goldsmith (who studied under Rozsa at the
University of Southern California) with scores which included Von Ryan's
Express, The Sand Pebbles, The Blue Max, and Chinatown. Like Bernstein and
Schifrin, he is still working today (Alien, Total Recall, Basic Instinct).
The fifties also saw some movie directors experimenting (very successfully, as
it turned out) with jazz music. The aforementioned Bernstein wrote a memorable
jazz score for Otto Preminger's The Man with the Golden Arm, Duke Ellington
provided the music for the same director's Anatomy of a Murder, and the great
Alex North relied heavily on New Orleans jazz for Elia Kazan's A Streetcar
Named Desire.
But in the late fifties old scores were unsettled by the arrival of
rock'n'roll. All bets were cancelled with movies such as Blackboard Jungle and
Rock Around the Clock which introduced pop music to the big screen. The
public's apparently insatiable demand for rock'n'roll almost killed off the
large-scale orchestral scores.
They went out of fashion as a new breed of Hollywood director turned to turgid,
anodyne, guitar-based movie music (which always seemed to sound as if it was
played by a very bad amateur nightclub combo). It was tacky material for the
most part; second-rate soul music, cheap jazz, and (for those almost compulsory
dream sequences after the hero has his drink spiked by the ubiquitous femme
fatale) weird psychedelia.
This was not a vintage period for film music. To make matters worse, in
addition to poor scores, there was also the dreaded ``theme song'', without
which, it appeared, no self-respecting blockbuster movie would be seen dead.
Consider the songs in films like The Way We Were, Love Story, Shaft, or (much
better) The Graduate, and Midnight Cowboy. It was a marketing ploy, of course.
You get a pop star to make a hit record of your theme and you promote your
movie in the process. And it still happens (Wet Wet Wet with Love Is All Around
from Four Weddings).
It was a case of orchestral maneouvres in the dark during the sixties and
seventies, a time when only a handful of composers continued to persevere with
intelligent movie scores. Indeed, it was arguably left to two of them - John
Barry and Jerry Goldsmith - to re-invent the art form. These guys were astute
enough to recognise that orchestral scores had moved on a pace. So they took
the best elements of popular music and merged them with the big orchestral
scores.
Barry's consistently brilliant music for the Bond films is a perfect example.
However (this is one of those ``not-a-lot-of-people-know-this'' snippets of
information), he didn't write the James Bond theme; that was Monty Norman.
Another thing to remember about John Barry is the fact that, in a former life,
he'd been a pop composer/ arranger. One of his early successes (with the John
Barry Seven) was Hit or Miss, the best forgotten theme to Juke Box Jury.
In the seventies it was a case of Cinema - The Wilderness Years. The movie
industry's arch-enemy, television, was winning the battle for the hearts and
minds of the audience. People weren't going to the pictures. They preferred to
sit at home and watch the tube.
Hollywood was forced to take a long, hard, look at itself. And somewhere along
the line it decided to fight back. What could it offer that television could
not? The answer was bigger and better movies. Directors such as George Lucas
and Stephen Spielberg led the charge with films like the Star Wars trilogy, ET,
Indiana Jones, and Close Encounters of the Third Kind.
And, with the return of big movies came the return of big scores, another thing
with which cost-conscious, low-budget, television could not hope to compete.
Enter a genius called John Williams, the quintessential film composer.
Consider again those two simple notes from Jaws, delivered in the rhythm of a
heartbeat. Powerful music, designed to ensure that you will never dip your toe
in the sea again. And then Close Encounters. Five notes this time. Williams
wanted to create a musical beacon, something which would conjure up the image
of mankind communicating with an alien. There were, according to
mathematicians, at least 250,000 ways to combine five musical notes. Somehow
the composer found the right combination.
Only one other modern-day film composer can genuinely claim to rival John
Williams. The prolific Italian, Ennio Morricone, is surely one of the most
versatile talents in the business.
With a huge body of work which includes The Battle of Algiers, The Mission,
Once upon a time in the West, The Untouchables, and Cinema Paradiso, he has
written some of the most memorable scores of the past 20 years.
Today, like the industry it serves, film composing is wonderfully vibrant and
alive. A new breed of stars have emerged. Writers and arrangers like Alan
Silvestri, James Horner, Hans Zimmer and, in Britain, Michael Nyman. You can
even count a Scot among them. Patrick Doyle, Lanarkshire-born and a graduate of
the RSAMD, has written the scores for Kenneth Branagh's Henry V, Dead Again and
Mary Shelley's Frankenstein, as well as Hollywood movies like Carlito's Way and
the French film, Indochine.
Another promising development is the fact that many highly respected pop
musicians, perhaps realising that they're a little too old to rock and roll,
have turned their talents to film scores. Ry Cooder (Paris Texas, The Long
Riders, Crossroads, The Border), Mark Knopfler (Local Hero, Last Exit to
Brooklyn, Cal), Vangelis (Chariots of Fire, Blade Runner), David Byrne (The
Last Emperor, Married To The Mob), Ryuchi Sakamoto (Sheltering Sky, Merry
Christmas Mr Lawrence), Mike Oldfield (The Killing Fields) and, perhaps the
most successful of all, Randy Newman (The Natural, Ragtime, Parenthood, Avalon,
The Paper). Newman, it is perhaps worth noting, is the nephew of the
distinguished Hollywood film composer, Alfred Newman.
I end this hopelessly nostalgic and shamefully superficial article with a
rather pathetic caveat. Memory being not what it once was, I have almost
certainly omitted to mention numerous talented and influential film composers.
Glaringly obvious absentees are classical composers such as Benjamin Britten,
William Walton, Arthur Bliss, and Ralph Vaughan Williams, all of whom
contributed so much to British movies of the 1940s.
It is also a dead cert that, among this movie trivia, are some dreadful factual
mistakes. For my sins I apologise in advance. It is remiss of me. Movie buffs
will doubtless write in to point out the error of my ways. However, while
they're at it, they might care to answer a question for me. Whatever happened
to Jack Nitszche after One Flew over the Cuckoo's Nest?
Finally, I would like to thank Matthew Rooke, director of music at the Scottish
Arts Council (and a closet film-score enthusiast), for allowing me to pick his
brains. It should be pointed out that any mistakes are mine and not his.
</TEXT>
