<TEXT>
n IT was wee Jaikie of the Gorbals Diehards who intro-duced me to the word.
Whaups must have been burned into John Buchan's memory from his wanderings ovet
Tweedsmuir.
That bubbling song, purling to its diminuendo as the bird planes across the
moors and down to a little run on a patch of burnt heather, is as evocative a
spirit of place as any bird's in Scotland.
Yet the French name for curlew, ``courlis'' is more on-omatopoeic and the old
Scots ``whaup'' is what John Buchan preferred. And so do we.
Happily curlews have ex-tended their nesting areas in this country from
moorland to lowland fields and mead-ows, sand dunes and shingle, though they
still prefer their vegetation unimproved by man.
In summer and winter the Orkneys above all are drip-ping with curlews. At this
time of the year the breeding grounds are silent and the birds are scattered
around our coasts, though two thirds of our curlews winter in Ire-land and we
receive a few thousand visitors form fur-ther north.
There is something worth remembering when you hear the clamorous double note of
a winter curlew echoing off the cold rocks.
It will be eight weeks be-fore the first birds are prospecting the warming
in-land valleys. Not long after, the full song will come quiv-ering up from
that winter note like spring flowers. Imagine the warmth.
