<HEADLINE>Far more stars than there are in heaven</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Kerr ponders the way the great studios moulded their charges into
fantasy images, with even their private lives fodder for voracious publicity
departments
WHAT makes a star a star? From the late 1920s until the late 1950s, the answer
would almost certainly have been: a major Hollywood studio. During this period
studios operated like factories. Management made all the decisions about who
was to work on which projects and management spies kept a close watch on
proceedings. The production line mentality of the moguls meant that everyone
moved from one film to the next as soon as their involvement in the first job
was finished.
Tasks were strictly demarcated: producers produced, directors directed and
writers wrote. Only a handful of mavericks combined roles. Actors and actresses
may have been treated like royalty outside the studio, but inside it they were
workers like everyone else; subject to the same indignities even though they
were being promoted as super human stars by the relentless machinery of the
publicity departments.
The studio which set the standards to which all the rest aspired was MGM. From
1924, when Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer was founded, until his premature death in 1936,
Irving Thalberg - Hollywood's ``Boy Wonder'' - was the dominant force behind
the studio. Blessed with an eye for talent, he spotted the likes of Greta
Garbo, Clark Gable, Joan Crawford and Jean Harlow and steered them all to
stardom. Once they were there, he chose the supporting actors, storylines,
directors and photographers which would best complement his stars to ensure
that nothing could knock them from their pedestals of popularity. That the
personality of the star came across was more important to Thalberg than the
plot of a movie. Top on his list of priorities was Norma Shearer, whom he
married in 1927, and who did indeed become a major, Oscar-winning, star under
his guidance.
Thalberg believed that ``the public makes the stars'', and so he regularly
tested the star potential of minor contractees by observing audience reaction
to them. At least once a week a Pullman carriage called the ``MGM Special''
would hitch itself up to a train heading for a small town outside the Los
Angeles area. On it would be Thalberg and his closest colleagues, plus a
preview copy of their latest movie which they would show to an audience whose
comments were crucial to the future of both the film and the star.
In the space of 12 years, MGM had built up a roster of the brightest stars in
Hollywood. Thalberg's gift for mixing and matching personalities produced many
inspired combinations (like Gable and Charles Laughton in Mutiny on the
Bounty), and his inistence that once you were a star you were always a star
resulted in second chances for many actors and actresses who had become
casualties of the popularity polls. He established MGM in the public
consciousness as the studio of opulence; the dreamiest of all the dream
factories and it remained the leader of the pack throughout the studio era.
The other studios followed MGM's shining example in accumulating and nurturing
future stars - but on a lesser scale. The Warner Brothers product was a less
polished affair: whereas in the 1930s MGM specialised in expensive escapist
costume dramas, Warners' greatest asset was its gritty realism. Its stars -
Humphrey Bogart, Joan Blondell, Errol Flynn among them - were not the urbane
sophisticates of MGM. They were more recognisable as ordinary Americans. Unlike
MGM's paternalistic head honcho, Louis B Mayer, Jack Warner at Warner Brothers
and Harry Cohn at Columbia were more tyrannical characters. Warner conducted
running battles with some of his employees, most famously Bette Davis and James
Cagney who both protested publicly at the volume of work they were given (a
Warners actor could expect to make seven films a year), and at the fact that
they were not allowed any say in what they did.
Mussolini's methods provided the inspiration for the way Harry Cohn ran his
Columbia studio, and intimidation was the philosophy behind his technique when
dealing with all members of staff - star or no star. His bullying nature lost
him at least one big name - Jean Arthur, the beautiful but nervy actress who
co-starred with Gary Cooper in Mr Deeds Goes to Town and Mr Smith Goes to
Washington. Arthur was scared stiff of Cohn, refused to have direct contact
with him and was frequently suspended by the studio. When her contract expired
she was only too glad to be free of a boss who continued business discussions
with employees even when he was otherwise occupied in his private toilet.
In addition to being one of the toughest studio chiefs, Cohn was notorious for
concerning himself directly with the private lives of his stars. As late as the
mid 1950s, when the whole set-up of the studio system was collapsing, Cohn was
dictating who could be seen with whom. Sammy Davis Jr was given no shortage of
incentives to discontinue his relationship with Kim Novak, then a Cohn starlet
being groomed for the bigtime. Cohn felt that going out with a black man - even
a popular entertainer like Davis - would harm Novak's image-in-progress.
Studio interference with the private lives of stars was par for the course.
There was really no such thing as a private life for a star: anything that
could be used by the publicity department would not remain private very long.
David Niven's first experience of MGM's publicity department was recalled in
his autobiography, The Moon's a Balloon. Jock Lawrence, the head of publicity,
wanted a run-down of Niven's life. The conversation went as follows:
``Mother?''
``French.''
``Good, we can use that.''
``Father?''
``Killed in the war.''
``Great! What rank?''
``Lieutenant.''
``Jesus, that's terrible, we'd better make him a General.''
Not only did the studios thrive on the publicity generated by their stars; a
whole industry of fan magazines flourished on the gossip. In the 1920s, 26
different weekly film magazines devoured the lurid details of the many scandals
of the decade. With the establishment of the studio system in the early 1930s,
there was closer co-operation between the studio's publicity departments and
the magazine writers - and less scandal.
Anything remotely harmful to the reputation of a star - and therefore of the
studio - would be hushed up at often ridiculous cost. MGM had to cope with the
suicide of studio executive Paul Bern, who was married to Jean Harlow - its
``Blonde Bombshell'' star. A more routine part of the job of unfortunate
publicity men was to sober up stars who were due in front of the cameras, or
the press.
The closer co-operation between the publicity departments and the magazines
also led to more fiction. From the 1930s, studios would plant unmarried stars
in nightclubs and let the film reporters and photographers do the rest. Going
out at night with the escort of the studio's choice was as much a part of a
star's remit as learning lines before filming began. Thus in August 1942,
Modern Screen's big picture spread was ``a date with Betty Grable and George
Raft'': four pages of photos of Betty and George's evening together, from
getting dressed to go out, to their goodnight kiss.
Between them, publicity departments and magazine writers cooked up all kinds of
myths. Greta Garbo's aloof, I vant to be alone, public persona was probably
down to the fact that she was a naturally private person who hated publicity.
The explanation offered by MGM was that she was a ``Woman Without Love''. Fans
lapped it up.
The love problems of the stars were the main area of concern of fan magazines.
One debate that continued throughout the heyday of the fan magazine was whether
a male star would lose fans by getting married. As one writer put it: ``If the
girls who watch him think that he is going home to his wife they will have more
difficulty in thinking of him as their own Prince Charming''. The magazines
didn't just reiterate gossip about the stars and their love lives, they offered
opinions on them. The actress Janet Gaynor (of A Star is Born) was criticised
for marrying Lydell Peck, because she had cheated her fans out of the wedding
they had been expecting - to her screen partner, Charlie Farrell. And the
criticism wasn't a one-off: Farrell's supposedly broken heart and Gaynor's own
alleged restlessness became an ongoing saga in the press.
Regular features of the fan magazines, which were useful publicity stunts for
stars, were fashion spreads encouraging readers to take tips from their
favourite actress. Modern Screen ran spreads on some of the most elegant and
distinctive stars - Carole Lombard and Jean Harlow among them - and in some
cases, like Bette Davis's, offered patterns so that readers could reproduce
their dresses. Beauty advice pages were often filled with tips from top names
like Claudette Colbert and Joan Crawford.
Very often, the studios used the magazines as a ``direct'' means of
communication between stars and their public - especially if the star had
fallen from favour and was seeking to redeem him/herself: in 1931 Jean Harlow
sent a message to her fans which was more or less an apology for the failure of
her marriage (to Hal Rosson). Stars also dispensed advice. Olivia de Havilland
counselled Silver Screen's readers: ``Don't be Afraid of a Broken Heart''. Joan
Crawford revealed ``The Difference Between Friendship and Love'' for Movie
Mirror, while her former husband Douglas Fairbanks Jr outlined the ``Four Rules
of Married Love'' for columnist Dora Albert.
It wasn't all glamour, though. While the studios tried to portray stars as
superhumans, unconcerned with the more mundane aspects of normal life, their
partners in exploitation - the fan magazines - occasionally preferred to
emphasise the fact that stars were ordinary folk at heart. It was, after all,
slightly distasteful to read that both Constance Bennett and Joan Crawford were
paying $15,000 annually on household bills when men were queueing on
breadlines. The magazines' antidote to the extravagance of the matinee idols
was to bring them firmly down to earth with some good old-fashioned common
sense. Miss Crawford told Modern Screen: ``I'd rather know that the seams of my
stockings are straight than wear diamonds''.
But this film fan's most cherished magazine article is one from the Modern
Screen of April 1939 about the culinary preferences of the star of that year's
Mr Smith Goes To Washington - James Stewart. Jimmy, clearly a home-loving boy
(when he wasn't out on the town), shared his two favourite recipes with lucky
readers: chicken pie and American apple pie.
The end of the reign of the fan magazines was bound up with the decline of the
studio system in the late 1950s and early 1960s: without the dream factories it
was impossible to establish a stable of stars which could rival those of the
1930s when a publicity man declared that a film had ``more stars than there are
in heaven''.
</TEXT>
