<HEADLINE>Under their own steamer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jimmie Macgregor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The battle to keep the Maid of the Loch afloat is being won, Jimmie Macgregor
is delighted to report
ON Monday December 4, 1995, Pat O'Neil, Dumbarton District Council's affable
provost made the official transfer of ownership of the paddle steamer Maid of
the Loch to Michael Hughen, representative of the Maid of the Loch Trust.
The trust will pass the ship on to the Loch Lomond Steamship Company, a
recently formed Scottish charity. The couthy little ceremony at Balloch pier
ended years of uncertainty and speculation as to the fate of the ship.
In the summer of 1981 I invited a dear old friend to join me for a trip on the
Maid. An elderly lady from the south, Aga was much travelled, but on her first
visit to Scotland.
On our day, sunlight sparkled on the water and an uncharacteristically
cloud-free Ben Lomond was sculpted against a deep blue sky. The great paddles
churned, people drank tea, scoffed buns, and enthused about the scenery in half
a dozen languages.
Having made a radio series on the West Highland Way earlier in the season, I
was able to tell my companion something of the area's history, wildlife and
topography, and to explain some of the names of the scatter of islands. (There
are more than 30.) She was enchanted by the whole experience, and later was
quite horrified when I told her that this was to be the Maid's last season. A
major overhaul was required, and with no funds available, it was thought that
she would never sail again.
At one time Loch Lomond had five steamers in service, carrying mail and freight
as well as passengers. In the early 1950s when the remaining vessels, Princess
May and Prince Edward, had reached the end of their working lives, the Glasgow
shipbuilders A &amp; J Inglis were commissioned to build the Maid of the Loch,
while Rankin and Blackmore of Greenock supplied the engine.
The tradition had always been to bring the loch steamers up the river Leven,
but the Maid, at 191ft and 555 tons had to be transported by rail in sections
and assembled at Balloch. Her ceremonial maiden voyage was on Friday May 22,
1953, and she last sailed at the end of the 1981 season.
The Maid was moored at Balloch pier and her owners Caledonian MacBrayne offered
her for sale. Steamer enthusiasts, concerned that their darling might end as
scrap, were heartened when an Australian leisure group showed interest, but it
soon became clear that the pier and the surrounding group was the attraction as
the site for a hotel. The next potential saviour was a brewery company who had
run the little steamer Countess Fiona. That too came to nothing.
As the upper deck deteriorated, water found its way in, causing further damage
to woodwork and decking below. The dreaded rust attacked exposed metal, and the
even more dreaded vandals began to strip the ship of anything they thought
could be sold. The dirty dogs even took the steam whistle.
It really began to look as though the old girl's days were numbered, but over
the hill came the cavalry in the shape of Dumbarton District Council who, to
their eternal credit, acquired the ship to hold until her fate could be
resolved. A trust was then formed and the council agreed to pass the ship into
their care if they raised #200,000 towards the cost of restoration. That figure
has now been passed, but a sum nearer #2m will be required to put the Maid back
into service. Security alone is costing #30,000 per annum, but enthusiasm and
optimism are unbounded, with a dedicated group already working evenings and
weekends to prepare the vessel for a total refit.
Some time ago Dumbarton District Council, displaying a touching faith in human
nature, made an appeal for the return of stolen artifacts, with a promise of no
questions asked. Astonishingly, much has already been recovered, certain items
from as far away as Newcastle, though the steam whistle is still missing. In a
scene reminiscent of a B movie, the ship's bell changed hands in a darkened car
park.
The twin aims of the restoration are technical and aesthetic; to upgrade the
ship's performance while maintaining her traditional appearance. The huge
boiler system will be replaced by something much smaller but more efficient.
There will be modern ventilation, but two of the great horn shaped ventilators
will still grace the deck. An up-to-date audio visual system is to be installed
and much thought given to catering facilities. Steam vessels are non-polluting
and there will be no discharges of any kind into the loch, everything being
collected in tanks and off-loaded on land.
Andrew Cumming, the marine architect overseeing the project, points out that
thanks to the fact that fresh water is less corrosive than salt, the hull is in
very sound condition, but the decks are to be replaced with steel overlaid with
wood. The area between the upper and lower decks will be enclosed and glazed,
recognising at last that Scottish loch steamers require slightly different
specifications from those plying the Mediterranean.
The Maid will need good piers, and while Luss, Rowardennan and Inversnaid are
sound, Balloch pier requires a great deal of work. Those at Balmaha and Tarbet
present a problem, having been reduced in size, and Ardlui pier has gone.
All in all a very encouraging picture, and with the combined efforts of experts
and volunteers, supported by the Millennium Fund and other help, the Maid of
the Loch will live again. The target for the relaunch is 1998. In the meantime,
can we have our whistle back please?
</TEXT>
