<HEADLINE>Breakdown of trust</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Hewitson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra scotching the myths</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jim Hewitson recalls an incident in the capital which shook the Auld Alliance
to its core
MAYBE now that we're approaching the end of the 700th anniversary Auld Alliance
jollifications (some might say palaver) it can be pointed out that just
occasionally the Franco-Scottish old pals act could be far from hunky dory.
Perhaps the most notorious breakdown in the cordiality of ``la Vieille
Alliance'' came about in 1548 when French troops - our sworn allies, remember -
treated Edinburgh like a captured city, running amok among the citizens and
slaying the provost.
A formidable French force had been in Scotland for months defending Edinburgh
and attempting to dislodge a stubborn English garrison which was holed up
behind its defences at Haddington, East Lothian, under its astute leader Sir
John Wilford.
Historians noted a ``certain incompatibility of temper'' between the Scots and
the French despite their mutual loathing of the English. The French were
apparently not over-impressed by either Scotland or the Scots, the scribes
suggesting that the land was a wilderness and the people savages. When they
marched under the same banner there were ``scowling looks of mutual mistrust''.
Having turned back an English assault on the capital, the French - without
formal permission - quartered themselves in Edinburgh. A minor skirmish, when a
French soldier tried to confiscate a rifle from an Edinburgh citizen, lit the
powder keg.
The scuffle attracted a crowd and the French suffered a severe going-over
before breaking out and being chased from the Cross down Niddry Street, two of
their number having been killed. As this was taking place, the provost arrested
two more Frenchmen and was leading them to prison when a group of about 60
French soldiers burst from the lodgings of their commander, M D'Esse, with
drawn swords, slew the provost and several others, and rescued the prisoners.
The death of the provost, James Hamilton, who was also captain of the castle,
and the period of two hours when the French went on the rampage, drew universal
condemnation. When things calmed down there were demands for retribution and
threats that if there was no official action the citizens would do the needful.
This was a chivalrous time, however, and it was agreed that the most
appropriate compensation would be for the French to perform some brave deed of
war which would satisfy the thirst for vengeance. The French were to storm
Haddington as a signal of repentance. Within 24 hours of the affray at the
Cross they marched off into East Lothian under cover of darkness. Details of
this chivalrous contract had been kept secret and they had reached the outworks
of the town before the alarm was raised.
Half-naked and half-asleep, the English garrison stood to the defence of the
town but the outer perimeter was quickly taken. The course of this swift and
violent action was spectacularly altered by a French deserter who had been
spying for the English garrison. He fired two large cannon into the gateway,
which disintegrated and sent lethal wooden slivers in all directions.
Incredibly, it's reported that up to 100 of his fellow countrymen died in this
incident. The French could not be induced to attempt another assault and
returned to Edinburgh, their tails between their legs. Their shame and defeat
was said to have been welcomed by Edinburgh's citizens.
</TEXT>
