<TEXT>
John Davidson, like an American president before him, goes a-hunting, and is
charmed
LET'S explode one of the great myths of anthropology. People absolutely do not
grow to resemble their dogs. Or cats. Or, for that matter, goldfish. In adult
life, however, they do develop uncanny similarities to the Teddy bears of their
formative years.
Believe me, parents' influence on the development of their offspring is
secondary to that of any Teddy. Consider the characteristics of a 40-year-old.
Whether he has turned out soft, rounded and rather loveable - or dark and
rather grizzly . . . it's always the bear who is to blame.
German toy manufacturers have been making bears for children since the 1870's.
But it was an early twentieth century American president who really started the
bear craze. Out hunting one fine day, Theodore Roosevelt spared a small brown
bear and the embrionic American toy industry shifted into overdrive. And
overtime. For the public began to reassess those big, brown monsters as cuddly,
adoreable creatures. And alongside princess-like dolls and toy soldiers, Teddy
(Theodore seemed a little too formal) took up his rightful place in every
nursery.
He hasn't moved out ever since. While Space Invaders come and go, while each
hi-tech wonder passes in and out of favour, no childhood is complete without a
bear. All too soon, children discover that Teddy is their most trustworthy
confidant and reliable companion -their finest role model for later life. Which
must explain why so many adults ask of their spouses, `Darling, why can't you
be more like Teddy?'
Understandably, some grown men and women just won't be parted from their bears.
And many more find every Teddy bear teacup, Teddy bear notebook and Teddy bear
cushion quite irresistably cute. Which is why this Christmas - like just about
every other since Theodore Roosevelt's abortive hunting expedition, Teddies top
the gift lists.
