<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Open the door to a  colourful Christmas</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>33</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The mood is medieval this year and thank goodness colours are back to red and
green. Leila Aitken puts out a welcome wreath for a whole new wave of inventive
decorations
CHRISTMAS decorations are now big business. Jenners in Edinburgh give over a
whole department to Christmas trimmings as early as mid-September and many
major cities have a Christmas shop open the whole year round.
There is a fashion element in Christmas decorations, too. Two years ago the
Christmas theme was blue and gold; last year saw new baubles in the shape of
antique bronze stars, suns and moons and this year the trend is medieval.
Candles come in rich jewel colours as well as striped and marbled and this year
they are available in much larger sizes. Fat pillar candles now come in dark
colours as well as the traditional ivory and combine well with very realistic
and luscious-looking artificial fruit, including peaches so authentic that I
saw a small child reach from a pushchair, grab one and suck it with gusto.
The Christmas colours this year, thank goodness, are back to the traditional
red, holly green and gold and nothing is more cheering and reminiscent of
Dickens than a sumptuous fireplace garland of fresh greenery. This one is
really two decorations in one - a centre arrangement of candles and fruit with
a garland draped at each side. The centrepiece can be lifted out on Christmas
Day and placed in the middle of the table for Christmas dinner.
The basic framework for the garland is made from half blocks of oasis cut
lengthwise, wrapped in a continuous length of clingfilm and tied on each side
of the blocks like a string of sausages. Or, larger florists may sell you a
ready-made garland frame made by Smithers Oasis from oasis foam.
To decorate a mantelpiece you will also need:
Greenery -- choose a selection from your garden of different leaf shapes and
texture (eg laurel, spruce, holly, golden cupressus, cedar - cedrus atlantica
``Glauca'' is particularly good), yew, lonicera nitida, variegated ivy,
euonymus).
Trims - red and green tartan ribbon; fir cones; florist's stem wire.
For the centrepiece:
You will need a large block of soaked oasis in a flat oblong dish; five candles
in oasis candle-holders; artificial or fresh fruit and walnuts.
n Cut the foliage into short sprigs 5 to 7.5 cm long. Using flat leaves, such
as laurel, as the background, insert the first  foliage at intervals along the
length of the garland.
n Alternate with other leaves and sprigs of foliage and holly, evenly spaced
until all the oasis is hidden. For soft stems you may need to pierce the
clingfilm first with a skewer. Wrap florist's wire around the base of a fir
cone and add these. Add loops of ribbon wire in the same way.
For the mantelpiece:
n Place the oasis and holder in the centre of the mantelpiece. Insert five
candles in secure oasis candle holders. Vary the height of the candles, by
cutting a little from the base of one or two.
n Insert short branches of spruce and sprigs of holly and ivy, keep them low
and well away from the candles.
n Group a selection of fruit at the base of the candles, anchoring some of them
on cocktail sticks or stub wires. Scatter nuts and small fir cones over the
fruit.
n Drape a garland at each side of the centrepiece to hang over the edge of the
mantelpiece. Add loops and trails of tartan ribbon with variegated ivy at each
end.
The welcome wreath on the door is by far the most popular Christmas decoration.
It puzzles me why people buy these; they are expensive and often sparse. It is
quite easy to make one. Buy an oasis wreath ring from a florist, soak the foam
and pack it with garden greenery as above. At the base of the circle add a
point of interest, red silk poinsettia. For a Christmas party or a welcome
arrangement on a side table, lavish use of gold and red will effectively create
the right Christmassy atmosphere. Gold fabric is plentiful and cheap and a
metre will be plenty to drape at the base of a flower display. This is about
the only time of year when artificial glitter does not look out of place with
natural foliage.
For a Christmas party arrangement: You will need a shallow dish, a block of
oasis foam, two tall red candles, oasis candle-holders, gold artificial fern
and gold cane scrolls (many florists have these);
Flowers - red single carnations; red spray carnations.
Foliage - variegated holly; ivy; rosemary; contorted hazel (corylus avellana)
sprayed with gold paint.
Set the dish with the soaked oasis foam on the drape of gold fabric. Insert the
sprays of hazel curling upwards at the back of the foam and the candles in
holders in front. Add holly to form a roughly triangular shape with the sprigs
of rosemary and ivy trailing at the base to the front and sides.
Arrange the large carnations to the centre and the spray carnations to the
sides and base. Add the gold ferns and scrolls.
By far the best decoration for the Christmas tea table is the Christmas cake
and there are some showstoppers in Joanna Farrow's Creative Christmas Cakes,
published by Merehurst at #10.99, which is an absolutely delightful book of
very original ways to decorate a cake. I couldn't wait to make my cake which is
now decorated with an exhausted Father Christmas flat out on a bed with a
spotted quilt, his empty sack, wellies, slippers and half-eaten sandwich behind
him.
There are other novelty cakes in the book, which I was just as tempted to make
- a complete Nativity scene, a pile of Christmas story books and if you wish to
keep to a medieval theme, there are individual jewelled boxed, an original idea
for decorating small cakes for those who don't need a large one. The cakes are
fun to create in either bought or homemade sugar paste and the instructions are
good.
OUR BEST &amp; WORST BUYS
n William Craig and Karen Allen - Scottish Green Party
Best buys - Anything from an Oxfam shop or catalogue. Membership of an
environmental organisation (eg RSPB, Reforesting Scotland). Wild flower seeds,
bird/bat box or bird table. Organic produce such as beer or wine, Body Shop
products, Beeswax candles, unbleached cotton or string bags, rail ticket,
cycling accessories, solar panels, rechargeable batteries, anything reusable,
recycled, biodegradable, energy-saving, long-lasting or useful.
Worst buys - Anything French or Nigerian. Anything from a Shell catalogue, a
new car, Nescafe coffee, farmed turkey, a plane ticket, war toys, anything made
from (unsustainable) tropical hardwoods. Anything ``disposable''
non-biodegradable, excessively packaged or useless.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000183</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000183</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Douglas Corrigan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is not given to many people to achieve celebrity through monumental
ineptitude. Such, however, was the fate of veteran aviator Douglas
``Wrong-Way'' Corrigan, who became a transatlantic folk hero in 1938 after he
took off from New York supposedly bound for California and ended up in Ireland.
The disorientated flier has died in California at the age of 88.
Corrigan was 31 when US aviation officials refused to grant him an exit permit
for a solo transatlantic flight, saying his rickety plane was unsafe for such a
long trip. When he took off on July 17, 1938, he said he was heading back to
Long Beach, California. But 28 hours later he landed in Dublin.
Corrigan had a novel explanation for being thousands of miles off course - his
compass froze. And he stuck to that story for the rest of his life, though he
often recounted it with a twinkle in his eye. Whatever the truth of the matter,
he became an instant celebrity on both sides of the Atlantic. He was feted in
Ireland and received a ticker-tape parade when he returned to New York. Later
he starred in a Hollywood movie about his exploits entitled The Flying Irishman.
The authorities let him off lightly, suspending his pilot's licence for only
five days. Corrigan served as a transport pilot in the Second World War and
later ran an air freight service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000184</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000184</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Darren Robinson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DARREN Robinson, who died in New York this week aged 28, helped propel rap
music into mainstream of global culture as one third of the Fat Boys. Rap owes
much of its current popularity to its outlaw status: music of the Afro-American
ghetto for the inhabitants of the Afro-American ghetto. It wasn't always that
way, as the Fat Boys' multi-media success in the mid-eighties proved.
Having earned Top 10 hits with rap remakes of the Surfaris' Wipe Out and Chubby
Checker's The Twist, the Fat Boys went on to appear in TV's Miami Vice as well
as a movie, Disorderlies. Nicknamed the Human Beat Box, Robinson propelled all
their music with the percussive grunts, exhalations and clicks he could
generate within his 450lb body.
As their name indicates, the heavyweight trio's forte, whether captured on
vinyl or celluloid, was comic self-parody. Their mission was to spread smiles,
not angry polemic. Rap mutated into self-aggrandisement in the nineties,
forcing the Fat Boys into redundancy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000185</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000185</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dowager Countess of Haddington</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarah, Dowager Countess of Haddington; born November 13, 1903, died December
14, 1995
SARAH, Dowager Countess of Haddington, a driving force behind the first
Edinburgh International Festival, has died after a long illness. She was 92.
Her work in helping to steer the festival, which started in 1947, through its
early years received praise throughout Britain. It was her love of all kinds of
music which led to her involvement in the festival committee which she served
on for 14 years.
Being a classically-trained pianist she loved Chopin but an indication of her
wide-ranging musical taste was that the Rod Stewart song, Sailing, was a
particular favourite of hers.
Away from music and her extensive work with the Edinburgh Festival she managed
to fit in fund-raising work with the Royal British Legion Scotland. She became
president of the women's section in 1939 and was a driving force in its work
for many years.
During the war her country home, Mellerstain near Kelso, became an emergency
military convalescent hospital. Soldiers from Canada, Britain, Poland, and
Australia were welcomed to the house and its grounds. The soldiers never forgot
the kindness they received and many of them, particularly Australian and
Canadian, kept in touch through the years.
One of her biggest and most successful projects after the war was the
fund-raising campaign between 1949 and 1952 for the Scottish National
Institution for the War Blinded at Linburn.
A British Legion Scotland spokesman praised her work and said Lady Haddington
helped raise thousands of pounds for them throughout the years. ``Her efforts
were magnificent,'' said the spokesman. ``At Linburn alone her efforts resulted
in a new house for the blinded being donated and built.''
Lady Haddington was born in Montreal and she met her future husband George, the
12th Earl of Haddington, while he was serving as an ADC to the Governor-General
of Canada. They married in 1923 and settled down at the family home at
Mellerstain.
She was a keen gardener and when the family moved to Tyninghame House near
Haddington in East Lothian her skills came to the fore. She helped restore the
interior of the house and created the world-famous gardens which are open
occasionally to the public through the Scotland's Garden Scheme.
Lady Haddington, a former president of the scheme, also helped set up the East
Lothian Amenity Society which cared for local planting and landscaping.
Her husband George died nine years ago at the age of 91. She is survived by her
son, John, the 13th Earl of Haddington, and her daughter, Lady Mary Russell.
She had eight grandchildren and four great grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000186</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000186</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thomas Evans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Thomas Richard Evans, marine engineer; born September 10, 1911, died December
10, 1995
THOMAS Richard Evans, former managing director of Alexander Stephen
Engineering, has died at the Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, at the age of
84. He was considered a first class manager of the old school.
A Renfrew man by birth, Mr Evans was brought up and educated locally,
continuing his studies at Paisley Technical College. A chartered engineer and a
fellow of the Institute of Marine Engineers, he started his career as a
draughtsman and served his apprenticeship with the Renfrew shipbuilding firm of
Lobnitz. From there he went to work in London with the aircraft manufacturers
Handley Page, until, in the words of his widow Annie, ``the bombs chased us
home''.
Joining Simons of Renfrew, Tom Evans became their chief draughtsman. The two
firms Simons and Lobnitz (neighbours on the riverbank) were traditionally at
daggers drawn and a 1960s merger proved unsuccessful. When the joint company
closed, Mr Evans had the task of finishing a number of orders for dredgers and
then overseeing the closure. ``He really felt bad,'' recalls his widow, and he
tried to find jobs for the displaced workforce.
He subsequently became managing director of Alexander Stephen Engineering - one
of the successor companies created from the original Alexander Stephen and Sons
Ltd when Upper Clyde Shipbuilders came into existence.
``He was a very fine manager in a very onerous job,'' recalled Mr Alexander
Stephen, manager director of the original firm, yesterday, ``and was very able
and forceful and good with his men. He was a first-class manager of the old
school.''
Despite angina, Tom Evans travelled the world, from the west coast of America
to South Africa, seeking orders for the company which, in a period of
recession, was making stabilisers, pressure vessels for power stations, and
variable-pitch propellers for warships, among many other things.
Tom Evans was counselled to retire at the age of 63, having been told his life
expectancy was very short; he would look back 21 years later on this premature
medical advice. Meanwhile his firm closed two years after his retirement. Its
main building, with its cast-iron columns and roof trusses, has now been
re-erected at the Scottish Maritime Museum in Irvine.
Mr Evans was a staunch churchman and a member of Renfrew Trinity's
congregation. His hobbies included stamp collecting and horticulture and he was
a former president of the Orchid Society of Glasgow.
Alexander Stephen paid tribute yesterday to Tom Evans's ``huge personality'',
recalling a man who was ``full of fun and very tough. What he said he meant. It
was a joy to have him as a colleague. He was very forthright and one of the
most loyal people I've ever met.''
Mr Evans leaves his widow and his daughter Anne and family. His funeral takes
place today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000187</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000187</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A fish's head and trousers of flame</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Liz Taylor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra under the hammer</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Liz Taylor marvels at Diaghilev's
colourful costumes
CASTLE Howard, the Yorkshire stately home where Brideshead Revisited was
filmed, has figured strongly in the saleroom scene this week.
One of the attractions for visitors to the house used to be a display of
costumes created for Diaghilev's Ballet Russe in the early years of the
twentieth century. That colourful display will, however, no longer be seen at
Castle Howard because the costumes were dispersed by auction before an eager
audience at Sotheby's in London last week.
The magnificent costumes were acquired in the late 1960s and early 70s by the
late George Howard, former chairman of the BBC. He started buying in 1967 when
Sotheby's held an auction of the contents of several hampers filled with
wonderful clothes which had been discovered in a Paris warehouse.
The moving spirit behind the Ballet Russe, which began in Paris in 1909, was a
non-dancing, non-performing Russian, Sergei Diaghilev (1872-1929), who,
however, managed to gather round himself the most original and artistically
talented people of his time. His dancers included such names as Nijinsky,
Massine, Pavlova, and Karsavina; he used the music of Stravinsky, Debussy, and
Ravel commissioned artists like Leon Bakst, Henri Matisse, Georges Braque and
Pablo Picasso to design the costumes.
Diaghilev's productions took the artistic world by storm, transformed popular
taste by setting a fashion for exuberant colours, flowing lines, and gold and
silver threads which made the dancers look as if they were shimmering with
light as they danced under the spotlights.
Some of the most striking pieces were designed by Leon Bakst for the 1912
production of Le Dieu Bleu in which the dancers wore towering head-dresses,
gem-studded skirts, gold silk breeches embroidered with gold and silver
sequins, and haloes of wired gold that flared from their heads like flames.
A costume designed by Natalia Gontcharova in 1916 for Sadko, about a
fantastical sea creature, consisted of a head-dress like a fish's head with
bodice and trousers of flame-like material. Its estimate in the sale was around
#8000.
Matisse was responsible for the costumes in the 1925 production of Stravinsky's
Le Chant de Rossignol. Tinsel discs and flower petals on the costume of one of
the mourners in the ballet were painted directly on to the silk by Matisse
himself. The estimate for that robe was also around #8000. The pink leotard
embroidered with appliqued velvet and silk petals which was worn by Nijinsky in
Le Spectre de la Rose, his most notable role, was in the sale with an estimate
of #800 to #1200.
Castle Howard also figured in a now closed exhibition of Faberge pieces which
has been running at Tessier's, the Bond Street jewellers, but which will reopen
at Castle Howard in the New Year. There are 24 items in the exhibition which is
a testimony to the art of Carl Faberge, jeweller to the Imperial Russian Court
at the turn of the century. Amazingly these treasures lay forgotten since the
1940s, in a storeroom at Castle Howard, and have only recently been
re-discovered.
Some of the pieces are tiny carvings of birds and animals - ibexes carved from
brown agate; a rat, a rabbit, a hoopoe, and owls carved from hardstone; a
rhinoceros carved from obsidian; two cheerful looking elephants carved from
chalcedony and others carved from crystal. There are also little nephrite
pumpkins, a gold-mounted Easter egg, a little silver and blue enamel clock, and
a jade and gold mounted cigar holder and cutter. This exquisite little
exhibition will do something to make up for the loss of the Diaghilev costumes
for future visitors to Castle Howard.
</TEXT>
