<HEADLINE>George MacKenzie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK WEBSTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
George A MacKenzie, schoolmaster and author; born February 18, 1926, died
December 3, 1995
GEORGE MacKenzie, former deputy rector of Cathkin High School, near Glasgow,
came into that category of Scottish lad-o'-pairts who had to fight his way to
education, against the odds of his generation.
Born in Aberdeen in 1926, he was left without a father at four and depended on
bursaries to get him first to Robert Gordon's College and then to Aberdeen
University, where he graduated with honours in French and German.
But even that suffered the interruption of the Second World War when, before
graduation, he was called up for the war effort, or rather ``called down,'' as
George liked to joke about it - because his service was to be as one of the
much-publicised Bevin Boys who would work in the coal mines.
He was not required to go underground but George volunteered to do so and was
down the pits for two years before resuming his honours course at Aberdeen. He
would later utilise the experience to write about his memories as a Bevin Boy.
His authorship included a book called From Aberdeen to Ottawa, which he based
on the detailed diary of an Aberdeen lawyer who set out in 1845 to find his
relations in Canada.
For his bread and butter, however, George MacKenzie embarked on a teaching
career in his native North-east in 1951, first at Maud Higher Grade School and
then at Ellon Academy.
He took his linguistic skills south to Lanark Grammar - he also served on the
local town council, became a Kirk elder, and was active in the Educational
Institute of Scotland - before becoming principal teacher of French and German
at Bishopbriggs High. In 1970 he moved to Cathkin High where later he became
deputy rector to Sir James Munn, though he was forced into early retirement
when he suffered a stroke 15 years ago.
George MacKenzie nevertheless used those years to spread his breadth of
interests, from travel and writing to music and philately. With his language
skills, he had travelled widely in Europe, both with family and pupils, and was
deeply affected by a visit to the Dachau concentration camp in Germany.
An interest in genealogy took him exploring in the United States and Canada.
With his teaching career largely concentrated on the Glasgow area, Bishopbriggs
became the family home. Again with his languages, he became a prime mover - and
interpreter - in the twinning of Bishopbriggs and the French town of
Corbeil-Essonne.
An undying devotion to his native North-east found expression through the West
of Scotland Gordonians, with whom he attended the recent farewell Glasgow
performance of Scotland The What?
So George MacKenzie didn't waste his time and was busy on his various
activities till he went into hospital for what was thought to be a routine
gall-bladder operation. But complications set in and he did not rally. He is
survived by his wife Jessie and three sons, James, Andrew, and Gordon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000189</DOCNO>
