<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fay Young suggests  that the energy  expended in battle  with your garden could  be put to better use Allowing nature to gain the upper hand</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Fay Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra green fingers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHY on earth dig when worms will do the job for you? Why mow the grass when,
left well alone, it produces a tapestry of orange hawkweed, yarrow, buttercups
and ox-eye daisies? A path cut through the meadow is enough to give the
impression it is all under control.
That's the Rosemary Wilkes method and it gets straight to the essential problem
of gardening - how to work with nature. ``People are torn by the desire to have
control over their garden, which means keeping it neat and tidy, yet somewhere
inside everybody there is a craving for a little share of the wild.''
As far as Wilkes is concerned there is no real contest. She is happy to give
nature the upper hand which results in a kind of gardening which she says may
not seem like gardening at all. ``When I had an Open Day one woman came up to
me and said: `my husband thinks your garden is really beautiful but it would
drive him crazy, he would have to tidy it up'.''
There is no routine tidy-up in the garden behind Prestonmill Cottage for good
reason. Summer's growth is not cut back in autumn because it provides food and
shelter for wildlife over the winter. Leaf litter is there for ground beetles.
Seed heads, rose hips and berries attract birds during winter. Dried herbaceous
plants and ornamental grasses are home for all kinds of hibernating insects.
The effect in winter is rather like a rough homespun tweed of greys, browns and
greens with sparks of red.
The craft teacher who runs workshops in weaving, spinning and knitting has
developed her own planting style using plants for texture and colour just as
she grows the woad, chamomile and madder which produce natural blue, yellow and
vivid red dyes. But there is more to it than that. This ``little bit of
jungle'' in the middle of East Lothian's vigorously farmed fields is a part of
a particular outlook on life which sees order in the seasons and chaos in the
self-imposed routine of the city.
Ten years ago Rosemary and Peter Wilkes decided they did not want to stay in
the city for the rest of their working lives. The peaceful cottage with a
spinning wheel in the corner seems an idyllic refuge - especially while the
rest of the world is revving up for the Christmas rush. It is never quite that
easy.
The banker follows the East Lothian commuter trail into Edinburgh while the
craft teacher is based at home with opportunity to contemplate the changing
patterns of rural communities. Since their garden backs on to Preston Mill,
owned by the National Trust for Scotland, the surrounding environment is
probably secure but traditional local jobs are disappearing. ``I know I am one
of very few people at home during the day and that has social implications,
particularly for older people.''
A friendly and thoughtful woman Wilkes knows there are no easy solutions. She
believes hobbies such as gardening and weaving express a growing desire for
closer contact with nature and more direct control of our lives. In her own
case, gardening was a discovery. After 16 years in a top flat with a distant
back green she arrived in East Linton with a few pots of woad and ``complete
blind ignorance'' about the challenge lying in wait at the back door. ``We just
didn't know what we were letting ourselves in for.''
They began with a wide expanse of lawn in the shelter of shrubs and beautiful,
mature but overcrowded trees - a blue cedar jostles for headroom with a red oak
which has lime green leaves in spring and turns to flame in autumn. The garden
was created in 1938 by John Burns, a local engineer who developed the cottage
and laid out an extravagant design. The remains of a waterfall and rockery
gradually emerged as the Wilkes cut back grass and sprawling shrubs.
While Peter drew plans for new beds and borders, Rosemary ``read and read and
read''. Christopher Lloyd is her reference for sensible advice, Beth Chatto her
bible for plants in dry gardens. Kellie Castle, just across the Forth in Fife,
shows what thrives on the cold, dry east coast. Her scrapbook of notes and
photographs recorded over the past 10 years shows an undeniably methodical
approach to the apparent informality of the garden. And, of course, there is
control.
Some of those cotoneasters which are already attracting red wings into the
garden are neatly clipped into columns or wrapped close to walls , roses (briar
and rugosa) are set out in a semi-circle providing a ``scented hot spot'' in
summer, an ancient holly has been cut into a comfortable round shape, ``like a
Christmas pudding on legs'', and herbs are bursting out of their brick-lined
borders.
``You need formal and wild elements,'' says Rosemary Wilkes, leading the way to
the woodland corner where curved benches provide a view of birds visiting the
garden. The flycatcher's nesting box had to be removed when the family cat took
to sitting in wait above it but there are ways of accommodating pets and
wildlife.
A delay in cutting one area of the lawn revealed wildflowers which had lain
dormant from the original meadow. Now it is cut with shears in August. The
cuttings are removed immediately to prevent fertilising dominant weeds and
grasses and the ay, ``very nutritious'', is used to mulch the rhododendrons.
``The area can look untidy but we just mow round the edge in June and July so
that it looks under control.''
Nature can be used to our advantage. Digging may be no more than a waste of
energy, ``if you dump organic material on the surface the worms will take it
down for you''. Too much tidying up could be destructive. In many areas of
Scotland, earthworms are threatened by the fearful New Zealand flatworm, which
seems to have no natural (or chemical) enemy. New evidence suggests that ground
beetles eat the disgusting alien but ground beetles need a nice supply of leaf
litter. ``The urge to tidy up could prevent nature from finding its own
solutions. I have found flatworms under pots and stones in one damp corner bu
the soil in other areas is still teeming with earth worms.''
Doing what comes naturally, Wilkes, the craft organiser of the Royal Highland
Show, was horrified to discover she was regarded as a gardening expert when an
appearance on The Beechgrove Garden led to a series of invitations to talk to
groups of amateur gardeners. ``People began to ask me terrible questions, such
as what do you do about black spot on roses and I had to answer - `nothing'. I
don't do anything at all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
