<HEADLINE>For the big night out - and morning after</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr, Anvar Khana</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n FOR those with a predeliction for plunging necklines on their party frocks,
the onslaught of Christmas parties means the uplift of the chest. The people to
turn to - your chest in their hands, so to speak - are Gossard, whose tip for
success this Christmas is to invest in one of the bras in the Gossard Ultrabra
Perfection range.
These combine Gossard's celebrated uplift element with day-long comfort.
Perhaps the most practical of the range (and the cheapest) is the strapless
Ultrabra. Unlike most strapless bras, the Gossard version doesn't squash and
flatten the bust. Rather, it creates the same cleavage as its strappy
equivalent would. Available only in black and white, the sizes of Ultrabra
range from 30-38A and B, and 32-38C; and the price is #16.99.
n NOW that you've got your bosom squeezed into your little black dress, the
next problem on the checklist is the hair. The way to wear your hair this
season is  la Julie Christie circa 1965, darling. It should be blow dried
straight, teased back slightly, but with a heavy fringe skimming the tops of
smoky, heavily lined eyes.
All very well, if your locks are thick and stay where they're put. If they
verge on the wispy, baby soft side, then the thing to try is Vidal Sassoon
Salon Smooth Protective Styling Spray (#1.99 for 150ml) which builds body in
fine hair and gives it a healthy sheen. The style can then be set with Vidal
Sassoon Holding Spray (#1.99 for 150ml).
n THE most common contact allergy among women in the industrialised world is
nickel allergy - an allergy to the component metal of most costume jewellery.
Reactions vary from itching through to severe dermatitis, and mean that for
many women, wearing costume jewellery is out of the question. Until recently,
only three costume jewellery brands had been awarded the Sheffield Assay Office
``N'' Mark which guarantees that their products are nickel-free.
Now, a new mail order costume jewellery catalogue has joined them. Jessica
Maybury offers more than 200 nickel-free pieces of jewellery, and the entire
collection is plated - either with 22 carat gold or sterling silver. Classic
styles of chokers, chains and bracelets sit alongside more up-to-the-minute
matte silver and gold pendants and novelty diamante brooches.
Prices range from #1 for a pair of stud earrings to #49 for a silver panther
brooch. There are also items in such unusual, but attractive, combinations as
copper and black diamond. Delivery is guaranteed within seven days, whether
orders were placed by post or by phone.
q For a catalogue contact Jessica Maybury, Maybury House, Hove, East Sussex BN3
6HA. Telephone: 01273 747374.
n IF your hair's too long to be brought under control by a squoosh of holding
spray, you could dress it up with some of the bejewelled hair accessories that
are all the rage this winter. Haircare company Celeste offers a wide selection
of attractive party accessories ranging in price from #1.99 to #3.99. Among the
styles they're promoting this winter are silver and gold beaded side combs
(pictured above), lacy snoods, velvet slides studded with pearls, ribbed satin
scrunchies in jewel colours and diamante clips. To find your local stockist,
call the consumer helpline on 0500 979899.
n BEAUTY expert Liz Earle, pictured, has more qualifications than most folk for
dispensing a little pre-festive season advice on how to reduce the effects on
your skin of little sleep: not only is she the author of more than 30 natural
health and beauty books, but as one of the team of GMTV presenters, she is
contract-bound to rise even before the larks. As a result, she has had to
develop ways of combatting the effects of the night before.
To fully wake yourself up of a morning, 20 quick splashes of ice cold water
over your closed eyelids should help, and will also serve to stimulate the
lymphatic system and reduce puffiness.
Tired, dull, and blotchy skin can be treated with a homemade natural compress
comprising one tablespoon of ground oatmeal, one tablespoon of warm water and
two drops of camomile essential oil.
Once all these ingredients have been mixed together and left to thicken, you
should dip a face cloth into the mixture and gently pat it all over your face
several times, before leaving it there. After 15 minutes, wash your face
thoroughly and pat dry.
Earle also suggests that spots be treated by applying a little tea-tree
essential oil to them. And, possibly most usefully at this time of year: Earle
suggests that if - in your drunken stupor - you can remember to down a couple
of evening primrose oil capsules and a B complex vitamin supplement after
you've been out boozing, you will reduce your suffering the next morning.
n TO its existing range of treatments geared mainly towards women, VIP Beauty
of Jordanhill, Glasgow, has introduced the Dermalogica skincare system, which
has products designed for men and women. A treatment consists of a deep cleanse
which prepares the beard; an exfoliation; which helps to free ingrowing hairs
before they become infected; a shave and application of a facial masque. geared
towards the customer's skin type.
The part which may appeal most to the man in your life, however, is the
10-minute nap while the masque sets. The Dermalogica treatment costs #18.75.
During December, the salon is running a special introductory offer:
two-for-the-price-of-one skincare treatment for couples who make a joint
appointment. Prices for women's treatments start at #12.85 for a pick-me-up
facial, but the special offer would be based on the cost of the more expensive
treatment.
q VIP Beauty, 482 Crow Road, Jordanhill. Telephone: 0141 334 0866.
</TEXT>
