<TEXT>
BIRTHDAYS:
Graham Stevenson, Yorkshire and England cricketer, 40.
Stephanie Lawrence, singer, 42.
Joel Garner, West Indies cricketer, 43.
Benny Andersson, singer with Abba, 49.
Christopher Ellison, actor, 49.
Liv Ullmann, Norwegian actress, 57.
The Hon Peter Dickinson, author, 68.
Arthur C Clarke, science fact and fiction writer, 78.
EVENTS:
1653 Oliver Cromwell became Lord Protector of England, ruling for more than
four years.
1773 The Boston Tea Party took place off Griffin's Wharf in Boston Harbour as a
protest against British taxation.
1809 The 13-year marriage between Josephine and Napoleon Bonaparte, being
childless, was dissolved.
1830 A five-arch bridge over the Don at Aberdeen, built with the accumulated
interest of a gift of #2 in 1605, was completed.
1838 The Zulu Chief Dingaan was defeated by a small force of Boers at Blood
River. It is celebrated in South Africa as ``Dingaan's Day''.
1853 Antonio-Lpez de Santa Anna was declared dictator of Mexico.
1911 A Norwegian expedition led by Roald Amundsen reached the South Pole, one
month ahead of Britain's Captain Scott.
1929 The British airship R100, designed by Barnes Wallis, first flew on trials.
1944 The Battle of the Bulge began when the Germans under Von Rundstedt
launched a strong attack in the Ardennes.
1955 The new terminal buildings at London airport opened.
1960 A United DC-8 jet and a TWA Super-Constellation collided over New York
City killing all 128 aboard the planes and six on the ground.
1971 Bangladesh formally came into existence after East Pakistan surrendered in
the war with India.
1983 Scots nannie Carol Compton was freed by an Italian court after being
accused of starting a fire in a house on Elba. There had been allegations of
witchcraft against her.
1991 Mrs Stella Rimington was appointed head of M15 from February 1992.
BORN ON THIS DAY:
1485 Catherine of Aragon, first wife of Henry VIII.
1714 George Whitefield, evangelist.
1742 Field Marshal Gebhard Leberecht von Blucher, Prussian military commander.
1770 Ludwig van Beethoven.
1775 Jane Austen.
1787 Mary Russell Mitford, author.
1857 Edward Emerson Barnard, US astronomer.
1899 Sir Noel Coward.
1900 Sir Victor Pritchett, author and critic.
1901 Dr Margaret Mead, US anthropologist.
DIED ON THIS DAY:
1816 Charles, 3rd Earl of Stanhope, reformer and inventor.
1821 James Sinclair, Earl of Caithness, inventor of a road-going steam
locomotive.
1859 Wilhelm Grimm, German philologist and folklorist, the younger of the two
brother philologists who wrote a great collection of fairy tales.
1933 Robert Chambers, US novelist and artist.
1944 Glenn Miller, lost without trace after a routine plane flight to France
where his band was due to play. No distress call was heard and no wreckage
sighted.
1965 Somerset Maugham.
1989 Lee Van Cleef, aged 64.
</TEXT>
