<HEADLINE>Joel Shulman (Joe Saye)</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Appreciation by JIM GALLOWAY, director of the Toronto Jazz Festival.</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Joel Shulman, born, Glasgow, February 25, 1923, died, Toronto, December 12, 1995
AFTER an extended illness, Joel Shulman, also known professionally as Joe Saye,
died on the evening of December 12 in Toronto where he made his home for the
last 23 years. He had suffered from multiple sclerosis but died of cancer.
Mr Shulman was born in Glasgow in 1923 and as a young boy showed great promise
as a musician; there was no family history of musical talents but Joel's
abilities were such that at age 14, Roy Fox, a leading bandleader of the day,
hired him as a featured accordion player, (1937-38), managing to get Joel
released from school at Greenhead Academy to do so.
He then spent eight years in vaudeville, formed his own trio in 1948, (piano
was now his preferred instrument), and made his BBC debut in 1949. In that same
year he married Joan Warner.
Joel moved to the US in 1955 and in 1958-9, on the recommendation of his friend
George Shearing, worked as accompanist for singer Dakota Staton. At this time
he also performed with his own trio, Joe Saye's Scottish Jazz. Throughout the
sixties his playing took him all over the US. He developed a very personal solo
style on his instrument.
In 1972 the Shulmans moved to Toronto when he quickly become a favourite. Joel
and Joan opened The Garden Party, an intimate little room in the heart of the
city, which they ran for seven years. It was the setting for a series of Sunday
evening musical dialogues with the leading jazz instrumentalists on the Toronto
scene.
The achievements of Mr Shulman are all the more impressive given the fact that
from age two he was blind, caused by the effects of retinoblastoma.
His courage, dedication and sense of humour speak to a remarkable strength of
character which was put to the test many times throughout his life. His wife
Joan described Joel as ``a truly lovely and good man''.
For my own part, I never knew a wittier pianist, both verbally and musically.
It was a joy and a challenge to play with him. A memorial service, to be held
in London is planned for January 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
