<HEADLINE>To launch a thousand sniffs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr, Anvar Khand</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Kerr and Anvar Khan look
at two sets of famous features
flogging fragrances this Christmas
IT seems appropriate that the face launching Africa, Britain's newest teen
perfume should be Britain's latest teen supermodel - the unhealthily (even by
superwaif standards) scrawny, but undeniably beautiful, Jodie Kidd, main
picture. Africa - an exotic combination of ylang ylang, jasmine, precious
woods, amber and vanilla - is the ideal choice for younger fragrance fans. Not
least because none of the three items in its range costs more than #9. The 30ml
eau de parfum costs #8.95; the 15ml eau de parfum costs #4.95, and the 100ml
body spray costs #2.45. The collection is exclusively available from Boots
stores.
At the age of thirteen, Paulina Porizkova, the new face of Red by Giorgio
Beverly Hills, left, whose surname sounds like a sausage, had to be smuggled
out of Czechoslovakia by her refugee parents. She was discovered by a scout in
Sweden (I can just see him in his shorts and braces and feathered cap) who sent
her photo to modelling agency Elite. She says, somewhat pretentiously, that
modelling is like ``being an apple in a still life painting''. What she's
trying to say is that she simulates extraneous vegetable matter. And, lord,
she's good at it too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000194</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000194</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charles Warrell</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974864581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHARLES Warrell, the man who wrote the I-Spy children's books and was known as
Big Chief I-Spy, has died at the age of 106.
The books, from the first in 1948, encouraged youngsters to search out the
wonders of their world. Children scored points for spotting objects such as
birds, cars, and oil tankers. The sixpenny books were so popular they were
turned into columns in the Daily Mail and the News Chronicle.
Youngsters who managed to score all the points in a book could join the I-Spy
Club. But for sixpence any ``pale-face'' was welcome to the great Tribe of
Redskins. Further up the I-Spy hierarchy, members could become patrol leaders
or tally book keepers, organising their own meetings. Mass theatre outings were
also arranged for the young. On one occasion 8000 children - travelling in 80
hired double-decker buses - enjoyed an I-Spy day out in London.
Charles Warrell spent his early life as a science teacher before becoming a
headmaster in Nottinghamshire. His idea for children's books was rejected by
several publishers so, at the age of 59, he published the first book himself.
He pulled off a major coup when he persuaded Woolworths to sell it. He never
looked back - 25 million books were sold in 20 years. The whole series lasted
until 1986 and it has since reappeared under different imprints.
Charles Warrell lived in Budleigh Salterton, Devon. He died at the Valley Lodge
Nursing Home in Matlock, Derbyshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000195</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000195</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A BOOK AT BEDTIME</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Donald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974864582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Willie  Anderson,  managing director of John Smith &amp; Son Bookshops and
president of the Booksellers Association, tells ANN DONALD about his night time
reading.
n I'M a real grasshopper when it comes to reading as I've always got four or
five books on the go at the same time. That's the problem of being a bookseller
- too much choice. Though since I came off the shopfloor in 1984 I tend to read
those books that are thrust into my hands by publishers or those that nobody
else wants.
I do prefer fiction to other genres and of course a lot of that tends to be
American fiction because that's where the quality is.
I still don't think that there are any British authors that compare with the
likes of John Updike or Saul Bellow and their tremendous rhythm and poetry. One
book that I really got into recently was George Mackay Brown's collection of
short stories called Winter Tales. I haven't read much of his work but this was
impossible to put down once I'd started it.
Another one was Bill Bryson's Notes From A Small Island. I think he's a highly
amusing author though his book isn't as funny as previous titles set in small
town America. He's very good fun to read because of his relaxed style of
writing.
The last one that I really had to persevere with was Oscar Huejelos novel, Mr
Ives' Christmas. It could be described as a modern parable of Christmas centred
around a very, very religious gentleman who has lost his only son and is coming
to terms with this loss, his life and thoughts of God.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951216-000196</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000196</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A toast to Christmas present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lady Claire Macdonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra Lady Claire's Kitchen</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUR eldest daughter is a nurse, and has had to spend the occasional Christmas
working, so we should never forget those for whom Christmas Day is not a
holiday.
However, for the majority of us Christmas Day is a holiday. No mother can ever
forget the exhaustion of Christmas morning when children were very young! First
the Christmas Eve evenings, going into the night, spent hovering about on the
landing waiting for various children to drop off to sleep before being able to
deliver the filled stockings to the ends of their beds, followed by too few
hours sleep before pre-dawn awakenings by the children, mouths crammed with
chocolate money, exclaiming over the contents of their stockings!
Christmas Day should be, as far as possible, as much a holiday for host or
hostess as for the rest of the household. Last week I wrote about preparing the
turkey early - next week I shall be giving attention to the numerous ways that
the rest of the food preparation can be finished off in advance.
My aim is to get everything done in the kitchen in advance of Christmas
morning, bar the things that just have to be done for each meal and the table
setting and clearing. For these tasks you should be inundated with offers of
help from family and friends - do not hesitate, accept all offers of help with
alacrity! I do. Adopting a martyred air and turning down offers of help do not
make for a good atmosphere in the house over Christmas!
I have experimented with the content for breakfast for Christmas over the
years. We have had a brunch, of the black pudding, sausage, bacon and egg and
fried bread variety, with Bucks Fizz to drink. We all felt so ill by midday
that we had to force ourselves outside for much-needed exercise. We had rallied
just sufficiently to enjoy Christmas dinner that evening.
Another year, not long ago, I made cranberry muffins for breakfast. I felt
rather pleased with myself but Godfrey is not one to hide his feelings, and he
discovered then that he had a deep dislike for cranberries. So did our four
children. They went in search of bread for toasting.
My desire for breakfast for this special day is for something more special than
toast, and so I evolved my own recipe for a spicy dough with marzipan through
the centre. You need look no further than the Stollen on sale in good
supermarkets to find the source for my inspiration.
My recipe contains no mixed peel - but you can get a citrus taste by adding
grated lemon and orange rinds to the dough. Making your own almond paste is
much nicer than buying a block of marzipan. Every brand of commercial marzipan
I've tried is too sickly. The more you work the almond paste the more the heat
of your hand will release the natural oil from the almonds, making the paste
bind together.
If you add any liquid to speed this process, use more lemon juice. This bread
freezes well. Thaw it overnight at room temperature, and warm the loaf before
slicing thickly to serve.
It is delicious toasted lightly, but you really need to grill-toast it rather
than try to put the slices in a toaster, most of which don't take slices as
thick as I like to serve (and eat) of this particular bread. You can serve and
eat it with butter and marmalade, or any other type of jam, if you like, This
bread makes breakfast on Christmas Day that bit more special, which is just
what I aim to do on this, the best day of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
