<HEADLINE>Just the picture of a demanding kitchen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Catherine Brown</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ihad been wondering if this year's Christmas gift problems might be solved by
getting everyone a food book. There are so many angles on food, and so few
straight recipe collections, that the choice is wide for both cooks and
non-cooks. But now, looking through the pile I've collected, there is the
question of who should get what. Even more difficult is deciding which books I
can, or cannot, happily part with.
I am tempted to keep Darina Allen's Irish Traditional Cooking (Kyle Cathie,
#19.99) since she has written an evocative food book. Unpretentious and
informative, it's a portrait of the people and their foods, with a large recipe
collection.
The fascination for Scots is the similarity between the two Celtic food
cultures. If anything, though, the Irish are ahead of us when it comes to
inventive potato cooking. I am working my way through her repertoire of dishes
based on mashed potatoes and butter, otherwise known as champ. So far: spring
onion, parsley, chive, dulse, pea, and leek, but nettle will have to wait until
the spring. They're a reminder of the power of old potato, before we discovered
rice and pasta.
Also using potatoes, as their source of filling carbohydrate, were the Smoked
Haddock Fish Cakes which I made from Quaglino's: The Cookbook, by Richard
Whittington (Conran Octopus, #14.99) - and very good they were too. I've
flipped through the book to admire the stunning food photography and the
photojournalism in the first section which gives a lively picture of this
Terence Conran restaurant in operation. But now I'm happy to pass it on.
As I am with The Gastrodome Cookbook by Rory Ross (Conran Octopus, #17.99).
Similar in style, with superb design and luscious food pictures, this book
captures the cooking and atmosphere of the trio of Conran restaurants at
Butler's Wharf. Like Quaglino's, it's first and foremost an advert for the
restaurants, so I will give them both to I and C, who live in London and might
make use of them before sampling the restaurants.
I have decided not to part, however, with Silvija Davidson's Loaf, Crumb and
Crust (Michael Joseph, #17.99) in which she takes an original look - not at
baking breads, but at cooking with them. A subject which she has pursued in
cooking cultures around the world. There is still so much to read, so many
intriguing recipes to try. A state of affairs which also applies to Fiona
Armstrong's Commuter's Cookbook (Neil Wilson Publishing, #7.99). Anyone who
titles a chapter ``Easy, Easy, Easy . . . '' instantly commands the attention
of all cooks-in-a-hurry who know that it's possible to cook more cheaply from
scratch at speed, without compromising on quality, than reach for a ready-made.
But I will give Kit Chapman's Great British Chefs (Mitchell Beazley, #19.99) to
N, who works as a chef, and who will enjoy reading about the tortuous routes to
the top of the 18 chefs whose profiles are included in the book. Though I'm no
slouch when it comes to experimenting with food, I was not inspired to try any
of the recipes in this book. Rather than well-cooked food, looking good enough
to eat, there is an excess, to my mind, of hands-on, fussy plate presentation.
For S, who is a vegetarian, I have picked out Mary Gwynn's Vegetarian Food for
Friends (BBC Books, #12.99), though I will photocopy, before I hand over the
book, her recipes for Roasted Root Vegetables with Cranberry and Orange Sauce
and New Potato Casserole with Fresh Greens, both of which had enthusiastic
meat-eaters asking for seconds.
Harold Bagust's Breadmaking at Home (Hale, #25) will go to home-baker J, who
will, hopefully, appreciate a bread book with reliable recipes since Bagust
claims that he wrote the book because so many other bread books he'd used were
full of recipes which did not work.
And that's about it. Except for gardener-cooks R and G who will get the
stunningly beautiful, as well as practical, Bob Flowerdew's Complete Fruit
Book: A definitive source book to growing, harvesting and cooking fruit (Kyle
Cathie, 19.99) along with Jekka's Complete Herb Kit (Kyle Cathie, #9.99).
For last-minute stuffing into stockings on Christmas Eve, that leaves me with
the delightful A la Pym: The Barbara Pym Cookery Book by Hilary Pym and Honor
Wyatt (Prospect Books, #9.99) as well as One Year at Books for Cooks (Pryor
Publications, #3.99) which, besides providing a lively collection of recipes,
tried and tested in their little restaurant, also publicises London's
best-stocked cookbook shop.
</TEXT>
