<HEADLINE>Steps to a dancer's diet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Leila Farrah</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra A Slice of Life</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SLICE OF LIFE
n Galina Samsova talks to Leila Farrah about a typical day's eating
MY breakfast is always Nescafe, although sometimes when I'm on tour I might
have breakfast with the company. Then more Nescafe until lunch. Normally I skip
lunch altogether: I'll really only eat a sandwich in the office three out of
six days or have a toasted ham and cheese sandwich at the pub over the road
because I like eating quite late. The only time I'll have a proper regular
lunch is on holiday in the South of France.
Food is a pleasure, I really love it and always did, but I particularly like
eating with friends. And I like cooking but not on my own. For myself I just do
tuna fish with beans and onions or something from Marks &amp; Spencer or Safeway.
But I have my great niece from Russia staying with me and she cooks for me
which is nice. We like Mexican chilli con carne and pasta. We do eat meat but
not serious pieces, just chops or meat in a pasta sauce.
I'm afraid I don't eat much fruit or salads, but I love tomato and basil salad
and always make a green salad if I have guests. Haricots and mange touts I
love. I always have a glass of wine in my kitchen, a dry white, such as
Frascati. La Brasserie in West Regent Street is a good place to go after a
performance and the food at La Parmigiana in Great Western Road is lovely.
My eating habits are the same as when I danced. I still lead the life of a
dancer and so I find that if I eat during the day I want to have a siesta. If I
eat between meals it'll be nuts or salami which I love. When I was dancing, I
was never on a diet in my life, but now I should be, as the hips tend to
stretch out.
I love Russian dishes like vinaigrette salads and kotletki cutlets which I make
in enough quantities for a whole week and just heat up. And I love Russian
soups but they take too long to prepare.
Being born and bred in Russia, I can't eat anything raw . . . I like looking at
steak tartare and fresh oysters but can't actually swallow them. Caviar and
smoked salmon are my favourite foods - I get quite a lot of the second but very
little of the first - except in Russia.
n GALINA Samsova was born in Stalingrad and began her career in Kiev,
eventually emigrating to the west with official permission. She has performed
as principal dancer with the National Ballet of Canada and the Sadler's Wells
Royal Ballet, the London Festival Ballet as Ballerina, and is acknowledged as
one of the greatest interpreters of the classical repertoire. Latterly, she
produces, and participates as juror in international ballet competitions. She
was appointed Artistic Director of Scottish Ballet in January 1991 and this
year was appointed Honorary Professor of Choreography in the Ukraine.
</TEXT>
