<HEADLINE>Waiting for Santa, for another eternity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Weekend Extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS A CHILD our street was our territory. The town was our kingdom. There was
nothing beyond it. The news of the outside world was a meaningless babble that
chased children's programmes off the TV screen. We knew certain things: the
baby Jesus loved us, to be bold was bad, and Santa lived in the Co-op.
He was the king of the castle. As our eyes were not yet big enough to see
around our town, there could be nothing else. Of course, this was the real
Santa. Where else would he go? Other towns did not exist, besides it was such a
great home.
You had to climb four whole flights of stairs to reach his grotto. Each step
was huge. One Christmas we saw a movie with Tommy Steele as a broken doll,
discarded in the basement of a store, to be used as kindling for the Christmas
Day furnace. But he climbed all the steps to the toy department and Santa saved
him and his broken toy friends.
We got so excited: our Co-op was on the telly!
When you reached the top of the stairs you stood in line, back straight like
the big toy-soldier sentries and clutched your mum's hand - or your aunt's if
you'd told her you hadn't been to see Santa yet; even if you had. You would
then pray that Santa would not reach into the wrong sack, the pink one, instead
of the blue one for boys and you'd end up with Sindy.
It had happened before.
Father Renucci had already explained eternity, but you figured it was the
length of Christmas Eve. Which was how long it felt before the elf, a big girl
in green, ushered you through the tinsel drawbridge. You shut your eyes to
avoid the coloured strips of plastic and opened them after they had dragged
over the bobble of your hat.
And there he was, sitting on a chair draped in silver - Santa was smiling. He
smelt of oranges, talc, and old jumpers and you sat on his knee and answered
all his questions and you left clutching a bright parcel wrapped up with
red-holly sticky tape.
And as you grew up you never quite forgot, whatever they said. You wished he
was real, so he was real. And why shouldn't he be?
Today it is technology that makes the existence of Santa plausible. In the
Christmases past it could not be explained how one man could be in all those
department stores, down all those chimneys, and eat all those mince pies. But
today we have technology. If man with all his corruptions can design software
to send a billion messages to computer screens worldwide in less time than a
snowdrop takes to melt, then one ageless old man, fuelled on goodwill and
blessed by God as a saint, can gallop the information superhighway, pulled by
cyber-reindeers. Children today can e-mail Santa. I think it's
``sckidweb.gimmie.iwanna''.
It remains, however, the big-store visit to Santa's grotto which puts the match
to the festive spirit which can burn so bright, for so long. The relationship
between Jenners store in Edinburgh and the crimson-clad man extends back into
the last century - and he arrived for his winter season by carriage, swept
along Princes Street by two strong horses called Harvey and Storm.
Initial requests for an audience were rebuffed by the ladies at the perfume
counter: ``If you're looking for Santa, he's on the fourth floor but he doesn't
start till 11''. But out on the streetwere Claire Cherry and Stephen, her
four-year-old son, who were waiting for his imminent arrival. While Stephen
chewed at the handle of his mother's plastic bag - in acute anticipation,
obviously - she explained that her husband was Santa's driver and that another
carriage guest had included Julia Roberts while filming Mary Reilly in
Edinburgh.
I just had time to joke about asking Santa for Julia Roberts for Christmas when
they both appeared; Santa and Claire's husband, not Santa and Julia Roberts.
There appeared not to have been a lot of children around earlier but at the
first sight of their hero clip-clopping toward the pavement, dozens of little
hands were waving.
One little blond boy with woollen shark-shaped gloves was waving so hard it
resembled an aerial feeding frenzy. Stephen by this time had lost interest in
wandering round in circles and chewing plastic bags and was now drooling, his
jaw slack with awe.
After a brief photocall Santa in red robes and thick woollen beard - a bit like
an inquisitor, really - was striding through the front door, through the
perfume counter and on to an escalator. A stream of little boys and girls, held
by mums and grans, followed. While one little girl frantically tried to tug at
his robes another recoiled in terror, squirming in her gran's arms. The hike
upstairs led us through glassworks, menswear, bathroom accessories to the
fourth floor and rugs.
And here in a festive oasis, among sand-dunes of stacked Persian rugs, sat
Santa's log cabin, smaller, he would later confess, than last year's, but
cosier. While he strode through the front door, the children queued around the
red rope that weaved towards a side entrance. Santa soon settled into his chair
and then beckoned the first two children in.
Laura, 6!s, led her little brother David, 4!s, through the door (by his hood)
as his eyes resembled saucers staring at the mechanical elves relentlessly
wrapping gifts. After smiling and asking their names, while David chewed on his
toggle, Santa asked what they wanted for Christmas.
``Laura, honey, what would you like?'' he inquired gently.
``Blusher!'' she replied, while her mother leaned in the doorway, raising her
eyes to the strip-lighting.
``Oh, that's nice,'' said Santa, a little surprised, ``anything else?''
``Blusher, a make-up set and dressing-up clothes.''
Laura then had to whisper into her brother's ear that he wanted an Action Man
and he agreed, and so did Santa, but only if they were both very good, went to
bed early, and didn't grow up to be a Clueless model or mercenary soldier.
As they emerged the next child entered while the younger ones waiting in the
queue played trampoline on the Chinese superwashed 9ft x 6ft rugs, a snip at
#395. You could see the sales assistants on the floor staring into space,
watching their carpet sales drift out the window.
But Santa was on a roll. Besides, it was only an hour before he was off for
one. Lunch begins at midday in the Jenners magic kingdom. Before his break he
listened to four-year-old Grant splutter out how he would like a new bike
because his old one was going to a car-boot sale. Then there was the mother of
two little boys who had to explain that they weren't getting toy guns for
Christmas after one gave the other a black eye with the butt.
``Was it sore, did you cry?'' asked Santa. The boy nodded his head, sticking
out a petted lip. Santa promised to get him something better and so the sun
shone again. During a quiet point Santa's wife arrived to explain that his
grandchild had a cold and couldn't come. Maureen Kennedy, the store's
promotional manager, looked stricken: ``Santa doesn't have any children,'' she
corrected. But Santa said no, that's wrong,  he had millions.
Saint Nicholas, the patron saint of boys and girls, began as the Bishop of
Myra, an ancient city in Asia Minor. Legend said he began his good works by
saving a merchant's three daughters from being sold into slavery by heaving
sacks of gold into his back garden, saving them from the hell of the harem.
Wandering out of the dark ages he was re-employed after the Reformation by the
Germans, where his work spread throughout Europe to Britain. However it was the
Coca-Cola Company in America who redesigned his robes.
Yet when such a CV was mentioned to him, he only smiled and said: ``You may
think that but I couldn't possibly comment,'' before showing off his throne.
``Look at that chair,'' he said, ``what a beauty! I bet the first young boy I
held on my knee here will be an old man now. Time flies quickly.''
He explained that he could not be happier than when spreading festive joy. But
he saves his greatest rewards for the handicapped children who arrive in
organised visits. ``Last year a young spastic boy rushed in to see me and he
was crying with joy, shouting: `Santa, Santa!'. He hugged me, with his arms
round my neck so tight that I thought he would choke me. He was distraught when
his mother made him leave, yet so, so pleased to have met me.''
Blind children find a reassuring comfort in the feel of his beard and the soft
warmth of his furry boots - fake, of course. ``They'll spend ages feeling your
face and beard, just to make sure you are the real McCoy, or the real McClaus.
It's lovely. Not sad at all.''
Older girls often pay Father Christmas a house call: ``They'll ask me for a
millionaire for Christmas or a big hunky man.'' I did think about asking Santa
if he ever got a bit frisky, what with having sixth-form girls sitting on his
knee, but I thought better of it. He is the embodiment of goodness and light,
not dark, stockings and gym-slips.
At lunchtime we went to the staff canteen where Santa ordered sausage roll,
beans and chips. When the woman was pouring his tea he said, ``No milk,
please''. So I looked at him. ``C'mon, not in my tea. I'll take it straight
with some mince pies, but that's it.'' During our meal we were joined by a
mutual friend, Jimmy, who visits the store regularly after working there for 37
years.
As a trio we talked about Christmas past, present, and future.
Jimmy: ``I remember the first time I saw Santa. It was at a Sunday School party
and I must have been three or four. All the lights were turned out. The only
light came from the glow of the candles on the Christmas tree. From out of the
darkness came Santa - I couldn't believe it. I still remember it so clearly.''
Santa: ``So do I. You were nervous about collecting a parcel, so many small
children are, but you took it. What saddens me is that there are so many shabby
Santas in stores today, with costumes you could spit peas through. And they
charge! Can you imagine a child being told his parents can't afford to let him
see Santa?It's outrageous!''
Me: ``Well, what about the World Santa Claus Conference in Copenhagen last
July. The Finns boycotted, claiming Santa belongs to them alone. They said you
only come from Lapland. If the organisers can't dispense Christmas cheer what
hope have the rest of us?''
Santa: ``Plenty! Why it's all in the heart. Who needs officials, you've got
me!''
We all nodded and poked our beans around our plates.
As Santa left to feed the reindeers, wedging scraps into his belt, I went to
wander the store. From the outside Jenners resembles a Christmas present all
wrapped up in the scaffold and tarpaulin of a #2m restoration. Inside it
remains a wonderland of presents. It is either a commercial horror or people in
the act of giving. You have to choose which eyes to look through.
In the basement toy department, children's eyes were on stalks at the parade of
potential presents; Lego, Action Men, Sindys, the toys of my youth saved from
the furnace by popularity. One little boy was in the corner, trying to clamber
on to a rocking-horse while his mother prised open his gloved hands.
``You'll just have to wait and see what Santa brings,'' she said.
But he still wasn't happy. For a child, you see, Santa's visit will always
remain an eternity away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
