<DOCNO>GH951216-000202</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951216-000202</DOCID>
<DATE>951216</DATE>
<HEADLINE>So much death, so many stories untold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Bold</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974864589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE KGB's LITERARY ARCHIVE
Vitaly Shentalinsky
Harvill Press, #18
LITERATURE
AFTER the suicide of the Soviet literary cheerleader Maya-kovsky in 1930, a
poem was found in his pocket.  One line stated: ``As they say, that's the end
of the story.'' It was not the end of the story.
Stalin described Mayakovsky as ``the best and most talented poet of our Soviet
epoch'' and ominously declared that ``indifference to his memory is a crime''.
It was obviously suicidal to interpret Mayakovsky's death as an expression of
despair at the horrific state of the Soviet Union.
At the first Congress of Soviet Writers in 1934, Isaac Babel made the fatal
mistake of suggesting Mayakovsky's suicide amounted to ``the poet's conclusion
that it was impossible to work under Soviet conditions''.
Accused of various crimes against the Soviet state, Babel was shot in 1940. A
literary master of the art of silence had been silenced though the secret
police withheld this information from his widow who was told, as late as 1947,
to look forward to Babel's release from the camps.
Stalin, and his secret police, had struck again. As the secret police files
examined by Vitaly Shentalinsky show, Stalin encouraged his secret police to
strike brutally again and again and again.
The day Stalin died - March 5, 1953 - Shentalinsky was 13. Shentalinsky's
father was the only man in his village with a radio so was the first to know
the news in his corner of a collective farm. He told Shentalinsky to spread the
news and he did and watched face after face fold into tears. Not tears of joy,
but tears of genuine anguish. In 1953 Shentalinsky had no idea Stalin was a
monster. He was not alone in his ignorance.
It now seems astonishing that Stalin was once widely regarded at home and
abroad as an avuncular figure on the side of the angels opposed to the diabolic
Hitler. Stalin, by this fiction, was the saviour of the Soviet Union and a man
who helped defeat a maniac.
In fact Stalin killed at least as many Russians as Hitler did. Stalin was
Hitler's soulmate, a murderer of millions of Russians. Among the millions were
many men and women of letters: some 1500 Russian writers died as a direct
result of their refusal to accept the authority of Stalin.
One of those Russian writers, the poet Osip Mandelstam, signed his own death
warrant when, at the request of his interrogator Shivarov in May 1934, he wrote
out the following anti-Stalinist satire (which I give in translation by
Vladimir Markov and Merrill Sparks):
``We exist in a country grown unreal and strange;/No one ten steps away hears
the talk we exchange./ But when chances for half-conversation appear,/We will
never omit the Kremlin mountaineer./Each thick finger, a fattened worm,
gesticulates,/And his words strike you like they were many-pound weights./His
full cockroach moustache hints a laughter benigning,/And the shafts of his
boots: always spotlessly shining./And the gang of thick-skinned leaders near
him obeys;/Semi-humans are at his disposal always./ Decree after decree he
incessantly coins/Which hit people on foreheads, eyebrows, eyes and groins./ He
possesses the broad chest, a Georgian perfection,/And each new death for him is
a berry confection.''
Mandelstam had never dared put his poem to paper before his intimidating
encounter with Shivarov.
In his cell in Lubyanka's inner prison, Mandelstam attempted suicide by
slashing the veins on both his wrists with a razor blade he had concealed in
the sole of his boot. He was saved by jailers who bound up his wrists. Saved
from a relatively quick death, so that he could suffer slowly until he died of
heart failure in a transit camp near Vladivostok in the winter of 1938.  KGB
files contain a letter written by Mandelstam's widow to Beria, head of the
Soviet secret police. It contained a question. Did the NKVD - the title of the
secret police of the time, after the fearful force was known as Cheka then GPU
then OGPU and before it was known as NKGB then MGB then MVD then KGB - have
``sufficient grounds for destroying a poet, a master''?
Beria did not bother to reply. He could do what he wanted until the death of
Stalin. And then he was done to death, on the orders of Khrushchev and others,
in December 1953.
So much death; and so much of it manufactured in the Lubyanka, headquarters of
the Soviet secret police from 1917. When Shentalinsky was allowed into the
Lubyanka to look at secret police files in 1989, a KGB official observed:
``You're the first writer, it seems, who has come here of his own free will.''
In the bad old days writers were taken to the Lubyanka to be beaten into
confessing crimes they had never committed. The files tell a sustained tale of
terror.
For example, the case file on Vsevolod Mayerhold preserves a letter written by
this theatrical genius who was arrested in 1939 for disagreeing with the
official doctrine of Socialist Realism:
``The investigators began to use force on me, a sick, 65-year-old man. I was
made to lie face down and then beaten on the soles of my feet and my spine with
a rubber strap . . . For the next few days, when those parts of my legs were
covered with extensive internal haemorrhaging, they again beat the
red-blue-and-yellow bruises with the strap and the pain was so intense that it
felt as if boiling hot water was being poured on those sensitive areas. I
howled and wept from the pain. They beat my back with the same rubber strap and
punched my face, swinging their fists from a great height . . . I began to
incriminate myself in the hope that this, at least, would lead quickly to the
scaffold.''
Vsevolod Mayerhold was arrested in 1939 for disagreeing with the official
doctrine of Socialist Realism. He was shot in 1940, the same year as Babel, who
had doubtless endured the same atrocities.
Pavel Alexandrovich Florensky was taken to the Lubyanka in 1928 and
subsequently shot at Solovki islands camp in 1937 as Shentalinsky discovered
from the files. Honoured by his admirers as the Russian Leonardo da Vinci,
Florensky was a mathematician, physicist, inventor, engineer, priest and author
of The Pillar and Ground of the Truth (1913) - an influential exploration of
spiritual values.
His ``crime'', of course, was having an Orthodox faith in an unorthodox Soviet
state. He told his interrogators he was well disposed towards the Soviet Union
as a force capable of improving the condition of the common people but he was
done for and duly became yet another victim of Soviet violence.
Another was Boris Pilnyak - author of The Hungry Year (1921) - who was shot in
the same year as Florensky. Another was Nikolay Klyuev, a peasant poet also
shot in 1937. Yet another was Vladimir Kirshon, a playwright shot in 1938.
Shentalinsky's book (translated from the Russian and expertly annotated by Jon
Crowfoot) explains why some Soviet citizens - take the case of Marina Tsvetaeva
- killed themselves rather than face the official consequences of their own
creativity. And why other Soviet citizens - take the case of Maxim Gorky -
killed their own creativity by cooperating with Stalinism.
Shentalinsky has not told the whole story because so many documents were
destroyed: ``For years a soot-stained chimney released a stream of smoke over
the Lubyanka and for decades sprinkled Moscow with the ash of incinerated
manuscripts.'' But he has mastered his distressing material, and he
convincingly tells the terrifying truth about the Stalinist terror.
ALAN BOLD
